(Aramaic) corresponding to אוֹת; a portent: sign.

apparent contracted from אוֹת in the demonstrative sense of entity; properly, self (but generally used to point out more definitely the object of a verb or preposition, even or namely): (as such unrepresented in English).

probably from אָנָה; properly, nearness (used only as a preposition or an adverb), near; hence, generally, with, by, at, among, etc.: against, among, before, by, for, from, in(-to), (out) of, with. Often with another prepositional prefix.
of uncertain derivation; a hoe or other digging implement: coulter, plowshare.
from אוֹת and בַּ֫עַל; with Baal; Ethbaal, a Phoenician king: Ethbaal.
or matha; a primitive root (collateral to 225 contraction); to arrive: (be-, things to) come (upon), bring.
(Aramaic) or wathaw (Aramaic); corresponding to אָתָה: (be-)come, bring.

or (shortened) aatta; or wath; feminine (irregular) sometimes nattiy; plural masculine attem; feminine atten; or oattenah; or fattennah; a primitive pronoun of the second person; thou and thee, or (plural) ye and you: thee, thou, ye, you.
probably from the same as אֵיתָן (in the sense of patience); a female donkey (from its docility): (she) ass.
(Aramaic) probably from the corresponding to אֵשׁ; probably a fire-place, i.e. furnace: furnace.
or mattiyq; from נָתַק in the sense of decreasing; a ledge or offset in a building: gallery.
or Iythay; from אוֹת; near; Ittai or Ithai, the name of a Gittite and of an Israelite: Ithai, Ittai.
of Egyptian derivation; Etham, a place in the Desert: Etham.
or tithmowl; or methmuwl; probably from אוֹת or אוֹת and מוֹאל; heretofore; definitely yesterday: + before (that) time, + heretofore, of late (old), + times past, yester(day).
from תָּנָה; a present (as the price of harlotry): reward.
perhaps from אֶתְנָה; munificence; Ethni, an Israelite: Ethni.
the same as אֶתְנָה; a gift (as the price of harlotry or idolatry): hire, reward.
the same as אֶתְנָן in the sense of אֶתְנִי; Ethnan, an Israelite: Ethnan.
(Aramaic) from a root corresponding to that of אֲתָרִים; a place; (adverb) after: after, place.
plural from an unused root (probably meaning to step); places; Atharim, a place near Palestine: spies.
from בּוֹא; an entrance to a building: entry.
(Aramaic) from בְּאֵשׁ; wicked: bad.
a primitive root; to dig; by analogy, to engrave; figuratively, to explain: declare, (make) plain(-ly).
from בָּאַר; a pit; especially a well: pit, well.
the same as בְּאֵר; Beer, a place in the Desert, also one in Palestine: Beer.
from בָּאַר; a cistern: cistern.
from בְּאֵר; a well; Beera, an Israelite: Beera.
from בְּאֵר and the plural of אֵל; well of heroes; Beer-Elim, a place in the Desert: Beer-elim.
the same as בְּאֵרָא; Beerah, an Israelite: Beerah.
feminine plural of בְּאֵר; wells; Beeroth, a place in Palestine: Beeroth.
from בְּאֵר; fountained; Beeri, the name of a Hittite and of an Israelite: Beeri.
from בְּאֵר and חָי (with prefix) and רֹאֶה; well of a living (One) my Seer; Beer-Lachai-Roi, a place in the Desert: Beer-lahai-roi.
from בְּאֵר and שֶׁ֫בַע (in the sense of שָׁבַע); well of an oath; Beer-Sheba, a place in Palestine: Beer-shebah.
from the feminine plural of בְּאֵר, and the plural contraction of בֵּן, and יַעֲקָן; wells of (the) sons of Jaakan; Beeroth-Bene-Jaakan, a place in the Desert: Beeroth of the children of Jaakan.
patrial from בְּאֵרוֹת; a Beerothite or inhabitant of Beeroth: Beerothite.
a primitive root; to smell bad; figuratively, to be offensive morally: (make to) be abhorred (had in abomination, loathsome, odious), (cause a, make to) stink(-ing savour), X utterly.
(Aramaic) corresponding to בָּאַשׁ: displease.
from בֹּארוֹת; a stench: stink.
feminine of בְּאֹשׁ; stink-weed or any other noxious or useless plant: cockle.
plural of בְּאֹשׁ; poison-berries: wild grapes.
feminine active participle of an unused root meaning to hollow out; something hollowed (as a gate), i.e. pupil of the eye: apple (of the eye).
probably of foreign origin; Bebai, an Israelite: Bebai.
from בָּלַל; confusion; Babel (i.e. Babylon), including Babylonia and the Babylonian empire: Babel, Babylon.
(Aramaic) corresponding to בָּבֶל: Babylon.
(Aramaic) patrial from בָּבֶל; a Babylonian: Babylonia.
a Persian word; food: spoil (from the margin for baz.)

a primitive root; to cover (with a garment); figuratively, to act covertly; by implication, to pillage: deal deceitfully (treacherously, unfaithfully), offend, transgress(-or), (depart), treacherous (dealer, -ly, man), unfaithful(-ly, man), X very.
from בָּגַד; a covering, i.e. clothing; also treachery or pillage: apparel, cloth(-es, ing), garment, lap, rag, raiment, robe, X very (treacherously), vesture, wardrobe.
feminine plural active participle of בָּגַד; treacheries: treacherous.
from בָּגַד; treacherous: treacherous.
probably of foreign origin; Bigvai, an Israelite: Bigvai.
of Persian derivation; Bigtha, a eunuch of Xerxes: Bigtha.
or Bigthanad; of similar derivation to בִּגְתָא; Bigthan or Bigthana, a eunuch of Xerxes: Bigthan, Bigthana.

from בָּדַד; properly, separation; by implication, a part of the body, branch of a tree, bar for carrying; figuratively, chief of a city; especially (with prepositional prefix) as an adverb, apart, only, besides: alone, apart, bar, besides, branch, by self, of each alike, except, only, part, staff, strength.
perhaps from בָּדַד (in the sense of divided fibres); flaxen thread or yarn; hence, a linen garment: linen.
from בָּדָא; a brag or lie; also a liar: liar, lie.
a primitive root; (figuratively) to invent: devise, feign.
a primitive root; to divide, i.e. (reflex.) be solitary: alone.
from בָּדַד; separate; adverb, separately: alone, desolate, only, solitary.
from בָּדַד; separation; Bedad, an Edomite: Bedad.
probably a shortened form עֹבַדְיָה; servant of Jehovah; Bedejah, an Israelite: Bedeiah.
from בָּדַל; alloy (because removed by smelting); by analogy, tin: + plummet, tin.

a primitive root; to divide (in variation senses literally or figuratively, separate, distinguish, differ, select, etc.)(make, put) difference, divide (asunder), (make) separate (self, -ation), sever (out), X utterly.
from בָּדַל; a part: piece.
probably from בָּדַל; something in pieces, i.e. bdellium, a (fragrant) gum (perhaps amber); others a pearl: bdellium.
probably shortened for עַבְדּוֹן; servile; Bedan, the name of two Israelites: Bedan.
a primitive root; to gap open; used only as a denominative from בֶּ֫דֶק; to mend a breach: repair.
from בָּדַק; a gap or leak (in a building or a ship): breach, + calker.
probably from דָּקַר with a prepositional prefix; by stabbing, i.e. assassin; Bidkar, an Israelite: Bidkar.
(Aramaic) corresponding (by transposition) to פָּרַד; to scatter: scatter.
from an unused root (meaning to be empty); a vacuity, i.e. (superficially) an undistinguishable ruin: emptiness, void.
from an unused root (probably meaning to glisten); white marble or perhaps alabaster: red (marble).
(Aramaic) from בְּהַל; a hurry; only adverb, hastily: in haste.
from an unused root (meaning to be bright); shining: bright.

a primitive root; to tremble inwardly (or palpitate), i.e. (figuratively) be (causative, make) (suddenly) alarmed or agitated; by implication to hasten anxiously: be (make) affrighted (afraid, amazed, dismayed, rash), (be, get, make) haste(-n, -y, -ily), (give) speedy(-ily), thrust out, trouble, vex.
(Aramaic) corresponding to בָּהַל; to terrify, hasten: in haste, trouble.
from בָּהַל; panic, destruction: terror, trouble.
from an unused root (probably meaning to be mute); properly, a dumb beast; especially any large quadruped or animal (often collective): beast, cattle.
in form a plural of בְּהֵמָה, but really a singular of Egyptian derivation; a water-ox, i.e. the hippopotamus or Nile- horse: Behemoth.
from an unused root apparently meaning to be thick; the thumb of the hand or great toe of the foot: thumb, great toe.
an orthographical variation of בֹּ֫הֶן; thumb, Bohan, an Israelite: Bohan.
from an unused root meaning to be pale; white scurf: freckled spot.
feminine active participle of the same as בָּהִיר; a whitish spot on the skin: bright spot.

a primitive root; to go or come (in a wide variety of applications): abide, apply, attain, X be, befall, + besiege, bring (forth, in, into, to pass), call, carry, X certainly, (cause, let, thing for) to come (against, in, out, upon, to pass), depart, X doubtless again, + eat, + employ, (cause to) enter (in, into, -tering, -trance, -try), be fallen, fetch, + follow, get, give, go (down, in, to war), grant, + have, X indeed, (in-)vade, lead, lift (up), mention, pull in, put, resort, run (down), send, set, X (well) stricken (in age), X surely, take (in), way.
a primitive root; to disrespect: contemn, despise, X utterly.
from בּוּז; disrespect: contempt(-uously), despised, shamed.
the same as בּוּז; Buz, the name of a son of Nahor, and of an Israelite: Buz.
feminine passive participle of בּוּז; something scorned; an object of contempt: despised.
patronymic from בּוּז; a Buzite or descendant of Buz: Buzite.
the same as בּוּזִי; Buzi, an Israelite: Buzi.
probably of Persian origin; Bavvai, an Israelite: Bavai.
a primitive root; to involve (literally or figuratively): be entangled, (perplexed).
for יְבוּל; produce (of the earth, etc.): food, stock.
the same as בוּל (in the sense of rain); Bul, the eighth Hebrew month: Bul.
from בִּין; discretion; Bunah, an Israelite: Bunah.
a primitive root; to trample (literally or figuratively): loath, tread (down, under (foot)), be polluted.
from an unused root (of the same form) meaning to bleach, i.e. (intransitive) be white; probably cotton (of some sort): fine (white) linen.
from the same as בּוּץ; shining; Botsets, a rock near Michmash: Bozez.
feminine passive participle of an unused root (meaning to be hollow); emptiness (as adjective): empty.
properly, active participle from בָּקַר as denominative from בָּקָר; a cattle-tender: herdman.
a primitive root; to bore, i.e. (figuratively) examine: declare.
from בּוּר (in the sense of בֹּארוֹת); a pit hole (especially one used as a cistern or a prison): cistern, dungeon, fountain, pit, well.

a primitive root; properly, to pale, i.e. by implication to be ashamed; also (by implication) to be disappointed or delayed: (be, make, bring to, cause, put to, with, a-)shamed(-d), be (put to) confounded(-fusion), become dry, delay, be long.
feminine participle passive of בּוּשׁ; shame: shame.
(Aramaic) apparent denominative from בַּיְתָא; to lodge over night: pass the night.
from בָּזַז; plunder: booty, prey, spoil(-ed).
a primitive root; probably to cleave: spoil.
a primitive root; to disesteem: despise, disdain, contemn(-ptible), + think to scorn, vile person.
from בָּזָה; scorned: despise.
feminine of בָּז; booty: prey, spoil.
a primitive root; to plunder: catch, gather, (take) for a prey, rob(-ber), spoil, take (away, spoil), X utterly.
from בָּזָה: disesteem:--contempt.
from בָּזָה and יָהּ; contempts of Jah; Bizjothjah, a place in Palestine: Bizjothjah.
from an unused root meaning to lighten; a flash of lightning: flash of lightning.
from בָּזָק; lightning; Bezek, a place in Palestine: Bezek.
a primitive root; to disperse: scatter.
of Persian origin; Biztha, a eunuch of Xerxes: Biztha.
from בָּחַן; an assayer or metals: tower.
or bachur; participle passive of בָּחַר; properly, selected, i.e. a youth (often collective): (choice) young (man), chosen, X hole.
another form of בַּ֫חַן; a watch-tower of besiegers: tower.
from בָּחַר; select: choose, chosen one, elect.
a primitive root; to loathe: abhor, get hastily (from the margin for bahal).
a primitive root; to test (especially metals); generally and figuratively, to investigate: examine, prove, tempt, try (trial).
from בָּחַן (in the sense of keeping a look-out); a watch-tower: tower.
from בָּחַן; trial: tried.
a primitive root; properly, to try, i.e. (by implication) select: acceptable, appoint, choose (choice), excellent, join, be rather, require.
patrial from בַּחוּרִים (by transposition); a Bacharumite or inhabitant of Bachurim: Baharumite.
or bchuwrowth; feminine plural of בָּחוּר; also (masculine plural) bchuriym; youth (collectively and abstractly): young men, youth.
or Bachuwriym; masculine plural of בָּחוּר; young men; Bachurim, a place in Palestine: Bahurim.
or batah; a primitive root; to babble; hence, to vociferate angrily: pronounce, speak (unadvisedly).

a primitive root; properly, to hie for refuge (but not so precipitately as חָסָה); figuratively, to trust, be confident or sure: be bold (confident, secure, sure), careless (one, woman), put confidence, (make to) hope, (put, make to) trust.

from בָּטַח; properly, a place of refuge; abstract, safety, both the fact (security) and the feeling (trust); often (adverb with or without preposition) safely: assurance, boldly, (without) care(- less), confidence, hope, safe(-ly, -ty), secure, surely.
the same as בֶּ֫טַח; Betach, a place in Syria: Betah.
feminine of בֶּ֫טַח; trust: confidence.
from בָּטַח; trust: confidence, hope.
feminine plural from בָּטַח; security: secure.
a primitive root; to desist from labor: cease.
(Aramaic) corresponding to בָּטֵל; to stop: (cause, make to), cease, hinder.
from an unused root probably meaning to be hollow; the belly, especially the womb; also the bosom or body of anythingbelly, body, + as they be born, + within, womb.
the same as בָּ֫טֶן; Beten. a place in Palestine: Beten.
from בָּ֫טֶן; (only in plural) a pistachio-nut (from its form): nut.
probably plural from בָּטְנִים; hollows: Betonim, a place in Palestine: Betonim.
perhaps from בָּעָה (in the sense of asking); properly, a request; used only adverbially (always with "my Lord"); Oh that!; with leave, or if it please: alas, O, oh.

a primitive root; to separate mentally (or distinguish), i.e.(generally) understand: attend, consider, be cunning, diligently, direct, discern, eloquent, feel, inform, instruct, have intelligence, know, look well to, mark, perceive, be prudent, regard, (can) skill(-full), teach, think, (cause, make to, get, give, have) understand(-ing), view, (deal) wise(-ly, man).

(sometimes in the plural masculine or feminine); properly, the constructive form of an otherwise unused noun from בִּין; a distinction; but used only as a prep, between (repeated before each noun, often with other particles); also as a conjunction, either...or: among, asunder, at, between (-twixt...and), + from (the widest), X in, out of, whether (it be...or), within.
(Aramaic) corresponding to בֵּין: among, between.
from בִּין; understanding: knowledge, meaning, X perfectly, understanding, wisdom.
(Aramaic) corresponding to בִּינָה: knowledge.
from the same as בּוּץ; an egg (from its whiteness): egg.
(Aramaic) corresponding to בִּירָה; a palace: palace.
of foreign origin; a castle or palace: palace.
from בִּירָה; a fortress: castle.

probably from בָּנָה abbreviated; a house (in the greatest variation of applications, especially family, etc.): court, daughter, door, + dungeon, family, + forth of, X great as would contain, hangings, home(born), (winter)house(-hold), inside(-ward), palace, place, + prison, + steward, + tablet, temple, web, + within(-out).
(Aramaic) corresponding to בָּ֫יִת: house.
the same as בָּ֫יִת; Bajith, a place in Palestine: Bajith.
from בָּ֫יִת and אָ֫וֶן; house of vanity; Beth- Aven, a place in Palestine: Beth-aven.
from בָּ֫יִת and אֵל; house of God; Beth-El, a place in Palestine: Beth-el.
from בָּ֫יִת and אָ֫רֶב and אֵל; house of God's ambush; Beth-Arbel, a place in Palestine: Beth-Arbel.

from בָּ֫יִת and בַּ֫עַל and מָעוֹן; house of Baal of (the) habitation of (apparently by transposition); or (shorter) Beyth M own; house of habitation of (Baal); Beth- Baal-Meon, a place in Palestine: Beth-baal-meon. Compare בַּ֫עַל מְעוֹן and בְּעֹן.
from בָּ֫יִת and בָּרָא; house of a creative one; Beth-Biri, a place in Palestine: Beth-birei.
probably from בָּ֫יִת and עֲבָרָה; house of (the) ford; Beth-Barah, a place in Palestine: Beth-barah.
from בָּ֫יִת and גָּדֵר; house of (the) wall; Beth-Gader, a place in Palestine: Beth-gader.
from בָּ֫יִת and the passive participle of גְּמוּל; house of (the) weaned; Beth-Gamul, a place East of the Jordan: Beth- gamul.
from בָּ֫יִת and the dual of דְּבֵלִים; house of (the) two figcakes; Beth-Diblathajim, a place East of the Jordan: Beth-diblathaim.
from בָּ֫יִת and דָּגוֹן; house of Dagon; Beth-Dagon, the name of two places in Palestine: Beth-dagon.
patrial from בֵּית־אֵל with the article interposed; a Beth-elite, or inhabitant of Bethel: Bethelite.
from בָּ֫יִת and אֵ֫צֶל with the article interposed; house of the side; Beth-ha-Etsel, a place in Palestine: Beth- ezel.
from בָּ֫יִת and הַגִּלְגָּל with the article interposed; house of Gilgal (or rolling); Beth-hag-Gilgal, a place in Palestine: Beth-gilgal.
from בָּ֫יִת and the plural of יַשִּׁ֫ימָ֫וֶת with the article interposed; house of the deserts; Beth-ha- Jeshimoth, a town East of the Jordan: Beth-jeshimoth.
from בָּ֫יִת and כָּ֫רֶם with the article interposed; house of the vineyard; Beth-hak-Kerem, a place in Palestine: Beth-haccerem.
patrial from בֵּית לָ֫חֶם with the article inserted; a Beth-lechemite, or native of Bethlechem: Bethlehemite.
from בָּ֫יִת and מֶרְחָק with the article interposed; house of the breadth; Beth-ham-Merchak, a place in Palestine: place that was far off.

or (shortened) Beyth Mar-kabowth; from בָּ֫יִת and the plural of מֶרְכָּבָה (with or without the article interposed); place of (the) chariots; Beth-ham-Markaboth or Beth-Markaboth, a place in Palestine: Beth-marcaboth.
from בָּ֫יִת and עֵ֫מֶק with the article interposed; house of the valley; Beth-ha-Emek, a place in Palestine: Beth- emek.
from בָּ֫יִת and עֲרָבָה with the article interposed; house of the Desert; Beth-ha-Arabah, a place in Palestine: Beth-arabah.
from בָּ֫יִת and רוּם with the article interposed; house of the height; Beth-ha-Ram, a place East of the Jordan: Beth-aram.
probably for בֵּית הָרָם; Beth-ha-Ram, a place East of the Jordan: Beth-haran.
from בָּ֫יִת and שִׁטִּים with the article interposed; house of the acacia; Beth-hash-Shittah, a place in Palestine: Beth-shittah.
patrial from בֵּית שָׁ֫מֶשׁ with the article inserted; a Beth-shimshite, or inhabitant of Bethshemesh: Bethshemite.
from בָּ֫יִת and the same as חָגְלָה; house of a partridge; Beth-Choglah, a place in Palestine: Beth-hoglah.
from בָּ֫יִת and חֹר; house of hollowness; Beth-Choron, the name of two adjoining places in Palestine: Beth- horon.
from בָּ֫יִת and כָּר; house of pasture; Beth-Car, a place in Palestine: Beth-car.
from בָּ֫יִת and the plural of לָבִיא; house of lionesses; Beth-Lebaoth, a place in Palestine: Beth-lebaoth. Compare לְבָאוֹת.
from בָּ֫יִת and לָ֫חֶם; house of bread; Beth- Lechem, a place in Palestine: Beth-lehem.
from בָּ֫יִת and the feminine of עָפָר (with preposition interposed); house to (i.e. of) dust; Beth-le-Aphrah, a place in Palestine: house of Aphrah.
or Beyth Mil-loh; from בָּ֫יִת and מִלּוֹא; house of (the) rampart; Beth-Millo, the name of two citadelshouse of Millo.
from בָּ֫יִת and מַעֲכָה; house of Maakah; Beth-Maakah, a place in Palestine: Beth-maachah.
from בָּ֫יִת and the feminine of נָמֵר; house of (the) leopard; Beth-Nimrah, a place east of the Jordan: Beth-Nimrah. Compare נִמְרָה.
from בָּ֫יִת and עֲדָנִים; house of pleasure; Beth-Eden, a place in Syria: Beth-eden.
from בָּ֫יִת and עַזְמָ֫וֶת; house of Azmaveth, a place in Palestine: Beth-az-maveth. Compare עַזְמָ֫וֶת.
from בָּ֫יִת and a plural from עָנָה; house of replies; Beth-Anoth, a place in Palestine: Beth-anoth.
an orthographical variation for בֵּית עֲנוֹת; Beth-Anath, a place in Palestine: Beth-anath.
from בָּ֫יִת and a derivative of עָקַד; house of (the) binding (for sheep-shearing); Beth-Eked, a place in Palestineshearing house.
:  : from בָּ֫יִת and עַשְׁתָּרוֹת; house of Ashtoreths; Beth-Ashtaroth, a place in Palestine: house of Ashtaroth. Compare בְּעֶשְׁתְּרָה, עַשְׁתָּרוֹת.
from בָּ֫יִת and פָּלִיט; house of escape; Beth- Palet, a place in Palestine: Beth-palet.
from בָּ֫יִת and פְּעוֹר; house of Peor; Beth- Peor, a place East of the Jordan: Beth-peor.
from בָּ֫יִת and a derivative from פּוּץ; house of dispersion; Beth-Patstsets, a place in Palestine: Beth-pazzez.
from בָּ֫יִת and צוּר; house of (the) rock; Beth-Tsur, a place in Palestine: Beth-zur.
from בָּ֫יִת and רְחוֹב; house of (the) street; Beth-Rechob, a place in Palestine: Beth-rehob.
from בָּ֫יִת and רָפָא; house of (the) giant; Beth-Rapha, an Israelite: Beth-rapha.
or Beyth Shan; from בָּ֫יִת and שָׁאַן; house of ease; Beth-Shean or Beth-Shan, a place in Palestine: Beth- shean, Beth-Shan.
from בָּ֫יִת and שָׁ֫מֶשׁ; house of (the) sun; Beth-Shemesh, a place in Palestine: Beth-shemesh.
from בָּ֫יִת and תַּפּ֫וּחַ; house of (the) apple; Beth-Tappuach, a place in Palestine: Beth-tappuah.
probably from בָּ֫יִת; a palace (i.e. large house): palace.
from בָּכָה, weeping; Baca, a valley in Palestine: Baca.
the same as הַבָּכָא; the weeping tree (some gum- distilling tree, perhaps the balsam): mulberry tree.
a primitive root; to weep; generally to bemoan: X at all, bewail, complain, make lamentation, X more, mourn, X sore, X with tears, weep.
from בָּכָה; a weeping: X sore.
from בָּכַר; firstborn; hence, chief: eldest (son), firstborn(-ling).
from בָּכַר; the first-fruits of the crop: first fruit (-ripe (figuratively)), hasty fruit.
or (short) bkorah; feminine of בְּכוֹר; the firstling of man or beast; abstractly primogeniture: birthright, firstborn(-ling).
feminine of בִּכּוּרִים; the early fig: firstripe (fruit).
feminine of בְּכֹרָה; primogeniture; Bekorath, an Israelite: Bechorath.
from בָּכָה; a weeping; by analogy, a dripping: overflowing, X sore, (continual) weeping, wept.
plural active participle of בָּכָה; (with the article) the weepers; Bo-kim, a place in Palestine: Bochim.
feminine from בָּכַר; the eldest daughter: firstborn.
from בָּכָה; a weeping: mourning.

a primitive root; properly, to burst the womb, i.e. (causatively) bear or make early fruit (of woman or tree); also (as denominative from בִּכּוּרִים) to give the birthright: make firstborn, be firstling, bring forth first child (new fruit).
from בָּכַר (in the sense of youth); a young cameldromedary.
the same as בִּכְרֵי; Beker, the name of two IsraelitesBecher.
feminine of בִּכְרֵי; a young she-camel: dromedary.
by orthographical variation for בִּכּוּרָה; a first- ripe fig: firstripe.
from בָּכַר; first-born; Bokeru, an Israelite: Bocheru.
from בָּכַר; youth-ful; Bikri, an Israelite: Bichri.
patronymically from בָּ֫כֶר; a Bakrite (collectively) or descendants of Beker: Bachrites.
from בָּלָה; properly, a failure; by implication nothing; usually (adverb) not at all; also lest: lest, neither, no, none (that...), not (any), nothing.
by contraction for בַּ֫עַל; Bel, the Baal of the BabyloniansBel.
(Aramaic) from בְּלָא; properly, anxiety, i.e. (by implication) the heart (as its seat): heart.
(Aramaic) corresponding to בָּלָה (but used only in a mental sense); to afflict: wear out.
from בֵּל and אָדוֹן (contracted); Bel (is his) lord; Baladan, the name of a Babylonian prince: Baladan.
a primitive root; to break off or loose (in a favorable or unfavorable sense), i.e. desist (from grief) or invade (with destruction): comfort, (recover) strength(-en).
from בָּלַג; desistance; Bilgah, the name of two Israelites: Bilgah.
from בָּלַג; desistant; Bilgai, an Israelite: Bilgai.
of uncertain derivation; Bildad, one of Job's friends: Bildad.
a primitive root; to fail; by implication to wear out, decay (causatively, consume, spend): consume, enjoy long, become (make, wax) old, spend, waste.
from בָּלָה; worn out: old.
feminine of בָּלִים; failure; Balah, a place in Palestine: Balah.
a primitive root (rather by transposition for בָּהַל); to palpitate; hence, (causatively) to terrify: trouble.
from בָּלַהּ; timid; Bilhah, the name of one of Jacob's concubines; also of a place in Palestine: Bilhah.
from בָּלַהּ; alarm; hence, destruction: terror, trouble.
from בָּלַהּ; timid; Bilhan, the name of an Edomite and of an Israelite: Bilhan.
(Aramaic) from a root corresponding to בָּלָה; excise (on articles consumed): tribute.
or (fully) blowy; from בָּלָה; (only in plural construction) rags: old.
of foreign derivation; Belteshatstsar, the Babylonian name of Daniel: Belteshazzar.
(Aramaic) corresponding to בֵּלְטְשַׁאצַּר: Belteshazzar.

from בָּלָה; properly, failure, i.e. nothing or destruction; usually (with preposition) without, not yet, because not, as long as, etc.: corruption, ig(norantly), for lack of, where no...is, so that no, none, not, un(awares), without.
from בָּלַל; mixed, i.e. (specifically) feed (for cattle): corn, fodder, provender.
from בְּלִי and מָה; (as indef.) nothing whatever: nothing.
from בְּלִי and יָעַל; without profit, worthlessness; by extension, destruction, wickedness (often in connection with אּישׁ, נָשִׁים, בֵּן, etc.): Belial, evil, naughty, ungodly (men), wicked.
a primitive root; to overflow (specifically with oil.); by implication, to mix; also (denominatively from בְּלִיל) to fodder: anoint, confound, X fade, mingle, mix (self), give provender, temper.
a primitive root; to muzzle: be held in.
a primitive root; to pinch sycamore figs (a process necessary to ripen them): gatherer.
a primitive root; to make away with (specifically by swallowing); generally, to destroy: cover, destroy, devour, eat up, be at end, spend up, swallow down (up).
from בָּלַע; a gulp; figuratively, destruction: devouring, that which he hath swallowed up.
the same as בֶּ֫לַע; Bela, the name of a place, also of an Edomite and of two Israelites: Bela.
or balmadey; constructive plural from בַּל and עַד, not till, i.e. (as preposition or adverb) except, without, besides: beside, not (in), save, without.
patronymically from בָּ֫לַע: a Belaite (collectively) or descendants of Bela: Belaites.
probably from בַּל and עָם; not (of the) people, i.e. foreigner; Bilam, a Mesopotamian prophet; also a place in Palestine: Balaam, Bileam.
a primitive root; to annihilate: (make) waste.
from בָּלַק; waster; Balak, a Moabitish king: Balak.
or Belshatstsar; of foreign origin (compare בֵּלְטְשַׁאצַּר); Belshatstsar, a Babylonian king: Belshazzar.
(Aramaic) corresponding to בֵּלְשַׁאצַּר: Belshazzar.
of uncertain derivation; Bilshan, an Israelite: Bilshan.

constructive feminine of בָּלָה (equivalent to בְּלִי); properly, a failure of, i.e. (used only as a negative particle, usually with a prepositional prefix) not, except, without, unless, besides, because not, until, etc.: because un(satiable), beside, but, + continual, except, from, lest, neither, no more, none, not, nothing, save, that no, without.
from an unused root (meaning to be high); an elevation: height, high place, wave.
the same as בָּמָה; Bamah, a place in Palestine: Bamah. See also בָּמוֹת.
probably from מָהַל with prepositional prefix; with pruning; Bimhal, an Israelite: Bimhal.
prolongation for prepositional prefix; in, with, by, etc.: for, in into, through.
plural of בָּמָה; heights; or (fully) Bamowth Bahal; from the same and בַּ֫עַל; heights of Baal; Bamoth or Bamoth-Baal, a place East of the Jordan: Bamoth, Bamoth-baal.

from בָּנָה; a son (as a builder of the family name), in the widest sense (of literal and figurative relationship, including grandson, subject, nation, quality or condition, etc., (like אָב, אָח, etc.)): + afflicted, age, (Ahoh-) (Ammon-) (Hachmon-) (Lev-)ite, (anoint-)ed one, appointed to, (+) arrow, (Assyr-) (Babylon-) (Egypt-) (Grec-)ian, one born, bough, branch, breed, + (young) bullock, + (young) calf, X came up in, child, colt, X common, X corn, daughter, X of first, + firstborn, foal, + very fruitful, + postage, X in, + kid, + lamb, (+) man, meet, + mighty, + nephew, old, (+) people, + rebel, + robber, X servant born, X soldier, son, + spark, + steward, + stranger, X surely, them of, + tumultuous one, + valiant(-est), whelp, worthy, young (one), youth.
the same as בֵּן; Ben, an Israelite: Ben.
(Aramaic) corresponding to בֵּן: child, son, young.
(Aramaic) or bnah (Aramaic); corresponding to בָּנָה; to build: build, make.
from בֵּן and אֲבִימֶ֫לֶך; (the) son of Abinadab; Ben-Abinadab, an Israelite: the son of Abinadab.
from בֵּן and אָ֫וֶן; son of my sorrow; Ben-Oni, the original name of Benjamin: Ben-oni.
from בֵּן and גָּ֫בֶר; son of (the) hero; Ben- Geber, an Israelite: the son of Geber.
from בֵּן and a derivative of דָּקַר; son of piercing (or of a lance); Ben-Deker, an Israelite: the son of Dekar.
a primitive root; to build (literally and figuratively): (begin to) build(-er), obtain children, make, repair, set (up), X surely.
from בֵּן and הֲדָד; son of Hadad; Ben-Hadad, the name of several Syrian kings: Ben-hadad.
from בָּנָה; built up; Binnui, an Israelite: Binnui.
from בֵּן and זוֹחֵת; son of Zocheth; Ben- Zocheth, an Israelite: Ben-zoketh.
from בֵּן and חוּר; son of Chur; Ben-Chur, an Israelite: the son of Hur.
from בֵּן and חָ֫יִל; son of might; Ben-Chail, an Israelite: Ben-hail.
from בֵּן and חָנָן; son of Chanan; Ben- Chanan, an Israelite: Ben-hanan.
from בֵּן and חָ֫סֶד; son of kindness; Ben- Chesed, an Israelite: the son of Hesed.
from בָּנָה; built; Bani, the name of five Israelites: Bani.
or (fuller) Buwniy; from בָּנָה; built; Bunni or Buni, an Israelite: Bunni.
from the plural construction of בֵּן and בָּרָק; sons of lightning, Bene-berak, a place in Palestine: Bene-barak.
feminine from בָּנָה; a structure: building.
or (prolonged) Bnayahuw; from בָּנָה and יָהּ; Jah has built; Benajah, the name of twelve IsraelitesBenaiah.
from the plural of בֵּן and יַעֲקָן; sons of Yaakan; Bene-Jaakan, a place in the Desert: Bene-jaakan.
dual of בֵּין; a double interval, i.e. the space between two armies: + champion.
from בֵּן and יָמִין; son of (the) right hand; Binjamin, youngest son of Jacob; also the tribe descended from him, and its territory: Benjamin.

sometimes (with the article inserted) Ben-ha-yminiy; with אּישׁ inserted (1 Sam. 9:1) Ben-miysh Ymiyniy; son of a man of Jemini; or shortened (1 Sam. 9:4; Esth. 2:5) Iysh Ymiyniy; a man of Jemini, or (1 Sam. 20:1) simply Yminiy; a Jeminite; (plural Bniy Ymiyniy; patron from בִּנְיָמִן; a Benjaminite, or descendent of Benjamin: Benjamite, of Benjamin.
from בָּנָה; an edifice: building.
(Aramaic) corresponding to בִּנְיָן: building.
probably from בֵּן with pron. suff.; our son; Beninu, an Israelite: Beninu.
(Aramaic) of uncertain affinity; to be enraged: be angry.
or Bincah; of uncertain derivation; Bina or Binah, an Israelite: Binea, Bineah.
from בֵּן and עָם with pronomial suffix; son of my people; Ben-Ammi, a son of Lot: Ben-ammi.
from סוֹד and יָהּ with prepositional prefix; in (the) counsel of Jehovah; Besodejah, an Israelite: Besodeiah.
from בּוּס; domineering; Besai, one of the Nethinim: Besai.
from an unused root meaning to be sour; an immature grape: unripe grape.
from the same as בֵּ֫סֶר: sour grape.
(Aramaic) or b ah (Aramaic); corresponding to בָּעָה; to seek or ask: ask, desire, make (petition), pray, request, seek.
from עַד with prepositional prefix; in up to or over against; generally at, beside, among, behind, for, etc.: about, at by (means of), for, over, through, up (-on), within.
a primitive root; to gush over, i.e. to swell; (figuratively) to desire earnestly; by implication to ask: cause, inquire, seek up, swell out.
(Aramaic) from בְּעָא; a request: petition.
from בָּעַר (in the sense of burning); a lamp; Beor, the name of the father of an Edomitish king; also of that of Balaam: Beor.
masculine plural from בָּעַת; alarms: terrors.
from an unused root of uncertain meaning; Boaz, the ancestor of David; also the name of a pillar in front of the temple: Boaz.
a primitive root; to trample down, i.e. (figuratively) despise: kick.
from בָּעָה; a prayer: grave.
from בָּעַר (in the sense of eating): cattle: beast, cattle.
a primitive root; to be master; hence, (as denominative from בַּ֫עַל) to marry: have dominion (over), be husband, marry(-ried, X wife).

from בָּעַל; a master; hence, a husband, or (figuratively) owner (often used with another noun in modifications of this latter sense): + archer, + babbler, + bird, captain, chief man, + confederate, + have to do, + dreamer, those to whom it is due, + furious, those that are given to it, great, + hairy, he that hath it, have, + horseman, husband, lord, man, + married, master, person, + sworn, they of.
the same as בַּ֫עַל; Baal, a Phoenician deity: Baal, (plural) Baalim.
(Aramaic) corresponding to בַּ֫עַל: + chancellor.
from בַּ֫עַל and בְּרִית; Baal of (the) covenant; Baal-Berith, a special deity of the Shechemites: Baal-berith.
from בַּ֫עַל and גָּד; Baal of Fortune; Baal-Gad, a place in Syria: Baal-gad.
feminine of בַּ֫עַל; a mistress: that hath, mistress.
the same as בַּעֲלַת; Baalah, the name of three places in Palestine: Baalah.
from בַּ֫עַל and הָמוֹן; possessor of a multitude; Baal-Hamon, a place in Palestine: Baal-hamon.
plural of בַּעֲלַת; mistresses; Bealoth, a place in Palestine: Bealoth, in Aloth (by mistake for a plural from `alah with prepositional prefix).
from בַּ֫עַל and זְבוּב; Baal of (the) Fly; Baal-Zebub, a special deity of the Ekronites: Baal-zebub.
from בַּ֫עַל and חָנַן; possessor of grace; Baal-Chanan, the name of an Edomite, also of an Israelite: Baal-hanan.
from בַּ֫עַל and a modification of חָצֵר; possessor of a village; Baal-Chatsor, a place in Palestine: Baal-hazor.
from בַּ֫עַל and חֶרְמוֹן; possessor of Hermon; Baal-Chermon, a place in Palestine: Baal-hermon.
from בַּ֫עַל with pron. suff.; my master; Baali, a symbolical name for Jehovah: Baali.
from the plural of בַּ֫עַל and the plural of בָּמָה; Baals of (the) heights; Baale-Bamoth, a place East of the Jordan: lords of the high places.
from בַּ֫עַל and יָדַע; Baal has known; Beeljada, an Israelite: Beeliada.
from בַּ֫עַל and יָהּ; Jah (is) master; Bealjah, an Israelite: Bealiah.
from the plural of בַּ֫עַל and יְהוּדָה; masters of Judah; Baale-Jehudah, a place in Palestine: Baale of Judah.
probably from a derivative of עָלַס with prepositional prefix; in exultation; Baalis, an Ammonitish king: Baalis.
from בַּ֫עַל and מָעוֹן; Baal of (the) habitation (of) (compare בֵּית בַּ֫עַל מְעוֹן); Baal-Meon, a place East of the Jordan: Baal-meon.
from בַּ֫עַל and פְּעוֹר; Baal of Peor; Baal-Peor, a Moabitish deity: Baal-peor.
from בַּ֫עַל and the plural of פָּ֫רֶץ; possessor of breaches; Baal-Peratsim, a place in Palestine: Baal- perazim.
from בַּ֫עַל and צָפוֹן (in the sense of cold) (according to others an Egyptian form of Typhon, the destroyer); Baal of winter; Baal-Tsephon, a place in Eqypt: Baal-zephon.
from בַּ֫עַל and שָׁלִ֫שָׁה; Baal of Shalishah, Baal-Shalishah, a place in Palestine: Baal-shalisha.
a modification of בַּעֲלַת; mistressship; Baalath, a place in Palestine: Baalath.
from בַּעֲלַת and בְּאֵר; mistress of a well; Baalath-Beer, a place in Palestine: Baalath-beer.
from בַּ֫עַל and תָּמָר; possessor of (the) palm-tree; Baal-Tamar, a place in Palestine: Baal-tamar.
probably a contraction of בֵּית בַּ֫עַל מְעוֹן; Beon, a place East of the Jordan: Beon.
the same as בַּעֲנָה; Banana, the name of four Israelite: Baana, Baanah.
from a derivative of עָנָה with prepositional prefix; in affliction: Baanah, the name of four Israelites:--Baanah.

a primitive root; to kindle, i.e. consume (by fire or by eating); also (as denominative from בָּ֫עַר) to be(-come) brutish: be brutish, bring (put, take) away, burn, (cause to) eat (up), feed, heat, kindle, set ((on fire)), waste.
from בָּעַר; properly, foot (as consumed); i.e. (by exten.) of cattle brutishness; (concretely) stupid: brutish (person), foolish.
from בָּ֫עַר; brutish: Baara, an Israelitish woman: Baara.
from בָּעַר; a burning: fire.
from an unused root meaning to stink; offensiveness; Basha, a king of Israel: Baasha.
from עָשָׂה and יָהּ with a prepositional prefix; in (the) work of Jah; Baasejah, an Israelite: Baaseiah.
from עַשְׁתְּרוֹת (as singular of עַשְׁתָּרוֹת) with a prepositional prefix; with Ashtoreth; Beeshterah, a place East of the Jordan: Beeshterah.
a primitive root; to fear: affright, be (make) afraid, terrify, trouble.
from בָּעַת; fear: trouble.
probably the same as בּוּץ; mud (as whitish clay): mire.
intensive from בֹּץ; a swamp: fen, mire(-ry place).
from בָּצַר; inaccessible, i.e. lofty: vintage (by confusion with batsiyr).
perhaps the same as בֵּסָי; Betsai, the name of two Israelites: Bezai.
from בָּצַר; clipped, i.e. the grape crop: vintage.
from an unused root apparently meaning to peel; an onion: onion.
probably from צֵל and אֵל with a prepositional prefix; in (the) shadow (i.e. protection) of God; Betsalel, the name of two Israelites: Bezaleel.
or Batsliyth; from the same as בְּצָלִים; a peeling; Batsluth or Batslith, an Israelite: Bazlith, Bazluth.

a primitive root to break off, i.e. (usually) plunder; figuratively, to finish, or (intransitively) stop: (be) covet(- ous), cut (off), finish, fulfill, gain (greedily), get, be given to (covetousness), greedy, perform, be wounded.
from בָּצַע; plunder; by extension, gain (usually unjust): covetousness, (dishonest) gain, lucre, profit.
a primitive root; perhaps to swell up, i.e. blister: swell.
from בָּצֵק; dough (as swelling by fermentation): dough, flour.
from בָּצֵק; a swell of ground; Botscath, a place in Palestine: Bozcath, Boskath.

a primitive root; to clip off; specifically (as denominative from בָּצִיר) to gather grapes; also to be isolated (i.e. inaccessible by height or fortification): cut off, (de-)fenced, fortify, (grape) gather(-er), mighty things, restrain, strong, wall (up), withhold.
from בָּצַר; strictly a clipping, i.e. gold (as dug out): gold defence.
the same as בָּ֫צֶר, an inaccessible spot; Betser, a place in Palestine; also an Israelite: Bezer.
another form for בָּ֫צֶר; gold: gold.
feminine from בָּצַר; an enclosure, i.e. sheep fold: Bozrah.
the same as בָּצְרָה; Botsrah, a place in Edom: Bozrah.
masculine intensive from בָּצַר; a fortress: stronghold.
feminine intensive from בָּצַר; restraint (of rain), i.e. drought: dearth, drought.
the same as בַּקְבֻּק; Bakbuk, one of the Nethinim: Bakbuk.
from בָּקַק; a bottle (from the gurgling in emptying): bottle, cruse.
from בַּקְבֻּק and יָהּ; emptying (i.e. wasting) of Jah; Bakbukjah, an Israelite: Bakbukiah.
reduplicated from בָּקַר; searcher; Bakbakkar, an Israelite: Bakbakkar.
from בָּקַק; wasteful; Bukki, the name of two Israelites: Bukki.
from בָּקַק and יָהּ; wasting of Jah; Bukkijah, an Israelite: Bukkiah.
from בָּקַע; a fissure: breach, cleft.

a primitive root; to cleave; generally, to rend, break, rip or open: make a breach, break forth (into, out, in pieces, through, up), be ready to burst, cleave (asunder), cut out, divide, hatch, rend (asunder), rip up, tear, win.
from בָּקַע; a section (half) of a shekel, i.e. a beka (a weight and a coin): bekah, half a shekel.
(Aramaic) corresponding to בִּקְעָה: plain.
from בָּקַע; properly, a split, i.e. a wide level valley between mountains: plain, valley.
a primitive root; to pour out, i.e. to empty, figuratively, to depopulate; by analogy, to spread out (as a fruitful vine): (make) empty (out), fail, X utterly, make void.
a primitive root; properly, to plough, or (generally) break forth, i.e. (figuratively) to inspect, admire, care for, consider: (make) inquire (-ry), (make) search, seek out.
(Aramaic) corresponding to בָּקַר: inquire, make search.
from בָּקַר; beef cattle or an animal of the ox family of either gender (as used for plowing); collectively, a herdbeeve, bull (+ -ock), + calf, + cow, great (cattle), + heifer, herd, kine, ox.
from בָּקַר; properly, dawn (as the break of day); generally, morning: (+) day, early, morning, morrow.
intensive from בָּקַר; a looking after: seek out.
from בָּקַר; properly, examination, i.e. (by implication) punishment: scourged.

a primitive root; to search out (by any method, specifically in worship or prayer); by implication, to strive after: ask, beg, beseech, desire, enquire, get, make inquisition, procure, (make) request, require, seek (for).
from בָּקַשׁ; a petition: request.
(Aramaic) corresponding to בֵּן; a son, grandson, etc.: X old, son.
borrowed (as a title) from בַּר; the heir (apparent to the throne): son.
from בָּרַר (in its various senses); beloved; also pure, empty: choice, clean, clear, pure.
or bar; from בָּרַר (in the sense of winnowing); grain of any kind (even while standing in the field); by extens. the open country: corn, wheat.
(Aramaic) corresponding to בָּר; a field: field.
from בָּרַר; purify: cleanness, pureness.
the same as בֹּר; vegetable lye (from its cleansing); used as a soap for washing, or a flux for metals: X never so, purely.
a primitive root; (absolutely) to create; (qualified) to cut down (a wood), select, feed (as formative processes)choose, create (creator), cut down, dispatch, do, make (fat).
a variation of מְרֹאדַךְ בַּלְאָדָן; Berodak-Baladan, a Babylonian king: Berodach-baladan.Birliy.
from בָּרָא and שְׁמוּאֵל; Jah has created; Berajah, an Israelite: Beraiah.
by reduplication from בָּר; a fowl (as fattened on grain): fowl.
a primitive root, to hail: hail.
from בָּרַד; hail -hail ((stones)).
from בָּרַד; hail; Bered, the name of a place south of Palestine, also of an Israelite: Bered.
from בָּרַד; spotted (as if with hail): grisled.
a primitive root; to select; also (as denominative from בָּר) to feed; also (as equivalent to בָּרַר) to render clear (Eccl. 3:18): choose, (cause to) eat, manifest, (give) meat.
passive participle from בָּרַך; blessed; Baruk, the name of three Israelites: Baruch.
probably of foreign origin; damask (stuff of variegated thread): rich apparel.
of uncertain derivation; a cypress (?) tree; hence, a lance or a musical instrument (as made of that wood): fir (tree).
a variation of בְּרוֹשׁ; the cypress (or some elastic tree): fir.
: , from בָּרָה; food: meat.
or Berothay; probably from בְּרוֹתִים; cypress or cypresslike; Berothah or Berothai, a place north of Palestine: Berothah, Berothai.
probably feminine plural from an unused root (apparently mean to pierce); holes; Birzoth, an Israelite: Birzavith (from the marg.).
perhaps from the root of בִּרְזוּת; iron (as cutting); by extension, an iron implement: (ax) head, iron.
from בַּרְזֶל; iron-hearted; Barzillai, the name of three Israelites: Barzillai.
a primitive root; to bolt, i.e. figuratively, to flee suddenly: chase (away); drive away, fain, flee (away), put to flight, make haste, reach, run away, shoot.
by transposition for בַּחֲרוּמִי; a Barchumite, or native of Bachurim: Barhumite.
from בָּרָה; fat: fat.
probably by contraction from בְּאֵרִי; Beri, an Israelite: Beri.
of uncertain derivation; (only in the plural and with the article) the Berites, a place in Palestine: Berites.
from בָּרָא (in the sense of בָּרָה); fatted or plump: fat ((fleshed), -ter), fed, firm, plenteous, rank.
feminine from בָּרָא; a creation, i.e. a novelty: new thing.
feminine from בָּרָה; food: meat.
from בָּרַח; a bolt: bar, fugitive.
or (shortened) bariach; from בָּרַח; a fugitive, i.e. the serpent (as fleeing), and the constellation by that name: crooked, noble, piercing.
the same as בָּרִ֫יחַ; Bariach, an Israelite: Bariah.
apparently from the feminine of רָע with a prepositional prefix; in trouble; Beriah, the name of four IsraelitesBeriah.
patronymically from בְּרִיעָה; a Beriite (collectively) or descendants of Beriah: Beerites.
from בָּרָה (in the sense of cutting (like בָּרָא)); a compact (because made by passing between pieces of flesh): confederacy, (con-)feder(-ate), covenant, league.
the same as בְּרִית; Berith, a Shechemitish deity: Berith.
feminine of בֹּר; vegetable alkali: sope.

a primitive root; to kneel; by implication to bless God (as an act of adoration), and (vice-versa) man (as a benefit); also (by euphemism) to curse (God or the king, as treason): X abundantly, X altogether, X at all, blaspheme, bless, congratulate, curse, X greatly, X indeed, kneel (down), praise, salute, X still, thank.
(Aramaic) corresponding to בָּרַך: bless, kneel.
from בָּרַך; a knee: knee.
(Aramaic) corresponding to בֶּ֫רֶך: knee.
from בָּרַך and אֵל, God has blessed; Barakel, the father of one of Job's friends: Barachel.
from בָּרַך; benediction; by implication prosperity: blessing, liberal, pool, present.
the same as בְּרָכָה; Berakah, the name of an Israelite, and also of a valley in Palestine: Berachah.
from בָּרַך; a reservoir (at which camels kneel as a resting-place): (fish-)pool.
or Berekyahuw; from בֶּ֫רֶך and יָהּ; knee (i.e. blessing) of Jah; Berekjah, the name of six Israelites: Berachiah, Berechiah.
(Aramaic) perhaps from רוּם with a prepositional prefix; properly, highly, i.e. surely; but used adversatively, however: but, nevertheless, yet.
of uncertain derivation; Bera, a Sodomitish king: Bera.
a primitive root; to lighten (lightning): cast forth.
from בָּרַק; lightning; by analogy, a gleam; concretely, a flashing sword: bright, glitter(-ing sword), lightning.
the same as בָּרָק; Barak, an Israelite: Barak.
of uncertain derivation; Barkos, one of the Nethimim: Barkos.
from בָּרָק; a thorn (perhaps as burning brightly): brier.
or barkath; from בָּרָק; a gem (as flashing), perhaps the emerald: carbuncle.
a primitive root; to clarify (i.e. brighten), examine, select: make bright, choice, chosen, cleanse (be clean), clearly, polished, (shew self) pure(-ify), purge (out).
probably from רֶ֫שַׁע with a prepositional prefix; with wickedness; Birsha, a king of Gomorrah: Birsha.
patrial from בֵּרֹתַי; a Berothite, or inhabitant of Berothai: Berothite.
from בָּשַׂר; cheerful; Besor, a stream of Palestine: Besor.
or (shortened) bsorah; feminine from בָּשַׂר; glad tidings; by implication, reward for good news: reward for tidings.
a primitive root; properly, to boil up; hence, to be done in cooking; figuratively to ripen: bake, boil, bring forth, roast, seethe, sod (be sodden).
from בָּשַׁל; boiled: X at all, sodden.
of foreign derivation; Bishlam, a Pers.: Bishlam.
from an unused root meaning to be fragrant; (compare סַמִּים) the balsam plant: spice.
or bosem; from the same as בָּשָׂם; fragrance; by implication, spicery; also the balsam plant: smell, spice, sweet (odour).
feminine of בְּשָׂמִים (the second form); fragrance; Bosmath, the name of a wife of Esau, and of a daughter of SolomonBashemath, Basmath.
of uncertain derivation; Bashan (often with the article), a region East of the Jordan: Bashan.
feminine from בּוּשׁ; shamefulness: shame.
a primitive root; to trample down: tread.

a primitive root; properly, to be fresh, i.e. full (rosy, (figuratively) cheerful); to announce (glad news): messenger, preach, publish, shew forth, (bear, bring, carry, preach, good, tell good) tidings.
from בָּשַׂר; flesh (from its freshness); by extension, body, person; also (by euphem.) the pudenda of a man: body, (fat, lean) flesh(-ed), kin, (man-)kind, + nakedness, self, skin.
(Aramaic) corresponding to בָּשָׂר: flesh.
from בּוּשׁ; shame (the feeling and the condition, as well as its cause); by implication (specifically) an idol: ashamed, confusion, + greatly, (put to) shame(-ful thing).

from בָּנָה (as feminine of בֵּן); a daughter (used in the same wide sense as other terms of relationship, literally and figuratively): apple (of the eye), branch, company, daughter, X first, X old, + owl, town, village.
probably from the same as בַּתּוֹת; a bath or Hebrew measure (as a means of division) of liquids: bath.
(Aramaic) corresponding to בָּת: bath.
probably an orthographical variation for בַּתּוֹת; desolation: waste.
feminine from an unused root (meaning to break in pieces); desolation: desolate.
apparently from the same as בָּתָה and אֵל; destroyed of God; Bethuel, the name of a nephew of Abraham, and of a place in Palestine: Bethuel. Compare בְּתוּל.
for בְּתוּאֵל; Bethul (i.e. Bethuel), a place in Palestine: Bethuel.
feminine passive participle of an unused root meaning to separate; a virgin (from her privacy); sometimes (by continuation) a bride; also (figuratively) a city or state: maid, virgin.
masculine plural of the same as בְּתוּלָה; (collectively and abstractly) virginity; by implication and concretely, the tokens of it: X maid, virginity.
from בַּת and יָהּ; daughter (i.e. worshipper) of Jah; Bithjah, an Egyptian woman: Bithiah.
a primitive root; to cut in pieces: thrust through.
a primitive root, to chop up: divide.
from בָּתַר; a section: part, piece.
the same as בֶּ֫תֶר; Bether, a (craggy) place in Palestine: Bether.
from בַּת and a masculine plural from רָב; the daughter (i.e. city) of Rabbah: Bath-rabbim.
from בָּתַר; (with the article) the craggy spot; Bithron, a place East of the Jordan: Bithron.
from בַּת and שֶׁ֫בַע (in the sense of שָׁבַע); daughter of an oath; Bath-Sheba, the mother of Solomon: Bath- sheba.
from בַּת and שׁ֫וֹעַ; daughter of wealth; Bath-shua, the same as בַּת־שֶׁ֫בַע: Bath-shua.
for גֵּאֶה; haughty: proud.
a primitive root; to mount up; hence, in general, to rise, (figuratively) be majestic: gloriously, grow up, increase, be risen, triumph.
from גָּאָה; lofty; figuratively, arrogant: proud.
feminine from גָּאָה; arrogance: pride.
from גָּאָה and אֵל; majesty of God; Geuel, an Israelite: Geuel.
from גָּאָה; arrogance or majesty; by implication, (concretely) ornament: excellency, haughtiness, highness, pride, proudly, swelling.
from גָּאָה; the same as גַּאֲוָה: arrogancy, excellency(-lent), majesty, pomp, pride, proud, swelling.
from גָּאָה; the same as גַּאֲוָה: excellent things, lifting up, majesty, pride, proudly, raging.
from גָּאָה: haughty: proud.

a primitive root, to redeem (according to the Oriental law of kinship), i.e. to be the next of kin (and as such to buy back a relative's property, marry his widow, etc.): X in any wise, X at all, avenger, deliver, (do, perform the part of near, next) kinsfolk(-man), purchase, ransom, redeem(-er), revenger.
a primitive root, (rather identified with גָּאַל, through the idea of freeing, i.e. repudiating); to soil or (figuratively) desecrate: defile, pollute, stain.
from גָּאַל; profanation: defile.
feminine passive participle of גָּאַל; redemption (including the right and the object); by implication, relationship: kindred, redeem, redemption, right.

from an unused root meaning to hollow or curve; the back (as rounded (compare גֵּו and גּוּף); by analogy, the top or rim, a boss, a vault, arch of eye, bulwarks, etc.: back, body, boss, eminent (higher) place, (eye)brows, nave, ring.
(Aramaic) corresponding to גָּב: back.
from גּוּב; a log (as cut out); also well or cistern (as dug): beam, ditch, pit.
probably from גּוּב (compare גֹּבַי); a locust (from its cutting): locust.
(Aramaic) from a root corresponding to גּוּב; a pit (for wild animals) (as cut out): den.
or (fully) Gowb; from גּוּב; pit; Gob, a place in Palestine: Gob.
from an unused root meaning probably to collect; a reservoir; by analogy, a marsh: marish, pit.
a primitive root; to soar, i.e. be lofty; figuratively, to be haughty: exalt, be haughty, be (make) high(-er), lift up, mount up, be proud, raise up great height, upward.
from גָּבַהּ; lofty (literally or figuratively): high, proud.
from גָּבַהּ; elation, grandeur, arrogance: excellency, haughty, height, high, loftiness, pride.
or (fully) gabowahh; from גָּבַהּ; elevated (or elated), powerful, arrogant: haughty, height, high(-er), lofty, proud, X exceeding proudly.
from גָּבַהּ; pride: loftiness, lofty.
or (shortened) gbul; from גָּבַל; properly, a cord (as twisted), i.e. (by implication) a boundary; by extens. the territory inclosed: border, bound, coast, X great, landmark, limit, quarter, space.
or (shortened) gbulah; feminine of גְּבוּל; a boundary, region: border, bound, coast, landmark. place.
or (shortened) gibbor; intensive from the same as גָּ֫בֶר; powerful; by implication, warrior, tyrantchampion, chief, X excel, giant, man, mighty (man, one), strong (man), valiant man.
feminine passive participle from the same as גִּבּוֹר; force (literally or figuratively); by implication, valor, victoryforce, mastery, might, mighty (act, power), power, strength.
(Aramaic) corresponding to גְּבוּרָה; power: might.
from an unused root meaning to be high (in the forehead); bald in the forehead: forehead bald.
from the same as גִּבֵּ֫חַ; baldness in the forehead; by analogy, a bare spot on the right side of cloth: bald forehead, X without.
from the same as גָּב; collective: Gabbai, an Israelite:--Gabbai.
plural of גֵּבִים; cisterns; Gebim, a place in Palestine: Gebim.
from an unused root (meaning to be convex); a goblet; by analogy, the calyx of a flower: house, cup, pot.
from גָּבַר; a master: lord.
feminine of גְּבִיר; a mistress: queen.
from an unused root (probably meaning to freeze); crystal (from its resemblance to ice): pearl.
a primitive root; properly, to twist as a rope; only (as a denominative from גְּבוּל) to bound (as by a line): be border, set (bounds about).
from גָּבַל (in the sense of a chain of hills); a mountain; Gebal, a place in Phoenicia: Gebal.
the same as גְּבַל; Gebal, a region in Idumaea: Gebal.
:  : patrial from גְּבַל; a Gebalite, or inhabitant of Gebal: Giblites, stone-squarer.
from גָּבַל; a twisted chain or lace: end.
from an unused root meaning to be arched or contracted; hunch-backed: crookbackt.
feminine from the same as גִּבֵּן; curdled milk: cheese.
from the same as גִּבֵּן; a hump or peak of hills: high.
from the same as גָּבִ֫יעַ, a hillock; Geba, a place in Palestine: Gaba, Geba, Gibeah.
by permutation for גִּבְעָה; a hill; Giba, a place in Palestine: Gibeah.
feminine from the same as גָּ֫בַע; a hillock: hill, little hill.
the same as גִּבְעָה; Gibah; the name of three places in Palestine: Gibeah, the hill.
from the same as גָּ֫בַע; hilly; Gibon, a place in Palestine: Gibeon.
prolonged from גָּבִ֫יעַ; the calyx of a flower: bolled.
patrial from גִּבְעוֹן; a Gibonite, or inhabitant of Gibon: Gibeonite.
from the same as גָּבִ֫יעַ; hilliness; Gibath: Gibeath.
patrial from גִּבְעָה; a Gibathite, or inhabitant of Gibath: Gibeathite.
a primitive root; to be strong; by implication, to prevail, act insolently: exceed, confirm, be great, be mighty, prevail, put to more (strength), strengthen, be stronger, be valiant.
from גָּבַר; properly, a valiant man or warrior; generally, a person simply: every one, man, X mighty.
the same as גָּ֫בֶר; Geber, the name of two Israelites: Geber.
from גָּבַר; the same as גָּ֫בֶר; a person: man.
(Aramaic) corresponding to גְּבַר: certain, man.
(Aramaic) intensive of גְּבַר; valiant, or warrior: mighty.
intensive of גְּבַר; Gibbar, an Israelite: Gibbar.
from גָּ֫בֶר and אֵל; man of God; Gabriel, an archangel: Garbriel.
feminine of גְּבִיר; mistress: lady, mistress.
intensive from גִּבְעָה; a hilly spot; Gibbethon, a place in Palestine: Gibbethon.
probably by reduplication from גָּאָה; a roof; by analogy, the top of an altar: roof (of the house), (house) top (of the house).
from גָּדַד (in the sense of cutting); coriander seed (from its furrows): coriander.
a variation of גָּד; Fortune, a Babylonian deity: that troop.
from גּוּד (in the sense of distributing); fortune: troop.
from גּוּד; Gad, a son of Jacob, including his tribe and its territory; also a prophet: Gad.
(Aramaic) corresponding to גִּזְבָּר; a treasurer: treasurer.
by reduplication from גָּדַד (in the sense of cutting) cleft; Gudgodah, a place in the Desert: Gudgodah.
a primitive root (compare גּוּד); to crowd; also to gash (as if by pressing into): assemble (selves by troops), gather (selves together, self in troops), cut selves.
(Aramaic) corresponding to גָּדַד; to cut down: hew down.
from an unused root (meaning to cut off); a border of a river (as cut into by the stream): bank.
from גָּדַד; a crowd (especially of soldiers): army, band (of men), company, troop (of robbers).
or (feminine) gdudah; from גָּדַד; a furrow (as cut): furrow.
feminine participle passive of גָּדַד; an incision: cutting.

or (shortened) gadol; from גָּדַל; great (in any sense); hence, older; also insolent: + aloud, elder(-est), + exceeding(-ly), + far, (man of) great (man, matter, thing,-er,-ness), high, long, loud, mighty, more, much, noble, proud thing, X sore, (X) very.
or (shortened) gdullah; or (less accurately) gduwllah; feminine of גָּדוֹל; greatness; (concretely) mighty acts: dignity, great things(-ness), majesty.
or (shortened) gidduph; and (feminine) gidduphah; or gidduphah; from גְּדוּפָה; vilification: reproach, reviling.
feminine passive participle of גָּדַף; a revilement: taunt.
from the same as גְּדוֹת; a young goat (from browsing): kid.
from גָּד; fortunate; Gadi, an Israelite: Gadi.
patronymically from גָּד; a Gadite (collectively) or descendants of Gad: Gadites, children of Gad.
intensive for גָּדִי; Gaddi, an Israelite: Gaddi.
from גָּד and אֵל; fortune of God; Gaddiel, an Israelite: Gaddiel.
or gadyah; the same as גְּדוֹת; a river brink: bank.
feminine of גֶּ֫דִי; a young female goat: kid.
from an unused root (meaning to heap up); a stack of sheaves; by analogy, a tomb: shock (stack) (of corn), tomb.

a primitive root; properly, to twist (compare גְּדִלִים), i.e. to be (causatively make) large (in various senses, as in body, mind, estate or honor, also in pride): advance, boast, bring up, exceed, excellent, be(-come, do, give, make, wax), great(-er, come to...estate, + things), grow(up), increase, lift up, magnify(-ifical), be much set by, nourish (up), pass, promote, proudly (spoken), tower.
from גָּדַל; large (literally or figuratively): great, grew.
from גָּדַל; magnitude (literally or figuratively)greatness, stout(-ness).
from גָּדַל (in the sense of twisting); thread, i.e. a tassel or festoon: fringe, wreath.
from גָּדַל; stout; Giddel, the name of one of the Nethinim, also of one of "Solomon's servants": Giddel.
or (prolonged) Gdalyahuw; from גָּדַל and יָהּ; Jah has become great; Gedaljah, the name of five Israelites: Gedaliah.
from גָּדַל; I have made great; Giddalti, an Israelite: Giddalti.
a primitive root; to fell a tree; generally, to destroy anything: cut (asunder, in sunder, down, off), hew down.
from גָּדַע; feller (i.e. warrior); Gidon, an Israelite: Gideon.
from גָּדַע; a cutting (i.e. desolation); Gidom, a place in Palestine: Gidom.
from גָּדַע; warlike (compare גִּדְעוֹן); Gidoni, an Israelite: Gideoni.
a primitive root; to hack (with words), i.e. revile: blaspheme, reproach.
a primitive root; to wall in or around: close up, fence up, hedge, inclose, make up (a wall), mason, repairer.
from גָּדַר; a circumvallation: wall.
:  : the same as גֶּ֫דֶר; Geder, a place in Palestine: Geder.
or (fully) Gdowr; from גָּדַר; inclosure; Gedor, a place in Palestine; also the name of three Israelites: Gedor.
from גָּדַר; a circumvallation; by implication, an inclosure: fence, hedge, wall.
feminine of גָּדֵר; enclosure (especially for flocks): (sheep-) cote (fold) hedge, wall.
the same as גְּדֵרָה; (with the article) Gederah, a place in Palestine: Gederah, hedges.
plural of גְּדֵרָה; walls; Gederoth, a place in Palestine: Gederoth.
patrial from גֶּ֫דֶר; a Gederite, or inhabitant of Geder: Gederite.
patrial from גְּדֵרָה; a Gederathite, or inhabitant of Gederah: Gederathite.
dual of גְּדֵרָה; double wall; Gederothajim, a place in Palestine: Gederothaim.
probably a clerical error for זֶה; this: this.
a primitive root; to remove (a bandage from a wound, i.e. heal it): cure.
from גָּהָה; a cure: medicine.
a primitive root; to prostrate oneself: cast self down, stretch self.
another form for גֵּו; the back: back.
(Aramaic) corresponding to גֵּו; the middle: midst, same, there- (where-) in.
from גָּאָה (corresponding to גָּב); the back; by analogy, the middle: + among, back, body.
a primitive root; to dig: husbandman.
from גּוּב; the locust (from its grubbing as a larvae)grasshopper, X great.
of uncertain derivation; Gog, the name of an Israelite, also of some nothern nation: Gog.
a primitive root (akin to גָּדַד); to crowd upon, i.e. attack: invade, overcome.
feminine of גֵּו; the back, i.e. (by extensive) the person: body.
the same as גֵּוָה; exaltation; (figuratively) arrogance: lifting up, pride.
(Aramaic) corresponding to גֵּוָה: pride.
a primitive root (compare גָּזַז); properly, to shear off; but used only in the (figuratively) sense of passing rapidly: bring, cut off.
or (shortened) gozal; from גָּזַל; a nestling (as being comparatively nude of feathers): young (pigeon).
probably from גּוּז; a quarry (as a place of cutting stones); Gozan, a province of Assyria: Gozan.

rarely (shortened) goy; apparently from the same root as גֵּוָה (in the sense of massing); a foreign nation; hence, a Gentile; also (figuratively) a troop of animals, or a flight of locusts: Gentile, heathen, nation, people.
prolonged for גֵּוָה; a body, whether alive or dead: (dead) body, carcase, corpse.
or (shortened) golah; active participle feminine of גָּלָה; exile; concretely and collectively exiles: (carried away), captive(-ity), removing.
from גּוֹלָה; captive; Golan, a place east of the Jordan: Golan.
of uncertain derivation; a pit: pit.
probably from גָּנַן; protected; Guni, the name of two Israelites: Guni.
patronymically from גּוּנִי; a Gunite (collectively with article prefix) or descendants of Guni: Gunites.
a primitive root; to breathe out, i.e. (by implication) expire: die, be dead, give up the ghost, perish.
a primitive root; properly, to hollow or arch, i.e. (figuratively) close; to shut: shut.
from גּוּף; a corpse (as closed to sense): body.

a primitive root; properly, to turn aside from the road (for a lodging or any other purpose), i.e. sojourn (as a guest); also to shrink, fear (as in a strange place); also to gather for hostility (as afraid): abide, assemble, be afraid, dwell, fear, gather (together), inhabitant, remain, sojourn, stand in awe, (be) stranger, X surely.
or (shortened) gur; perhaps from גּוּר; a cub (as still abiding in the lair), especially of the lion: whelp, young one.
the same as גּוּר; Gur, a place in Palestine: Gur.
or (feminine) gorah; a variation of גּוּר: whelp.
from גּוּר and בַּ֫עַל; dwelling of Baal; Gur- Baal, a place in Arabia: Gur-baal.

or (shortened) goral; from an unused root meaning to be rough (as stone); properly, a pebble, i.e. a lot (small stones being used for that purpose); figuratively, a portion or destiny (as if determined by lot): lot.
or rather (by permutation) giysh; of uncertain derivation; a mass of earth: clod.
from גָּזַז; a fleece (as shorn); also mown grass: fleece, mowing, mown grass.
of foreign derivation; treasurer: treasurer.
(Aramaic) corresponding to גִּזְבָּר: treasurer.
a primitive root (akin to גּוּז); to cut off, i.e. portion out: take.
feminine from גָּזַז; a fleece: fleece.
patrial from the unused name of a place apparently in Palestine; a Gizonite or inhabitant of Gizoh: Gizonite.
a primitive root (akin to גּוּז); to cut off; specifically to shear a flock or shave the hair; figuratively to destroy an enemy: cut off (down), poll, shave, ((sheep-)) shear(-er).
from גָּזַז; shearer; Gazez, the name of two Israelites: Gazez.
from גָּזָה; something cut, i.e. dressed stone: hewed, hewn stone, wrought.
a primitive root; to pluck off; specifically to flay, strip or rob: catch, consume, exercise (robbery), pluck (off), rob, spoil, take away (by force, violence), tear.
from גָּזַל; robbery, or (concretely) plunder: robbery, thing taken away by violence.
from גָּזַל; plunder, i.e. violence: violence, violent perverting.. gozal. See גּוֹזָל.
feminine of גָּזֵל and mean the same: -that (he had robbed) (which he took violently away), spoil, violence.
from an unused root meaning to devour; a kind of locust: palmer-worm.
from the same as גָּזָם; devourer: Gazzam, one of the Nethinim:--Gazzam.
from an unused root meaning to cut down (trees); the trunk or stump of a tree (as felled or as planted): stem, stock.
a primitive root; to cut down or off; (figuratively) to destroy, divide, exclude, or decide: cut down (off), decree, divide, snatch.
(Aramaic) corresponding to גָּזַר; to quarry; determine: cut out, soothsayer.
from גָּזַר; something cut off; a portion: part, piece.
the same as גְּזָרִים; Gezer, a place in Palestine: Gazer, Gezer.
feminine of גְּזָרִים; the figure or person (as if cut out); also an inclosure (as separated): polishing, separate place.
from גָּזַר; a desert (as separated): not inhabited.
(Aramaic) from גְּזַר (as גָּזַר); a decree: decree.

(in the m patrial from גָּ֫זֶר; a Gezerite (collectively) or inhabitants of Gezer; but better (as in the text) by transposition Girziy; patrial of גְּרִזִים; a Grizite (collectively) or member of a native tribe in Palestine: Gezrites.
probably from גִּ֫יחַ; the external abdomen, belly (as the source of the faetus (compare גִּיחוֹן)): belly.
or (feminine) gacheleth; from an unused root meaning to glow or kindle; an ember: (burning) coal.
from an unused root meaning to burn; flame; Gacham, a son of Nahor: Gaham.
from an unused root meaning to hide; lurker; Gachar, one of the Nethinim: Gahar.
or (shortened) gay; probably (by transmutation) from the same root as גֵּוָה (abbreviated); a gorge (from its lofty sides; hence, narrow, but not a gully or winter-torrent): valley.
probably from גּוּד; a thong (as compressing); by analogy, a tendon: sinew.
or (shortened) goach; a primitive root; to gush forth (as water), generally to issue: break forth, labor to bring forth, come forth, draw up, take out.
(Aramaic) or (shortened) guwach (Aramaic); corresponding to גִּ֫יחַ; to rush forth: strive.
from גִּ֫יחַ; a fountain; Giach, a place in Palestine: Giah.
or (shortened) Gichown; from גִּ֫יחַ; stream; Gichon, a river of Paradise; also a valley (or pool) near Jerusalem: Gihon.
or Gechaziy; apparently from גָּיְא and חָזָה; valley of a visionary; Gechazi, the servant of Elisha: Gehazi.
or (by permutation) guwl; a primitive root; properly, to spin round (under the influence of any violent emotion), i.e. usually rejoice, or (as cringing) fear: be glad, joy, be joyful, rejoice.
from גִּיל; a revolution (of time, i.e. an age); also joy: X exceedingly, gladness, X greatly, joy, rejoice(-ing), sort.
or giylath; feminine of גִּיל; joy: joy, rejoicing.
patrial from גִּלֹה; a Gilonite or inhabitant of Giloh: Gilonite.
of uncertain derivation; Ginath, an Israelite: Ginath.
(Aramaic) corresponding to גִּר; lime: plaster.
from the same as גִּישׁ; lumpish; Geshan, an Israelite: Geshan.
from גָּלַל; something rolled, i.e. a heap of stone or dung (plural ruins), by analogy, a spring of water (plural waves): billow, heap, spring, wave.
from גָּלַל; a cup for oil (as round): bowl.
from an unused root meaning to shave; a barber: barber.
from גָּל and בָּעָה; fountain of ebullition; Gilboa, a mountain of Palestine: Gilboa.
by reduplication from גָּלַל; a wheel; by analogy, a whirlwind; also dust (as whirled): heaven, rolling thing, wheel.
(Aramaic) corresponding to גַּלְגַּל; a wheel: wheel.
a variation of גַּלְגַּל: wheel.
the same as גִּלְגַּל (with the article as a properly, noun); Gilgal, the name of three places in Palestine: Gilgal. See also בֵּית הַגִּלְגָּל.
by reduplication from גָּלַל; a skull (as round); by implication, a head (in enumeration of persons): head, every man, poll, skull.
from an unused root probably meaning to polish; the (human) skin (as smooth): skin.

a primitive root; to denude (especially in a disgraceful sense); by implication, to exile (captives being usually stripped); figuratively, to reveal: + advertise, appear, bewray, bring, (carry, lead, go) captive (into captivity), depart, disclose, discover, exile, be gone, open, X plainly, publish, remove, reveal, X shamelessly, shew, X surely, tell, uncover.
(Aramaic) or glat (Aramaic); corresponding to גָּלָה: bring over, carry away, reveal.
or (fully) Giyloh; from גָּלָה; open; Giloh, a place in Palestine: Giloh.
feminine from גָּלַל; a fountain, bowl or globe (all as round): bowl, pommel, spring.
or (shortened) gillul; from גָּלַל; properly, a log (as round); by implication, an idol: idol.
from גָּלַם; clothing (as wrapped): clothes.
feminine from גָּלָה; captivity; concretely, exiles (collectively): (they that are carried away) captives(-ity).
(Aramaic) corresponding to גָּלוּת: captivity.
a primitive root; properly, to be bald, i.e. (causatively) to shave; figuratively to lay waste: poll, shave (off).
or gilyown; from גָּלָה; a tablet for writing (as bare); by analogy, a mirror (as a plate): glass, roll.
from גָּלַל; a valve of a folding door (as turning); also a ring (as round): folding, ring.
or (prolonged) Galiylah; the same as גְּלִילִים; a circle (with the article); Galil (as a special circuit) in the North of Palestine: Galilee.
feminine of גְּלִילִים; a circuit or region: border, coast, country.
plural of גְּלִילָה; circles; Geliloth, a place in Palestine: Geliloth.
plural of גָּל; springs; Gallim, a place in Palestine: Gallim.
perhaps from גָּלָה; exile; Goljath, a Philistine: Goliath.
a primitive root; to roll (literally or figuratively): commit, remove, roll (away, down, together), run down, seek occasion, trust, wallow.
from גָּלַל; dung (as in balls): dung.
from גָּלַל; a circumstance (as rolled around); only used adverbially, on account of: because of, for (sake).
from גָּלַל, in the sense of גְּלָל; great; Galal, the name of two Israelites: Galal.
(Aramaic) from a root corresponding to גָּלַל; weight or size (as if rolled): great.
a variation of גָּלָל; dung (plural balls of dung): dung.
from גֵּ֫לֶל; dungy; Gilalai, an Israelite: Gilalai.
a primitive root; to fold: wrap together.
from גָּלַם; a wrapped (and unformed mass, i.e. as the embryo): substance yet being unperfect.
probably by prolonged from גָּלַם; sterile (as wrapped up too hard); figuratively, desolate: desolate, solitary.
a primitive root; to be obstinate: (inter-)meddle (with).
from גָּל and עֵד; heap of testimony; Galed, a memorial cairn East of the Jordan: Galeed.
probably from גַּלְעֵד; Gilad, a region East of the Jordan; also the name of three Israelites: Gilead, Gileadite.
patronymically from גִּלְעָד; a Giladite or descendant of Gilad: Gileadite.
a primitive root; probably to caper (as a goat): appear.

by contraction from an unused root meaning to gather; properly, assemblage; used only adverbially also, even, yea, though; often repeated as correl. both...and: again, alike, also, (so much) as (soon), both (so)...and, but, either...or, even, for all, (in) likewise (manner), moreover, nay...neither, one, then(-refore), though, what, with, yea.
a primitive root (literally or figuratively) to absorb: swallow, drink.
from גָּמָא; properly, an absorbent, i.e. the bulrush (from its porosity); specifically the papyrus: (bul-)rush.
from an unused root apparently meaning to grasp; properly, a span: cubit.
from the same as גֹּ֫מֶד; a warrior (as grasping weapons): Gammadims.
from גָּמַל; treatment, i.e. an act (of good or ill); by implication, service or requital: + as hast served, benefit, desert, deserving, that which he hath given, recompense, reward.
passive participle of גָּמַל; rewarded; Gamul, an Israelite: Gamul. See also בֵּית גָּמוּל.
feminine of גְּמוּל; meaning the same: deed, recompense, such a reward.
of uncertain derivation; Gimzo, a place in Palestine: Gimzo.

a primitive root; to treat a person (well or ill), i.e. benefit or requite; by implication (of toil), to ripen, i.e. (specifically) to wean: bestow on, deal bountifully, do (good), recompense, requite, reward, ripen, + serve, mean, yield.
apparently from גָּמַל (in the sense of labor or burden-bearing); a camel: camel.
probably from גָּמָל; camel-driver; Gemalli, an Israelite: Gemalli.
from גָּמַל and אֵל; reward of God; Gamliel, an Israelite: Gamaliel.
a primitive root; to end (in the sense of completion or failure): cease, come to an end, fail, perfect, perform.
(Aramaic) corresponding to גָּמַר: perfect.
from גָּמַר; completion; Gomer, the name of a son of Japheth and of his descendants; also of a Hebrewess: Gomer.
or Gmaryahuw; from גָּמַר and יָהּ; Jah has perfected; Gemarjah, the name of two Israelites: Gemariah.
from גָּנַן; a garden (as fenced): garden.
a primitive root; to thieve (literally or figuratively); by implication, to deceive: carry away, X indeed, secretly bring, steal (away), get by stealth.
from גָּנַב; a stealer: thief.
from גָּנַב; stealing, i.e. (concretely) something stolen: theft.
from גָּנַב; theft; Genubath, an Edomitish prince: Genubath.
feminine of גָּן; a garden: garden.
another form for גַּנָּה: garden.
from an unused root meaning to store; treasure; by implication, a coffer: chest, treasury.
(Aramaic) corresponding to גִּנְזֵי; treasure: treasure.
prolonged from גִּנְזֵי; a treasury: treasury.
a primitive root; to hedge about, i.e. (generally) protect: defend.
or Ginnthow; from גָּנַן; gardener; Ginnethon or Ginnetho, an Israelite: Ginnetho, Ginnethon.
a primitive root; to bellow (as cattle): low.
feminine active participle of גָּעָה; lowing; Goah, a place near Jerusalem: Goath.
a primitive root; to detest; by implication, to reject: abhor, fail, lothe, vilely cast away.
from גָּעַל; loathing; Gaal, an Israelite: Gaal.
from גָּעַל; abhorrence: loathing.
a primitive root; to chide: corrupt, rebuke, reprove.
from גָּעַר; a chiding: rebuke(-ing), reproof.
a primitive root to agitate violently: move, shake, toss, trouble.
from גָּעַשׁ; a quaking; Gaash, a hill in Palestine: Gaash.
of uncertain derivation; Gatam, an Edomite: Gatam.
from an unused root meaning to arch; the back; by extensive the body or self: + highest places, himself.
(Aramaic) corresponding to גַּף; a wing: wing.
from an unused root meaning to bend; a vine (as twining), especially the grape: vine, tree.
from an unused root, probably meaning to house in; a kind of tree or wood (as used for building), apparently the cypressgopher.
probably feminine of גֹּ֫פֶר; properly, cypress- resin; by analogy, sulphur (as equally inflammable): brimstone.
perhaps from כּוּר; lime (from being burned in a kiln): chalk(-stone).
or (fully) geyr (gare); from גּוּר; properly, a guest; by implication, a foreigner: alien, sojourner, stranger.
perhaps from גֵּרָה; a grain; Gera, the name of six Israelites: Gera.
from an unused root meaning to scratch; scurf (from itching): scab, scurvy.
from the same as גָּרָב; scabby; Gareb, the name of an Israelite, also of a hill near Jerusalem: Gareb.
by reduplication from גָּרַר; a berry (as if a pellet of rumination): berry.
feminine plural from גָּרַר; the throat (as used in rumination): neck.
patrial from an unused name (of uncertain derivation); a Girgashite, one of the native tribes of Canaan: Girgashite, Girgasite.
a primitive root; to abrade: scrape.
a primitive root; properly, to grate, i.e. (figuratively) to anger: contend, meddle, stir up, strive.
from גָּרַר; the cud (as scraping the throat): cud.
from גָּרַר (as in גֵּרָה); properly, (like גַּרְגְּרִים) a kernel (round as if scraped), i.e. a gerah or small weight (and coin)gerah.
or (shortened) garon; from גָּרַר; the throat (compare גַּרְגְּרוֹת) (as roughened by swallowing): X aloud, mouth, neck, throat.
from גּוּר; a (temporary) residence: habitation.
a primitive root; to cut off: cut off.
plural of an unused noun from גָּרַז (compare גִּרְזִי), cut up (i.e. rocky); Gerizim, a mountain of Palestine: Gerizim.
from גָּרַז; an axe: ax.
from the same as גּוֹרָל; harsh: man of great (as in the margin which reads gadowl).
a primitive root; to be spare or skeleton-like; used only as a denominative from גָּ֫רֶם; (causative) to bone, i.e. denude (by extensive, craunch) the bones: gnaw the bones, break.
from גָּרַם; a bone (as the skeleton of the body); hence, self, i.e. (figuratively) very: bone, strong, top.
(Aramaic) corresponding to גָּ֫רֶם; a bone: bone.
from גָּ֫רֶם; bony, i.e. strong: Garmite.
from an unused root meaning to smooth; a threshing- floor (as made even); by analogy, any open area: (barn, corn, threshing-)floor, (threshing-, void) place.
a primitive root; to crush; also (intransitively and figuratively) to dissolve: break.
a primitive root; to scrape off; by implication, to shave, remove, lessen, withhold: abate, clip, (di-)minish, do (take) away, keep back, restrain, make small, withdraw.
a primitive root; to bear off violently: sweep away.
a primitive root; to drag off roughly; by implication, to bring up the cud (i.e. ruminate); by analogy, to saw: catch, chew, X continuing, destroy, saw.
probably from גָּרַר; a rolling country; Gerar, a Philistine city: Gerar.
from an unused root meaning to husk; a kernel (collectively), i.e. grain: beaten corn.
a primitive root; to drive out from a possession; especially to expatriate or divorce: cast up (out), divorced (woman), drive away (forth, out), expel, X surely put away, trouble, thrust out.
from גָּרַשׁ; produce (as if expelled): put forth.
feminine passive participle of גָּרַשׁ; (abstractly) dispossession: exaction.
for גֵּרְשׁוֹן; Gereshom, the name of four Israelites: Gershom.
or Gershowm; from גָּרַשׁ; a refugee; Gereshon or Gereshom, an Israelite: Gershon, Gershom.
patronymically from גֵּרְשׁוֹן; a Gereshonite or descendant of Gereshon: Gershonite, sons of Gershon.
from an unused root (meaning to join); bridge; Geshur, a district of Syria: Geshur, Geshurite.
patrial from גְּשׁוּר; a Geshurite (also collectively) or inhabitants of Geshur: Geshuri, Geshurites.
a primitive root; to shower violently: (cause to) rain.
from גָּשַׁם; a shower: rain, shower.
or (prolonged) Gashmuw; the same as גֶּ֫שֶׁם; Geshem or Gashmu, an Arabian: Geshem, Gashmu.
(Aramaic) apparently the same as גֶּ֫שֶׁם; used in a peculiar sense, the body (probably for the (figuratively) idea of a hard rain): body.
from גָּשַׁם; equivalent to גֶּ֫שֶׁם: rained upon.
probably of Egyptian origin; Goshen, the residence of the Israelites in Egypt; also a place in Palestine: Goshen.
of uncertain derivation; Gishpa, an Israelite: Gispa.
a primitive root; apparently to feel about: grope.
probably from נָגַן (in the sense of treading out grapes); a wine-press (or vat for holding the grapes in pressing them)(wine-)press (fat).
the same as גַּת; Gath, a Philistine city: Gath.
or (abridged) Gittah-Chepher; from גַּת and חָפַר with the article inserted; wine- press of (the) well; Gath-Chepher, a place in Palestine: Gath-kephr, Gittah-kephr.
patrial from גַּת; a Gittite or inhabitant of Gath: Gittite.
dual of גַּת; double wine-press; Gittajim, a place in Palestine: Gittaim.
feminine of גִּתִּי; a Gittite harp: Gittith.
of uncertain derivation; Gether, a son of Aram, and the region settled by him: Gether.
from גַּת and רִמּוֹן; wine-press of (the) pomegranate; Gath-Rimmon, a place in Palestine: Gath-rimmon.
(Aramaic) corresponding to זֶה; this: one..another, this.
a primitive root; to pine: mourn, sorrow(-ful).
from דָּאַב; properly, pining; by analogy, fear: sorrow.
from דָּאַב; pining: sorrow.
a primitive root; be anxious: be afraid (careful, sorry), sorrow, take thought.
or (fully) Dowoeg; active participle of דָּאַג; anxious; Doeg, an Edomite: Doeg.
from דָּאַג; anxiety: care(-fulness), fear, heaviness, sorrow.
a primitive root; to dart, i.e. fly rapidly: fly.
from דָּאַו; the kite (from its rapid flight): vulture. See רָאָה.
or (fully) dowb; from דָּבַב; the bear (as slow)bear.
(Aramaic) corresponding to דֹּב: bear.
from an unused root (compare דָּבַב) (probably meaning to be sluggish, i.e. restful); quiet: strength.
a primitive root (compare דֹּ֫בֶא); to move slowly, i.e. glide: cause to speak.
from דָּבַב (in the sense of furtive motion); slander: defaming, evil report, infamy, slander.
or (shortened) dborah; from דָּבַר (in the sense of orderly motion); the bee (from its systematic instincts): bee.
or (shortened) Dborah; the same as דְּבוֹרִים; Deborah, the name of two Hebrewesses: Deborah.
(Aramaic) corresponding to זָבַח; to sacrifice (an animal): offer (sacrifice).
(Aramaic) from דְּבַח; a sacrifice: sacrifice.
