in the margin for the textual reading, cheryown; both (in the plural only and) of uncertain derivation; probably some cheap vegetable, perhaps a bulbous root: dove's dung.
or (shortened) dbir; from דָּבַר (apparently in the sense of oracle); the shrine or innermost part of the sanctuary: oracle.
or (shortened) Dbir (Josh. 13:26 (but see לֹא דְּבַר)); the same as דְּבִיר; Debir, the name of an Amoritish king and of two places in Palestine: Debir.
probably an orthographical error for רִבְלָה; Diblah, a place in Syria: Diblath.
from an unused root (akin to זָבַל) probably meaning to press together; a cake of pressed figs: cake (lump) of figs.
dual from the masculine of דְּבֵלִים; two cakes; Diblajim, a symbolic name: Diblaim.

a primitive root; properly, to impinge, i.e. cling or adhere; figuratively, to catch by pursuit: abide fast, cleave (fast together), follow close (hard after), be joined (together), keep (fast), overtake, pursue hard, stick, take.
(Aramaic) corresponding to דָּבַק; to stick to: cleave.
from דָּבַק; a joint; by implication, solder: joint, solder.
from דָּבַק; adhering: cleave, joining, stick closer.

a primitive root; perhaps properly, to arrange; but used figuratively (of words), to speak; rarely (in a destructive sense) to subdue: answer, appoint, bid, command, commune, declare, destroy, give, name, promise, pronounce, rehearse, say, speak, be spokesman, subdue, talk, teach, tell, think, use (entreaties), utter, X well, X work.

from דָּבַר; a word; by implication, a matter (as spoken of) or thing; adverbially, a cause: act, advice, affair, answer, X any such (thing), because of, book, business, care, case, cause, certain rate, + chronicles, commandment, X commune(-ication), + concern(-ing), + confer, counsel, + dearth, decree, deed, X disease, due, duty, effect, + eloquent, errand, (evil favoured-)ness, + glory, + harm, hurt, + iniquity, + judgment, language, + lying, manner, matter, message, (no) thing, oracle, X ought, X parts, + pertaining, + please, portion, + power, promise, provision, purpose, question, rate, reason, report, request, X (as hast) said, sake, saying, sentence, + sign, + so, some (uncleanness), somewhat to say, + song, speech, X spoken, talk, task, + that, X there done, thing (concerning), thought, + thus, tidings, what(-soever), + wherewith, which, word, work.
from דָּבַר (in the sense of destroying); a pestilence: murrain, pestilence, plague.
from דָּבַר (in its original sense); a pasture (from its arrangement of the flock): fold, manner.
feminine of דָּבָר; a reason, suit or style: cause, end, estate, order, regard.
(Aramaic) corresponding to דִּבְרַת: intent, sake.
feminine active participle of דָּבַר in the sense of driving (compare דֹּ֫בֶר); a raft: float.
intensive from דָּבַר; a word: word.
from דָּבָר; wordy; Dibri, an Israelite: Dibri.
from דָּבָר (perhaps in the sense of דֹּ֫בֶר); Daberath, a place in Palestine: Dabareh, Daberath.
from an unused root meaning to be gummy; honey (from its stickiness); by analogy, syrup: honey((-comb)).
intensive from the same as דְּבָשׁ; a sticky mass, i.e. the hump of a camel: hunch (of a camel).
the same as דַּבֶּ֫שֶׁת; Dabbesheth, a place in Palestine: Dabbesheth.

or (fully) dag (Nehemiah 13:16); from דָּגָו; a fish (as prolific); or perhaps rather from דָּאַג (as timid); but still better from דָּאַג (in the sense of squirming, i.e. moving by the vibratory action of the tail); a fish (often used collectively): fish.
feminine of דָּאג, and meaning the same: fish.
a primitive root; to move rapidly; used only as a denominative from דָּאג; to spawn, i.e. become numerous: grow.
from דָּאג; the fish-god; Dagon, a Philistine deity: Dagon.
a primitive root; to flaunt, i.e. raise a flag; figuratively, to be conspicuous: (set up, with) banners, chiefest.
from דָּגַל; a flag: banner, standard.
from דָּגָו; properly, increase, i.e. grain: corn ((floor)), wheat.
a primitive root, to brood over eggs or young: gather, sit.
apparently from the same as דּוֹד; the breast (as the seat of love, or from its shape): breast, teat.
a doubtful root; to walk gently: go (softly, with).
or (prolonged) Ddaneh (Ezek. 25:13); of uncertain derivation; Dedan, the name of two Cushites and of their territory: Dedan.
plural of דְּדָן (as patrial); Dedanites, the descendants or inhabitants of Dedan: Dedanim.
or (by orthographical error) Rodaniym (1 Chron. 1:7); a plural of uncertain derivation; Dodanites, or descendants of a son of Javan: Dodanim.
(Aramaic) corresponding to זָהָב; gold: gold(- en).
(Aramaic) of uncertain derivation; Dahava, a people colonized in Samaria: Dehavites.
a primitive root (compare דּ֫וּחַ); to be dumb, i.e. (figuratively) dumbfounded: astonished.
a primitive root; to curvet or move irregularly: pause.
by reduplication from דָּהַר; a gallop: pransing.
a primitive root; to mope, i.e. (figuratively) pinesorrow.
an orthographical variation of דָּאג as a denominative (דַּיָּגִים); a fisherman: fisher.
feminine from the same as דַּוָּגִים; properly, fishery, i.e. a hook for fishing: fish (hook).

or (shortened) dod; from an unused root meaning properly, to boil, i.e. (figuratively) to love; by implication, a love- token, lover, friend; specifically an uncle: (well-)beloved, father's brother, love, uncle.
from the same as דּוֹד; a pot (for boiling); also (by resemblance of shape) a basket: basket, caldron, kettle, (seething) pot.
rarely (fully); Daviyd; from the same as דּוֹד; loving; David, the youngest son of Jesse: David.
feminine of דּוֹד; an aunt: aunt, father's sister, uncle's wife.
from דּוֹד; loving; Dodo, the name of three Israelites: Dodo.
from דּוֹד and יָהּ; love of Jah; Dodavah, an Israelite: Dodavah.
from דּוּד; a boiler or basket; also the mandrake (as an aphrodisiac): basket, mandrake.
formed like דּוּדָאּים; amatory; Dodai, an Israelite: Dodai.
a primitive root; to be sick (as if in menstruation): infirmity.
from דָּוָה; sick (especially in menstruation): faint, menstruous cloth, she that is sick, having sickness.
a primitive root; to thrust away; figuratively, to cleanse: cast out, purge, wash.
from דָּוֶה; sickness; figuratively, loathing: languishing, sorrowful.
from דָּוֶה; sick; figuratively, troubled: faint.
a primitive root; to bruise in a mortar: beat.
of uncertain derivation; the hoopoe or else the grouse: lapwing.
from an unused root meaning to be dumb (compare דָּמָה); silence; figuratively, death: silence.
the same as דּוּמָה; Dumah, a tribe and region of Arabia: Dumah.
from דָּמָה; stillness; adverbially, silently; abstractly quiet, trust: silence, silent, waiteth.
from דָּמַם; still; adverbially, silently: dumb, silent, quietly wait.
of uncertain derivation; wax; -wax.
a primitive root; to leap: be turned.
(Aramaic) corresponding to דָּקַק; to crumble: be broken to pieces.
a primitive root; properly, to gyrate (or move in a circle), i.e. to remain: dwell.
(Aramaic) corresponding to דּוּר; to reside: dwell.
from דּוּר; a circle, ball or pile: ball, turn, round about.
or (shortened) dor; from דּוּר; properly, a revolution of time, i.e. an age or generation; also a dwelling: age, X evermore, generation, (n-)ever, posterity.
or (by permutation) Dorr (Josh. 17:11; 1 Kings 4:11); from דּוֹר; dwelling; Dor, a place in Palestine: Dor.
(Aramaic) probably from דּוּר; circle or dwelling; Dura, a place in Babylonia: Dura.
or dowsh; or diysh; a primitive root; to trample or thresh: break, tear, thresh, tread out (down), at grass (Jer. 50:11, by mistake for דֶּ֫שֶׁא).
(Aramaic) corresponding to דּוּשׁ; to trample: tread down.
or dachach (Jer. 23:12); a primitive root; to push down: chase, drive away (on), overthrow, outcast, X sore, thrust, totter.
(Aramaic) from the equivalent of דָּחָה; probably a musical instrument (as being struck): instrument of music.
from דָּחָה; a push, i.e. (by implication) a fall: falling.
(Aramaic) corresponding to זָחַל; to slink, i.e. (by implication) to fear, or (causatively) be formidable: make afraid, dreadful, fear, terrible.
of uncertain derivation; millet: millet.
a primitive root; to urge, i.e. hasten: (be) haste(-ned), pressed on.
a primitive root; to press, i.e. oppress: thrust, vex.

of uncertain derivation; enough (as noun or adverb), used chiefly with preposition in phrases: able, according to, after (ability), among, as (oft as), (more than) enough, from, in, since, (much as is) sufficient(-ly), too much, very, when.

(Aramaic) apparently for דָּא; that, used as relative conjunction, and especially (with a preposition) in adverbial phrases; also as preposition of: X as, but, for(-asmuch +), + now, of, seeing, than, that, therefore, until, + what (-soever), when, which, whom, whose.
or (shortened) Diybon; from דִּיב; pining: Dibon, the name of three places in Palestine:--Dibon. (Also, with גָּד added, Dibon-gad.)
denominative from דָּאג; to fish: fish.
from דִּיג; a fisherman: fisher.
intensive from דָּאַו; a falcon (from its rapid flight): vulture.
of uncertain derivation; ink: ink.
as if from דִּי and זָהָב; of gold; Dizahab, a place in the Desert: Dizahab.
perhaps for דִּיבוֹן; Dimon, a place in Palestine: Dimon.
feminine of דִּימוֹן; Dimonah, a place in Palestine: Dimonah.
or (Gen. 6:3) duwn; a primitive roy a straight course, i.e. sail direct: (come) with a straight course.
(Aramaic) corresp. to דִּין; to judge: judge. Or diyn,; or (Job 19:29).
from דִּין; judgement (the suit, justice, sentence or tribunal); by impl. also strife: cause, judgement, plea, strife.
(Aramaic) corresp. to דִּין: judgement.
from דִּין; a judge or advocate: judge.
(Aramaic) corresp. to דַּיָּן: judge.
fem. of דִּין; justice; Dinah, the daughter of Jacob: Dinah.
(Aramaic) partial from uncertain primitive; a Dinaite or inhabitant of some unknown Assyria province: Dinaite.
from a root corresp. to דּוּק; a battering-tower: fort.
from דּוּשׁ; threshing-time: threshing.
(Diyshon, the same as דִּישֹׁן; Dishon, the name of two Edomites: Dishon.
from דּוּשׁ; the leaper, i.e. an antelope: pygarg.
another form of דִּישׁוֹן Dishan, an Edomite: Dishon.
from an unused root (compare דָּכָה); crushed, i.e. (fig.) injured: afflicted, oppressed.
(Aramaic) or dak (Aramaic); prolonged from דָּא; this: the same, this.
a primitive root (compare דָּכָה); to crumble; transitively, to bruise (literally or figuratively): beat to pieces, break (in pieces), bruise, contrite, crush, destroy, humble, oppress, smite.
from דָּכָא; crushed (literally powder, or figuratively, contrite): contrite, destruction.
a primitive root (compare דָּך, דָּכָא); to collapse (phys. or mentally): break (sore), contrite, crouch.
from דָּכָה like דַּכָּא; mutilated: + wounded.
from דָּכָה; a dashing of surf: wave.
(Aramaic) prolonged from דֵּך; this: same, that, this.
(Aramaic) corresponding to זָכָר; properly, a male, i.e. of sheep: ram.
(Aramaic) or dokran (Aramaic); corresponding to זִכָּרוֹן; a register: record.
from דָּלַל; properly, dangling, i.e. (by implication) weak or thin: lean, needy, poor (man), weaker.
a primitive root; to spring: leap.
a primitive root (compare דָּלַל); properly, to dangle, i.e. to let down a bucket (for drawing out water); figuratively, to deliver: draw (out), X enough, lift up.
from דָּלָה; properly, something dangling, i.e. a loose thread or hair; figuratively, indigent: hair, pining sickness, poor(-est sort).
a primitive root; to roil water: trouble.
or doliy; from דָּלָה; a pail or jar (for drawing water): bucket.
or (prolonged) Dlayahhuw; from דָּלָה and יָהּ; Jah has delivered; Delajah, the name of five Israelites: Dalaiah, Delaiah.
from דָּלַל; languishing: Delilah, a Philistine woman:--Delilah.
from דָּלָה; something dangling, i.e. a bough: branch.
a primitive root (compare דָּלָה); to slacken or be feeble; figuratively, to be oppressed: bring low, dry up, be emptied, be not equal, fail, be impoverished, be made thin.
of uncertain derivation; Dilan, a place in Palestine: Dilean.
a primitive root; to drip; by implication, to weep: drop through, melt, pour out.
from דָּלַף; a dripping: dropping.
from דָּלַף; dripping; Dalphon, a son of Haman: Dalphon.
a primitive root; to flame (literally or figuratively): burning, chase, inflame, kindle, persecute(-or), pursue hotly.
(Aramaic) corresponding to דָּלַק: burn.
:  : from דָּלַק; a burning fever: inflammation.
from דָּלָה; something swinging, i.e. the valve of a door: door (two-leaved), gate, leaf, lid. (In Psa. 141:3, dal, irreg.).

from דָּמַם (compare אָדַם); blood (as that which when shed causes death) of man or an animal; by analogy, the juice of the grape; figuratively (especially in the plural) bloodshed (i.e. drops of blood): blood(-y, -guiltiness, (-thirsty), + innocent.
a primitive root; to compare; by implication, to resemble, liken, consider: compare, devise, (be) like(-n), mean, think, use similitudes.
a primitive root; to be dumb or silent; hence, to fail or perish; trans. to destroy: cease, be cut down (off), destroy, be brought to silence, be undone, X utterly.
(Aramaic) corresponding to דָּמָה; to resemble: be like.
from דָּמָה; desolation; concretely, desolate: destroy.
from דָּמָה; resemblance; concretely, model, shape; adverbially, like: fashion, like (-ness, as), manner, similitude.
or domiy; from דָּמָה; quiet: cutting off, rest, silence.
from דָּמָה; resemblance: X like.

a prim root (compare דָּהַם, דָּמָה); to be dumb; by implication, to be astonished, to stop; also to perish: cease, be cut down (off), forbear, hold peace, quiet self, rest, be silent, keep (put to) silence, be (stand) still, tarry, wait.
feminine from דָּמַם; quiet: calm, silence, still.
of uncertain derivation; manure: dung.
feminine from the same as דֹּ֫מֶן; a dung-heap; Dimnah, a place in Palestine: Dimnah.
a primitive root; to weep: X sore, weep.
from דָּמַע; a tear; figuratively, juice: liquor.
feminine of דֶּ֫מַע; weeping: tears.
by orthographical variation from דַּמֶּשֶׂק; damask (as a fabric of Damascus): in Damascus.
or Duwmeseq; or Darmeseq; of foreign origin; Damascus, a city of Syria: Damascus.
from דִּין; judge; Dan, one of the sons of Jacob; also the tribe descended from him, and its territory; likewise a place in Palestine colonized by them: Dan.
(Aramaic) an orthographical variation of דֵּך; this(afore-)time, + after this manner, here (-after), one...another, such, there(-fore), these, this (matter), + thus, where(-fore), which.
of uncertain derivation; Dannah, a place in Palestine: Dannah.
of uncertain derivation; Dinhabah, an Edomitish town: Dinhaban.
patronymically from דָּן; a Danite (often collectively) or descendants (or inhabitants) of Dan: Danites, of Dan.
in Ezekiel it is: Daniel; from דָּן and אֵל; judge of God; Daniel or Danijel, the name of two Israelites: Daniel.
(Aramaic) corresponding to דָּנִיֵּאל; Danijel, the Heb. prophet: Daniel.
from דָּן and (apparently) יַ֫עַן; judge of purpose; Dan-Jaan, a place in Palestine: Dan-jaan.
from יָדַע; knowledge: knowledge, opinion.
feminine of דֵּעִי; knowledge: knowledge.
from יָדַע and אֵל; known of God; Deuel, an Israelite: Deuel.
a primitive root; to be extinguished; figuratively, to expire or be dried up: be extinct, consumed, put out, quenched.
from יָדַע; knowledge: cunning, (ig-)norantly, know(-ledge), (un-)awares (wittingly).
from an unused root (meaning to push over); a stumbling-block: slanderest.
a primitive root; to knock; by analogy, to press severely: beat, knock, overdrive.
from דָּפַק; a knock; Dophkah, a place in the Desert: Dophkah.
from דָּקַק; crushed, i.e. (by implication) small or thin: dwarf, lean(-fleshed), very little thing, small, thin.
from דָּקַק; something crumbling, i.e. fine (as a thin cloth): curtain.
of foreign origin; Diklah, a region of Arabia: Diklah.
a primitive root (compare הָדַך); to crush (or intransitively) crumble: beat in pieces (small), bruise, make dust, (into) X powder, (be, very) small, stamp (small).
(Aramaic) corresponding to דָּקַק; to crumble or (trans.) crush: break to pieces.
a primitive root; to stab; by analogy, to starve; figuratively, to revile: pierce, strike (thrust) through, wound.
from דָּקַר; a stab; Deker, an Israelite: Dekar.
apparently from the same as דְּרוֹר; properly, a pearl (from its sheen as rapidly turned); by analogy, pearl-stone, i.e. mother-of-pearl or alabaster: X white.
(Aramaic) corresponding to דּוֹר; an age: generation.
or dera)own; from an unused root (meaning to repulse); an object of aversion: abhorring, contempt.
(also dor-bawn'); of uncertain derivation; a goad: goad.
apparently from דַּר and דֵּעִי; pearl of knowledge; Darda, an Israelite: Darda.
of uncertain derivation; a thorn: thistle.
of uncertain derivation; the south; poet. the south wind: south.
from an unused root (meaning to move rapidly); freedom; hence, spontaneity of outflow, and so clear: liberty, pure.
the same as דְּרוֹר, applied to a bird; the swift, a kind of swallow: swallow.
of Persian origin; Darejavesh, a title (rather than name) of several Persian kings: Darius.
(Aramaic) corresponding to דָּֽרְיָוֵשׁ: Darius.
a primitive root; to tread; by implication, to walk; also to string a bow (by treading on it in bending): archer, bend, come, draw, go (over), guide, lead (forth), thresh, tread (down), walk.

from דָּרַך; a road (as trodden); figuratively, a course of life or mode of action, often adverb: along, away, because of, + by, conversation, custom, (east-)ward, journey, manner, passenger, through, toward, (high-) (path-)way(-side), whither(-soever).
of Pers. origin; a "drachma," or coin: dram.
(Aramaic) corresponding to זְר֫וֹעַ; an arm: arm.
probably a contraction from דַּרְדַּע; Dara, an Israelite: Dara.
of uncertain derivation; Darkon, one of "Solomon's servants": Darkon.

a primitive root; properly, to tread or frequent; usually to follow (for pursuit or search); by implication, to seek or ask; specifically to worship: ask, X at all, care for, X diligently, inquire, make inquisition, (necro-)mancer, question, require, search, seek (for, out), X surely.
a primitive root; to sprout: bring forth, spring.
from דָּשָׁא; a sprout; by analogy, grass: (tender) grass, green, (tender)herb.

a primitive root; to be fat; transitively, to fatten (or regard as fat); specifically to anoint; figuratively, to satisfy; denominatively (from דָּ֫שֶׁן) to remove (fat) ashes (of sacrifices): accept, anoint, take away the (receive) ashes (from), make (wax) fat.
from דָּשֵׁן; fat; figuratively, rich, fertile: fat.
from דָּשֵׁן; the fat; abstractly fatness, i.e. (figuratively) abundance; specifically the (fatty) ashes of sacrificesashes, fatness.
of uncertain (perhaps foreign) derivation: a royal edict or statute: commandment, commission, decree, law, manner.
(Aramaic) corresponding to דָּת; decree, law.
(Aramaic) corresponding to דֶּ֫שֶׁא: tender grass.
(Aramaic) of Pers. origin; meaning one skilled in law; a judge: counsellor.
of uncertain derivation; Dathan, an Israelite: Dathan.
or (Aramaic dual) Dothayin (Gen. 37:17); of uncertain derivation; Dothan, a place in Palestine: Dothan.
a primitive particle; lo!: behold, lo.
(Aramaic) or har (Aramaic); corresponding to הֵא: even, lo.
from הֵא and אָח; aha!: ah, aha, ha.
by reduplication from יָהַב; gift (in sacrifice), i.e. holocaust: offering.
a primitive root; to be vain in act, word, or expectation; specifically to lead astray: be (become, make) vain.
or (rarely in the abs.) habel; from הָבַל; emptiness or vanity; figuratively, something transitory and unsatisfactory; often used as an adverb: X altogether, vain, vanity.
the same as הָ֫בֶל; Hebel, the son of Adam: Abel.
only in plural, from an unused root meaning to be hard; ebony: ebony.
a primitive root of uncertain (perhaps foreign) derivation; to be a horoscopist: + (astro-)loger.
or (by permutation) Hegay; probably of Persian origin; Hege or Hegai, a eunuch of Xerxes: Hegai, Hege.
a primitive root (compare הֲגִיג); to murmur (in pleasure or anger); by implication, to ponder: imagine, meditate, mourn, mutter, roar, X sore, speak, study, talk, utter.
a primitive root; to remove: stay, stay away.
from הָגָה; a muttering (in sighing, thought, or as thunder): mourning, sound, tale.
from הָגָה; musing: meditation.
from an unused root akin to הָגָה; properly, a murmur, i.e. complaint: meditation, musing.

intensive from הָגָה; a murmuring sound, i.e. a musical notation (probably similar to the modern affettuoso to indicate solemnity of movement); by implication, a machination: device, Higgaion, meditation, solemn sound.
of uncertain derivation; perhaps suitable or turning: directly.
of uncertain (perhaps foreign) derivation; Hagar, the mother of Ishmael: Hagar.
or (prolonged) Hagris; perhaps patronymically from הָגָר; a Hagrite or member of a certain Arabian clanHagarene, Hagarite, Haggeri.
for הֵידָד; a shout: sounding again.
(Aramaic) probably of foreign origin; a vizier: counsellor.
probably of foreign origin (compare אֲדַד); Hadad, the name of an idol, and of several kings of Edom: Hadad.
from הֲדָד and עֵ֫זֶר; Hadad (is his) help; Hadadezer, a Syrian king: Hadadezer. Compare הֲדַרְעָ֫זֶר.
from הֲדָד and רִמּוֹן; Hadad-Rimmon, a place in Palestine: Hadad-rimmon.
a primitive root (compare יָדָה); to stretch forth the hand: put.
of foreign origin; Hodu (i.e. Hindu-stan): India.
or Hadoram; probably of foreign derivation; Hadoram, a son of Joktan, and the tribe descended from himHadoram.
of uncertain derivation; Hiddai, an Israelite: Hiddai.
a primitive root (compare דָּקַק); to crush with the foot: tread down.
from an unused root meaning to stamp upon; a foot stool: (foot-)stool.
(Aramaic) from a root corresponding to that of הֲדֹם; something stamped to pieces, i.e. a bit: piece.
of uncertain derivation; the myrtle: myrtle (tree).
feminine of הֲדַס; Hadassah (or Esther): Hadassah.
a prim root; to push away or down: cast away (out), drive, expel, thrust (away).
a primitive root; to swell up (literally or figuratively, active or passive); by implication, to favor or honour, be high or proud: countenance, crooked place, glorious, honour, put forth.
(Aramaic) corresponding to הָדַר; to magnify (figuratively): glorify, honour.
(Aramaic) from הֲדַר; magnificence: honour, majesty.
the same as הָדָר; Hadar, an Edomite: Hadar.
from הָדַר; honour; used (figuratively) for the capital city (Jerusalem): glory.
from הָדַר; magnificence, i.e. ornament or splendor: beauty, comeliness, excellency, glorious, glory, goodly, honour, majesty.
feminine of הָדָר; decoration: beauty, honour.
from הֲדַר and עֵ֫זֶר; Hadar (i.e. Hadad, הֲדָד) is his help; Hadarezer (i.e. Hadadezer, הֲדַדְעָ֫זֶר), a Syrian king: Hadarezer.
a shortened form of אֲהָהּ; ah! expressing grief: woe worth.
by permutation from הָהּ; oh!: alas.

of which the feminine (beyond the Pentateuch) is hiyw; a primitive word, the third person pronoun singular, he (she or it); only expressed when emphatic or without a verb; also (intensively) self, or (especially with the article) the same; sometimes (as demonstrative) this or that; occasionally (instead of copula) as or are: he, as for her, him(-self), it, the same, she (herself), such, that (...it), these, they, this, those, which (is), who.
(Aramaic) or (feminine) hiyo (Aramaic); corresponding to הוּא: X are, it, this.
or havah; a primitive root (compare אָוָה, הָיָה) supposed to mean properly, to breathe; to be (in the sense of existence): be, X have.

(Aramaic) or havah (Aramaic); corresponding to הָוָה; to exist; used in a great variety of applications (especially in connection with other words): be, become, + behold, + came (to pass), + cease, + cleave, + consider, + do, + give, + have, + judge, + keep, + labour, + mingle (self), + put, + see, + seek, + set, + slay, + take heed, tremble, + walk, + would.
from an unused root; grandeur (i.e. an imposing form and appearance): beauty, comeliness, excellency, glorious, glory, goodly, honour, majesty.
the same as הוֹד; Hod, an Israelite: Hod.
a form of הוֹדַוְיָה; Hodevah (or Hodevjah), an Israelite: Hodevah.
from הוֹד and יָהּ; majesty of Jah; Hodavjah, the name of three Israelites: Hodaviah.
a form of הוֹדַוְיָה; Hodajvah, an Israelite: Hodaiah.
a form for the feminine of יְהוּדִי; a Jewess: Hodiah.
a form of הוֹדַוְיָה; Hodijah, the name of three Israelites: Hodijah.

from הָוָה (in the sense of eagerly coveting and rushing upon; by implication, of falling); desire; also ruin: calamity, iniquity, mischief, mischievous (thing), naughtiness, naughty, noisome, perverse thing, substance, very wickedness.
another form for הַוַּת; ruin: mischief.
of uncertain derivation; Hoham, a Canaanitish king: Hoham.
a prolonged form of הוֹ (akin to אוֹי); oh!: ah, alas, ho, O, woe.
(Aramaic) corresponding to הֲלַך; to go; causatively, to bring: bring again, come, go (up).
feminine active participle of הָלַל; folly: madness.
from active participle of הָלַל; folly: madness.
a primitive root (compare הָמַם); to make an uproar, or agitate greatly: destroy, move, make a noise, put, ring again.
from הָמַם; raging; Homam, an Edomitish chieftain: Homam. Compare הֵימָם.
a primitive root; properly, to be naught, i.e. (figuratively) to be (causatively, act) light: be ready.
from the same as הוּן in the sense of אוֹן; wealth; by implication, enough: enough, + for nought, riches, substance, wealth.
from יְהֹוָה and שָׁמַע; Jehovah has heard; Hoshama, an Israelite: Hoshama.
from יָשַׁע; deliverer; Hoshea, the name of five Israelites: Hosea, Hoshea, Oshea.
from יָשַׁע and יָהּ; Jah has saved; Hoshajah, the name of two Israelites: Hoshaiah.
from יָתַר; he has caused to remain; Hothir, an Israelite: Hothir.
a primitive root (compare חָזָה); to dream: sleep.
for נֶ֫הִי; lamentation: woe. (For hiyr. See הוּא, הוּ.)
from an unused root (meaning to shout); acclamation: shout(-ing).
from the same as הֵידָד; properly, an acclaim, i.e. a choir of singers: thanksgiving.

a primitive root (compare הָוָה); to exist, i.e. be or become, come to pass (always emphatic, and not a mere copula or auxiliary): beacon, X altogether, be(-come), accomplished, committed, like), break, cause, come (to pass), do, faint, fall, + follow, happen, X have, last, pertain, quit (one-)self, require, X use.
another form for הֹוָה; ruin: calamity.
another form for אֵיךְ; how?: how.
probably from יָכֹל (in the sense of capacity); a large public building, such as a palace or temple: palace, temple.
(Aramaic) corresponding to הֵיכָל: palace, temple.
from הָלַל (in the sense of brightness); the morning-star: lucifer.
another form for הוֹמָם; Hemam, an Idumaean: Hemam.
probably from אָמַן; faithful; Heman, the name of at least two Israelites: Heman.
probably of Egyptian origin; a hin or liquid measure: hin.
a primitive root; apparently to injure: make self strange.
from נָכַר; respect, i.e. partiality: shew.
probably denominatively from הָלְאָה; to remove or be remote: cast far off.
from the primitive form of the article (hal); to the distance, i.e. far away; also (of time) thus far: back, beyond, (hence,-)forward, hitherto, thence,forth, yonder.
from הָלַל (in the sense of rejoicing); a celebration of thanksgiving for harvest: merry, praise.
from הַלָּזֶה; this or that: side, that, this.
from the article (see הָלְאָה) and זֶה; this very: this.
another form of הַלָּזֶה; that: this.
from הָלַך; a walk, i.e. (by implication) a step: step.
feminine of הֲלִיכִים; a walking; by implication, a procession or march, a caravan: company, going, walk, way.

akin to יָלַך; a primitive root; to walk (in a great variety of applications, literally and figuratively): (all) along, apace, behave (self), come, (on) continually, be conversant, depart, + be eased, enter, exercise (self), + follow, forth, forward, get, go (about, abroad, along, away, forward, on, out, up and down), + greater, grow, be wont to haunt, lead, march, X more and more, move (self), needs, on, pass (away), be at the point, quite, run (along), + send, speedily, spread, still, surely, + tale-bearer, + travel(-ler), walk (abroad, on, to and fro, up and down, to places), wander, wax, (way-)faring man, X be weak, whirl.
(Aramaic) corresponding to הָלַך (compare הוּך); to walk: walk.
from הָלַך; properly, a journey, i.e. (by implication) a wayfarer; also a flowing: X dropped, traveller.
(Aramaic) from הֲלַך; properly, a journey, i.e. (by implication) toll on goods at a road: custom.

a primitive root; to be clear (orig. of sound, but usually of color); to shine; hence, to make a show, to boast; and thus to be (clamorously) foolish; to rave; causatively, to celebrate; also to stultify: (make) boast (self), celebrate, commend, (deal, make), fool(- ish, -ly), glory, give (light), be (make, feign self) mad (against), give in marriage, (sing, be worthy of) praise, rage, renowned, shine.
from הָלַל; praising (namely God); Hillel, an Israelite: Hillel.
a primitive root; to strike down; by implication, to hammer, stamp, conquer, disband: beat (down), break (down), overcome, smite (with the hammer).
from הָלַם; smiter; Helem, the name of two Israelites: Helem.
from the article (see הָלְאָה); hither: here, hither(-(to)), thither.
from הָלַם; a hammer (or mallet): hammer.
of uncertain derivation; Ham, a region of Palestine: Ham.
from הָמָה; abundance, i.e. wealth: any of theirs.

or (prolonged) hemmah; masculine plural from הֲלַך; they (only used when emphatic): it, like, X (how, so) many (soever, more as) they (be), (the) same, X so, X such, their, them, these, they, those, which, who, whom, withal, ye.

a primitive root (compare הוּם); to make a loud sound like Engl. "hum"); by implication, to be in great commotion or tumult, to rage, war, moan, clamor: clamorous, concourse, cry aloud, be disquieted, loud, mourn, be moved, make a noise, rage, roar, sound, be troubled, make in tumult, tumultuous, be in an uproar.
(Aramaic) or (prolonged) himmown (Aramaic); corresponding to הֵם; they: X are, them, those.
or hamon (Ezek. 5:7); from הָמָה; a noise, tumult, crowd; also disquietude, wealth: abundance, company, many, multitude, multiply, noise, riches, rumbling, sounding, store, tumult.
from הָמוֹן and גּוֹג; the multitude of Gog; the fanciful name of an emblematic place in Palestine: Hamogog.
feminine of הָמוֹן; multitude; hamonah, the same as הֲמוֹן גּוֹג: Hamonah.
from הָמָה; sound: noise.
or (too fully) hamuwllah (Jer. 11:16); feminine passive participle of an unused root meaning to rush (as rain with a windy roar); a sound: speech, tumult.
a primitive root (compare הוּם, הָמָה); properly, to put in commotion; by implication, to disturb, drive, destroy: break, consume, crush, destroy, discomfit, trouble, vex.
of foreign derivation; Haman, a Persian vizier: Haman.
(Aramaic) but the text is hamuwnek; of foreign origin; a necklace: chain.
from an unused root apparently meaning to crackle; a dry twig or brushwood: melting.
feminine plural from הוּא; they (only used when emphatic)X in, such like, (with) them, thereby, therein, (more than) they, wherein, in which, whom, withal.
a primitive particle; lo!; also (as expressing surprise) if: behold, if, lo, though.
(Aramaic) corresponding to הֵן: lo! also there(-fore), (un-)less, whether, but, if: (that) if, or, whether.

prolongation for הֵן; themselves (often used emphatic for the copula, also in indirect relation): X in, X such (and such things), their, (into) them, thence, therein, these, they (had), on this side, whose, wherein.
from הֵן; hither or thither (but used both of place and time): here, hither(-to), now, on this (that) side, + since, this (that) way, thitherward, + thus far, to...fro, + yet.
prolongation for הֵן; lo!: behold, lo, see.
from נ֫וּחַ; permission of rest, i.e. quiet: release.
probably of foreign origin; Hinnom, apparently a Jebusite: Hinnom.
probably of foreign derivation; Hena, a place apparently in Mesopotamia: Hena.
a primitive root; to hush: hold peace (tongue), (keep) silence, be silent, still.
from פּוּג; relaxation: intermission.

a primitive root; to turn about or over; by implication, to change, overturn, return, pervert: X become, change, come, be converted, give, make (a bed), overthrow (-turn), perverse, retire, tumble, turn (again, aside, back, to the contrary, every way).
:  : or hephek; from הָפַך; a turn, i.e. the reverse: contrary.
from הָפַך; an upset, i.e. (abstract) perversity: turning of things upside down.
feminine of הֵ֫פֶך; destruction: overthrow.
by reduplication from הָפַך; very perverse: froward.
from נָצַל; rescue: deliverance.
from an unused root meaning apparently to be sharp or strong; a weapon of war: chariot.
a shortened form of הָ֫רַר; a mountain or range of hills (sometimes used figuratively): hill (country), mount(-ain), X promotion.
another form of הָר; mountain; Hor, the name of a peak in Idumaea and of one in Syria: Hor.
perhaps from הָר; mountainousness; Hara, a region of Media: Hara.
from הָר and אֵל; mount of God; figuratively, the altar of burnt-offering: altar. Compare אֲרִיאֵל.
a primitive root; to smite with deadly intent: destroy, out of hand, kill, murder(-er), put to (death), make (slaughter), slay(-er), X surely.
from הָרַג; slaughter: be slain, slaughter.
feminine of הֶ֫רֶג; slaughter: slaughter.
a primitive root; to be (or become) pregnant, conceive (literally or figuratively): been, be with child, conceive, progenitor.
or hariy (Hosea 14:1); from הָרָה; pregnant: (be, woman) with child, conceive, X great.
(Aramaic) from a root corresponding to הָרָה; a mental conception: thought.
or herayown; from הָרָה; pregnancy: conception.
another form for הָרָרִי; a Harorite or mountaineer: Harorite.
from הָרַס; something demolished: ruin.
from הָרַס; demolition: destruction.
from an unused root (meaning to tower up); high; Horam, a Canaanitish king: Horam.
passive participle of the same as הֹרָם; high; Harum, an Israelite: Harum.
from the same as הֹרָם; a castle (from its height): palace.
perhaps from הָר; mountaineer; Haran, the name of two men: Haran.
a primitive root; to pull down or in pieces, break, & destroy: beat down, break (down, through), destroy, overthrow, pluck down, pull down, ruin, throw down, X utterly.
from הָרַס; demolition: destruction.
from an unused root meaning to loom up; a mountain: hill, mount(-ain).
or Harariy (2 Sam. 23:11); or Haarariy (2 Sam. 23:34, last clause); apparently from הָ֫רַר; a mountaineer: Hararite.
perhaps from the same as חָשֻׁם; wealthy; Hashem, an Israelite: Hashem.
from שָׁמַע; announcement: to cause to hear.
from נָתַך; a melting: is melted.
probably of foreign origin; Hathak, a Persian eunuch: Hatach.
a primitive root; to deride; by implication, to cheat: deal deceitfully, deceive, mock.
from הָתַל (only in plural collectively); a derision: mocker.
a primitive root; properly, to break in upon, i.e. to assail: imagine mischief.
perhaps for עֲדָנִים; Vedan (or Aden), a place in Arabia: Dan also.
of uncertain derivation; Vaheb, a place in Moab: what he did.
probably a hook (the name of the sixth Heb. letter): hook.
presumed to be from an unused root meaning to bear guilt; crime: X strange.
of foreign origin; Vajezatha, a son of Haman: Vajezatha.
for יָ֫לֶד; a boy: child.
perhaps for עֲנָיָה; Vanjah, an Israelite: Vaniah.
probably from יָסַף; additional; Vophsi, an & Israelite: Vophsi.
probably from יִשְׁמְרַי; weak; Vashni, an Israelite: Vashni.
of Persian origin; Vashti, the queen of Xerxes: Vashti.
from an unused root meaning to be yellow; a wolf: wolf.
the same as זְאֵב; Zeeb, a Midianitish prince: Zeeb.
irregular feminine of שֶׂה; this (often used adverb)hereby (-in, -with), it, likewise, the one (other, same), she, so (much), such (deed), that, therefore, these, this (thing), thus.
a primitive root; to confer: endure.
from זָבַד; a gift: dowry.
from זָבַד; giver; Zabad, the name of seven Israelites: Zabad.
from זֵ֫בֶד; giving; Zabdi, the name of four & Israelites: Zabdi.
from זֵ֫בֶד and אֵל; gift of God: zabdiel, the name of two Israelites: Zabdiel.
or Zbadyahuw; from זָבַד and יָהּ; Jah has given; Zebadjah, the name of nine Israelites: Zebadiah.
from an unused root (meaning to flit); a fly (especially one of a stinging nature): fly.
from זָבַד; given, Zabud, an Israelite: Zabud.
a form of זָבוּד; given; Zabbud, an Israelite: Zabbud.
or zbul; from זָבַל; a residence: dwell in, dwelling, habitation.
or Zbuluwn; or Zbuwlun; from זָבַל; habitation; Zebulon, a son of Jacob; also his territory and tribe: Zebulun.
patronymically from זְבוּלוּן; a Zebulonite or descendant of Zebulun: Zebulonite.
a primitive root; to slaughter an animal (usually in sacrifice): kill, offer, (do) sacrifice, slay.
from זָבַח; properly, a slaughter, i.e. the flesh of an animal; by implication, a sacrifice (the victim or the act): offer(- ing), sacrifice.
the same as זֶ֫בַח; sacrifice; Zebach, a Midianitish prince: Zebah.
probably by orthographical error for זַכָּי; Zabbai (or Zaccai), an Israelite: Zabbai.
feminine from זָבַד; giving; Zebidah, an Israelitess: Zebudah.
from an unused root (meaning to purchase); gainfulness; Zebina, an Israelite: Zebina.
a primitive root; apparently properly, to inclose, i.e. to reside: dwell with.
the same as זְבֻל; dwelling; Zebul, an Israelite: Zebul. Compare זְבֻל.
(Aramaic) corresponding to the root of זְבִינָא; to acquire by purchase: gain.
from an unused root probably meaning to inclose; the skin of a grape: husk.
from זִיד; arrogant: presumptuous, proud.
from זִיד; arrogance: presumptuously, pride, proud (man).

a primitive word; the masculine demonstrative pronoun, this or that: he, X hence, X here, it(-self), X now, X of him, the one...the other, X than the other, (X out of) the (self) same, such (a one) that, these, this (hath, man), on this side...on that side, X thus, very, which. Compare זֹאת, זוֹ, זוֹ, זוּ.
(1 Samuel by permutation for שֶׂה; a sheep: lamb.
for זֶה; this or that: as well as another, it, this, that, thus and thus.
from an unused root meaning to shimmer; gold, figuratively, something gold-colored (i.e. yellow), as oil, a clear skygold(-en), fair weather.
a primitive root; to be rancid, i.e. (transitively) to loathe: abhor.
from זָהַם; loathing; Zaham, an Israelite: Zaham.
a primitive root; to gleam; figuratively, to enlighten (by caution): admonish, shine, teach, (give) warn(-ing).
(Aramaic) corresponding to זָהַר; (passively) be admonished: take heed.
from זָהַר; brilliancy: brightness.
for זֶה; this or that: that, this.
for זֶה; this or that: that, this, X wherein, which, whom.
probably from an unused root meaning to be prominent; properly, brightness (compare זִיו), i.e. (figuratively) the month of flowers; Ziv (corresponding to Ijar or May): Zif.
a primitive root; to flow freely (as water), i.e. (specifically) to have a (sexual) flux; figuratively, to waste away; also to overflow: flow, gush out, have a (running) issue, pine away, run.
from זוּב; a seminal or menstrual flux: issue.
or (by permutation) ziyd; a primitive root; to seethe; figuratively, to be insolent: be proud, deal proudly, & presume, (come) presumptuously, sod.
(Aramaic) corresponding to זִיד; to be proud: in pride.
plural probably from the same as זִיז; prominent; Zuzites, an aboriginal tribe of Palestine: Zuzims.
of uncertain origin; Zocheth, an Israelite: Zoheth.
apparently from the same root as זִו (in the sense of prominence); an angle (as projecting), i.e. (by implication) a corner-column (or anta): corner(stone).
a primitive root (compare זָלַל); probably to shake out, i.e. (by implication) to scatter profusely; figuratively, to treat lightly: lavish, despise.
from זוּל; probably scattering, i.e. removal; used adverbially, except: beside, but, only, save.
a primitive root; perhaps properly, to be plump, i.e. (transitively) to nourish: feed.
(Aramaic) corresponding to זוּן: feed.
a primitive root; properly, to shake off, i.e. (figuratively) to agitate (as with fear): move, tremble, vex.
(Aramaic) corresponding to ז֫וּעַ; to shake (with fear): tremble.
from ז֫וּעַ; agitation, fear: be removed, trouble, vexation. Compare זַעֲוָה.

a primitive root; to turn aside (especially for lodging); hence to be a foreigner, strange, profane; specifically (active participle) to commit adultery: (come from) another (man, place), fanner, go away, (e-)strange(-r, thing, woman).
a primitive root (compare צוֹק); to press together, & tighten: close, rush, thrust together.
from זוּר; trodden on: that which is crushed.
probably from the root of זִיז; prominent; Zaza, an Israelite: Zaza.
a primitive root; to shove or displace: loose.
a primitive root; to crawl; by implication, to fear: be afraid, serpent, worm.
feminine active participle of זָחַל; crawling (i.e. serpent); Zocheleth, a boundary stone in. Palestine: Zoheleth.
from זִיד; boiling of water, i.e. wave: proud.
(Aramaic) corresponding to זִו; (figuratively) cheerfulness: brightness, countenance.
from an unused root apparently meaning to be conspicuous; fulness of the breast; also a moving creature: abundance, wild beast.
apparently from the same as זִיז; prominence; Ziza, the name of two Israelites: Ziza.
another form for זִיזָא; Zizah, an Israelite: Zizah.
from זוּן; well-fed; or perhaps an orthographical error for זִיזָא; Zina, an Israelite: Zina.
from ז֫וּעַ; agitation; Zia, an Israelite: Zia.
from the same as זָ֫פֶת; flowing; Ziph, the name of a place in Palestine; also of an Israelite: Ziph.
feminine of זִיף; a flowing; Ziphah, an Israelite: Ziphah.
patrial from זִיף; a Ziphite or inhabitant of Ziph: Ziphim, Ziphite.

(Isa. 50: (feminine); and ziq; or zeq; from זָנַק; properly, what leaps forth, i.e. flash of fire, or a burning arrow; also (from the original sense of the root) a bond: chain, fetter, firebrand, spark.
probably from an unused root (akin to זִו); an olive (as yielding illuminating oil), the tree, the branch or the berry: olive (tree, -yard), Olivet.
from זַ֫יִת; olive grove; Zethan, an Israelite: Zethan.
from זָכַך; clear: clean, pure.
a primitive root (compare זָכַך); to be translucent; figuratively, to be innocent: be (make) clean, cleanse, be clear, count pure.
(Aramaic) from a root corresponding to זָכָה; purity: innocency.
from זָכָה; properly, transparency, i.e. glass: crystal.
properly, passive participle of זָכַר, but used for זָכָר; a male (of man or animals): males, men-children.
from זָכַר; mindful; Zakkur, the name of seven Israelites: Zaccur, Zacchur.
from זָכַך; pure; Zakkai, an Israelite: Zaccai.
a primitive root (compare זָכָה); to be transparent or clean (phys. or morally): be (make) clean, be pure(-r).

a primitive root; properly, to mark (so as to be recognized), i.e. to remember; by implication, to mention; also (as denominative from זָכָר) to be male: X burn (incense), X earnestly, be male, (make) mention (of), be mindful, recount, record(-er), remember, make to be remembered, bring (call, come, keep, put) to (in) remembrance, X still, think on, X well.
or zeker; from זָכַר; a memento, abstr. recollection (rarely if ever); by implication, commemoration: memorial, memory, remembrance, scent.
the same as זֵ֫כֶר; Zeker, an Israelite: Zeker.
from זָכַר; properly, remembered, i.e. a male (of man or animals, as being the most noteworthy sex): X him, male, man(child, -kind).
from זָכַר; a memento (or memorable thing, day or writing): memorial, record.
from זָכַר; memorable; Zicri, the name of twelve Israelites: Zichri.
or Zkaryahuw; from זָכַר and יָהּ; Jah has remembered; Zecarjah, the name of twenty-nine Israelites: Zachariah, Zechariah.
from זָלַל; properly, a shaking, i.e. perhaps a tempest: vilest.
by reduplication from זָלַל; tremulous, i.e. a twig: sprig.
a primitive root (compare זוּל); to shake (as in the wind), i.e. to quake; figuratively, to be loose morally, worthless or prodigal: blow down, glutton, riotous (eater), vile.
or ziliaphaph; from זָעַף; a glow (of wind or anger); also a famine (as consuming): horrible, horror, terrible.
:  : from an unused root apparently meaning to trickle, as myrrh; fragrant dropping; Zilpah, Leah's maid: Zilpah.
or zammah; from זָמַם; a plan, especially a bad one: heinous crime, lewd(-ly, -ness), mischief, purpose, thought, wicked (device, mind, -ness).
the same as זִמָּה; Zimmah, the name of two Israelites: Zimmah.
or zmorah (feminine); and zmor (masculine); from זָמַר; a twig (as pruned): vine, branch, slip.
from זָמַם; intriguing; a Zamzumite, or native tribe of Palestine: Zamzummim.
or zamir; and (feminine) zmirah; from זָמַר; a song to be accompanied with instrumental music: psalm(-ist), singing, song.
from זָמַר; a twig (as pruned): branch.
feminine of זָמִיר; song; Zemirah, an Israelite: Zemira.
a primitive root; to plan, usually in a bad sense: consider, devise, imagine, plot, purpose, think (evil).
from זָמַם; a plot: wicked device.
a primitive root; to fix (a time): appoint.
(Aramaic) corresponding to זָמַן; to agree (on a time and place): prepare.
from זָמַן; an appointed occasion: season, time.
(Aramaic) from זְמָן; the same as זְמָן: season, time.

a primitive root (perhaps ident. with זָמַר through the idea of striking with the fingers); properly, to touch the strings or parts of a musical instrument, i.e. play upon it; to make music, accompanied by the voice; hence to celebrate in song and music: give praise, sing forth praises, psalms.
a primitive root (compare זָמַר, סָמַר, צָ֫מֶר); to trim (a vine): prune.
apparently from זָמַר or זָמַר; a gazelle (from its lightly touching the ground): chamois.
(Aramaic) from a root corresponding to זָמַר; instrumental music: musick.
(Aramaic) from the same as זְמָרָא; an instrumental musician: singer.
from זָמַר; a musical piece or song to be accompanied by an instrument: melody, psalm.
from זָמַר; pruned (i.e. choice) fruit: best fruit.
from זָמַר; musical; Zimri, the name of five Israelites, and of an Arabian tribe: Zimri.
from זָמַר; musical; Zimran, a son of Abraham by Keturah: Zimran.
from זָמַר; instrumental music; by implication, praise: song.
from זוּן; properly, nourished (or fully developed), i.e. a form or sort: divers kinds, X all manner of store.
(Aramaic) corresponding to זַן; sort: kind.
a primitive root meaning to wag; used only as a denominative from זָנָב; to curtail, i.e. cut off the rear: smite the hindmost.
from זָנַב (in the original sense of flapping); the tail (literally or figuratively): tail.

a primitive root (highly-fed and therefore wanton); to commit adultery (usually of the female, and less often of simple fornication, rarely of involuntary ravishment); figuratively, to commit idolatry (the Jewish people being regarded as the spouse of Jehovah): (cause to) commit fornication, X continually, X great, (be an, play the) harlot, (cause to be, play the) whore, (commit, fall to) whoredom, (cause to) go a-whoring, whorish.
from זָנַח; rejected; Zanoach, the name of two places in Palestine: Zanoah.
from זָנָה; adultery; figuratively, idolatry: whoredom.
from זָנָה; adultery, i.e. (figuratively) infidelity, idolatry: whoredom.
regarded by some as if from זוּן or an unused root, and applied to military equipments; but evidently the feminine plural active participle of זָנָה; harlots: armour.
a primitive root meaning to push aside, i.e. reject, forsake, fail: cast away (off), remove far away (off).
a primitive root; properly, to draw together the feet (as an animal about to dart upon its prey), i.e. to spring forwardleap.
from ז֫וּעַ (in the sense of יָ֫זַע); perspiration: sweat.
by transposition for זְוָעָה; agitation, maltreatment: X removed, trouble.
from ז֫וּעַ; disquiet; Zaavan, an Idumaean: Zaavan.
from an unused root (akin (by permutation) to צָעַר), meaning to dwindle; small: little.
(Aramaic) corresponding to זְעֵיר: little.
a primitive root; to extinguish: be extinct.
a primitive root; properly, to foam at the mouth, i.e. to be enraged: abhor, abominable, (be) angry, defy, (have) indignation.
from זָעַם; strictly froth at the mouth, i.e. (figuratively) fury (especially of God's displeasure with sin): angry, indignation, rage.
a primitive root; properly, to boil up, i.e. (figuratively) to be peevish or angry: fret, sad, worse liking, be wroth.
from זָעַף; anger: indignation, rage(-ing), wrath.
from זָעַף; angry: displeased.

a primitive root; to shriek (from anguish or danger); by analogy, (as a herald) to announce or convene publiclyassemble, call (together), (make a) cry (out), come with such a company, gather (together), cause to be proclaimed.
(Aramaic) corresponding to זָעַק; to make an outcry: cry.
and (feminine) zoaqah; from זָעַק; a shriek or outcry: cry(-ing).
from an unused root (meaning to be fragrant); Ziphron, a place in Palestine: Ziphron.
from an unused root (meaning to liquify); asphalt (from its tendency to soften in the sun): pitch.
a primitive root; to be old: aged man, be (wax) old (man).
from זָקֵן; old: aged, ancient (man), elder(-est), old (man, men and...women), senator.
from זָקֵן; the beard (as indicating age): beard.
from זָקֵן; old age: age.
properly, passive participle of זָקֵן (used only in the plural as a noun); old age:-old age.
feminine of זָקֵן; old age: old (age).
a primitive root; to life, i.e. (figuratively) comfort: raise (up).
(Aramaic) corresponding to זָקַף; to hang, i.e. impale: set up.
a primitive root; to strain, (figuratively) extract, clarify: fine, pour down, purge, purify, refine.
from זָרַר (in the sense of scattering); a chaplet (as spread around the top), i.e. (specifically) a border moulding: crown.
from זוּר (in the sense of estrangement) (compare זָרָה); disgust: loathsome.
a primitive root; to flow away: wax warm.
from זָרַב and בָּבֶל; descended of (i.e. from) Babylon, i.e. born there; Zerubbabel, an Israelite: Zerubbabel.
(Aramaic) corresponding to זְרֻבָּבֶל: Zerubbabel.
from an unused root meaning to be exuberant in growth; lined with shrubbery; Zered, a brook East of the Dead Sea: Zared, Zered.
a primitive root (compare זוּר); to toss about; by implication, to diffuse, winnow: cast away, compass, disperse, fan, scatter (away), spread, strew, winnow.
or (shortened) zroao; and (feminine) zrowpah; or zrowah; from זָרַע; the arm (as stretched out), or (of animals) the foreleg; figuratively, force: arm, + help, mighty, power, shoulder, strength.
from זָרַע; something sown, i.e. a plant: sowing, thing that is sown.
by reduplication from an unused root meaning to flow; a pouring rain: water.
by reduplication from זוּר; properly, tightly girt, i.e. probably a racer, or some fleet animal (as being slender in the waist): + greyhound.
a primitive root; properly, to irradiate (or shoot forth beams), i.e. to rise (as the sun); specifically, to appear (as a symptom of leprosy): arise, rise (up), as soon as it is up.
from זָרַח; a rising of light: rising.
the same as זֶ֫רַח; Zerach, the name of three Israelites, also of an Idumaean and an Ethiopian prince: Zarah, Zerah.
patronymically from זָ֫רַח; a Zarchite or descendant of Zerach: Zarchite.
from זֶ֫רַח and יָהּ; Jah has risen: Zerachjah, the name of two Israelites: Zerahiah.
a primitive root; to gush (as water): carry away as with a flood, pour out.
from זָרַם; a gush of water: flood, overflowing, shower, storm, tempest.
feminine of זָ֫רֶם; a gushing of fluid (semen): issue.
a primitive root; to sow; figuratively, to disseminate, plant, fructify: bear, conceive seed, set with sow(-er), yield.
from זָרַע; seed; figuratively, fruit, plant, sowing-time, posterity: X carnally, child, fruitful, seed(-time), sowing- time.
(Aramaic) corresponding to זָ֫רַע; posterity: seed.
or zeraSon; from זָרַע; something sown (only in the plural), i.e. a vegetable (as food): pulse.
a primitive root; to sprinkle (fluid or solid particles): be here and there, scatter, sprinkle, strew.
a primitive root (compare זוּר); perhaps to diffuse, i.e. (specifically) to sneeze: sneeze.
of Persian origin; Zeresh, Haman's wife: Zeresh.
from זָרָה; the spread of the fingers, i.e. a span: span.
of uncertain derivation; Zattu, an Israelite: Zattu.
apparently a variation for זֵיתָן; Zetham, an & Israelite: Zetham.
of Persian origin; Zethar, a eunuch of Xerxes: Zethar.
by contraction from חָבַב; properly, a cherisher, i.e. the bosom: bosom.
a primitive root (compare חָבַב); to secrete: X held, hide (self), do secretly.
a primitive root (compare חָבָא, חָבָה); properly, to hide (as in the bosom), i.e. to cherish (with affection): love.
from חָבַב; cherished; Chobab, father-in-law of Moses: Hobab.
a primitive root (compare חָבַב); to secrete: hide (self).
(Aramaic) from חֲבַל; properly, overthrown, i.e. (morally) crime: hurt.
from חָבַר; united; Chabor, a river of Assyria: Habor.
or chabburah; or chaburah; from חָבַר; properly, bound (with stripes), i.e. a weal (or black-and-blue mark itself): blueness, bruise, hurt, stripe, wound.
a primitive root; to knock out or off: beat (off, out), thresh.
or Chabayah; from חָבָה and יָהּ; Jah has hidden; Chabajah, an Israelite: Habaiah.
from חָבָה; a concealment: hiding.

a primitive root; to wind tightly (as a rope), i.e. to bind; specifically, by a pledge; figuratively, to pervert, destroy; also to writhe in pain (especially of parturition): X at all, band, bring forth, (deal) corrupt(-ly), destroy, offend, lay & to (take a) pledge, spoil, travail, X very, withhold.
(Aramaic) corresponding to חָבַל; to ruin: destroy, hurt.

or chebel; from חָבַל; a rope (as twisted), especially a measuring line; by implication, a district or inheritance (as measured); or a noose (as of cords); figuratively, a company (as if tied together); also a throe (especially of parturition); also ruin: band, coast, company, cord, country, destruction, line, lot, pain, pang, portion, region, rope, snare, sorrow, tackling.
(Aramaic) from חֲבַל; harm (personal or pecuniary): damage, hurt.
or (feminine) chabolah; from חָבַל; a pawn (as security for debt): pledge.
active participle from חָבַל (in the sense of handling ropes); a sailor: pilot, shipmaster.
from חָבַל (in the sense of furnished with ropes); a mast: mast.
of uncertain derivation; probably meadow-saffron: rose.
of uncertain derivation; Chabatstsanjah, a Rechabite: Habazaniah.
a primitive root; to clasp (the hands or in embrace): embrace, fold.
from חָבַק; a clasping of the hands (in idleness): fold.
by reduplication from חָבַק; embrace; Chabakkuk, the prophet: Habakkuk.

a primitive root; to join (literally or figuratively); specifically (by means of spells) to fascinate: charm(- er), be compact, couple (together), have fellowship with, heap up, join (self, together), league.
from חָבַר; a society; also a spell: + charmer(- ing), company, enchantment, X wide.
the same as חָ֫בֶר; community; Cheber, the name of a Kenite and of three Israelites: Heber.
(Aramaic) from a root corresponding to חָבַר; an associate: companion, fellow.
from חָבַר; an associate: companion, fellow, knit together.
from חָבַר; a partner: companion.
by reduplication from חָבַר; a streak (like a line), as on the tiger: spot.
(Aramaic) feminine of חַבְרִין; an associate: other.
feminine of חָ֫בֶר; association: company.
from חָ֫בֶר; seat of association; Chebron, a place in Palestine, also the name of two Israelites: Hebron.
or Chebroniy; patronymically from חֶבְרוֹן; Chebronite (collectively), an inhabitant of Chebron: Hebronites.
patronymically from חָ֫בֶר; a Chebrite (collectively) or descendants of Cheber: Heberites.
feminine of חָבֵר; a consort: companion.
feminine active participle of חָבַר; a joint: which coupleth, coupling.
a primitive root; to wrap firmly (especially a turban, compress, or saddle); figuratively, to stop, to rule: bind (up), gird about, govern, healer, put, saddle, wrap about.
from an unused root probably meaning to cook (compare מַחֲבַת); something fried, probably a griddle-cake: pan.
or chag; from חָגַג; a festival, or a victim therefor: (solemn) feast (day), sacrifice, solemnity.
from an unused root meaning to revolve (compare חָגַג); properly, vertigo, i.e. (figuratively) fear: terror.
of uncertain derivation; a locust: locust.
the same as חָגָב; locust; Chagab, one of the Nethinim: Hagab.
or Chagabah; feminine of חָגָב; locust; Chagaba or Chagabah, one of the Nethinim: Hagaba, Hagabah.

a primitive root (compare חָגָּא, חוּג); properly, to move in a circle, i.e. (specifically) to march in a sacred procession, to observe a festival; by implication, to be giddy: celebrate, dance, (keep, hold) a (solemn) feast (holiday), reel to and fro.
from an unused root meaning to take refuge; a rift in rocks: cleft.
from חָגַר; belted: girded with.
or chagor; and (feminine) chagowrah; or chagorah; from חָגַר; a belt (for the waist): apron, armour, gird(-le).
from חָגַג; festive, Chaggi, an Israelite; also (patronymically) a Chaggite, or descendant of the same: Haggi, Haggites.
from חָג; festive; Chaggai, a Heb. prophet: Haggai.
from חָג and יָהּ; festival of Jah; Chaggijah, an Israelite: Haggiah.
feminine of חַגִּי; festive; Chaggith, a wife of David: Haggith.
of uncertain derivation; probably a partridge; Choglah, an Israelitess: Hoglah. See also בֵּית חָגְלָה.
a primitive root; to gird on (as a belt, armor, etc.): be able to put on, be afraid, appointed, gird, restrain, X on every side.
abridged from אֶחָד; one: one.
(Aramaic) corresponding to חַד; as card. one; as article single; as an ordinal, first; adverbially, at once: a, first, one, together.
from חָדַד; sharp: sharp.
a primitive root; to be (causatively, make) sharp or (figuratively) severe: be fierce, sharpen.
from חָדַד; fierce; Chadad, an Ishmaelite: Hadad.
a primitive root; to rejoice: make glad, be joined, rejoice.
from חָדַד; a point: sharp.
from חָדָה; rejoicing: gladness, joy.
(Aramaic) corresponding to חֶדְוָה: joy.
(Aramaic) corresponding to חָזֶה; a breast: breast.
from חָדַד; a peak; Chadid, a place in Palestine: Hadid.
a primitive root; properly, to be flabby, i.e. (by implication) desist; (figuratively) be lacking or idle: cease, end, fall, forbear, forsake, leave (off), let alone, rest, be unoccupied, want.
from חָדַל; rest, i.e. the state of the dead: world.
from חָדַל; vacant, i.e. ceasing or destitute: he that forbeareth, frail, rejected.
from חָ֫דֶל; idle; Chadlai, an Israelite: Hadlai.
from an unused root meaning to sting; a prickly plant: brier, thorn.
probably of foreign origin; the Chiddekel (or Tigris) river: Hiddekel.
a primitive root; properly, to inclose (as a room), i.e. (by analogy,) to beset (as in a siege): enter a privy chamber.
from חָדַר; an apartment (usually literal): ((bed) inner)chamber, innermost(-ward) part, parlour, + south, X within.
another form for חֶ֫דֶר; chamber; Chadar, an Ishmaelite: Hadar.
of uncertain derivation; Chadrak, a Syrian deity: Hadrach.
a primitive root; to be new; causatively, to rebuild: renew, repair.
from חָדַשׁ; new: fresh, new thing.
from חָדַשׁ; the new moon; by implication, a month: month(-ly), new moon.
the same as חֹ֫דֶשׁ; Chodesh, an Israelitess: Hodesh.
feminine of חָדָשׁ; new; Chadashah, a place in Palestine: Hadashah.
(Aramaic) corresponding to חָדָשׁ; new: new.
(Aramaic) corresponding to חָוָה; to show: shew.
also chayab; a primitive root; properly, perhaps to tie, i.e. (figuratively and reflexively) to owe, or (by implication) to forfeit: make endanger.
from חוּב; debt: debtor.
feminine active participle of חָבָה; hiding place; Chobah, a place in Syria: Hobah.
a primitive root (compare חָגַג); to describe a circle: compass.
from חוּג; a circle: circle, circuit, compass.
a primitive root; properly, to tie a knot, i.e. (figuratively) to propound a riddle: put forth.
a primitive root; (compare חֲוָא, חָיָה); properly, to live; by implication (intensively) to declare or show: show.
causatively from חָוָה; life-giver; Chavvah (or Eve), the first woman: Eve.
properly, the same as חַוָּה (life-giving, i.e. living-place); by implication, an encampment or village: (small) town.
from the plural of חַוֹּת and a modification of יָעוּר; hamlets of Jair, a region of Palestine: (Bashan-)Havoth-jair.
from חֹזֶה; visionary; Chozai, an Israelite: the seers.
from an unused root apparently meaning to pierce; a thorn; by analogy, a ring for the nose: bramble, thistle, thorn.
perhaps the same as ח֫וֹחַ; a dell or crevice (as if pierced in the earth): thicket.
(Aramaic) corresponding to the root of חוּט, perhaps as a denominative; to string together, i.e. (figuratively) to repair: join.
from an unused root probably meaning to sew; a string; by implication, a measuring tape: cord, fillet, line, thread.
perhaps from חַוֹּת; a villager; a Chivvite, one of the aboriginal tribes of Palestine: Hivite.
probably from חוּל; circular; Chavilah, the name of two or three eastern regions; also perhaps of two men: Havilah.

or chiyl; a primitive root; properly, to twist or whirl (in a circular or spiral manner), i.e. (specifically) to dance, to writhe in pain (especially of parturition) or fear; figuratively, to wait, to pervert: bear, (make to) bring forth, (make to) calve, dance, drive away, fall grievously (with pain), fear, form, great, grieve, (be) grievous, hope, look, make, be in pain, be much (sore) pained, rest, shake, shapen, (be) sorrow(-ful), stay, tarry, travail (with pain), tremble, trust, wait carefully (patiently), be wounded.
from חוּל; a circle; Chul, a son of Aram; also the region settled by him: Hul.
from חוּל; sand (as round or whirling particles): sand.
from an unused root meaning to be warm, i.e. (by implication) sunburnt or swarthy (blackish): brown.
feminine active participle of an unused root apparently meaning to join; a wall of protection: wall, walled.
a primitive root; properly, to cover, i.e. (figuratively) to compassionate: pity, regard, spare.
from an unused root meaning to cover; a cove (as a sheltered bay): coast (of the sea), haven, shore, (sea-)side.
from the same as חוֹף; protection: Chupham, an Israelite: Hupham.
patronymically from חוּפָם; a Chuphamite or descendant of Chupham: Huphamites.

or (shortened) chuts; (both forms feminine in the plural) from an unused root meaning to sever; properly, separate by a wall, i.e. outside, outdoors: abroad, field, forth, highway, more, out(-side, -ward), street, without.
or (shortened) chur; from an unused root probably meaning to bore; the crevice of a serpent; the cell of a prison: hole.
from חָוַר; white linen: white.
the same as חוּר or חֻר; Chur, the name of four Israelites and one Midianite: Hur.
the same as חוּר; white linen: network. Compare חֹרִים.
or (shortened) chor; the same as חֻר; a cavity, socket, den: cave, hole.
a primitive root; to blanch (as with shame): wax pale.
(Aramaic) from a root corresponding to חָוַר; white: white.
probably from חוּר; linen-worker; Churi, an Israelite: Huri.
probably an orthographical variation for חוּרִי; Churai, an Israelite: Hurai.
probably from חוּר; whiteness, i.e. noble; Churam, the name of an Israelite and two Syrians: Huram. Compare חִירָם.
apparently from חָוַר (in the sense of חֻר); cavernous; Chavran, a region East of the Jordan: Hauran.
a primitive root; to hurry; figuratively, to be eager with excitement or enjoyment: (make) haste(-n), ready.
from חוּשׁ; haste; Chushah, an Israelite: Hushah.
from חוּשׁ; hasty; Chushai, an Israelite: Hushai.
or Chushiym; or Chushim; plural from חוּשׁ; hasters; Chushim, the name of three Israelites: Hushim.
or Chusham; from חוּשׁ; hastily; Chusham, an Idumaean: Husham.
or chotham; from חָתַם; a signature-ring: seal, signet.
the same as חוֹתָם; seal; Chotham, the name of two Israelites: Hotham, Hothan.
(Aramaic) or chazah (Aramaic); corresponding to חָזָה; to gaze upon; mentally to dream, be usual (i.e. seem): behold, have (a dream), see, be wont.
or Chazahoel; from חָזָה and אֵל; God has seen; Chazael, a king of Syria: Hazael.
a primitive root; to gaze at; mentally, to perceive, contemplate (with pleasure); specifically, to have a vision of: behold, look, prophesy, provide, see.
from חָזָה; the breast (as most seen in front): breast.
active participle of חָזָה; a beholder in vision; also a compact (as looked upon with approval): agreement, prophet, see that, seer, (star-)gazer.
from חָזָה; seer; Chazo, a nephew of Abraham: Hazo.
(Aramaic) from חֲזָה; a sight: look, vision.
from חָזָה; a sight (mentally), i.e. a dream, revelation, or oracle: vision.
from חָזָה; a revelation: vision.
(Aramaic) from חֲזָה; a view: sight.
from חָזָה; a look; hence (figuratively) striking appearance, revelation, or (by implication) compact: agreement, notable (one), vision.
from חָזָה and אֵל; seen of God; Chaziel, a Levite: Haziel.
from חָזָה and יָהּ; Jah has seen; Chazajah, an Israelite: Hazaiah.
from חָזָה; vision; Chezjon, a Syrian: Hezion.
from חָזָה; a revelation, expectation by dream: vision.
from an unused root meaning to glare; a flash of lightning: bright cloud, lightning.
from an unused root probably meaning to enclose; a hog (perhaps as penned): boar, swine.
from the same as חֲזִיר; perhaps protected; Chezir, the name of two Israelites: Hezir.

a primitive root; to fasten upon; hence, to seize, be strong (figuratively, courageous, causatively strengthen, cure, help, repair, fortify), obstinate; to bind, restrain, conquer: aid, amend, X calker, catch, cleave, confirm, be constant, constrain, continue, be of good (take) courage(-ous, -ly), encourage (self), be established, fasten, force, fortify, make hard, harden, help, (lay) hold (fast), lean, maintain, play the man, mend, become (wax) mighty, prevail, be recovered, repair, retain, seize, be (wax) sore, strengthen (self), be stout, be (make, shew, wax) strong(-er), be sure, take (hold), be urgent, behave self valiantly, withstand.
from חָזַק; strong (usu. in a bad sense, hard, bold, violent): harder, hottest, + impudent, loud, mighty, sore, stiff(-hearted), strong(-er).
from חָזַק; powerful: X wax louder, stronger.
from חָזַק; help: strength.
from חָזַק; power: strength.
feminine of חֵ֫זֶק; prevailing power: strength(- en self), (was) strong.
feminine of חֹ֫זֶק; vehemence (usually in a bad sense): force, mightily, repair, sharply.
from חָזַק; strong; Chizki, an Israelite: Hezeki.

or Chizqiyahuw; also Ychizqiyah; or Ychizqiyahuw; from חָזַק and יָהּ; strengthened of Jah; Chizkijah, a king of Judah, also the name of two other Israelites: Hezekiah, Hizkiah, Hizkijah. Compare יְחִזְקִיָּה.
once (Ezek. 29:4) chachiy; from the same as ח֫וֹחַ; a ring for the nose (or lips): bracelet, chain, hook.

a primitive root; properly, to miss; hence (figuratively and generally) to sin; by inference, to forfeit, lack, expiate, repent, (causatively) lead astray, condemn: bear the blame, cleanse, commit (sin), by fault, harm he hath done, loss, miss, (make) offend(-er), offer for sin, purge, purify (self), make reconciliation, (cause, make) sin(-ful, -ness), trespass.
from חָטָא; a crime or its penalty: fault, X grievously, offence, (punishment of) sin.
intensively from חָטָא; a criminal, or one accounted guilty: offender, sinful, sinner.
feminine of חֵטְא; an offence, or a sacrifice for it: sin (offering).
(Aramaic) corresponding to חֲטָאָה; an offence, and the penalty or sacrifice for it: sin (offering).

or chattacth; from חָטָא; an offence (sometimes habitual sinfulness), and its penalty, occasion, sacrifice, or expiation; also (concretely) an offender: punishment (of sin), purifying(-fication for sin), sin(-ner, offering).
a primitive root; to chop or carve wood: cut down, hew(-er), polish.
feminine passive participle of חָטַב; properly, a carving; hence, a tapestry (as figured): carved.
of uncertain derivation; wheat, whether the grain or the plant: wheat(-en).
from an unused root of uncertain signification; Chattush, the name of four or five Israelites: Hattush.
(Aramaic) from a root corresponding to חָטָא; an offence: sin.
(Aramaic) from the same as חֲטֵי; an expiation: sin offering.
from an unused root apparently meaning to dig out; explorer; Chatita, a temple porter: Hatita.
from an unused root apparently meaning to wave; fluctuating; Chattil, one of "Solomon's servants": Hattil.
from חָטַף; robber; Chatipha, one of the Nethinim: Hatipha.
a primitive root; to stop: refrain.
a primitive root; to clutch; hence, to seize as a prisoner: catch.
from an unused root of uncertain signification; a twig: rod.

from חָיָה; alive; hence, raw (flesh); fresh (plant, water, year), strong; also (as noun, especially in the feminine singular and masculine plural) life (or living thing), whether literally or figuratively: + age, alive, appetite, (wild) beast, company, congregation, life(-time), live(-ly), living (creature, thing), maintenance, + merry, multitude, + (be) old, quick, raw, running, springing, troop.
(Aramaic) from חֲיָא; alive; also (as noun in plural) life: life, that liveth, living.
(Aramaic) or chayah (Aramaic); corresponding to חָיָה; to live: live, keep alive.
from חָי and אֵל; living of God; Chiel, an Israelite: Hiel.
from חוּד; a puzzle, hence, a trick, conundrum, sententious maxim: dark saying (sentence, speech), hard question, proverb, riddle.

a primitive root (compare חָוָה, חָיָה); to live, whether literally or figuratively; causatively, to revive: keep (leave, make) alive, X certainly, give (promise) life, (let, suffer to) live, nourish up, preserve (alive), quicken, recover, repair, restore (to life), revive, (X God) save (alive, life, lives), X surely, be whole.
from חָיָה; vigorous: lively.
(Aramaic) from חֲיָא; an animal: beast.
from חָיָה; life: X living.
a primitive root (compare חָיָה); to live; causatively to revive: live, save life.
or (shortened) chel; a collateral form of חָ֫יִל; an army; also (by analogy,) an intrenchment: army, bulwark, host, + poor, rampart, trench, wall.
and (feminine) chiylah; from חוּל; a throe (expectant of childbirth): pain, pang, sorrow.

from חוּל; probably a force, whether of men, means or other resources; an army, wealth, virtue, valor, strength: able, activity, (+) army, band of men (soldiers), company, (great) forces, goods, host, might, power, riches, strength, strong, substance, train, (+)valiant(-ly), valour, virtuous(-ly), war, worthy(-ily).
(Aramaic) corresponding to חָ֫יִל; an army, or strength: aloud, army, X most (mighty), power.
feminine of חָ֫יִל; an intrenchment: bulwark.
or Cheleam; from חָ֫יִל; fortress; Chelam, a place East of Palestine: Helam.
from חָ֫יִל; fortress; Chilen, a place in Palestine: Hilen.
another form for חֵן; beauty: comely.
another form for חוּץ; a wall: wall.
from חַ֫יִץ; properly, the (outer) wall side; hence, exterior; figuratively, secular (as opposed to sacred): outer, outward, utter, without.
or cheq; and chowq; from an unused root, apparently meaning to inclose; the bosom (literally or figuratively): bosom, bottom, lap, midst, within.
from חָוַר in the sense of splendor; Chirah, an Adullamite: Hirah.
or Chiyrowm; another form of חוּרָם; Chiram or Chirom, the name of two Tyrians: Hiram, Huram.
another form of חוּשׁ; to hurry: make haste.
from חִישׁ; properly, a hurry; hence (adverb) quickly: soon.
probably from חָנַך in the sense of tasting; properly, the palate or inside of the mouth; hence, the mouth itself (as the organ of speech, taste and kissing): (roof of the) mouth, taste.
a primitive root (apparently akin to חָקָה through the idea of piercing); properly, to adhere to; hence, to await: long, tarry, wait.
probably from חָכָה; a hook (as adhering): angle, hook.
from the same as חַכְלִיל; dark; Chakilah, a hill in Palestine: Hachilah.
(Aramaic) from a root corresponding to חָכַם; wise, i.e. a Magian: wise.
from the base of חַכְלִיל and יָהּ; darkness of Jah; Chakaljah, an Israelite: Hachaliah.
by reduplication from an unused root apparently meaning to be dark; darkly flashing (only of the eyes); in a good sense, brilliant (as stimulated by wine): red.
from חַכְלִיל; flash (of the eyes); in a bad sense, blearedness: redness.
a primitive root, to be wise (in mind, word or act): X exceeding, teach wisdom, be (make self, shew self) wise, deal (never so) wisely, make wiser.
from חָכַם; wise, (i.e. intelligent, skilful or artful): cunning (man), subtil, ((un-)), wise((hearted), man).
from חָכַם; wisdom (in a good sense): skilful, wisdom, wisely, wit.
(Aramaic) corresponding to חָכְמָה; wisdom: wisdom.
from חָכַם; skilful; Chakmoni, an Israelite: Hachmoni, Hachmonite.
or chakmowth; collateral forms of חָכְמָה; wisdom: wisdom, every wise (woman).
from חָלַל; properly, exposed; hence, profane: common, profane (place), unholy.
a primitive root (compare חָלָה); to be sick: be diseased.
from חָלָא; properly, disease; hence, rust: scum.
the same as חֶלְאַת; Chelah, an Israelitess: Helah.
or cheleb; from an unused root meaning to be fat; fat, whether literally or figuratively; hence, the richest or choice part: X best, fat(-ness), X finest, grease, marrow.
the same as חֵ֫לֶב; fatness; Cheleb, an Israelite: Heleb.
from the same as חֵ֫לֶב; milk (as the richness of kine): + cheese, milk, sucking.
feminine of חֵ֫לֶב; fertility: Chelbah, a place in Palestine: Helbah.
from חֵ֫לֶב; fruitful; Chelbon, a place in Syria: Helbah.
from חֵ֫לֶב; galbanam, an odorous gum (as if fatty): galbanum.
from an unused root apparently meaning to glide swiftly; life (as a fleeting portion of time); hence, the world (as transient): age, short time, world.
the same as חֶ֫לֶד; Cheled, an Israelite: Heled.
from the same as חֶ֫לֶד; a weasel (from its gliding motion): weasel.
feminine of חֹ֫לֶד; Chuldah, an Israelitess: Huldah.
from חֵ֫לֶד; worldliness; Cheldai, the name of two Israelites: Heldai.

a primitive root (compare חוּל, חָלָה, חָלַל); properly, to be rubbed or worn; hence (figuratively) to be weak, sick, afflicted; or (causatively) to grieve, make sick; also to stroke (in flattering), entreat: beseech, (be) diseased, (put to) grief, be grieved, (be) grievous, infirmity, intreat, lay to, put to pain, X pray, make prayer, be (fall, make) sick, sore, be sorry, make suit (X supplication), woman in travail, be (become) weak, be wounded.
from חָלַל; a cake (as usually punctured): cake.
or (shortened) chalom; from חָלַם; a dream: dream(-er).
or (shortened) Cholon; probably from חוֹל; sandy; Cholon, the name of two places in Palestine: Holon.
a window (as perforated): window.
from חָלַף; properly, surviving; by implication (collectively) orphans: X destruction.
feminine passive participle of חָלַשׁ; defeat: being overcome.
probably of foreign origin; Chalach, a region of Assyria: Halah.
by reduplication from חוּל; contorted; Chalchul, a place in Palestine: Halhul.
feminine from the same as חַלְחוּל; writhing (in childbirth); by implication, terror: (great, much) pain.
a primitive root; to snatch at: catch.
from חָלָה; a trinket (as polished): jewel, ornament.
the same as חֲלִי; Chali, a place in Palestine: Hali.
from חָלָה; malady, anxiety, calamity: disease, grief, (is) sick(-ness).
feminine of חֲלִי; a trinket: jewel.
from חָלַל; a flute (as perforated): pipe.
or chalilah; a directive from חָלַל; literal for a profaned thing; used (interj.) far be it!: be far, (X God) forbid.
from חָלַף; alternation: change, course.
from חָ֫לֶץ; spoil: armour.
or chelkah; apparently from an unused root probably meaning to be dark or (figuratively) unhappy; a wretch, i.e. unfortunate: poor.

a primitive root (compare חָלָה); properly, to bore, i.e. (by implication) to wound, to dissolve; figuratively, to profane (a person, place or thing), to break (one's word), to begin (as if by an "opening wedge"); denom. (from חָלִיל) to play (the flute): begin (X men began), defile, X break, defile, X eat (as common things), X first, X gather the grape thereof, X take inheritance, pipe, player on instruments, pollute, (cast as) profane (self), prostitute, slay (slain), sorrow, stain, wound.
from חָלַל; pierced (especially to death); figuratively, polluted: kill, profane, slain (man), X slew, (deadly) wounded.

a primitive root; properly, to bind firmly, i.e. (by implication) to be (causatively to make) plump; also (through the figurative sense of dumbness) to dream: (cause to) dream(-er), be in good liking, recover.
(Aramaic) from a root corresponding to חָלַם; a dream: dream.
from חָלַם; a dream; Chelem, an Israelite: Helem. Compare חֶלְדַּי.
from חָלַם (in the sense of insipidity); probably purslain: egg.
probably from חָלַם (in the sense of hardness); flint: flint(-y), rock.
from חָ֫יִל; strong; Chelon, an Israelite: Helon.

a primitive root; properly, to slide by, i.e. (by implication) to hasten away, pass on, spring up, pierce or change: abolish, alter, change, cut off, go on forward, grow up, be over, pass (away, on, through), renew, sprout, strike through.
(Aramaic) corresponding to חָלַף; to pass on (of time): pass.
from חָלַף; properly, exchange; hence (as preposition) instead of: X for.
the same as חֵ֫לֶף; change; Cheleph, a place in Palestine: Heleph.

a primitive root; to pull off; hence (intensively) to strip, (reflex.) to depart; by implication, to deliver, equip (for fight); present, strengthen: arm (self), (go, ready) armed (X man, soldier), deliver, draw out, make fat, loose, (ready) prepared, put off, take away, withdraw self.
or Chelets; from חָלַץ; perhaps, strength; Chelets, the name of two Israelites: Helez.
from חָלַץ (in the sense of strength); only in the dual; the loins (as the seat of vigor): loins, reins.

a primitive root; to be smooth (figuratively); by implication (as smooth stones were used for lots) to apportion or separate: deal, distribute, divide, flatter, give, (have, im-)part(-ner), take away a portion, receive, separate self, (be) smooth(-er).
from חָלַק; properly, smoothness (of the tongue); also an allotment: flattery, inheritance, part, X partake, portion.
the same as חֵ֫לֶק; portion; Chelek, an Israelite: Helek.
(Aramaic) from a root corresponding to חָלַק; a part: portion.
from חָלַק; smooth (especially of tongue): flattering, smooth.
the same as חָלָק; bare; Chalak, a mountain of Idumaea: Halak.
from חָלַק; smooth: smooth.
from חָלַק; smooth: smooth.

feminine of חֵ֫לֶק; properly, smoothness; figuratively, flattery; also an allotment: field, flattering(-ry), ground, parcel, part, piece of land (ground), plat, portion, slippery place, smooth (thing).
feminine from חָלַק; flattery: flattery.
feminine of חַלֻּקֵי; a distribution: division.
patronymically from חֵ֫לֶק; a Chelkite or descendant of Chelek: Helkites.
from חָלַק; apportioned; Chelkai, an Israelite: Helkai.
or Chilqiyahuw from חֵ֫לֶק and יָהּ; portion of Jah; Chilhijah, the name of eight IsraelitesHillkiah.
by reduplication from חָלַק; properly, something very smooth; i.e. a treacherous spot; figuratively, blandishment: flattery, slippery.
a form of חֶלְקָה; smoothness; Chelkath, a place in Palestine: Helkath.
from חֶלְקָת and the plural of צוּר, with the article inserted; smoothness of the rocks; Chelkath Hats-tsurim, a place in Palestine: Helkath-hazzurim.
a primitive root; to prostrate; by implication, to overthrow, decay: discomfit, waste away, weaken.
from חָלַשׁ; frail: weak.
from the same as חוֹמָה; a father-in-law (as in affinity): father in law.
from חָמַם; hot: hot, warm.
the same as חָם; hot (from the tropical habitat); Cham, a son of Noah; also (as a patronymic) his descendants or their country: Ham.
from חָמַם; heat: heat, to be hot (warm).
(Aramaic) or chamah (Aramaic); corresponding to חֵמָה; anger: fury.
or (shortened) chemah; from the same root as חוֹמָה; curdled milk or cheese: butter.
a primitive root; to delight in: beauty, greatly beloved, covet, delectable thing, (X great) delight, desire, goodly, lust, (be) pleasant (thing), precious (thing).
om חָמַד; delight: desirable, pleasant.
feminine of חֶ֫מֶד; delight: desire, goodly, pleasant, precious.
from חֶ֫מֶד; pleasant; Chemdan, an Idumaean: Hemdan.
or (Dan. 11:44) chemaC; from יָחַם; heat; figuratively, anger, poison (from its fever): anger, bottles, hot displeasure, furious(-ly, -ry), heat, indignation, poison, rage, wrath(- ful). See חֶמְאָה.
from חָם; heat; by implication, the sun: heat, sun.
from חַמָּה and אֵל; anger of God; Chammuel, an Israelite: Hamuel.
or Chamiytal; from חָם and טָל; father-in-law of dew; Chamutal or Chamital, an IsraelitessHamutal.
from חָמַל; pitied; Chamul, an Israelite: Hamul.
