patronymically from חָמוּל: a Chamulite (collectively) or descendants of Chamul: Hamulites.
from חָמַם; warm spring; Chammon, the name of two places in Palestine: Hammon.
from חָמֵץ; properly, violent; by implication, a robber: oppressed.
from חָמַק; a wrapping, i.e. drawers: joints.
or (shortened) chamor; from חָמַר; a male ass (from its dun red): (he)ass.
the same as חֲמוֹר; donkey; Chamor, a Canaanite: Hamor.
or (shortened) chamoth; feminine of חָם; a mother-in-law: mother in law.
from an unused root probably meaning, to lie low; a lizard (as creeping): snail.
feminine of חֹ֫מֶט; low; Chumtah, a place in Palestine: Humtah.
from חָמֵץ; seasoned, i.e. salt provender: clean.
or chamishshiy; ord. from חָמֵשׁ; fifth; also a fifth: fifth (part).
a primitive root; to commiserate; by implication, to spare: have compassion, (have) pity, spare.
from חָמַל; commiseration: merciful, pity.
a primitive root; to be hot (literally or figuratively): enflame self, get (have) heat, be (wax) hot, (be, wax) warm (self, at).
from חַמָּה; a sun-pillar: idol, image.
a primitive root; to be violent; by implication, to maltreat: make bare, shake off, violate, do violence, take away violently, wrong, imagine wrongfully.
from חָמַס; violence; by implication, wrong; by meton. unjust gain: cruel(-ty), damage, false, injustice, X oppressor, unrighteous, violence (against, done), violent (dealing), wrong.
a primitive root; to be pungent; i.e. in taste (sour, i.e. literally fermented, or figuratively, harsh), in color (dazzling): cruel (man), dyed, be grieved, leavened.
from חָמֵץ; ferment, (figuratively) extortion: leaven, leavened (bread).
from חָמֵץ; vinegar: vinegar.
a primitive root; properly, to wrap; hence, to depart (i.e. turn about): go about, withdraw self.
a primitive root; properly, to boil up; hence, to ferment (with scum); to glow (with redness); as denominative (from חֵמָר) to smear with pitch: daub, befoul, be red, trouble.
from חָמַר; wine (as fermenting): X pure, red wine.
(Aramaic) corresponding to חָ֫מֶר; wine: wine.
from חָמַר; properly, a bubbling up, i.e. of water, a wave; of earth, mire or clay (cement); also a heap; hence, a chomer or dry measure: clay, heap, homer, mire, motion.
from חָמַר; bitumen (as rising to the surface): slime(-pit).
from חָמַר (compare חֹ֫מֶר); a heap: heap.
from חָמַר; red; Chamran, an Idumaean: Amran.
a denominative from חָמֵשׁ; to tax a fifth:--take up the fifth participle
masculine chamishshah; a primitive numeral; five: fif(-teen), fifth, five (X apiece).
from חִמֵּשׁ; a fifth tax:--fifth participle
from an unused root probably meaning, to be stout; the abdomen (as obese): fifth (rib).
passive participle of the same as חֹ֫מֶשׁ; staunch, i.e. able-bodied soldiers: armed (men), harnessed.
multiple of חָמֵשׁ; fifty: fifty.
from the same as חוֹמָה; a skin bottle (as tied up): bottle.
from the same as חוֹמָה; walled; Chamath, a place in Syria: Hamath, Hemath.
a variation for the first part of חַמֹּת דֹּאר; hot springs; Chammath, a place in Palestine: Hammath.
from the plural of חַמָּה and דֹּאר; hot springs of Dor; Chammath-Dor, a place in Palestine: Hamath-Dor.
patrial from חֲמָת; a Chamathite or native of Chamath: Hamathite.
from חֲמָת and צוֹבָה; Chamath of Tsobah; Chamath-Tsobah; probably the same as חֲמָת: Hamath-Zobah.
from חֲמָת and רַבָּה; Chamath of Rabbah; Chamath-Rabbah, probably the same as חֲמָת.
from חָנַן; graciousness, i.e. subjective (kindness, favor) or objective (beauty): favour, grace(-ious), pleasant, precious, (well-)favoured.
the same as חֵן; grace; Chen, a figurative name for an Israelite: Hen.
probably from חֵן and הֲדָד; favor of Hadad; Chenadad, an Israelite: Henadad.

a primitive root (compare חָנַן); properly, to incline; by implication, to decline (of the slanting rays of evening); specifically, to pitch a tent; gen. to encamp (for abode or siege): abide (in tents), camp, dwell, encamp, grow to an end, lie, pitch (tent), rest in tent.
from חָנַן; favored; Channah, an Israelitess: Hannah.
from חָנַך; initiated; Chanok, an antediluvian patriach: Enoch.
from חָנַן; favored; Chanun, the name of an Ammonite and of two Israelites: Hanun.
from חָנַן; gracious: gracious.
from חָנָה; properly, a vault or cell (with an arch); by implication, a prison: cabin.
from חָנַן (in the sense of prayer); supplication: be gracious, intreated.
a primitive root; to spice; by implication, to embalm; also to ripen: embalm, put forth.
(Aramaic) corresponding to חִטִּים; wheat: wheat.
from חָנַן and אֵל; favor of God; Channiel, the name of two Israelites: Hanniel.
from חָנַך; initiated; i.e. practiced: trained.
from חָנַן; graciousness: favour.
from חָנָה; a lance (for thrusting, like pitching a tent): javelin, spear.
a primitive root; properly, to narrow (compare חָנַק); figuratively, to initiate or discipline: dedicate, train up.
(Aramaic) corresponding to חֲנֻכָּה; consecration: dedication.
from חָנַך; initiation, i.e. consecration: dedicating(-tion).
patronymically from חֲנוֹך; a Chanokite (collectively) or descendants of Chanok: Hanochites.
from חֵן; gratis, i.e. devoid of cost, reason or advantage: without a cause (cost, wages), causeless, to cost nothing, free(-ly), innocent, for nothing (nought, in vain.
probably by orthographical variation for חֲנַנְאֵל; Chanamel, an Israelite: Hanameel.
of uncertain derivation; perhaps the aphis or plantlouse: frost.

a primitive root (compare חָנָה); properly, to bend or stoop in kindness to an inferior; to favor, bestow; causatively to implore (i.e. move to favor by petition): beseech, X fair, (be, find, shew) favour(-able), be (deal, give, grant (gracious(-ly), intreat, (be) merciful, have (shew) mercy (on, upon), have pity upon, pray, make supplication, X very.
(Aramaic) corresponding to חָנַן; to favor or (causatively) to entreat: shew mercy, make supplication.
from חָנַן; favor; Chanan, the name of seven Israelites: Canan.
from חָנַן and אֵל; God has favored; Chananel, probably an Israelite, from whom a tower of Jerusalem was named: Hananeel.
from חָנַן; gracious; Chanani, the name of six Israelites: Hanani.
or Chananyahuw; from חָנַן and יָהּ; Jah has favored; Chananjah, the name of thirteen Israelites: Hananiah.
of Egyptian derivation; Chanes, a place in Egypt: Hanes.
a primitive root; to soil, especially in a moral sense: corrupt, defile, X greatly, pollute, profane.
from חָנֵף; soiled (i.e. with sin), impioushypocrite(-ical).
from חָנֵף; moral filth, i.e. wickedness: hypocrisy.
feminine from חָנֵף; impiety: profaneness.
a primitive root (compare חָנַך); to be narrow; by implication, to throttle, or (reflex.) to choke oneself to death (by a rope): hang self, strangle.
probably from חָנַן; favored; Channathon, a place in Palestine: Hannathon.

a primitive root; properly, perhaps to bow (the neck only (compare חָנַן) in courtesy to an equal), i.e. to be kind; also (by euphem. (compare בָּרַך), but rarely) to reprove: shew self merciful, put to shame.

from חָסַד; kindness; by implication (towards God) piety: rarely (by opposition) reproof, or (subject.) beauty: favour, good deed(-liness, -ness), kindly, (loving-)kindness, merciful (kindness), mercy, pity, reproach, wicked thing.
the same as חָ֫סֶד: favor; Chesed, an Israelite: Hesed.
from חָ֫סֶד and יָהּ; Jah has favored: Chasadjah, an Israelite: Hasadiah.
a primitive root; to flee for protection (compare בָּטַח); figuratively, to confide in: have hope, make refuge, (put) trust.
from חָסָה; hopeful; Chosah, an Israelite; also a place in Palestine: Hosah.
from חָסָה; confidence: trust.
from חָסַד; properly, kind, i.e. (religiously) pious (a saint): godly (man), good, holy (one), merciful, saint, (un-)godly.
feminine of חָסִיד; the kind (maternal) bird, i.e. a stork: X feather, stork.
from חָסַל; the ravager, i.e. a locust: caterpillar.
from חָסַן; properly, firm, i.e. (by implication) mighty: strong.
(Aramaic) from a root corresponding to חָסֵר; deficient: wanting.
a primitive root; to eat off: consume.
a primitive root; to muzzle; by analogy, to stop the nose: muzzle, stop.
a primitive root; properly, to (be) compact; by implication, to hoard: lay up.
(Aramaic) corresponding to חָסַן; to hold in occupancy: possess.
(Aramaic) from חֲסַן; strength: power.
from חָסַן; wealth: riches, strength, treasure.
from חָסַן; powerful: strong.
(Aramaic) from a root corresponding to that of מְחֻסְפָּס; a clod: clay.
reduplicated from an unused root meaning apparently to peel; a shred or scale: round thing.
a primitive root; to lack; by implication, to fail, want, lessen: be abated, bereave, decrease, (cause to) fail, (have) lack, make lower, want.
from חָסֵר; lacking; hence, without: destitute, fail, lack, have need, void, want.
from חָסֵר; lack; hence, destitution: poverty, want.
from חָסֵר; poverty: in want of.
from חָסֵר; want: Chasrah, an Israelite:--Hasrah.
from חָסֵר; deficiency: wanting.
from חָפַף (in the moral sense of covered from soil); pure: innocent.
an orthographical variation of חָפָה; properly, to cover, i.e. (in a sinister sense) to act covertly: do secretly.
a primitive root (compare חָפָא, חָפַף); to cover; by implication, to veil, to encase, protect: ceil, cover, overlay.
from חָפָה; a canopy: chamber, closet, defence.
the same as חֻפָּה; Chuppah, an Israelite: Huppah.
a primitive root; properly, to start up suddenly, i.e. (by implication) to hasten away, to fear: (make) haste (away), tremble.
from חֻלְדָּה; hasty flight: haste.
plural of חֻפָּה (compare חוּפָם); Chuppim, an Israelite: Huppim.
from an unused root of uncertain signification; a fist (only in the dual): fists, (both) hands, hand(-ful).
from חָפְנַ֫יִם; perhaps pugilist; Chophni, an Israelite: Hophni.
a primitive root (compare חָפָה, יָחֵף); to cover (in protection): cover.

a primitive root; properly, to incline to; by implication (literally but rarely) to bend; figuratively, to be pleased with, desire: X any at all, (have, take) delight, desire, favour, like, move, be (well) pleased, have pleasure, will, would.
from חָפֵץ; pleased with: delight in, desire, favour, please, have pleasure, whosoever would, willing, wish.

from חָפֵץ; pleasure; hence (abstractly) desire; concretely, a valuable thing; hence (by extension) a matter (as something in mind): acceptable, delight(-some), desire, things desired, matter, pleasant(-ure), purpose, willingly.
from חֵ֫פֶץ with suffixes; my delight (is) in her; Cheptsi-bah, a fanciful name for Palestine: Hephzi-bah.
a primitive root; properly, to pry into; by implication, to delve, to explore: dig, paw, search out, seek.

a primitive root (perhaps rath. the same as חָפַר through the idea of detection): to blush; figuratively, to be ashamed, disappointed; causatively, to shame, reproach: be ashamed, be confounded, be brought to confusion (unto shame), come (be put to) shame, bring reproach.
from חָפַר or חָפֵר; a pit of shame; Chepher, a place in Palestine; also the name of three Israelites: Hepher.
from חָפַר; a hole; only in connection with פֵּרוֹת, which ought rather to be joined as one word, thus chapharperah; by reduplication from חָפַר; a burrower, i.e. probably a rat: + mole.
patronymically from חֵ֫פֶר; a Chephrite (collectively) or descendants of Chepher: Hepherites.
dual of חֵ֫פֶר; double pit; Chapharajim, a place in Palestine: Haphraim.
a primitive root; to seek; causatively, to conceal oneself (i.e. let be sought), or mask: change, (make) diligent (search), disquise self, hide, search (for, out).
from חָפַשׂ; something covert, i.e. a trick: search.
a primitive root; to spread loose; figuratively, to manumit: be free.
from חָפַשׁ; something spread loosely, i.e. a carpet: precious.
from חָפַשׁ; liberty (from slavery): freedom.
and chophshiyth; from חָפַשׁ; prostration by sickness (with בָּ֫יִת, a hospital): several.
from חָפַשׁ; exempt (from bondage, tax or care): free, liberty.

from חָצַץ; properly, a piercer, i.e. an arrow; by implication, a wound; figuratively, (of God) thunder-bolt; (by interchange for עֵץ) the shaft of a spear: + archer, arrow, dart, shaft, staff, wound.
or chatseb; a primitive root; to cut or carve (wood), stone or other material); by implication, to hew, split, square, quarry, engrave: cut, dig, divide, grave, hew (out, -er), made, mason.
a primitive root (compare זֵד)); to cut or split in two; to halve:--divide, X live out half, reach to the midst, participle
a collective form of חָצֵר; village; Chatsor, the name (thus simply) of two places in Palestine and of one in ArabiaHazor.
from חָצוֹר and a Aramaizing form of the feminine of חָדָשׁ (compare חֲדַת); new Chatsor, a place in Palestine: Hazor, Hadattah (as if two places).
from חָצָה; the middle (of the night): mid(-night).
from חָצָה; the half or middle: half, middle, mid(-night), midst, part, two parts.
or chetsiy; prolongation from חֵץ; an arrow: arrow.
from חֵ֫צִי and the plural of מְנוּחָה, with the article interposed; midst of the resting- places; Chatsi-ham-Menuchoth, an Israelite: half of the Manahethites.
patronymically from חֲצִי הַמְּנֻחוֹת; a Chatsi-ham-Menachtite or descendant of Chatsi-ham-Menuchoth: half of the Manahethites.
a collateral form of חָצֵר; a court or abode: court.
perhaps originally the same as חָצִיר, from the greenness of a courtyard; grass; also a leek (collectively): grass, hay, herb, leek.
from an unused root meaning to hold firmly; the bosom (as comprised between the arms): bosom.
a collateral form of חֵ֫צֶן, and meaning the same: arm, lap.
(Aramaic) a primitive root; properly, to shear or cut close; figuratively, to be severe: hasty, be urgent.
a primitive root (compare חָצָה); properly, to chop into, pierce or sever; hence, to curtail, to distribute (into ranks); as denom. from חֵץ, to shoot an arrow: archer, X bands, cut off in the midst.
from חָצָץ; properly, something cutting; hence, gravel (as grit); also (like חֵץ) an arrow: arrow, gravel (stone).
or Chatsatson Tamar; from חָצַץ and תָּמָר; division (i.e. perhaps row) of (the) palm-tree; Chatsetson-tamar, a place in Palestine: Hazezon- tamar.
by reduplication from חָצַר; a trumpet (from its sundered or quavering note): trumpet(-er).

a primitive root; properly, to surround with a stockade, and thus separate from the open country; but used only in the reduplicated form chatsotser; or (2 Chronicles 5:12) chatsorer; as dem. from חֲצֹצְרָה; to trumpet, i.e. blow on that instrument: blow, sound, trumpeter.
(masculine and feminine); from חָצַר in its original sense; a yard (as inclosed by a fence); also a hamlet (as similarly surrounded with walls): court, tower, village.
from חָצֵר and אַדָּר; (the) village of Addar; Chatsar-Addar, a place in Palestine: Hazar-addar.
from חָצֵר and a feminine of גַּד; (the) village of (female) Fortune; Chatsar-Gaddah, a place in Palestine: Hazar-gaddah.
from חָצֵר and תִּיכוֹן with the article interposed; village of the middle; Chatsar-hat-Tikon, a place in Palestine: Hazar-hatticon.
by an orthographical variation for חֶצְרוֹן; enclosure; Chetsro, an Israelite: Hezro, Hezrai.
from חָצֵר; court-yard; Chetsron, the name of a place in Palestine; also of two Israelites: Hezron.
patronymically from חֶצְרוֹן; a Chetsronite or (collectively) descendants of Chetsron: Hezronites.
feminine plural of חָצֵר; yards; Chatseroth, a place in Palestine: Hazeroth.
plural masculine of חָצֵר; yards; Chatserim, a place in Palestine: Hazerim.
from חָצֵר and מָ֫וֶת; village of death; Chatsarmaveth, a place in Arabia: Hazarmaveth.
from חָצֵר and סוּסָה; village of cavalry; Chatsar-Susah, a place in Palestine: Hazar-susah.
from חָצֵר and the plural of סוּס; village of horses; Chatsar-Susim, a place in Palestine: Hazar- susim.
from חָצֵר and a derivative of עַ֫יִן; village of springs; Chatsar-Enon, a place in Palestine: Hazar- enon.
from חָצֵר and the same as עֵינָן; village of springs; Chatsar-Enan, a place in Palestine: Hazar-enan.
from חָצֵר and שׁוּעָל; village of (the) fox; Chatsar-Shual, a place in Palestine: Hazar-shual.

from חָקַק; an enactment; hence, an appointment (of time, space, quantity, labor or usage): appointed, bound, commandment, convenient, custom, decree(-d), due, law, measure, X necessary, ordinance(- nary), portion, set time, statute, task.
a primitive root; to carve; by implication, to delineate; also to entrench: carved work, portrayed, set a print.
feminine of חֹק, and meaning substantially the same: appointed, custom, manner, ordinance, site, statute.
from an unused root probably meaning to bend; crooked; Chakupha, one of the Nethinim: Hakupha.

a primitive root; properly, to hack, i.e. engrave (Judges 5:14, to be a scribe simply); by implication, to enact (laws being cut in stone or metal tablets in primitive times) or (gen.) prescribe: appoint, decree, governor, grave, lawgiver, note, pourtray, print, set.
from חָקַק; an enactment, a resolution: decree, thought.
or (fully) Chuwqoq; from חָקַק; appointed; Chukkok or Chukok, a place in Palestine: Hukkok, Hukok.
a primitive root; properly, to penetrate; hence, to examine intimately: find out, (make) search (out), seek (out), sound, try.
from חָקַר; examination, enumeration, deliberation: finding out, number, (un-)search(-able, -ed, out, -ing).
or (fully) chowr; from חָרַר; properly, white or pure (from the cleansing or shining power of fire (compare חֹרִי); hence (figuratively) noble (in rank): noble.
from an unused (and vulgar) root probably meaning to evacuate the bowels: excrement; -dung. Also chariy.
or chareb; a primitive root; to parch (through drought) i.e. (by analogy,) to desolate, destroy, killdecay, (be) desolate, destroy(-er), (be) dry (up), slay, X surely, (lay, lie, make) waste.
(Aramaic) a root corresponding to חָרַב; to demolish: destroy.
from חָרַב; drought; also a cutting instrument (from its destructive effect), as a knife, sword, or other sharp implement: axe, dagger, knife, mattock, sword, tool.
from חָרַב; parched or ruined: desolate, dry, waste.
a collaterally form of חָ֫רֶב; drought or desolation: desolation, drought, dry, heat, X utterly, waste.
from חָרַב; desolate; Choreb, a (generic) name for the Sinaitic mountains: Horeb.
feminine of חֹ֫רֶב; properly, drought, i.e. (by implication) a desolation: decayed place, desolate (place, -tion), destruction, (laid) waste (place).
feminine of חָרֵב; a desert: dry (ground, land).
from חָרַב; parching heat: drought.
or Charbownah; of Persian origin; Charbona or Charbonah, a eunuch of Xerxes: Harbona, Harbonah.
a primitive root; properly, to leap suddenly, i.e. (by implication) to be dismayed: be afraid.
from חָרַג; the leaping insect, i.e. a locust: beetle.
a primitive root; to shudder with terror; hence, to fear; also to hasten (with anxiety): be (make) afraid, be careful, discomfit, fray (away), quake, tremble.
from חָרַד; fearful; also reverential: afraid, trembling.
feminine of חָרֵד; fear, anxiety: care, X exceedingly, fear, quaking, trembling.
the same as חֲרָדָה; Charadah, a place in the Desert: Haradah.
patrial from a derivative of חָרַד (compare עֵין חֲרֹד); a Charodite, or inhabitant of Charod: Harodite.

a primitive root (compare חָרַר); to glow or grow warm; figuratively (usually) to blaze up, of anger, zeal, jealousy: be angry, burn, be displeased, X earnestly, fret self, grieve, be (wax) hot, be incensed, kindle, X very, be wroth. See תְּתַחֲרֶה.
from חֹר and a collateral (masculine) form of גֻּדְגֹּ֫דָה, with the article interposed; hole of the cleft: Chor-hag-Gidgad, a place in the Desert: Hor-hagidgad.
: ; from חָרָה and יָהּ; fearing Jah; Charhajah, an Israelite: Harhaiah.
from an unused root meaning to perforate; properly, pierced, i.e. a bead of pearl, gems or jewels (as strung): chain.
or (shortened) charul; apparently, a passive participle of an unused root probably meaning to be prickly; properly, pointed, i.e. a bramble or other thorny weed: nettle.
from passive participle of חָרַם and אַף; snub-nosed; Charumaph, an Israelite: Harumaph.
or (shortened) charon; from חָרָה; a burning of anger: sore displeasure, fierce(-ness), fury, (fierce) wrath(-ful).
a patrial from (probably) a collateral form of חָרִיף; a Charuphite or inhabitant of Charuph (or Chariph): Haruphite.

or charuts; passive participle of חָרַץ; properly, incised or (active) incisive; hence (as noun masculine or feminine) a trench (as dug), gold (as mined), a threshing-sledge (having sharp teeth); (figuratively) determination; also eager: decision, diligent, (fine) gold, pointed things, sharp, threshing instrument, wall.
the same as חָרוּץ; earnest; Charuts, an Israelite: Haruz.
a fuller form of חַרְחֻר; inflammation; Charchur, one of the Nethinim: Harhur.
from the same as חָ֫רֶס; perhaps shining; Charchas, an Israelite: Harhas.
from חָרַר; fever (as hot); -extreme burning.
from a primitive root meaning to engrave; a chisel or graver; also a style for writing: graving tool, pen.
from the same as חֶ֫רֶט; a horoscopist (as drawing magical lines or circles): magician.
(Aramaic) the same as חַרְטֹם: magician.
from חָרָה; a burning (i.e. intense) anger: fierce, X great, heat.
from the same as חוּר; white bread: white.
from חֹר; cave-dweller or troglodyte; a Chorite or aboriginal Idumaean: Horims, Horites.
or Chowriy; the same as חֹרִי; Chori, the name of two men: Hori.
or charit; from the same as חֶ֫רֶט; properly, cut out (or hollow), i.e. (by implication) a pocket: bag, crisping pin.

from the plural of חַרְאֵי and the plural of יוֹנִים; excrements of doves, or perhaps rather the plural of a single word charapyown; of similar or uncertain derivation, probably a kind of vegetable: doves' dung.
from חָרַף; autumnal; Chariph, the name of two Israelites: Hariph.
or charits; from חָרַץ; properly, incisure or (passively) incised (compare חָרוּץ); hence, a threshing-sledge (with sharp teeth): also a slice (as cut): + cheese, harrow.
from חָרַשׁ; ploughing or its season: earing (time), ground.
from חָרַשׁ in the sense of silence; quiet, i.e. sultry (as feminine noun, the sirocco or hot east wind): vehement.
a primitive root; to braid (i.e. to entangle or snare) or catch (game) in a net: roast.
(Aramaic) a root probably allied to the equivalent of חָרַר; to scorch: singe.
from חָרַך; properly, a net, i.e. (by analogy) lattice: lattice.

a primitive root; to seclude; specifically (by a ban) to devote to religious uses (especially destruction); physical and reflexive, to be blunt as to the nose: make accursed, consecrate, (utterly) destroy, devote, forfeit, have a flat nose, utterly (slay, make away).

or (Zecheriah 14:11) cherem; from חָרַם; physical (as shutting in) a net (either literally or figuratively); usually a doomed object; abstr. extermination: (ac-)curse(-d, -d thing), dedicated thing, things which should have been utterly destroyed, (appointed to) utter destruction, devoted (thing), net.
from חָרַם; devoted; Chorem, a place in Palestine: Horem.
from חָרַם; snub-nosed; Charim, an Israelite: Harim.
from חָרַם; devoted; Chormah, a place in Palestine: Hormah.
from חָרַם; abrupt; Chermon, a mount of Palestine: Hermon.
plural of חֶרְמוֹן; Hermons, i.e. its peaks: the Hermonites.
from חָרַם; a sickle (as cutting): sickle.
from חָרַר; parched; Charan, the name of a man and also of a place: Haran.
patrial from חֹרוֹנָ֫יִם; a Choronite or inhabitant of Choronaim: Horonite.
dual of a derivative from חֹר; double cave-town; Choronajim, a place in Moab: Horonaim.
of uncertain derivation; Charnepher, an Israelite: Harnepher.

UNIQUE_WORD: חָ֫רֶס (kheh'-res} or (with a directive enclitic) charcah (khar'- saw)
DESCRIPTION: : ; from an unused root meaning to scrape; the itch; also (perhaps from the mediating idea of חַרְסוּת) the sun: itch, sun.
the same as חָ֫רֶס; shining; Cheres, a mountain in Palestine: Heres.
from חָ֫רֶס (apparently in the sense of a red tile used for scraping); a potsherd, i.e. (by implication) a pottery; the name of a gate at Jerusalem: east.

a primitive root; to pull off, i.e. (by implication) to expose (as by stripping); specifically, to betroth (as if a surrender); figuratively, to carp at, i.e. defame; denominative (from חֹ֫רֶף) to spend the winter: betroth, blaspheme, defy, jeopard, rail, reproach, upbraid.
from חָרַף; properly, the crop gathered, i.e. (by implication) the autumn (and winter) season; figuratively, ripeness of age: cold, winter (-house), youth.
from חָרַף; reproachful; Chareph, an Israelite: Hareph.
from חָרַף; contumely, disgrace, the pudenda: rebuke, reproach(-fully), shame.
a primitive root; properly, to point sharply, i.e. (literally) to wound; figuratively, to be alert, to decide: bestir self, decide, decree, determine, maim, move.
(Aramaic) from a root corresponding to חָרַץ in the sense of vigor; the loin (as the seat of strength): loin.
of uncertain derivation; a fetter; figuratively, a pain: band.
from חָרַץ; a sour grape (as sharp in taste): kernel.
a primitive root; to grate the teeth: gnash.
a primitive root; to glow, i.e. literally (to melt, burn, dry up) or figuratively (to show or incite passion: be angry, burn, dry, kindle.
from חָרַר; arid: parched place.
a collateral form mediating between חָ֫רֶס and חֶ֫רֶשׁ; a piece of pottery: earth(-en), (pot-)sherd, + stone.

a primitive root; to scratch, i.e. (by implication) to engrave, plough; hence (from the use of tools) to fabricate (of any material); figuratively, to devise (in a bad sense); hence (from the idea of secrecy) to be silent, to let alone; hence (by implication) to be deaf (as an accompaniment of dumbness): X altogether, cease, conceal, be deaf, devise, ear, graven, imagine, leave off speaking, hold peace, plow(-er, man), be quiet, rest, practise secretly, keep silence, be silent, speak not a word, be still, hold tongue, worker.
from חָרַשׁ; magical craft; also silence: cunning, secretly.
the same as חֶ֫רֶשׁ: Cheresh, a Levite:--Heresh.
from חָרַשׁ; a forest (perhaps as furnishing the material for fabric): bough, forest, shroud, wood.
active participle of חָרַשׁ; a fabricator or mechanic: artificer.
from חָרַשׁ; deaf (whether literally or spir.): deaf.
from חָרַשׁ; a fabricator or any material: artificer, (+) carpenter, craftsman, engraver, maker, + mason, skilful, (+) smith, worker, workman, such as wrought.
from חֶ֫רֶשׁ; magician; Charsha, one of the Nethinim: Harsha.
plural of חָרָשׁ; mechanics, the name of a valley in Jerusalem: Charashim, craftsmen.
from חָרַשׁ; mechanical work: carving, cutting.
the same as חֲרֹ֫שֶׁת; Charosheth, a place in Palestine: Harosheth.
a primitive root; to engrave: graven.
from חָרַת (but equivalent to חֹ֫רֶשׁ); forest; Chereth, a thicket in Palestine: Hereth.

a primitive root; properly, to plait or interpenetrate, i.e. (literally) to weave or (gen.) to fabricate; figuratively, to plot or contrive (usually in a malicious sense); hence (from the mental effort) to think, regard, value, compute: (make) account (of), conceive, consider, count, cunning (man, work, workman), devise, esteem, find out, forecast, hold, imagine, impute, invent, be like, mean, purpose, reckon(-ing be made), regard, think.
(Aramaic) corresponding to חָשַׁב; to regard: repute.
from חָשַׁב; a belt or strap (as being interlaced): curious girdle.
from חָשַׁב and דִּין; considerate judge; Chasbaddanah, an Israelite: Hasbadana.
from חָשַׁב; estimation; Cashubah, an Israelite: Hashubah.
from חָשַׁב; properly, contrivance; by implication, intelligence: account, device, reason.
the same as חֶשְׁבּוֹן; Cheshbon, a place East of the Jordan: Heshbon.
from חָשַׁב; a contrivance, i.e. actual (a warlike machine) or mental (a machination): engine, invention.
or Chashabyahuw; from חָשַׁב and יָהּ; Jah has regarded; Chashabjah, the name of nine Israelites: Hashabiah.
feminine of חֶשְׁבּוֹן; inventiveness; Chashnah, an Israelite: Hashabnah.
from חֶשְׁבּוֹן and יָהּ; thought of Jah; Chashabnejah, the name of two Israelites: Hashabniah.
a primitive root; to hush or keep quiet: hold peace, keep silence, be silent, (be) still.
from חָשַׁב; intelligent; Chashshub, the name of two or three Israelites: Hashub, Hasshub.
(Aramaic) from a root corresponding to חָשַׁך; the dark: darkness.
or Chasuphao; from חָשַׂף; nakedness; Chasupha, one of the Nethinim: Hashupha, Hasupha.
(Aramaic) a collateral root to one corresponding to חוּשׁ in the sense of readiness; to be necessary (from the idea of convenience) or (transitively) to need: careful, have need of.
from a root corresponding to חֲשַׁח; necessity: be needful.

a primitive root; to restrain or (reflex.) refrain; by implication, to refuse, spare, preserve; also (by interch. with חָשַׁך) to observe: assuage, X darken, forbear, hinder, hold back, keep (back), punish, refrain, reserve, spare, withhold.
a primitive root; to be dark (as withholding light); transitively, to darken: be black, be (make) dark, darken, cause darkness, be dim, hide.
from חָשַׁך; the dark; hence (literally) darkness; figuratively, misery, destruction, death, ignorance, sorrow, wickedness: dark(-ness), night, obscurity.
from חָשַׁך; dark (figuratively, i.e. obscure):--meaning
from חָשַׁך; darkness: dark.
or chashekah; from חָשַׁך; darkness; figuratively, misery: darkness.
a primitive root; to make (intrans. be) unsteady, i.e. weak: feeble.
(Aramaic) a root corresponding to חָשַׁל; to weaken, i.e. crush: subdue.
from the same as חַשְׁמַנִּים; enriched; Chashum, the name of two or three Israelites: Hashum.
the same as חַשְׁמַנִּים; opulent; Cheshmon, a place in Palestine: Heshmon.
of uncertain derivation; probably bronze or polished spectrum metal: amber.
from an unused root (probably meaning firm or capacious in resources); apparently wealthy: princes.
feminine of חַשְׁמַנִּים; fertile; Chasmonah, a place in the Desert: Hashmonah.
from an unused root probably meaning to contain or sparkle; perhaps a pocket (as holding the Urim and Thummim), or rich (as containing gems), used only of the gorget of the highpriest: breastplate.
a primitive root; to strip off, i.e. generally to make naked (for exertion or in disgrace), to drain away or bail up (a liquid): make bare, clean, discover, draw out, take, uncover.
from חָשַׂף; properly, drawn off, i.e. separated; hence, a small company (as divided from the rest): little flock.
a primitive root; to cling, i.e. join, (figuratively) to love, delight in; elliptically (or by interchangeable for חָשַׂך) to deliver: have a delight, (have a) desire, fillet, long, set (in) love.
from חָשַׁק; delight: desire, pleasure.
or chashuwq; past participle of חָשַׁק; attached, i.e. a fence-rail or rod connecting the posts or pillars: fillet.
from חָשַׁק; conjoined, i.e. a wheel-spoke or rod connecting the hub with the rim: felloe.
from an unused root meaning to bind together; combined, i.e. the nave or hub of a wheel (as holding the spokes together): spoke.
from the same as חִשֻּׁרֵי; properly, a combination or gathering, i.e. of watery clouds: dark.
by variation for קָשׁ; dry grass: chaff.
patronymically from חוּשָׁה; a Chushathite or descendant of Chushah: Hushathite.
from חָתַת; concretely, crushed; also afraid; abstractly, terror: broken, dismayed, dread, fear.
from חָתַת; terror; Cheth, an aboriginal Canaanite: Heth.
a primitive root; to lay hold of; especially to pick up fire: heap, take (away).
from חָתַת; fear: terror.
from חָתַל; swathed, i.e. a bandage: roller.
from חָת; terror: fear.
patronymically from חֵת; a Chittite, or descendant of Cheth: Hittite, Hittities.
from חָתַת; fear: terror.
a primitive root; properly, to cut off, i.e. (figuratively) to decree: determine.
a primitive root; to swathe: X at all, swaddle.
from חָתַל; a swathing cloth (figuratively): swaddling band.
from חָתַל; enswathed; Chethlon, a place in Palestine: Hethlon.
a primitive root; to close up; especially to seal: make an end, mark, seal (up), stop.
(Aramaic) a root corresponding to חָתַם; to seal: seal.
feminine active participle of חָתַם; a seal: signet.
a primitive root; to give (a daughter) away in marriage; hence (generally) to contract affinity by marriage: join in affinity, father in law, make marriages, mother in law, son in law.
from חָתַן; a relative by marriage (especially through the bride); figuratively, a circumcised child (as a species of religious espousal): bridegroom, husband, son in law.
from חָתַן; a wedding: espousal.
a primitive root; to clutch: take away.
from חָתַף; properly, rapine; figuratively, robbery: prey.
a primitive root; to force a passage, as by burglary; figuratively, with oars: dig (through), row.

a primitive root; properly, to prostrate; hence, to break down, either (literally) by violence, or (figuratively) by confusion and fear: abolish, affright, be (make) afraid, amaze, beat down, discourage, (cause to) dismay, go down, scare, terrify.
from חָתַת; dismay: casting down.
the same as חֲתַת; Chathath, an Israelite: cathath.
(Aramaic) a primitive root; to rejoice: be glad.
(Aramaic) from טְאֵב; the same as טוֹב; good: fine, good.
from טוֹב and אֵל; pleasing (to) God; Tabeel, the name of a Syrian and of a Persian: Tabeal, Tabeel.
passive participle of טָבַל; properly, dyed, i.e. a turban (probably as of colored stuff): dyed attire.
from an unused root meaning to pile up; properly, accumulated; i.e. (by implication) a summit: middle, midst.
a primitive root; to slaughter (animals or men): kill, (make) slaughter, slay.
from טָבַח; properly, something slaughtered; hence, a beast (or meat, as butchered); abstr. butchery (or concretely, a place of slaughter): X beast, slaughter, X slay, X sore.
the same as טָ֫בַח; massacre; Tebach, the name of a Mesopotamian and of an Israelite: Tebah.
from טָבַח; properly, a butcher; hence, a lifeguardsman (because he was acting as an executioner); also a cook (usually slaughtering the animal for food): cook, guard.
(Aramaic) the same as טַבָּח; a lifeguardsman: guard.
feminine of טָ֫בַח and meaning the same: flesh, slaughter.
feminine of טַבָּח; a female cook: cook.
from טִבְחָה; slaughter; Tibchath, a place in Syria: Tibhath.
a primitive root; to dip, to immerse: dip, plunge.
from טָבַל and יָהּ; Jah has dipped; Tebaljah, an Israelite: Tebaliah.
a primitive root; to sink: drown, fasten, settle, sink.
plural of טַבַּ֫עַת; rings; Tabbaoth, one of the Nethinim: Tabaoth.
from טָבַע; properly, a seal (as sunk into the wax), i.e. signet (for sealing); hence (generally) a ring of any kind: ring.
from טוֹב and רִמּוֹן; pleasing (to) Rimmon; Tabrimmon, a Syrian: Tabrimmon.
probably of foreign derivation; Tebeth, the tenth Heb. month: Tebeth.
of uncertain derivation; Tabbath, a place East of the Jordan: Tabbath.
or tahor; from טָהֵר; pure (in a physical, chemical, ceremonial or moral sense): clean, fair, pure(-ness).
from טָהֵר; purity: pureness.

a primitive root; properly, to be bright; i.e. (by implication) to be pure (physical sound, clear, unadulterated; Levitically, uncontaminated; morally, innocent or holy): be (make, make self, pronounce) clean, cleanse (self), purge, purify(-ier, self).
from טָהֵר; literally brightness; ceremonially purification: clearness, glory, purifying.
feminine of טֹ֫הַר; ceremonial purification; moral purity: X is cleansed, cleansing, purification(-fying).
a primitive root; to sweep away: sweep.
a primitive root, to be (transitively, do or make) good (or well) in the widest sense: be (do) better, cheer, be (do, seem) good, (make) goodly, X please, (be, do, go, play) well.

from טוֹב; good (as an adjective) in the widest sense; used likewise as a noun, both in the masculine and the feminine, the singular and the plural (good, a good or good thing, a good man or woman; the good, goods or good things, good men or women), also as an adverb (well): beautiful, best, better, bountiful, cheerful, at ease, X fair (word), (be in) favour, fine, glad, good (deed, -lier, -liest, -ly, -ness, -s), graciously, joyful, kindly, kindness, liketh (best), loving, merry, X most, pleasant, + pleaseth, pleasure, precious, prosperity, ready, sweet, wealth, welfare, (be) well ((-favoured)).
the same as טוֹב; good; Tob, a region apparently East of the Jordan: Tob.
from טוֹב; good (as a noun), in the widest sense, especially goodness (superlative concretely, the best), beauty, gladness, welfare: fair, gladness, good(-ness, thing, -s), joy, go well with.
from טוֹב and אֲדֹנִיָּה; pleasing (to) Adonijah; Tob-Adonijah, an Israelite: Tob-adonijah.
or Towbiyahuw; from טוֹב and יָהּ; goodness of Jehovah; Tobijah, the name of three Israelites and of one Samaritan: Tobiah, Tobijah.
a primitive root; to spin: spin.
a primitive root; to smear, especially with lime: daub, overlay, plaister, smut.
from an unusued root meaning to go around or bind; a fillet for the forehead: frontlet.
a primitive root; to pitch over or reel; hence (transitively) to cast down or out: carry away, (utterly) cast (down, forth, out), send out.
from an unused root meaning to range in a regular manner; a row; hence, a wall: row.
(Aramaic) corresponding to צוּר; a rock or hill: mountain.
a primitive root; to pounce as a bird of prey: haste.
(Aramaic) from a root corresponding to טָוָה; hunger (as twisting): fasting.
a primitive root; to stretch a bow, as an archer: (bow-)shot.
from טָחָה (or ט֫וּחַ) in the sense of overlaying; (in the plural only) the kidneys (as being covered); hence (figuratively) the inmost thought: inward parts.
from טָחַן; a hand mill; hence, a millstone: to grind.
a primitive root; to grind meal; hence, to be a concubine (that being their employment): grind(-er).
from טָחַן; a hand mill; hence (figuratively) chewing: grinding.
from an unused root meaning to burn; a boil or ulcer (from the inflammation), especially a tumor in the anus or pudenda (the piles): emerod.
from (the equiv. of) ט֫וּחַ; mortar or plaster: daubing.
from an unused root meaning apparently to be sticky (rath. perb. a demon. from טוּא, through the idea of dirt to be swept away); mud or clay; figuratively, calamity: clay, dirt, mire.
(Aramaic) perhaps, by interchange, for a word corresponding to טִיט; clay: miry.
feminine of (an equivalent to) טוּר; a wall; hence, a fortress or a hamlet: (goodly) castle, habitation, palace, row.
from טָלַל; dew (as covering vegetation): dew.
(Aramaic) the same as טָל: dew.
a primitive root; properly, to cover with pieces; i.e. (by implication) to spot or variegate (as tapestry): clouted, with divers colours, spotted.
apparently from טָלָא in the (orig.) sense of covering (for protection); a lamb (compare טָלֶה): lamb.
from the plural of טְלָאּים; lambs; Telaim, a place in Palestine: Telaim.
by variation for טְלָאּים; a lamb: lamb.
from טוּל; overthrow or rejection: captivity.
a primitive root; properly, to strew over, i.e. (by implication) to cover in or plate (with beams): cover.
(Aramaic) corresponding to טָלַל; to cover with shade: have a shadow.
from an unused root meaning to break up or treat violently; oppression; Telem, the name of a place in Idumaea, also of a temple doorkeeper: Telem.
from the same as חָרְגֹּל; oppressive; Talmon, a temple doorkeeper: Talmon.
a primitive root; to be foul, especially in a ceremial or moral sense (contaminated): defile (self), pollute (self), be (make, make self, pronounce) unclean, X utterly.
from טָמֵא; foul in a relig. sense: defiled, + infamous, polluted(-tion), unclean.
from טָמֵא; religious impurity: filthiness, unclean(-ness).
a collateral form of טָמֵא; to be impure in a religious sense: be defiled, be reputed vile.
a primitive root; to hide (by covering over): hide, lay privily, in secret.
from an unused root probably meaning to weave; a basket (of interlaced osiers): basket.
a primitive root; to soil: defile.
a primitive root; to wander;,causatively to lead astray: seduce.
a primitive root; to taste; figuratively, to perceive: X but, perceive, taste.
(Aramaic) corresponding to טָעַם; to taste; causatively to feed: make to eat, feed.
from טָעַם; properly, a taste, i.e. (figuratively) perception; by implication, intelligence; transitively, a mandateadvice, behaviour, decree, discretion, judgment, reason, taste, understanding.
(Aramaic) from טְעַם; properly, a taste, i.e. (as in טָ֫עַם) a judicial sentence: account, X to be commanded, commandment, matter.

(Aramaic) from טְעַם, and equivalent to טַ֫עַם; properly, flavor; figuratively, judgment (both subjective and objective); hence, account (both subj. and obj.): + chancellor, + command, commandment, decree, + regard, taste, wisdom.
a primitive root; to load a beast: lade.
a primitive root; to stab: thrust through.
from טָפַף (perhaps referring to the tripping gait of children); a family (mostly used collectively in the singular): (little) children (ones), families.
a primitive root; to flatten out or extend (as a tent); figuratively, to nurse a child (as promotive of growth); or perhaps a denom. from טֶ֫פַח, from dandling on the palms: span, swaddle.
from טָפַח; a spread of the hand, i.e. a palm- breadth (not "span" of the fingers); architecturally, a corbel (as a supporting palm): coping, hand-breadth.
from טָפַח (the same as טֶ֫פַח): hand-breadth (broad).
from טָפַח; nursing: span long.
a primitive root; properly, to stick on as a patch; figuratively, to impute falsely: forge(-r), sew up.
of foreign derivation; a military governor: captain.
a primitive root; apparently to trip (with short steps) coquettishly: mince.
(Aramaic) from a root corresponding to צָפַר, and meaning the same as צִפֹּ֫רֶן; a finger-nail; also a hoof or claw: nail.
a primitive root; properly, apparently to be thick; figuratively, to be stupid: be fat.
probably from נָטַף; a dropping (of ointment); Taphath, an Israelitess: Taphath.
a primitive root; to drive on; figuratively, to follow close: continual.
(Aramaic) corresponding to טָרַד; to expel: drive.
a variation of טֶ֫רֶם; not yet: before.
a primitive root; to overburden: weary.
from טָרַח; a burden: cumbrance, trouble.
from an unused root apparently meaning to be moist; properly, dripping; hence, fresh (i.e. recently made such): new, putrefying.
from an unused root apparently meaning to interrupt or suspend; properly, non-occurrence; used adverbially, not yet or before: before, ere, not yet.
a primitive root; to pluck off or pull to pieces; causatively to supply with food (as in morsels): catch, X without doubt, feed, ravin, rend in pieces, X surely, tear (in pieces).
from טָרַף; something torn, i.e. a fragment, e.g. a fresh leaf, prey, food: leaf, meat, prey, spoil.
from טָרַף; recently torn off, i.e. fresh: pluckt off.
feminine (collectively) of טָ֫רֶף; prey, i.e. flocks devoured by animals: ravin, (that which was) torn (of beasts, in pieces).
(Aramaic) from a name of foreign derivation; a Tarpelite (collectively) or inhabitants of Tarpel, a place in Assyria: Tarpelites.
a primitive root; to desire: long.
a primitive root; to be suitable: appertain.
or Ya.azanyahuw; from הֶאֱזִין and יָהּ; heard of Jah; Jaazanjah, the name of four IsraelitesJaazaniah. Compare יְזַנְיָה.
from אוֹר; enlightener; Jair, the name of four Israelites: Jair.
patronymically from יָאּיר; a Jairite or descendant of Jair: Jairite.
a primitive root; properly, to be slack, i.e. (figuratively) to be foolish: dote, be (become, do) foolish(-ly).

a primitive root (probably rather the same as יָאַל through the idea of mental weakness); properly, to yield, especially assent; hence (pos.) to undertake as an act of volition: assay, begin, be content, please, take upon, X willingly, would.

of Egyptian origin; a channel, e.g. a fosse, canal, shaft; specifically the Nile, as the one river of Egypt, including its collateral trenches; also the Tigris, as the main river of Assyria: brook, flood, river, stream.
a primitive root; to desist, i.e. (figuratively) to despond: (cause to) despair, one that is desperate, be no hope.
: ; from the same root as אָשְׁוִיֹּת and יָהּ; founded of Jah; Joshijah, the name of two IsraelitesJosiah.
from אָתָה; an entry: entrance.
from the same as אֲתָרִים; stepping; Jeatherai, an Israelite: Jeaterai.
a primitive root; to bawl: cry out.
from יָבַל; produce, i.e. a crop or (figuratively) wealth: fruit, increase.
from בּוּס; trodden, i.e. threshing-place; Jebus, the aboriginal name of Jerusalem: Jebus.
patrial from יְבוּס; a Jebusite or inhabitant of Jebus: Jebusite(-s).
from בָּחַר; choice; Jibchar, an Israelite: Ibhar.
from בִּין; intelligent; Jabin, the name of two Canaanitish kings: Jabin.
a primitive root; properly, to flow; causatively, to bring (especially with pomp): bring (forth), carry, lead (forth).
(Aramaic) corresponding to יָבַל; to bring: bring, carry.
from יָבַל; a stream: (water-)course, stream.
the same as יִבְלֵי; Jabal, an antediluvian: Jabal.
from יָבַל; having running sores: wen.
from בָּלַע and עָם; devouring people; Jibleam, a place in Palestine: Ibleam.
a primitive root of doubtful meaning; used only as a denominative from יָבָם; to marry a (deceased) brother's widow: perform the duty of a husband's brother, marry.
from (the orig. of) יָבַם; a brother-in-law: husband's brother.
feminine participle of יָבַם; a sister-in-law: brother's wife, sister in law.
from בָּנָה and אֵל: built of God; Jabneel, the name of two places in Palestine: Jabneel.
from בָּנָה; a building; Jabneh, a place in Palestine: Jabneh.
from בָּנָה and יָהּ; built of Jah; Jibnejah, an Israelite: Ibneiah.
from בָּנָה and יָהּ; building of Jah; Jibnijah, an Israelite: Ibnijah.
probably from בָּקַק; pouring forth; Jabbok, a river east of the Jordan: Jabbok.
from בָּרַך and יָהּ: blessed of Jah; Jeberekjah, an Israelite: Jeberechiah.

a primitive root; to be ashamed, confused or disappointed; also (as failing) to dry up (as water) or wither (as herbage): be ashamed, clean, be confounded, (make) dry (up), (do) shame(-fully), X utterly, wither (away).
from יָבֵשׁ; dry: dried (away), dry.
the same as יָבֵשׁ (also Yabeysh; often with the addition of גִּלְעָד, i.e. Jabesh of Gilad); Jobesh, the name of an Israelite and of a place in Palestine: Jobesh ((-Gilead)).
from יָבֵשׁ; dry ground: dry (ground, land).
from the same as בְּשָׂמִים; fragrant; Jibsam, an Israelite: Jibsam.
a variation of יַבָּשָׁה; dry ground: dry land.
(Aramaic) corresponding to יַבָּ֫שֶׁת; dry land: earth.
from גָּאַל; avenger; Jigal, the name of three Israelites: Igal, Igeal.
a primitive root; to dig or plow: husbandman.
from יָגַב; a plowed field: field.
feminine from גָּבַהּ; hillock; Jogbehah, a place East of the Jordan: Jogbehah.
from גָּדַל and יָהּ; magnified of Jah; Jigdaljah, an Israelite: Igdaliah.
a primitive root; to grieve: afflict, cause grief, grieve, sorrowful, vex.
a primitive root (probably rather the same as יָגָה through the common idea of dissatisfaction); to push away; -be removed.
from יָגָה; affliction: grief, sorrow.
from יָגֹר; fearful: afraid, fearest.
probably from גּוּר; a lodging; Jagur, a place in Palestine: Jagur.
from יָגַע; toil; hence, a work, produce, property (as the result of labor): labour, work.
from יָגַע; tired: weary.
from גָּלָה; exiled; Jogli, an Israelite: Jogli.
a primitive root; properly, to gasp; hence, to be exhausted, to tire, to toil: faint, (make to) labour, (be) weary.
from יָגַע; earnings (as the product of toil); -that which he laboured for.
from יָגַע; tired; hence (transitive) tiresome: full of labour, weary.
feminine of יְגִיעֵי; fatigue: weariness.
a primitive root; to fear: be afraid, fear.

(Aramaic) from a word derived from an unused root (meaning to gather) and a derivation of a root corresponding to שָׂהֲדִי; heap of the testimony; Jegar-Sahadutha, a cairn East of the Jordan: Jegar-Sahadutha.

a primitive word; a hand (the open one (indicating power, means, direction, etc.), in distinction from כָּף, the closed one); used (as noun, adverb, etc.) in a great variety of applications, both literally and figuratively, both proximate and remote (as follows): (+ be) able, X about, + armholes, at, axletree, because of, beside, border, X bounty, + broad, (broken-)handed, X by, charge, coast, + consecrate, + creditor, custody, debt, dominion, X enough, + fellowship, force, X from, hand(-staves, -y work), X he, himself, X in, labour, + large, ledge, (left-)handed, means, X mine, ministry, near, X of, X order, ordinance, X our, parts, pain, power, X presumptuously, service, side, sore, state, stay, draw with strength, stroke, + swear, terror, X thee, X by them, X themselves, X thine own, X thou, through, X throwing, + thumb, times, X to, X under, X us, X wait on, (way-)side, where, + wide, X with (him, me, you), work, + yield, X yourselves.
(Aramaic) corresponding to יָד: hand, power.
(Aramaic) corresponding to יָדָה; to praise: (give) thank(-s).
of uncertain derivation; Jidalah, a place in Palestine: Idalah.
from the same as דְּבָשׁ; perhaps honeyed; Jidbash, an Israelite: Idbash.
a primitive root; properly, to handle (compare יָדָה), i.e. to throw, e.g. lots: cast.
from יְדִיד; properly, affection; concretely, a darling object: dearly beloved.

a primitive root; used only as denominative from יָד; literally, to use (i.e. hold out) the hand; physically, to throw (a stone, an arrow) at or away; especially to revere or worship (with extended hands); intensively, to bemoan (by wringing the hands): cast (out), (make) confess(-ion), praise, shoot, (give) thank(-ful, -s, -sgiving).
from יָדָה; praised; Jiddo, an Israelite: Iddo.
from יָדָה; thankful; Jadon, an Israelite: Jadon.
from יָדַע; knowing; Jaddua, the name of two Israelites: Jaddua.
or Yduthuwn; or Ydiythuwn; probably from יָדָה; laudatory; Jeduthun, an Israelite: Jeduthun.
from the same as דּוֹד; loved: amiable, (well-)beloved, loves.
feminine of יְדִיד; beloved; Jedidah, an Israelitess: Jedidah.
from יְדִיד and יָהּ; beloved of Jah; Jedidejah, a name of Solomon: Jedidiah.
from יָדָה and יָהּ; praised of Jah; Jedajah, the name of two Israelites: Jedaiah.
from יָדַע and אֵל; knowing God; Jediael, the name of three Israelites: Jediael.
from דָּלַף; tearful; Jidlaph, a Mesopotamian: Jidlaph.

a primitive root; to know (properly, to ascertain by seeing); used in a great variety of senses, figuratively, literally, euphemistically and inferentially (including observation, care, recognition; and causatively, instruction, designation, punishment, etc.) (as follow): acknowledge, acquaintance(-ted with), advise, answer, appoint, assuredly, be aware, (un-)awares, can(-not), certainly, comprehend, consider, X could they, cunning, declare, be diligent, (can, cause to) discern, discover, endued with, familiar friend, famous, feel, can have, be (ig-)norant, instruct, kinsfolk, kinsman, (cause to let, make) know, (come to give, have, take) knowledge, have (knowledge), (be, make, make to be, make self) known, + be learned, + lie by man, mark, perceive, privy to, X prognosticator, regard, have respect, skilful, shew, can (man of) skill, be sure, of a surety, teach, (can) tell, understand, have (understanding), X will be, wist, wit, wot.
(Aramaic) corresponding to יָדַע: certify, know, make known, teach.
from יָדַע; knowing; Jada, an Israelite: Jada.
from יָדַע and יָהּ; Jah has known; Jedajah, the name of two Israelites: Jedaiah.
from יָדַע; properly, a knowing one; specifically, a conjurer; (by impl) a ghost: wizard.
contraction for יְהֹוָה, and meaning the same; Jah, the sacred name: Jah, the Lord, most vehement. Compare names in "-iah," "- jah."
a primitive root; to give (whether literal or figurative); generally, to put; imperatively (reflexive) come: ascribe, bring, come on, give, go, set, take.
(Aramaic) corresponding to יָהַב; -deliver, give, lay, + prolong, pay, yield.
from יָהַב; properly, what is given (by Providence), i.e. a lot: burden.
denominative from a form corresponding to יְהוּד; to Judaize, i.e. become Jewish: become Jews.
a briefer form of one corresponding to יְהוּד; Jehud, a place in Palestine: Jehud.
perhaps from a form corresponding to יְהוּד; Judaistic; Jehdai, an Israelite: Jehdai.
feminine of יְהוּדִי; Jehudijah, a Jewess: -Jehudijah.
from יְהֹוָה and הוּא; Jehovah (is) He; Jehu, the name of five Israelites: Jehu.
from יְהֹוָה and אָחַז; Jehovah-seized; Jehoachaz, the name of three Israelites: Jehoahaz. Compare יוֹאָחָז.
from יְהֹוָה and (perhaps) אֵשׁ; Jehovah-fired; Jehoash, the name of two Israelite kings: Jehoash. Compare יוֹאָשׁ.
(Aramaic) contracted from a form corresponding to יְהוּדָה; properly, Judah, hence, Judaea: Jewry, Judah, Judea.
(Aramaic) patrial from יְהוּד; a Jehudaite (or Judaite), i.e. Jew: Jew.
from יָדָה; celebrated; Jehudah (or Judah), the name of five Israelites; also of the tribe descended from the first, and of its territory: Judah.
patronymically from יְהוּדָה; a Jehudite (i.e. Judaite or Jew), or descendant of Jehudah (i.e. Judah): Jew.
the same as יְהוּדִי; Jehudi, an Israelite: Jehudi.
feminine of יְהוּדִי; the Jewish (used adverbially) language: in the Jews' language.
the same as יְהוּדִית; Jewess; Jehudith, a Canaanitess: Judith.
from הָיָה; (the) self-Existent or Eternal; Jehovah, Jewish national name of God: Jehovah, the Lord. Compare יָהּ, יְהֹוִה.
a variation of יְהֹוָה (used after אֲדֹנָי, and pronounced by Jews as אֱלֹהִים, in order to prevent the repetition of the same sound, since they elsewhere pronounce יְהֹוָה as אֲדֹנָי): God.
from יְהֹוָה and רָאָה; Jehovah will see (to it); Jehovah-Jireh, a symbolical name for Mount Moriah: Jehovah- jireh.
from יְהֹוָה and נֵס with the prononimal suffix; Jehovah (is) my banner; Jehovah-Nissi, a symbolical name of an altar in the Desert: Jehovah-nissi.
from יְהֹוָה and צֶ֫דֶק with pronominal suffix; Jehovah (is) our right; Jehovah-Tsidkenu, a symbolical epithet of the Messiah and of Jerusalem: the Lord our righteousness.
from יְהֹוָה and שָׁלוֹם; Jehovah (is) peace; Jehovah-Shalom, a symbolical name of an altar in Palestine: -Jehovah-shalom.
from יְהֹוָה and שָׁם with directive enclitic; Jehovah (is) thither; Jehovah-Shammah, a symbolic title of Jerusalem: Jehovah-shammah.
from יְהֹוָה and זָבַד; Jehovah-endowed; Jehozabad, the name of three Israelites: Jehozabad. Compare יוֹזָבָד.
from יְהֹוָה and חָנַן; Jehovah-favored; Jehochanan, the name of eight Israelites: Jehohanan, Johanan. Compare יוֹחָנָן.
from יְהֹוָה and יָדַע; Jehovah-known; Jehojada, the name of three Israelites: Jehoiada. Compare יוֹיָדָע.
from יְהֹוָה and כּוּן; Jehovah will establish; Jehojakin, a Jewish king: Jehoiachin. Compare יוֹיָכִין.
from יְהֹוָה abbreviated and קוּם; Jehovah will raise; Jehojakim, a Jewish king: Jehoiakim. Compare יוֹיָקִים.
from יְהֹוָה and רִיב; Jehovah will contend; Jehojarib, the name of two Israelites: Jehoiarib. Compare יוֹיָרִיב.
from יָכֹל; potent; Jehukal, an Israelite: -Jehucal. Compare יוּכַל.
from יְהֹוָה and נָדַב; Jehovah-largessed; Jehonadab, the name of an Israelite and of an Arab: Jehonadab, Jonadab. Compare יוֹנָדָב.
from יְהֹוָה and נָתַן; Jehovah-given; Jehonathan, the name of four Israelites: Jonathan. Compare יוֹנָתָן.
a fuller form of יוֹסֵף; Jehoseph (i.e. Joseph), a son of Jacob: Joseph.
from יְהֹוָה and עָדָה; Jehovah-adorned; Jehoaddah, an Israelite: Jehoada.
or Yhowaddan; from יְהֹוָה and עָדַן; Jehovah-pleased; Jehoaddin or Jehoaddan, an Israelitess: Jehoaddan.
from יְהֹוָה and צָדַק; Jehovah-righted; Jehotsadak, an Israelite: Jehozadek, Josedech. Compare יוֹצָדָק.
from יְהֹוָה and רוּם; Jehovah-raised; Jehoram, the name of a Syrian and of three Israelites: Jehoram, Joram. Compare יוֹרָם.
from יְהֹוָה and שָׁבַע; Jehovah-sworn; Jehosheba, an Israelitess: Jehosheba. Compare יְהוֹשַׁבְעַת.
a form of יְהוֹשֶׁ֫בַע; Jehoshabath, an Israelitess: Jehoshabeath.
or Yhowshua; from יְהֹוָה and יָשַׁע; Jehovah-saved; Jehoshua (i.e. Joshua), the Jewish leader: Jehoshua, Jehoshuah, Joshua. Compare הוֹשֵׁ֫עַ, יֵשׁ֫וּעַ.
from יְהֹוָה and שָׁפַט; Jehovah-judged; Jehoshaphat, the name of six Israelites; also of a valley near Jerusalem: Jehoshaphat. Compare יוֹשָׁפָט.
probably from the same as הָר; elated; hence, arrogant: haughty, proud.
from הָלַל and אֵל; praising God; Jehallelel, the name of two Israelites: Jehalellel, Jehalelel.
from הָלַם (in the sense of hardness); a precious stone, probably onyx: diamond.
or Yahtsah; or (feminine) Yahtsah; from an unused root meaning to stamp; perhaps threshing-floor; Jahats or Jahtsah, a place East of the Jordan: Jahaz, Jahazah, Jahzah.
from יְהֹוָה and אָב; Jehovah-fathered; Joab, the name of three Israelites: Joab.
from יְהֹוָה and אָח; Jehovah-brothered; Joach, the name of four Israelites: Joah.
a form of יְהוֹאָחָז; Joachaz, the name of two Israelites: Jehoahaz, Joahaz.
from יְהֹוָה and אֵל; Jehovah (is his) God; Joel, the name of twelve Israelites: Joel.
or Yoash (2 Chron. 24:1); a form of יְהוֹאָשׁ; Joash, the name of six Israelites: Joash.
perhaps a form of יוֹבָב, but more probably by erroneous transcription for יָשׁוּב; Job, an Israelite: Job.
from יָבַב; howler; Jobab, the name of two Israelites and of three foreigners: Jobab.

or yobel; apparently from יָבַל; the blast of a horn (from its continuous sound); specifically, the signal of the silver trumpets; hence, the instrument itself and the festival thus introduced: jubile, ram's horn, trumpet.
from יָבַל; a stream: river.
from יָבַל; stream; Jubal, an antediluvian: Jubal.
a form of יְהוֹזָבָד; Jozabad, the name of ten Israelites: Josabad, Jozabad.
from יְהֹוָה and זָכַר; Jehovah-remembered; Jozacar, an Israelite: Jozachar.
probably from יְהֹוָה and a variation of חָיָה; Jehovah-revived; Jocha, the name of two Israelites: Joha.
a form of יְהוֹחָנָן; Jochanan, the name of nine Israelites: Johanan.
a form of יְהוֹיָדָע; Jojada, the name of two Israelites: Jehoiada, Joiada.
a form of יְהוֹיָכִין; Jojakin, an Israelite king: Jehoiachin.
a form of יְהוֹיָקִים; Jojakim, an Israelite: Joiakim. Compare יוֹקִים.
a form of יְהוֹיָרִיב; Jojarib, the name of four Israelites: Joiarib.
from יְהֹוָה contracted and כָּבַד; Jehovah-gloried; Jokebed, the mother of Moses: Jochebed.
a form of יְהוּכַל; Jukal, an Israelite: Jucal.

from an unused root meaning to be hot; a day (as the warm hours), whether literal (from sunrise to sunset, or from one sunset to the next), or figurative (a space of time defined by an associated term), (often used adverb): age, + always, + chronicals, continually(-ance), daily, ((birth-), each, to) day, (now a, two) days (agone), + elder, X end, + evening, + (for) ever(-lasting, -more), X full, life, as (so) long as (... live), (even) now, + old, + outlived, + perpetually, presently, + remaineth, X required, season, X since, space, then, (process of) time, + as at other times, + in trouble, weather, (as) when, (a, the, within a) while (that), X whole (+ age), (full) year(-ly), + younger.
(Aramaic) corresponding to יוֹם; a day: day (by day), time.
from יוֹם; daily: daily, (by, in the) day(-time).

probably from the same as יָ֫יִן; effervescing (i.e. hot and active); Javan, the name of a son of Joktan, and of the race (Ionians, i.e. Greeks) descended from him, with their territory; also of a place in Arabia: Javan.
from the same as יָ֫יִן; properly, dregs (as effervescing); hence, mud: mire, miry.
a form of יְהוֹנָדָב; Jonadab, the name of an Israelite and of a Rechabite: Jonadab.
probably from the same as יָ֫יִן; a dove (apparently from the warmth of their mating): dove, pigeon.
the same as יוֹנִים; Jonah, an Israelite: Jonah.
patronymically from יָוֵן; a Jevanite, or descendant of Javan: Grecian.
active participle of יָנַק; a sucker; hence, a twig (of a tree felled and sprouting): tender plant.
feminine of יוֹנֵק; a sprout: (tender) branch, young twig.

from יוֹנִים and אֵ֫לֶם and the plural of רָחוֹק; dove of (the) silence (i.e. dumb Israel) of (i.e. among) distances (i.e. strangers); the title of a ditty (used for a name of its melody): Jonath-elem-rechokim.
a form of יְהוֹנָתָן; Jonathan, the name of ten Israelites: Jonathan.
future of יָסַף; let him add (or perhaps simply active participle adding); Joseph, the name of seven Israelites: Joseph. Compare יְהוֹסֵף.
from active participle of יָסַף and יָהּ; Jah (is) adding; Josiphjah, an Israelite: Josiphiah.
perhaps feminine active participle of יָעַל; furthermore; Joelah, an Israelite: Joelah.
apparently the active participle of יָעַד; appointer; Joed, an Israelite: Joed.
from יְהֹוָה and עֵ֫זֶר; Jehovah (is his) help; Joezer, an Israelite: Joezer.
from יְהֹוָה and עוּשׁ; Jehovah-hastened; Joash, the name of two Israelites: Joash.
a form of יְהוֹצָדָק; Jotsadak, an Israelite: Jozadak.
a form of יוֹיָקִים; Jokim, an Israelite: Jokim.
active participle of יָרָה; sprinkling; hence, a sprinkling (or autumnal showers): first rain, former (rain).
from יָרָה; rainy; Jorah, an Israelite: Jorah.
from יָרָה; rainy; Jorai, an Israelite: Jorai.
a form of יְהוֹרָם; Joram, the name of three Israelites and one Syrian: Joram.
from שׁוּב and חָ֫סֶד; kindness will be returned; Jushab-Chesed, an Israelite: Jushab-hesed.
from יָשַׁב and יָהּ; Jehovah will cause to dwell; Josibjah, an Israelite: Josibiah.
probably a form of יוֹשַׁוְיָה; Joshah, an Israelite: Joshah.
from יְהֹוָה and שָׁוָה; Jehovah-set; Joshavjah, an Israelite: Joshaviah. Compare יוֹשָׁה.
a form of יְהוֹשָׁפָט; Joshaphat, an Israelite: Joshaphat.
from יְהֹוָה and תָּם־; Jehovah (is) perfect; Jotham, the name of three Israelites: Jotham.
active participle of יָתַר; properly, redundant; hence, over and above, as adjective, noun, adverb or conjunction (as follows): better, more(-over), over, profit.
from an unused root (meaning to sprinkle) and אֵל; sprinkled of God; Jezavel, an Israelite: Jeziel (from the margin).
from the same as the first part of יְזוּאֵל and יָהּ; sprinkled of Jah; Jizzijah, an Israelite: Jeziah.
from the same as זִיז; he will make prominent; Jaziz, an Israelite: Jaziz.
perhaps from an unused root (meaning to draw up); he will draw out; Jizliah, an Israelite: Jezliah.
or Yzanyahuw; probably for יַאֲזַנְיָה; Jezanjah, an Israelite: Jezaniah.
from an unused root mean to ooze; sweat, i.e. (by implication) a sweating dress: any thing that causeth sweat.
a variation for אֶזְרָחִי; a Jizrach (i.e. Ezrachite or Zarchite) or descendant of Zerach: Izrahite.
from זָרַח and יָהּ; Jah will shine; Jizrachjah, the name of two Israelites: Izrahiah, Jezrahiah.
from זָרַע and אֵל; God will sow; Jizreel, the name of two places in Palestine and of two Israelites: Jezreel.
patronymically from יִזְרְעֶאל; a Jizreelite or native of Jizreel: Jezreelite.
feminine of יִזְרְעֵאלִי; a Jezreelitess: Jezreelitess.
from חָבָה; hidden; Jechubbah, an Israelite: Jehubbah.
a primitive root; to be (or become) one: join, unite.
from יָחַד; properly, a unit, i.e. (adverb) unitedly: alike, at all (once), both, likewise, only, (al-)together, withal.
from יָ֫חַד with pronominal suffix; his unity, i.e. (adverb) together; Jachdo, an Israelite: Jahdo.
from יָ֫חַד and אֵל; unity of God; Jachdiel, an Israelite: Jahdiel.
from יָ֫חַד and יָהּ; unity of Jah; Jechdijah, the name of two Israelites: Jehdeiah.
from חָזָה and אֵל; beheld of God; Jachaziel, the name of five Israelites: Jahaziel, Jahziel.
from חָזָה and יָהּ; Jah will behold; Jachzejah, an Israelite: Jahaziah.
from חָזַק and אֵל; God will strengthen; Jechezkel, the name of two Israelites: Ezekiel, Jehezekel.
or Ychizqiyahuw; from יְרוּשָׁה and יָהּ; strengthened of Jah; Jechizkijah, the name of five Israelites: Hezekiah, Jehizkiah. Compare חִזְקִיָּה.
from the same as חֲזִיר; perhaps protection; Jachzerah, an Israelite: Jahzerah.
or (2 Chron. 29:14) Ychavrel; from חָיָה and אֵל; God will live; Jechiel (or Jechavel), the name of eight Israelites: Jehiel.
patronymically from יְחִיאֵל; a Jechielite or descendant of Jechiel: Jehieli.
from יָחַד; properly, united, i.e. sole; by implication, beloved; also lonely; (feminine) the life (as not to be replaced): darling, desolate, only (child, son), solitary.
from חָיָה and יָהּ; Jah will live; Jechijah, an Israelite: Jehiah.
from יָחַל; expectant: should hope.
a primitive root; to wait; by implication, to be patient, hope: (cause to, have, make to) hope, be pained, stay, tarry, trust, wait.
from יָחַל and אֵל; expectant of God; Jachleel, an Israelite: Jahleel.
patronymically from יַחְלְאֵל; a Jachleelite or descendant of Jachleel: Jahleelites.
a primitive root; probably to be hot; figuratively, to conceive: get heat, be hot, conceive, be warm.
from חָמַר; a kind of deer (from the color; compare חֲמוֹר): fallow deer.
probably from יָחַם; hot; Jachmai, an Israelite: Jahmai.
from an unused root meaning to take off the shoes; unsandalled: barefoot, being unshod.
from חָצָה and אֵל; God will allot; Jachtseel, an Israelite: Jahzeel. Compare יַחְצִיאֵל.
patronymically from יַחְצְאֵל; a Jachtseelite (collectively) or descendants of Jachtseel: Jahzeelites.
from חָצָה and אֵל; allotted of God; Jachtsiel, an Israelite: Jahziel. Compare יַחְצְאֵל.
a primitive root; to delay: tarry longer.
a primitive root; to sprout; used only as denominative from יַ֫חַשׂ; to enroll by pedigree: (number after, number throughout the) genealogy (to be reckoned), be reckoned by genealogies.
from יָחַשׂ; a pedigree or family list (as growing spontaneously): genealogy.
from יָחַד; unity; Jachath, the name of four Israelites: Jahath.

a primitive root; to be (causative) make well, literally (sound, beautiful) or figuratively (happy, successful, right): be accepted, amend, use aright, benefit, be (make) better, seem best, make cheerful, be comely, + be content, diligent(-ly), dress, earnestly, find favour, give, be glad, do (be, make) good((-ness)), be (make) merry, please (+ well), shew more (kindness), skilfully, X very small, surely, make sweet, thoroughly, tire, trim, very, be (can, deal, entreat, go, have) well (said, seen).
(Aramaic) corresponding to יָטַב: seem good.
from יָטַב; pleasantness; Jotbah, a place in Palestine: Jotbah.
from יָטְבָה; Jotbathah, a place in the Desert: Jotbath, Jotbathah.
or Yuwtah; from נָטָה; extended; Juttah (or Jutah), a place in Palestine: Juttah.
probably from the same as טוּר; encircled (i.e. inclosed); Jetur, a son of Ishmael: Jetur.
from an unused root meaning to effervesce; wine (as fermented); by implication, intoxication: banqueting, wine, wine(-bibber).
by erroneous transcription for יָד; a hand or side(way-)side.

a primitive root; to be right (i.e. correct); reciprocal, to argue; causatively, to decide, justify or convict: appoint, argue, chasten, convince, correct(-ion), daysman, dispute, judge, maintain, plead, reason (together), rebuke, reprove(-r), surely, in any wise.
from כּוּן; he (or it) will establish; Jakin, the name of three Israelites and of a temple pillar: Jachin.
patronymically from יָכִין; a Jakinite (collectively) or descendants of Jakin: Jachinites.

or (fuller) yakowl; a primitive root; to be able, literally (can, could) or morally (may, might): be able, any at all (ways), attain, can (away with, (-not)), could, endure, might, overcome, have power, prevail, still, suffer.
(Aramaic) or ykiyl (Aramaic); to יָכֹל: be able, can, couldest, prevail.
and Ykolyahuw; or (2 Chronicles 26:3) Ykiylyah; from יָכֹל and יָהּ; Jah will enable; Jekoljah or Jekiljah, an Israelitess: Jecholiah, Jecoliah.
and Ykonyahuw; or (Jereremiah 27:20) Ykownyah; from כּוּן and יָהּ; Jah will establish; Jekonjah, a Jewish king: Jeconiah. Compare כָּנְיָ֫הוּ.

a primitive root; to bear young; causatively, to beget; medically, to act as midwife; specifically, to show lineage: bear, beget, birth((-day)), born, (make to) bring forth (children, young), bring up, calve, child, come, be delivered (of a child), time of delivery, gender, hatch, labour, (do the office of a) midwife, declare pedigrees, be the son of, (woman in, woman that) travail(-eth, -ing woman).
from יָלַד; something born, i.e. a lad or offspring: boy, child, fruit, son, young man (one).
feminine of יָ֫לֶד; a lass: damsel, girl.
abstractly from יָ֫לֶד; boyhood (or girlhood): childhood, youth.
passive from יָלַד; born: born.
from לוּן; lodging; Jalon, an Israelite: Jalon.
from יָלַד; born: ((home-))born, child, son.

a primitive root (compare הָלַך); to walk (literally or figuratively); causatively, to carry (in various senses): X again, away, bear, bring, carry (away), come (away), depart, flow, + follow(-ing), get (away, hence, him), (cause to, made) go (away, -ing, -ne, one's way, out), grow, lead (forth), let down, march, prosper, + pursue, cause to run, spread, take away ((-journey)), vanish, (cause to) walk(-ing), wax, X be weak.
a primitive root; to howl (with a wailing tone) or yell (with a boisterous one): (make to) howl, be howling.
from יָלַל; a howl; -howling.
feminine of יְלֵל; a howling.
a primitive root; to blurt or utter inconsiderately: devour.
from an unused root apparently meaning to stick or scrape; scurf or tetter: scabbed.
from an unused root meaning to lick up; a devourer; specifically, the young locust: cankerworm, caterpillar.
from לָקַט; a travelling pouch (as if for gleanings):-scrip.

from an unused root meaning to roar; a sea (as breaking in noisy surf) or large body of water; specifically (with the article), the Mediterranean Sea; sometimes a large river, or an artifical basin; locally, the west, or (rarely) the south: sea (X -faring man, (-shore)), south, west (-ern, side, -ward).
(Aramaic) corresponding to יָם: sea.
from the same as יוֹם; a warm spring: mule.
from יוֹם and אֵל; day of God; Jemuel, an Israelite: Jemuel.
perhaps from the same as יוֹם; properly, warm, i.e. affectionate; hence, dove (compare יוֹנִים); Jemimah, one of Job's daughters: Jemimah.
from יָמַן; the right hand or side (leg, eye) of a person or other object (as the stronger and more dexterous); locally, the south: + left-handed, right (hand, side), south.
the same as יָמִין; Jamin, the name of three Israelites: Jamin. See also בִּנְיָמִן.
for יָמִין; right: (on the) right (hand).
patronymically from יָמִין; a Jeminite (collectively) or descendants of Jamin: Jaminites. See also בֶּן־יְמִינִי.
or Yimlah; from מָלֵא; full; Jimla or Jimlah, an Israelite: Imla, Imlah.
from מָלַך; he will make king; Jamlek, an Israelite: Jamlech.

a primitive root; to be (physically) right (i.e. firm); but used only as denominative from יָמִין and transitive, to be right-handed or take the right-hand side: go (turn) to (on, use) the right hand.
from יָמַן; prosperity (as betokened by the right hand); Jimnah, the name of two Israelites; also (with the article) of the posterity of one of them: Imna, Imnah, Jimnah, Jimnites.
from יָמַן; right (i.e. at the right hand): -(on the) right (hand).
from מָנַע; he will restrain; Jimna, an Israelite: -Imna.
a primitive root; to exchange; by implication, to change places: boast selves, change.
probably from יָמַר; interchange; Jimrah, an IsraeliteImrah.
a primitive root; to touch: feel.
a primitive root; to rage or be violent: by implication, to suppress, to maltreat: destroy, (thrust out by) oppress(-ing, -ion, -or), proud, vex, do violence.
: , or (with enclitic) Yanowchah from יָנַח; quiet; Janoach or Janochah, a place in Palestine: Janoah, Janohah.

a primitive root; to deposit; by implication, to allow to stay: bestow, cast down, lay (down, up), leave (off), let alone (remain), pacify, place, put, set (down), suffer, withdraw, withhold. (The Hiphil forms with the dagesh are here referred to, in accordance with the older grammarians; but if any distinction of the kind is to be made, these should rather be referred to נ֫וּחַ, and the others here.)
from נוּם; asleep; Janim, a place in Palestine: -Janum (from the margin).
from יָנַק; a sucker or sapling: young twig.
a primitive root; to suck; causatively, to give milk: milch, nurse(-ing mother), (give, make to) suck(-ing child, -ling).
or yanshowph; apparently from נָשַׁף; an unclean (acquatic) bird; probably the heron (perhaps from its blowing cry, or because the night-heron is meant (compare נֶ֫שֶׁף))): (great) owl.s

a primitive root; to set (literally or figuratively); intensively, to found; reflexively, to sit down together, i.e. settle, consult: appoint, take counsel, establish, (lay the, lay for a) found(-ation), instruct, lay, ordain, set, X sure.
from יָסַד; a foundation (figuratively, i.e. beginning): X began.
from יָסַד; a foundation (literally or figuratively):--bottom, foundation, repairing
feminine of יְסֻד; a foundation: foundation.
from סוּר; departing:--they that depart
from יָסַר; a reprover: instruct.
a primitive root; to pour (intransitive): be poured.
from an unused root meaning to watch; observant; Jiskah, sister of Lot: Iscah.
from סָמַך and יָהּ; Jah will sustain; Jismakjah, an Israelite: Ismachiah.

a primitive root; to add or augment (often adverbial, to continue to do a thing): add, X again, X any more, X cease, X come more, + conceive again, continue, exceed, X further, X gather together, get more, give more-over, X henceforth, increase (more and more), join, X longer (bring, do, make, much, put), X (the, much, yet) more (and more), proceed (further), prolong, put, be (strong-) er, X yet, yield.
(Aramaic) corresponding to יָסַף: add.
a primitive root; to chastise, literally (with blows) or figuratively (with words); hence, to instruct: bind, chasten, chastise, correct, instruct, punish, reform, reprove, sore, teach.
from יָעָה; a shovel: shovel.
from an unused root probably meaning to grieve; sorrowful; Jabets, the name of an Israelite, and also of a place in Palestine: -Jabez.

a primitive root; to fix upon (by agreement or appointment); by implication, to meet (at a stated time), to summon (to trial), to direct (in a certain quarter or position), to engage (for marriage): -agree,(maxke an) appoint(-ment,a time), assemble (selves), betroth, gather (selves, together), meet (together), set (a time).
from יָעַד; appointed; Jedi, an Israelite: Iddo (from the margin) See Yiddow.
a primitive root; apparently to brush aside: sweep away.
from יָעָה and אֵל; carried away of God; Jeuel, the name of four Israelites; -Jehiel, Jeiel, Jeuel. Compare יְעִיאֵל.
from עוּץ; counsellor; Jeuts, an Israelite: -Jeuz.(gl
a variation of יַעֲרֶשְׁיָה; a forest: wood.
apparently the passive participle of the same as יָ֫עַר; wooded; Jaur, an Israelite: Jair(from the margin).
from עוּשׁ; hasty; Jeush, the name of an Edomite and of four Israelites: Jehush, Jeush. Compare יְעִישׁ.
a primitive root; to be bold or obstinate: d-fierce.
from יָעַז and אֵל; emboldened of God; Jaaziel, an Israelite: Jaaziel.
from יָעַז and יָהּ; emboldened of Jah; Jaazijah, an Israelite: Jaaziah.
or Yazer; from עָזַר; helpful; Jaazer or Jazer, a place East of the Jordan: Jaazer, Jazer.
a primitive root; to clothe: cover.
(Aramaic) corresponding to יָעַץ; to counsel; reflexively, to consult: counsellor, consult together.
from יָעָה and אֵל; carried away of God; Jeiel, the name of six Israelites: Jeiel, Jehiel. Compare יְעוּאֵל.
from עוּשׁ; hasty; Jeish, the name of an Edomite and of a an Israelite: Jeush (from the margin). Compare יְעוּשׁ.
from the same as עָכָן; troublesome; Jakan, an Israelite: Jachan.
a primitive root; properly, to ascend; figuratively, to be valuable (objectively: useful, subjectively: benefited): X at all, set forward, can do good, (be, have) profit, (able).
from יָעַל; an ibex (as climbing): wild goat.
the same as יָעֵל; Jael, a Canaanite: Jael.
or Yaaalah; the same as יַעֲלַת or direct from יָעַל; Jaala or Jaalah, one of the Nethinim: Jaala, Jaalah.
feminine of יָעֵל: roe.
from עָלַם; occult; Jalam, an Edomite: Jalam.

from an unused root meaning to pay attention; properly, heed; by implication, purpose (sake or account); used adverbially to indicate the reason or cause: because (that), forasmuch (+ as), seeing then, + that, + wheras, + why.
from the same as יַ֫עַן; the ostrich (probably from its answering cry: ostrich.
feminine of יְעֵנִים, and meaning the same: + owl.
from the same as יְעֵנִים; responsive; Jaanai, an Israelite: Jaanai.
a primitive root; to tire (as if from wearisome flight): faint, cause to fly, (be) weary (self).
: ; from יָעַף; fatigued; figuratively, exhausted: faint, weary.
from יָעַף; fatigue (adverb, utterly exhausted): -swiftly.e
a primitive root; to advise; reflexively, to deliberate or resolve: advertise, take advise, advise (well), consult, (give, take) counsel(-lor), determine, devise, guide, purpose.
from עָקַב; heel-catcher (i.e. supplanter); Jaakob, the Israelitish patriarch: Jacob.
from יַעֲקֹב; Jaakobah, an Israelite: -Jaakobah.
from the same as עֲקָן; Jaakan, an Idumaean: -Jaakan. Compare בְּנֵי יַעֲקָן.
from an unused root probably meaning to thicken with verdure; a copse of bushes; hence, a forest; hence, honey in the comb (as hived in trees): (honey-)comb, forest, wood.
a form of יַעְרַת; Jarah, an Israelite: Jarah.
feminine of יָ֫עַר, and meaning the same: (honey-) comb, forest.
from the plural of יָ֫עַר and the masculine plural active participle of אָרַג; woods of weavers; Jaare-Oregim, an Israelite: Jaare-oregim.
plural of יָ֫עַר; forests; Jearim, a place in Palestine: Jearim. Compare קִרְיַת יְעָרִים.
from an unused root of uncertain signification and יָהּ; Jaareshjah, an Israelite: Jaresiah.
from עָשָׂה; they will do; Jaasu, an Israelite: -Jaasau.
from עָשָׂה and אֵל; made of God; Jaasiel, an Israelite: Jaasiel, Jasiel.
from פָּדָה and יָהּ; Jah will liberate; Jiphdejah, an Israelite: Iphedeiah.
a primitive root; properly, to be bright, i.e. (by implication) beautiful: be beautiful, be (make self) fair(-r), deck.
from יָפָה; beautiful (literally or figuratively): + beautiful, beauty, comely, fair(-est, one), + goodly, pleasant, well.
from יָפָה by reduplication; very beautiful: very fair.
or Yaphow (Ezra 3:7); from יָפָה; beautiful; Japho, a place in Palestine: Japha, Joppa.
a primitive root; properly, to breathe hard, i.e. (by implication) to sigh: bewail self.
from יָפַח; properly, puffing, i.e. (figuratively) meditating: such as breathe out.
from יָפָה; beauty: beauty.
from יָפַע; bright; Japhia, the name of a Canaanite, an Israelite, and a place in Palestine: Japhia.
from פָּלַט; he will deliver; Japhlet, an Israelite: Japhlet.
patronymically from יַפְלֵט; a Japhletite or descendant of Japhlet: Japhleti.
from פָּנָה; he will be prepared; Jephunneh, the name of two Israelites: Jephunneh.
a primitive root; to shine: be light, shew self, (cause to) shine (forth).
from יָפַע; splendor or (figuratively) beauty: -brightness.
from פָּתָה; expansion; Jepheth, a son of Noah; also his posterity: Japheth.
from פָּתַח; he will open; Jiphtach, an Israelite; also a place in Palestine: Jephthah, Jiphtah.
from פָּתַח and אֵל; God will open; Jiphtach-el, a place in Palestine: Jiphthah-el.

a primitive root; to go (causatively, bring) out, in a great variety of applications, literally and figuratively, direct and proxim.: X after, appear, X assuredly, bear out, X begotten, break out, bring forth (out, up), carry out, come (abroad, out, thereat, without), + be condemned, depart(-ing, -ure), draw forth, in the end, escape, exact, fail, fall (out), fetch forth (out), get away (forth, hence, out), (able to, cause to, let) go abroad (forth, on, out), going out, grow, have forth (out), issue out, lay (lie) out, lead out, pluck out, proceed, pull out, put away, be risen, X scarce, send with commandment, shoot forth, spread, spring out, stand out, X still, X surely, take forth (out), at any time, X to (and fro), utter.
(Aramaic) corresponding to יָצָא: finish.

a primitive root; to place (any thing so as to stay); reflexively, to station, offer, continue: present selves, remaining, resort, set (selves), (be able to, can, with-) stand (fast, forth, -ing, still, up).
(Aramaic) corresponding to יָצַב; to be firm; hence, to speak surely: truth.
a primitive root; to place permanently: establish, leave, make, present, put, set, stay.
from צָהַר; oil (as producing light); figuratively, anointing: + anointed oil.
the same as יִצְהָר; Jitshar, an Israelite: Izhar.
patronymically from יִצְהָר; a Jitsharite or descendant of Jitshar: Izeharites, Izharites.
passive participle of יָצַע; spread, i.e. a bed; (architecture) an extension, i.e. wing or lean-to (a single story or collectively): -bed, chamber, couch.
