from צָחַק; laughter (i.e. mochery); Jitschak (or Isaac), son of Abraham: Isaac. Compare יִשְׂחָק.
from the same as צָ֫חַר; he will shine; Jitschar, an Israelite: and Zehoar (from the margin).
from יָצָא; issue, i.e. offspring: those that came forth.
(Aramaic) from יְצֵב; fixed, sure; concretely, certainty: certain(-ty), true, truth.
a primitive root; to strew as a surface: make (one's) bed, X lie, spread.

a primitive root; properly, to pour out (transitive or intransitive); by implication, to melt or cast as metal; by extension, to place firmly, to stiffen or grow hard: cast, cleave fast, be (as) firm, grow, be hard, lay out, molten, overflow, pour (out), run out, set down, stedfast.
passive participle feminine of יָצַק; poured out, i.e. run into a mould: when it was cast.
a primitive root; to press (intransitive), i.e. be narrow; figuratively, be in distress: be distressed, be narrow, be straitened (in straits), be vexed.

probably identical with יָצַר (through the squeezing into shape); ((compare יָצַע)); to mould into a form; especially as a potter; figuratively, to determine (i.e. form a resolution): X earthen, fashion, form, frame, make(-r), potter, purpose.
from יָצַר; a form; figuratively, conception (i.e. purpose): frame, thing framed, imagination, mind, work.
the same as יֵ֫צֶר; Jetser, an Israelite: Jezer.
passive participle of יָצַר; structure, i.e. limb or part: member.ql
from יָצַר; formative; Jitsri, an Israelite: -Isri.
:  : patronymically from יֵ֫צֶר; a Jitsrite (collectively) or descendants of Jetser: Jezerites.
a primitive root; to burn or set on fire; figuratively, to desolate: burn (up), be desolate, set (on) fire ((fire)), kindle.

from an unused root meaning to excavate; a trough (as dug out); specifically, a wine-vat (whether the lower one, into which the juice drains; or the upper, in which the grapes are crushed): fats, presses, press-fat, wine(-press).
from קָבַץ and אֵל; God will gather; Jekabtseel, a place in Palestine: Jekabzeel. Compare קַבְצְאֵל.
a primitive root; to burn: (be) burn(-ing), X from the hearth, kindle.
(Aramaic) corresponding to יָקַד: burning.
(Aramaic) from יְקַד; a conflagration: -burning.
from יָקַד and עָם; burning of (the) people; Jokdeam, a place in Palestine: Jokdeam.
from an unused root probably meaning to obey; obedient; Jakeh, a symbolical name (for Solomon): Jakeh.
from the same as יָקֶה; obedience: -gathering, to obey.
from יָקַד; a burning: burning.
from קוּם; properly, standing (extant), i.e. by implication, a living thing: (living) substance.
from יָקֹשׁ; properly, entangling; hence, a snarer: -fowler.
passive participle of יָקֹשׁ; properly, entangled, i.e. by implication (intransitively) a snare, or (transitive) a snarer: fowler, snare.
from the same as יָקֶה and אֵל; obedience of God; Jekuthiel, an Israelite: Jekuthiel.
from קָטַן; he will be made little; Joktan, an Arabian patriarch: Joktan.
from קוּם; he will raise; Jakim, the name of two Israelites: Jakim. Compare יְהוֹיָקִים.
from יָקַר; precious: dear.
(Aramaic) corresponding to יַקִּיר: noble, rare.
from קוּם and יָהּ; Jah will rise; Jekamjah, the name of two Israelites: Jekamiah. Compare יְהוֹיָקִים.
from קוּם and עָם; (the) people will rise; Jekamam, an Israelite: Jekameam. Compare יְהוֹיָקִים, יָקְמְעָם.
from קוּם and עָם; (the) people will be raised; Jokmeam, a place in Palestine: Jokmeam. Compare יְקַמְעָם, יׇקְנְעָם.
from קוּן and עָם; (the) people will be lamented; Jokneam, a place in Palestine: Jokneam.

a primitive root; properly, to sever oneself, i.e. (by implication) to be dislocated; figuratively, to abandon; causatively, to impale (and thus allow to drop to pieces by rotting): be alienated, depart, hang (up), be out of joint.
a primitive root; to awake (intransitive): (be) awake(-d).
a primitive root; properly, apparently, to be heavy, i.e. (figuratively) valuable; causatively, to make rare (figuratively, to inhibit): be (make) precious, be prized, be set by, withdraw.
from יָקַר; value, i.e. (concretely) wealth; abstractly, costliness, dignity: honour, precious (things), price.
(Aramaic) corresponding to יְקָר: glory, honour.
from יָקַר; valuable (obj. or subj.): -brightness, clear, costly, excellent, fat, honourable women, precious, reputation.
a primitive root; to ensnare (literally or figuratively): fowler (lay a) snare.
from יָקֹשׁ; insidious; Jokshan, an Arabian patriarch: Jokshan.
probably from the same as יָקֶה and אֵל; veneration of God (compare יְקוּתִיאֵל); Joktheel, the name of a place in Palestine, and of one in Idumaea: Joktheel.

a primitive root; to fear; morally, to revere; caus. to frighten: affright, be (make) afraid, dread(-ful), (put in) fear(-ful, -fully, -ing), (be had in) reverence(-end), X see, terrible (act, -ness, thing).
from יָרֵא; fearing; morally, reverent: afraid, fear (-ful).
feminine of יָרֵא; fear (also used as infinitive); morally, reverence: X dreadful, X exceedingly, fear(-fulness).
from יָרֵא; fearfulness; Jiron, a place in Pal: -Iron.
from יָרֵא and יָהּ; fearful of Jah; Jirijah, an Israelite: Irijah.
from רִיב; he will contend; Jareb, a symbolical name for Assyria: Jareb. Compare יָרִיב.
from רִיב and בַּ֫עַל; Baal will contend; Jerubbaal, a symbol. name of Gideon: Jerubbaal.
from רִיב and עָם; (the) people will contend; Jarobam, the name of two Israelite kings: Jeroboam.
from רִיב and בֹּ֫שֶׁת; shame (i.e. the idol) will contend; Jerubbesheth, a symbol. name for Gideon: -Jerubbesheth.

a primitive root; to descend (literally, to go downwards; or conventionally to a lower region, as the shore, a boundary, the enemy, etc.; or figuratively, to fall); causatively, to bring down (in all the above applications); -X abundantly, bring down, carry down, cast down, (cause to) come(-ing) down, fall (down), get down, go(-ing) down(-ward), hang down, X indeed, let down, light (down), put down (off), (cause to, let) run down, sink, subdue, take down.
from יָרַד; a descent; Jered, the name of an antediluvian, and of an Israelite: Jared.
from יָרַד; a descender; Jarden, the principal river of Palestine: Jordan.

or (2 Chr. 26:15) yara; a primitive root; properly, to flow as water (i.e. to rain); transitively, to lay or throw (especially an arrow, i.e. to shoot); figuratively, to point out (as if by aiming the finger), to teach: (+) archer, cast, direct, inform, instruct, lay, shew, shoot, teach(-er,-ing), through.
from יָרָה and אֵל; founded of God; Jeruel, a place in Palestine: Jeruel.
perhaps denominative from יָרֵ֫חַ; (born at the) new moon; Jaroach, an Israelite: Jaroah.
from יָרַק; green, i.e. an herb: green thing.
or Yaruwshah feminine passive participle of יָרַשׁ; possessed; Jerusha or Jerushah, as Israelitess: Jerusha, Jerushah.

rarely Yruwshalayim; a dual (in allusion to its two main hills (the true pointing, at least of the former reading, seems to be that of יְרוּשְׁלֶם)); probably from (the passive participle of) יָרָה and שָׁלַם; founded peaceful; Jerushalaim or Jerushalem, the capital city of Palestine: Jerusalem.
(Chald)
from a unused root of uncertain signification; a lunation, i.e. month: month, moon.
the same as יֶ֫רַח; Jerach, an Arabian patriarch: Jerah.
(Aramaic) corresponding to יֶ֫רַח; a month: month.
from the same as יֶ֫רַח; the moon: moon. Yrechow. See יְרֵחוֹ.
from רָחַם; compassionate; Jerocham, the name of seven or eight Israelites: Jeroham.
from רָחַם and אֵל; God will compassionate; Jerachmeel, the name of three Israelites: Jerahmeel.
patronymically from יְרַחְמְאֵל; a Jerachmeelite or descendant of Jerachmeel: Jerahmeelites.
probably of Egyptian origin; Jarcha, an Egyptian: Jarha.
a primitive root; to precipitate or hurl (rush) headlong; (intransitively) to be rash: be perverse, turn over.
from יָרָה and אֵל; thrown of God; Jeriel, an Israelite: Jeriel. Compare יְרוּאֵל.
from רִיב; literally, he will contend; properly, adjective, contentious; used as noun, an adversary: that content(-eth), that strive.
the same as יָרִיב; Jarib, the name of three Israelites: Jarib.
from יָרִיב; contentious; Jeribai, an Israelite: Jeribai.
or Yriyahuw; from יָרָה and יָהּ; Jah will throw; Jerijah, an Israelite: Jeriah, Jerijah.
or Yrechow; or variation (1 Kings 16:34) Yriychoh; perhaps from יָרֵ֫חַ; its month; or else from ר֫וּחַ; fragrant; Jericho or Jerecho, a place in Palestine: Jericho.
or Yreymowth; or Yremowth; feminine plural from רוּם; elevations; Jerimoth or Jeremoth, the name of twelve Israelites: Jermoth, Jerimoth, and Ramoth (from the margin).
from יָרַע; a hanging (as tremulous): curtain.
plural of יְרִיעָה; curtains; Jerioth, an Israelitess: Jerioth.
from an unused root meaning to be soft; the thigh (from its fleshy softness); by euphem. the generative parts; figuratively, a shank, flank, side: X body, loins, shaft, side, thigh.
(Aramaic) corresponding to יַרְכַּת; a thigh: thigh.
feminine of יָרֵך; properly, the flank; but used only figuratively, the rear or recess: border, coast, part, quarter, side.
from רוּם; elevation; Jarmuth, the name of two places in Palestine: Jarmuth.
from רוּם; elevated; Jeremai, an Israelite: -Jeremai.
or Yirmyahuw; from רוּם and יָהּ; Jah will rise; Jirmejah, the name of eight or nine Israelites: Jeremiah.
a primitive root; properly, to be broken up (with any violent action) i.e. (figuratively) to fear: be grevious (only Isa. 15:4; the rest belong to רָעַע).
from רָפָא and אֵל; God will heal; Jirpeel, a place in Palestine: Irpeel.
a primitive root; to spit: X but, spit.
from יָרַק (in the sense of vacuity of color); properly, pallor, i.e. hence, the yellowish green of young and sickly vegetation; concretely, verdure, i.e. grass or vegetation: grass, green (thing).
from the same as יֶ֫רֶק; properly, green; concretely, a vegetable: green, herbs.
from יֶ֫רֶק; paleness, whether of persons (from fright), or of plants (from drought): greenish, yellow.
from רִיק and עָם; people will be poured forth; Jorkeam, a place in Palestine: Jorkeam.
from the same as יֶ֫רֶק; yellowishness: -greenish, yellow.

or yaresh; a primitive root; to occupy (by driving out previous tenants, and possessing in their place); by implication, to seize, to rob, to inherit; also to expel, to impoverish, to ruin: cast out, consume, destroy, disinherit, dispossess, drive(-ing) out, enjoy, expel, X without fail, (give to, leave for) inherit(-ance, -or) + magistrate, be (make) poor, come to poverty, (give to, make to) possess, get (have) in (take) possession, seize upon, succeed, X utterly.
from יָרַשׁ; occupancy: possession.
from יָרַשׁ; something occupied; a conquest; also a patrimony: heritage, inheritance, possession.

perhaps from an unused root meaning to stand out, or exist; entity; used adverbially or as a copula for the substantive verb (הָיָה); there is or are (or any other form of the verb to be, as may suit the connection): (there) are, (he, it, shall, there, there may, there shall, there should) be, thou do, had, hast, (which) hath, (I, shalt, that) have, (he, it, there) is, substance, it (there) was, (there) were, ye will, thou wilt, wouldest.

a primitive root; properly, to sit down (specifically as judge. in ambush, in quiet); by implication, to dwell, to remain; causatively, to settle, to marry: (make to) abide(-ing), continue, (cause to, make to) dwell(-ing), ease self, endure, establish, X fail, habitation, haunt, (make to) inhabit(-ant), make to keep (house), lurking, X marry(-ing), (bring again to) place, remain, return, seat, set(- tle), (down-)sit(-down, still, -ting down, -ting (place) -uate), take, tarry.
from יָשַׁב and אָב; seat of (his) father; Jeshebab, an Israelite: Jeshebeab.
from the active participle of יָשַׁב and שָׁ֫בֶת, with a preposition and the article interposed; sitting in the seat; Josheb-bash-Shebeth, an Israelite: that sat in the seat.
from יָשַׁב and נֹב, with a pronominal suffix and a preposition interposed; his dwelling (is) in Nob; Jishbo-be-Nob, a Philistine: Ishbi-benob (from the margin).
from שָׁבַח; he will praise; Jishbach, an Israelite: Ishbah.
patronymically from יָשׁוּב; a Jashubite, or descendant of Jashub: Jashubites.

from שׁוּב and לָ֫חֶם; returner of bread; Jashubi-Lechem, an Israelite: Jashubi-lehem. (Prob. the text should be pointed Yoshbev Lechem, and rendered "(they were) inhabitants of Lechem," i.e. of Bethlehem (by contraction). Compare לַחְמִי).
from שׁוּב and עָם; people will return; Jashobam, the name of two or three Israelites: Jashobeam.
from an unused root corresponding to שְׁבַק; he will leave; Jishbak, a son of Abraham: Ishbak.
from יָשַׁב and קָשֶׁה; a hard seat; Joshbekashah, an Israelite: Joshbekashah.
or Yashiyb; from שׁוּב; he will return; Jashub, the name of two Israelites: Jashub.
from שָׁוָה; he will level; Jishvah, an Israelite: -Ishvah, Isvah.
from the same as יֶ֫שַׁח and יָהּ; Jah will empty; Jeshochajah, an Israelite: Jeshoaiah.
from שָׁוָה; level; Jishvi, the name of two Israelites: Ishuai, Ishvi, Isui, Jesui.
patronymically from יִשְׁוִי; a Jishvite (collectively) or descendants of Jishvi: Jesuites.
for יְהוֹשׁ֫וּעַ; he will save; Jeshua, the name of ten Israelites, also of a place in Palestine: Jeshua.
(Aramaic) corresponding to יֵשׁ֫וּעַ: Jeshua.
feminine passive participle of יָשַׁע; something saved, i.e. (abstractly) deliverance; hence, aid, victory, prosperity: deliverance, health, help(-ing), salvation, save, saving (health), welfare.
from an unused root meaning to gape (as the empty stomach); hunger: casting down.
from שַׁחֲצוֹם; he will laugh; Jischak, the heir of Abraham: Isaac. Compare יִצְחָק.
a primitive root; to extend: hold out.
by Aramaic Iyshay; from the same as יֵשׁ; extant; Jishai, David's father: Jesse.
or Yishshiyahuw; from נָשָׁה and יָהּ; Jah will lend; Jishshijah, the name of five Israelites: Ishiah, Isshiah, Ishijah, Jesiah.
from שׂוּם and אֵל; God will place; Jesimael, an Israelite: Jesimael.
from יָשַׁם; desolation: let death seize (from the margin).
from יָשַׁם; a desolation: desert, Jeshimon, solitary, wilderness.
from יָשֵׁשׁ; an old man: (very) aged (man), ancient, very old.
from יָשִׁישׁ; aged; Jeshishai, an Israelite: Jeshishai.
a prim root; to place; intransitively, to be placed: be put (set).
a primitive root; to lie waste: be desolate.
from יָשַׁם; desolate; Jishma, an Israelite: -Ishma.
from שָׁמַע and אֵל; God will hear; Jishmael, the name of Abraham's oldest son, and of five Israelites: Ishmael.
patronymically from יִשְׁמָעֵאל; a Jishmaelite or descendant of Jishmael: Ishmaelite.
or Yishmacyahuw; from שָׁמַע and יָהּ; Jah will hear; Jishmajah, the name of two Israelites: Ishmaiah.
from שָׁמַר; preservative; Jishmerai, an Israelite: Ishmerai.
a primitive root; properly, to be slack or languid, i.e. (by implication) sleep (figuratively, to die); also to grow old, stale or inveterate: -old (store), remain long, (make to) sleep.
from יָשֵׁן; sleepy: asleep, (one out of) sleep(-eth, -ing), slept.
the same as יָשֵׁן; Jashen, an Israelite: Jashen.
from יָשֵׁן; old: old.
feminine of יָשָׁן; Jeshanah, a place in Palestine: Jeshanah.

a primitive root; properly, to be open, wide or free, i.e. (by implication) to be safe; causatively, to free or succor: X at all, avenging, defend, deliver(-er), help, preserve, rescue, be safe, bring (having) salvation, save(-iour), get victory.
or yeshai; from יָשַׁע; liberty, deliverance, prosperity: safety, salvation, saving.
from יָשַׁע; saving; Jishi, the name of four Israelites: Ishi.
or Yshayahuw; from יָשַׁע and יָהּ; Jah has saved; Jeshajah, the name of seven Israelites: Isaiah, Jesaiah, Jeshaiah.
from an unused root meaning to polish; a gem supposed to be jasper (from the resemblance in name): jasper.
perhaps from שָׁפָה; he will scratch; Jishpah, an Israelite: Ispah.
probably from the same as שָׁפָן; he will hide; Jishpan, an Israelite: Ishpan.

a primitive root; to be straight or even; figuratively, to be (causatively, to make) right, pleasant, prosperous: direct, fit, seem good (meet), + please (will), be (esteem, go) right (on), bring (look, make, take the) straight (way), be upright(-ly).
from יָשַׁר; the right; Jesher, an Israelite: -Jesher.
from יָשַׁר; the right: equity, meet, right, upright(-ness).
from יָשַׁר; straight (literally or figuratively): convenient, equity, Jasher, just, meet(-est), + pleased well right(-eous), straight, (most) upright(-ly, -ness).
from שָׂרָה and אֵל; he will rule as God; Jisrael, a symbolical name of Jacob; also (typically) of his posterity: Israel.
(Aramaic) corresponding to יִשְׂרָאֵל: Israel.
by variation from יָשָׁר and אֵל with directive enclitic; right towards God; Jesarelah, an Israelite: Jesharelah.
patronymically from יִשְׂרָאֵל; a Jisreelite or descendant of Jisrael: of Israel, Israelite.
feminine of יִשְׂרְאֵלִי; a Jisreelitess or female descendant of Jisrael: Israelitish.
feminine or יָשָׁר; rectitude: uprightness.
from יָשַׁר; upright; Jeshurun, a symbol. name for Israel: Jeshurun.
(strictly yis-saws-kawr'); from נָשָׂא and שָׂכָר; he will bring a reward; Jissaskar, a son of Jacob: Issachar.
from an unused root meaning to blanch; gray-haired, i.e. an aged man: stoop for age.
(Aramaic) corresponding to אוֹת; a sign of the object of a verb: + whom.
(Aramaic) corresponding to יָשַׁב; to sit or dwell: -dwell, (be) set, sit.
from an unused root meaning to pin through or fast; a peg: nail, paddle, pin, stake.
from an unused root meaning to be lonely; a bereaved person: fatherless (child), orphan.
passive participle of יָתַר; properly, what is left, i.e. (by implication) a gleaning: range.
from יָתַר; redundant; Jattir, a place in Palestine: Jattir.
(Aramaic) corresponding to יַתִּיר; preeminent; as an adverb, very: exceeding(-ly), excellent.
probably from תָּלָה; it will hang, i.e. be high; Jithlah, a place in Palestine: Jethlah.
from the same as יָתוֹם; orphanage; Jithmah, an Israelite: Ithmah.
from an unused root meaning to endure, and אֵל; continued of God; Jathniel, an Israelite: Jathniel.
from the same as תַּנִּין; extensive; Jithnan, a place in Palestine: Ithnan.

a primitive root; to jut over or exceed; by implication, to excel; (intransitively) to remain or be left; causatively, to leave, cause to abound, preserve: excel, leave (a remnant), left behind, too much, make plenteous, preserve, (be, let) remain(-der, -ing, - nant), reserve, residue, rest.

from יָתַר; properly, an overhanging, i.e. (by implication) an excess, superiority, remainder; also a small rope (as hanging free): + abundant, cord, exceeding, excellancy(-ent), what they leave, that hath left, plentifully, remnant, residue, rest, string, with.
the same as יֶ֫תֶר; Jether, the name of five or six Israelites and of one Midianite: Jether, Jethro. Compare יִתְרוֹ.
by variation for יִתְרָה; Jithra, an Israelite (or Ishmaelite): Ithra.
feminine of יֶ֫תֶר; properly, excellence, i.e. (by implication) wealth: abundance, riches.
from יֶ֫תֶר with pron. suffix; his excellence; Jethro, Moses' father-in-law: Jethro. Compare יֶ֫תֶר.
from יָתַר; preeminence, gain: better, excellency(-leth), profit(-able).
patronymically from יֶ֫תֶר; a Jithrite or descendant of Jether: Ithrite.
from יָתַר; excellent; Jithran, the name of an Edomite and of an Israelite: Ithran.
from יֶ֫תֶר and עָם; excellence of people; Jithream, a son of David: Ithream.
feminine active participle of יָתַר; the lobe or flap of the liver (as if redundant or outhanging): caul.
of uncertain derivation; Jetheth, an Edomite: -Jetheth.
a primitive root; properly, to feel pain; by implication, to grieve; figuratively, to spoil: grieving, mar, have pain, make sad (sore), (be) sorrowful.
from כָּאַב; suffering (physical or mental), adversity: grief, pain, sorrow.
a primitive root; to despond: causatively, to deject: broken, be grieved, make sad.

or kabed; a primitive root; to be heavy, i.e. in a bad sense (burdensome, severe, dull) or in a good sense (numerous, rich, honorable; causatively, to make weighty (in the same two senses): abounding with, more grievously afflict, boast, be chargeable, X be dim, glorify, be (make) glorious (things), glory, (very) great, be grievous, harden, be (make) heavy, be heavier, lay heavily, (bring to, come to, do, get, be had in) honour (self), (be) honourable (man), lade, X more be laid, make self many, nobles, prevail, promote (to honour), be rich, be (go) sore, stop.
from כָּבַד; weight, multitude, vehemence: -grievousness, heavy, great number.
from כָּבַד; heavy; figuratively in a good sense (numerous) or in a bad sense (severe, difficult, stupid): (so) great, grievous, hard(-ened), (too) heavy(-ier), laden, much, slow, sore, thick.
the same as כָּבֵד; the liver (as the heaviest of the viscera): liver.
feminine of כָּבֵד; difficulty: X heavily.
a primitive root; to expire or (causatively) to extinguish (fire, light, anger): go (put) out, quench.
rarely kabod; from כָּבַד; properly, weight, but only figuratively in a good sense, splendor or copiousness: glorious(-ly), glory, honour(-able).
irreg. feminine passive participle of כָּבַד; weightiness, i.e. magnificence, wealth: carriage, all glorious, stately.
from the same as כֶּ֫בֶל in the sense of limitation; sterile; Cabul, the name of two places in Palestine: Cabul.
from an unused root meaning to heap up; hilly; Cabon, a place in Palestine: Cabbon.
from כָּבַר in the original sense of plaiting; a matrass (of intertwined materials): pillow.
from כָּבַר; vast, whether in extent (figuratively, of power, mighty; of time, aged), or in number, many: + feeble, mighty, most, much, strong, valiant.
from an unused root meaning to twine or braid together; a fetter: fetter.
a primitive root; to trample; hence, to wash (properly, by stamping with the feet), whether literal (including the fulling process) or figurative: fuller, wash(-ing).
a primitive root; properly, to plait together, i.e. (figuratively) to augment (especially in number or quantity, to accumulate): in abundance, multiply.
from כָּבַר; properly, extent of time, i.e. a great while; hence, long ago, formerly, hitherto: already, (seeing that which), now.
the same as כְּבָר; length; Kebar, a river of Mesopotamia: Chebar. Compare חָבוֹר.
feminine of כְּבָר; properly, length, i.e. a measure (of uncertain dimension): X little.
from כָּבַר in its original sense; a sieve (as netted): sieve.
from an unused root meaning to dominate; a ram (just old enough to butt): lamb, sheep.
a primitive root; to tread down; hence, negatively, to disregard; positively, to conquer, subjugate, violate: bring into bondage, force, keep under, subdue, bring into subjection.
from כָּבַשׁ; a footstool (as trodden upon): -footstool.
or kabsah; feminine of כֶּ֫בֶשׂ; a ewe: (ewe) lamb.
from כָּבַשׁ; a smelting furnace (as reducing metals): furnace.
from an unused root meaning to deepen; properly, a pail; but generally of earthenware; a jar for domestic purposes: barrel, pitcher.
(Aramaic) from a root corresponding to כָּזַב; false: -lying.
from the same as כַּד in the sense of striking fire from a metal forged; a sparkling gem, probably the ruby: agate.
of foreign origin; Kedorlaomer, an early Persian king: Chedorlaomer.

from the prefix k and הוּא; properly, like this, i.e. by implication, (of manner) thus (or so); also (of place) here (or hither); or (of time) now: also, here, + hitherto, like, on the other side, so (and much), such, on that manner, (on) this (manner, side, way, way and that way), + mean while, yonder.
(Aramaic) corresponding to כֹּה: hitherto.
a primitive root; to be weak, i.e. (figuratively) to despond (causatively, rebuke), or (of light, the eye) to grow dulldarken, be dim, fail, faint, restrain, X utterly.
from כָּהָה; feeble, obscure: somewhat dark, darkish, wax dim, heaviness, smoking.
feminine of כֵּהָה; properly, a weakening; figuratively, alleviation, i.e. cure: healing.
(Aramaic) a root corresponding to יָכֹל and כּוּל; to be able: be able, could.

a primitive root, apparently meaning to mediate in religious services; but used only as denominative from כֹּהֵן; to officiate as a priest; figuratively, to put on regalia: deck, be (do the office of a, execute the, minister in the) priest('s office).
active participle of כָּהַן; literally, one officiating, a priest; also (by courtesy) an acting priest (although a layman): chief ruler, X own, priest, prince, principal officer.
(Aramaic) corresponding to כֹּהֵן: priest.
from כָּהַן; priesthood: priesthood, priest's office.
(Aramaic) from a root corresponding to לַ֫הַג in the sense of piercing; a window (as a perforation): window.
of foreign derivation; Kub, a country near Egypt: Chub.
from an unused root meaning to be high or rounded; a helmet (as arched): helmet. Compare קוֹבַע.
a primitive root; properly, to prick or penetrate; hence, to blister (as smarting or eating into): burn.
from כָּוָה; a branding: burning.
probably from the same as כַּבּוֹן (in the sense of rolling) or כָּוָה (in the sense of blazing); a star (as round or as shining); figuratively, a prince: star((-gazer)).

a primitive root; properly, to keep in; hence, to measure; figuratively, to maintain (in various senses): (be able to, can) abide, bear, comprehend, contain, feed, forbearing, guide, hold(-ing in), nourish(-er), be present, make provision, receive, sustain, provide sustenance (victuals).
from an unused root meaning to store away; a jewel (probably gold beads): tablet.

a primitive root; properly, to be erect (i.e. stand perpendicular); hence (causatively) to set up, in a great variety of applications, whether literal (establish, fix, prepare, apply), or figurative (appoint, render sure, proper or prosperous): certain(-ty), confirm, direct, faithfulness, fashion, fasten, firm, be fitted, be fixed, frame, be meet, ordain, order, perfect, (make) preparation, prepare (self), provide, make provision, (be, make) ready, right, set (aright, fast, forth), be stable, (e-)stablish, stand, tarry, X very deed.
probably from כּוּן; established; Kun, a place in Syria: Chun.
from כּוּן; something prepared, i.e. a sacrificial wafer: cake.
from כּוּן and יָהּ; Jah has sustained; Conanjah, the name of two Israelites: Conaniah, Cononiah. Compare כְּנַנְיָה.

from an unused root meaning to hold together; a cup (as a container), often figuratively, a lot (as if a potion); also some unclean bird, probably an owl (perhaps from the cup-like cavity of its eye): cup, (small) owl. Compare כִּיס.
from an unused root meaning properly, to dig through; a pot or furnace (as if excavated): furnace. Compare כִּירַ֫יִם.
from כּוּר and עָשָׁן; furnace of smoke; Cor-Ashan, a place in Palestine: Chor-ashan.
or (Ezra 1:1 (last time),2) Koresh; from the Persians; Koresh (or Cyrus), the Persian king: Cyrus.
(Aramaic) corresponding to כּ֫וֹרֶשׁ: Cyrus.
probably of foreign origin; Cush (or Ethiopia), the name of a son of Ham, and of his territory; also of an Israelite: Chush, Cush, Ethiopia.
patronymically from כּוּשׁ; a Cushite, or descendant of Cush: Cushi, Cushite, Ethiopian(-s).
the same as כּוּשִׁי; Cushi, the name of two Israelites: Cushi.
feminine of כּוּשִׁי; a Cushite woman: -Ethiopian.
perhaps from כּוּשׁ; Cushan, a region of Arabia: -Cushan.
apparently from כּוּשָׁן and the dual of רִשְׁעָה; Cushan of double wickedness; Cushan-Rishathajim, a Mesopotamian king: Chushan-rishathayim.
from כָּשֵׁר; prosperity; in plural freedom: -X chain.
or (feminine) Kuwthah; of foreign origin; Cuth or Cuthah, a province of Assyria: Cuth.
a primitive root; to lie (i.e. deceive), literally or figuratively: fail, (be found a, make a) liar, lie, lying, be in vain.
from כָּזַב; falsehood; literally (untruth) or figuratively (idol): deceitful, false, leasing, + liar, lie, lying.
from כָּזַב; fallacious; Cozeba, a place in Palestine: Choseba.
from כָּזַב; false; Cozbi, a Midianitess: Cozbi.
from כָּזַב; falsified; Kezib, a place in Palestine: Chezib.

or (Dan. 11:6) kowach; from an unused root meaning to be firm; vigor, literally (force, in a good or a bad sense) or figuratively (capacity, means, produce); also (from its hardiness) a large lizard: -ability, able, chameleon, force, fruits, might, power(-ful), strength, substance, wealth.
a primitive root; to secrete, by act or word; hence (intensively) to destroy: conceal, cut down (off), desolate, hide.
a primitive root; to paint (with stibium): -paint.
a primitive root; to be untrue, in word (to lie, feign, disown) or deed (to disappoint, fail, cringe): deceive, deny, dissemble, fail, deal falsely, be found liars, (be-)lie, lying, submit selves.
from כָּחַשׁ; literally, a failure of flesh, i.e. emaciation; figuratively, hypocrisy: leanness, lies, lying.
from כָּחַשׁ; faithless: lying.
from כָּוָה; a brand or scar: burning.

a primitive particle (the full form of the prepositional prefix) indicating causal relations of all kinds, antecedent or consequent; (by implication) very widely used as a relative conjunction or adverb (as below); often largely modified by other particles annexed: and, + (forasmuch, inasmuch, where-)as, assured(-ly), + but, certainly, doubtless, + else, even, + except, for, how, (because, in, so, than) that, + nevertheless, now, rightly, seeing, since, surely, then, therefore, + (al-)though, + till, truly, + until, when, whether, while, whom, yea, yet.
from a primitive root meaning to strike: a crushing; figuratively, calamity: destruction.
from the same as כִּיד (compare כַּדְכֹּד); properly, something struck off, i.e. a spark (as struck): spark.
from the same as כִּיד; properly, something to strike with, i.e. a dart (perhaps smaller that חֲנִית): lance, shield, spear, target.
the same as כִּידוֹן; Kidon, a place in Palestine: -Chidon.
of uncertain derivation; perhaps tumult: battle.
from כּוּן; properly, a statue, i.e. idol; but used (by euphemism) for some heathen deity (perhaps corresponding to Priapus or Baal-peor): Chiun.

or kiyor; from the same as כּוּר; properly, something round (as excavated or bored), i.e. a chafing-dish for coals or a caldron for cooking; hence (from similarity of form) a washbowl; also (for the same reason) a pulpit or platform: hearth, laver, pan, scaffold.
or kelay; from כּוּל in the sense of withholding; niggardly: churl.
from an unused root meaning to clap or strike with noise; a club or sledge-hammer: hammer.
from the same as כּוּמָז; a cluster of stars, i.e. the Pleiades: Pleiades, seven stars.
a form for כּוֹס; a cup; also a bag for money or weights: bag, cup, purse.
a form for כּוּר (only in the dual); a cooking range (consisting of two parallel stones, across which the boiler is set): -ranges for pots.
from כָּשֵׁר; literally, a director, i.e. the spindle or shank of a distaff (פֶּ֫לֶך), by which it is twirled: spindle.
from כֹּה; just so, referring to the previous or following context: after that (this) manner, this matter, (even) so, in such a case, thus.

from כָּרַר; a circle, i.e. (by implication) a circumjacent tract or region, expec. the Ghor or valley of the Jordan; also a (round) loaf; also a talent (or large (round) coin): loaf, morsel, piece, plain, talent.
(Aramaic) corresponding to כִּכָּר; a talent: talent.

or (Jer. 33:8) kowl; from כָּלַל; properly, the whole; hence, all, any or every (in the singular only, but often in a plural sense): (in) all (manner, (ye)), altogether, any (manner), enough, every (one, place, thing), howsoever, as many as, (no-)thing, ought, whatsoever, (the) whole, whoso(-ever).
(Aramaic) corresponding to כֹּל: all, any, + (forasmuch) as, + be-(for this) cause, every, + no (manner, -ne), + there (where)-fore, + though, what (where, who)-soever, (the) whole.
a primitive root; to restrict, by act (hold back or in) or word (prohibit): finish, forbid, keep (back), refrain, restrain, retain, shut up, be stayed, withhold.
from כָּלָא; a prison: prison. Compare כִּלְאָ֫יִם, כְּלִיא.
apparently from כָּלָא and אָב; restraint of (his) father; Kilab, an Israelite: Chileab.
dual of כֶּ֫לֶא in the original sense of separation; two heterogeneities: divers seeds (-e kinds), mingled (seed).
from an unused root means. to yelp, or else to attack; a dog; hence (by euphemism) a male prostitute: dog.
perhaps a form of כָּ֫לֶב, or else from the same root in the sense of forcible; Caleb, the name of three Israelites: Caleb.
from כָּלֵב and אֶפְרָת; Caleb- Ephrathah, a place in Egypt (if the text is correct): Caleb-ephrathah.
probably by erroneous transcription for Kalebiy; patronymically from כָּלֵב; a Calebite or descendant of Caleb: of the house of Caleb.

a primitive root; to end, whether intransitive (to cease, be finished, perish) or transitived (to complete, prepare, consume): accomplish, cease, consume (away), determine, destroy (utterly), be (when... were) done, (be an) end (of), expire, (cause to) fail, faint, finish, fulfil, X fully, X have, leave (off), long, bring to pass, wholly reap, make clean riddance, spend, quite take away, waste.
from כָּלָה; pining: fail.
from כָּלָה; a completion; adverb, completely; also destruction: altogether, (be, utterly) consume(-d), consummation(-ption), was determined, (full, utter) end, riddance.
from כָּלַל; a bride (as if perfect); hence, a son's wife: bride, daughter-in-law, spouse.
from the same as כָּ֫לֶב; a bird-trap (as furnished with a clap-stick or treadle to spring it); hence, a basket (as resembling a wicker cage): basket, cage.
the same as כְּלוּב; Kelub, the name of two Israelites: Chelub.
a form of כָּלֵב; Kelubai, an Israelite: -Chelubai.
from כָּלָה; completed; Keluhai, an Israelite: Chelluh.
denominative passive participle from כַּלָּה; bridehood (only in the plural): espousal.
from an unused root meaning to be complete; maturity: full (old) age.
the same as כָּ֫לַח; Kelach, a place in Assyria: -Calah.
from כֹּל and חֹזֶה; every seer; Col- Chozeh, an Israelite: Col-hozeh.

from כָּלָה; something prepared, i.e. any apparatus (as an implement, utensil, dress, vessel or weapon): armour ((-bearer)), artillery, bag, carriage, + furnish, furniture, instrument, jewel, that is made of, X one from another, that which pertaineth, pot, + psaltery, sack, stuff, thing, tool, vessel, ware, weapon, + whatsoever.
or kluw1; from כָּלָא (compare כֶּ֫לֶא); a prison: prison.
feminine of כְּלִי (only in the plural); a kidney (as an essential organ); figuratively, the mind (as the interior self): kidneys, reins.
a form of כִּלָּיוֹן; Kiljon, an Israelite: Chilion.
from כָּלָה; pining, destruction: -consumption, failing.
from כָּלַל; complete; as noun, the whole (specifically, a sacrifice entirely consumed); as adverb, fully: all, every whit, flame, perfect(-ion), utterly, whole burnt offering (sacrifice), wholly.
from כּוּל; sustenance; Calcol, an Israelite: Calcol, Chalcol.
a primitive root; to complete: (make) perfect.
(Aramaic) corresponding to כָּלַל; to complete: finish, make (set) up.
from כָּלַל; complete; Kelal, an Israelite: Chelal.
a primitive root; properly, to wound; but only figuratively, to taunt or insult: be (make) ashamed, blush, be confounded, be put to confusion, hurt, reproach, (do, put to) shame.
of foreign derivation; Kilmad, a place apparently in the Assyrian empire: Chilmad.
from כָּלָם; disgrace: confusion, dishonour, reproach, shame.
from כְּלִמָּה; disgrace: shame.
or Kalneh; also Kalnow; of foreign derivation; Calneh or Calno, a place in the Assyrian empireCalneh, Calno. Compare כַּנֵּה.
a primitive root; to pine after: long.
from כָּמַהּ; pining; Kimham, an Israelite: Chimham.
or kamow; a form of the prefix "k-", but used separately (compare כֵּן); as, thus, so: according to, (such) as (it were, well as), in comparison of, like (as, to, unto), thus, when, worth.
or (Jer. 48:7) Kmiysh; from an unused root meaning to subdue; the powerful; Kemosh, the god of the Moabites: Chemosh.
from an unused root meaning to store up or preserve; "cummin" (from its use as a condiment): cummin.
a primitive root; to store away, i.e. (figuratively) in the memory: lay up in store.
a primitive root; properly, to intertwine or contract, i.e. (by implication) to shrivel (as with heat); figuratively, to be deeply affected with passion (love or pity): be black, be kindled, yearn.
from כָּמַר; properly, an ascetic (as if shrunk with self-maceration), i.e. an idolatrous priest (only in plural): Chemarims (idolatrous) priests.
redupl. from כָּמַר; obscuration (as if from shrinkage of light, i.e. an eclipse (only in plural): blackness.

from כּוּן; properly, set upright; hence (figuratively as adjective) just; but usually (as adverb or conjunction) rightly or so (in various applications to manner, time and relation; often with other particles): + after that (this, -ward, -wards), as... as, + (for-)asmuch as yet, + be (for which) cause, + following, howbeit, in (the) like (manner, -wise), X the more, right, (even) so, state, straightway, such (thing), surely, + there (where)-fore, this, thus, true, well, X you.
(Aramaic) corresponding to כֵּן; so: thus.
the same as כֵּן, used as a noun; a stand, i.e. pedestal or station: base, estate, foot, office, place, well.
from כָּנַן in the sense of fastening; a gnat (from infixing its sting; used only in plural (and irreg. in Exod. 8:17,18; Heb. 13:14)): lice, X manner.
a primitive root; to address by an additional name; hence, to eulogize: give flattering titles, surname (himself).
for כַּלְנוֹ; Canneh, a place in Assyria: Canneh.
from כָּנַן; a plant (as set): X vineyard.
from a unused root meaning to twang; a harp: -harp.
for יְכָנְיָה; Conjah, an Israelite king: Coniah.
(Aramaic) corresponding to כְּמוֹ; so or thus: so, (in) this manner (sort), thus.
a primitive root; to set out, i.e. plant: X vineyard.
from כָּנַן; planted; Kenani, an Israelite: -Chenani.
or Knanyahuw; from כָּנַן and יָהּ; Jah has planted; Kenanjah, an Israelite: Chenaniah.
a primitive root; to collect; hence, to enfold: -gather (together), heap up, wrap self.
a primitive root; properly, to bend the knee; hence, to humiliate, vanquish: bring down (low), into subjection, under, humble (self), subdue.
from כָּנַע in the sense of folding (compare כָּנַס); a package: wares.
from כָּנַע; humiliated; Kenaan, a son a Ham; also the country inhabited by him: Canaan, merchant, traffick.
feminine of כְּנַ֫עַן; Kenaanah, the name of two Israelites: Chenaanah.

patrial from כְּנַ֫עַן; a Kenaanite or inhabitant of Kenaan; by implication, a pedlar (the Canaanites standing for their neighbors the Ishmaelites, who conducted mercantile caravans): Canaanite, merchant, trafficker.
a primitive root; properly, to project laterally, i.e. probably (reflexive) to withdraw: be removed.

from כָּנַף; an edge or extremity; specifically (of a bird or army) a wing, (of a garment or bed-clothing) a flap, (of the earth) a quarter, (of a building) a pinnacle: + bird, border, corner, end, feather(-ed), X flying, + (one an-)other, overspreading, X quarters, skirt, X sort, uttermost part, wing((-ed)).
or Kinnereth; respectively plural and singular feminine from the same as כִּנּוֹר; perhaps harp-shaped; Kinneroth or Kinnereth, a place in Palestine: Chinnereth, Chinneroth, Cinneroth.
(Aramaic) corresponding to כָּנַס; to assemble: gather together.
from כָּנָה; a colleague (as having the same title): companion.
(Aramaic) corresponding to כְּנָוֹת: companion.
apparently a contraction for כִּסֵּא, but probably by erroneous transcription for נֵס: sworn.
or keceh; apparently from כָּסָה; properly, fulness or the full moon, i.e. its festival: (time) appointed.
or kicceh; from כָּסָה; properly, covered, i.e. a throne (as canopied): seat, stool, throne.
for כַּשְׂדִּי: Chaldean.

a primitive root; properly, to plump, i.e. fill up hollows; by implication, to cover (for clothing or secrecy): clad self, close, clothe, conceal, cover (self), (flee to) hide, overwhelm. Compare כָּשָׂה.
passive participle of כָּסָה; properly, covered, i.e. (as noun) a covering: covering.
from כָּסָה; a cover (garment); figuratively, a veiling: covering, raiment, vesture.
a primitive root; to cut off: cut down (up).
from כָּסַל; properly, fat, i.e. (figuratively) stupid or silly: fool(-ish).
the same as כְּסִיל; any notable constellation; specifically Orion (as if a burly one): constellation, Orion.
the same as כְּסִיל; Kesil, a place in Palestine: -Chesil.
from כְּסִיל; silliness: foolish.
a primitive root; properly, to be fat, i.e. (figuratively) silly: be foolish.

from כָּסַל; properly, fatness, i.e. by implication (literally) the loin (as the seat of the leaf fat) or (generally) the viscera; also (figuratively) silliness or (in a good sense) trust: confidence, flank, folly, hope, loin.
feminine of כָּ֫סֶל; in a good sense, trust; in a bad one, silliness: confidence, folly.
probably of foreign origin; Kisleu, the 9th Heb. month: Chisleu.
from כָּסַל; hopeful; Kislon, an Israelite: Chislon.
from כָּסַל; fertile; Kesalon, a place in Palestine: Chesalon.
feminine plural of passive participle of כָּסַל; fattened; Kesulloth, a place in Palestine: Chesulloth.
a plural probably of foreign derivation; Casluchim, a people cognate to the Egyptians: Casluhim.
from the feminine plural of כָּ֫סֶל and תָּבוֹר; flanks of Tabor; Kisloth-Tabor, a place in Palestine: Chisloth- tabor.
a primitive root; to shear: X only, poll. Compare יְכַרְסְמֶנָּה.
from כָּסַם; spelt (from its bristliness as if just shorn): fitches, rie.
a primitive root; to estimate: make count.
a primitive root; properly, to become pale, i.e. (by implication) to pine after; also to fear: (have) desire, be greedy, long, sore.
from כָּסַף; silver (from its pale color); by implication, money: money, price, silver(-ling).
(Aramaic) corresponding to כָּ֫סֶפ: money, silver.
perhaps from כָּ֫סֶפ; silvery; Casiphja, a place in Bab.: Casiphia.
from כָּסָה; a cushion or pillow (as covering a seat or bed): pillow.
(Aramaic) probably from כֵּן; now: now.
(Aramaic) or kaeth (Aramaic); feminine of כְּעַן; thus (only in the formula "and so forth"): at such a time.
a primitive root; to trouble; by implication, to grieve, rage, be indignant: be angry, be grieved, take indignation, provoke (to anger, unto wrath), have sorrow, vex, be wroth.
or (in Job) kaoas; from כָּעַס; vexation: -anger, angry, grief, indignation, provocation, provoking, X sore, sorrow, spite, wrath.

from כָּפַף; the hollow hand or palm (so of the paw of an animal, of the sole, and even of the bowl of a dish or sling, the handle of a bolt, the leaves of a palm-tree); figuratively, power: branch, + foot, hand((-ful), -dle, (-led)), hollow, middle, palm, paw, power, sole, spoon.
from כָּפַף; a hollow rock: rock.
a primitive root; properly, to bend, i.e. (figuratively) to tame or subdue: pacify.
feminine of כָּף; a leaf of a palm-tree: branch.
from כָּפַר; properly, a cover, i.e. (by implication) a tankard (or covered goblet); also white frost (as covering the ground): bason, hoar(-y) frost.
from an unused root meaning to connect; a girder: beam.
from כָּפַר; a village (as covered in by walls); also a young lion (perhaps as covered with a mane): (young) lion, village. Compare כְּפַר.
feminine of כְּפִיר; the village (always with the art.); Kephirah, a place in Palestine: Chephirah.
a primitive root; to fold together; figuratively, to repeat: double.
from כָּפַל; a duplicate: double.
a primitive root; to bend: bend.
from כָּפַן; hunger (as making to stoop with emptiness and pain): famine.
a primitive root; to curve: bow down (self).

a primitive root; to cover (specifically with bitumen); figuratively, to expiate or condone, to placate or cancelappease, make (an atonement, cleanse, disannul, forgive, be merciful, pacify, pardon, purge (away), put off, (make) reconcile(-liation).
from כָּפַר; a village (as protected by walls): -village. Compare כְּפִיר.

from כָּפַר; properly, a cover, i.e. (literally) a village (as covered in); (specifically) bitumen (as used for coating), and the henna plant (as used for dyeing); figuratively, a redemption-price: bribe, camphire, pitch, ransom, satisfaction, sum of money, village.
from כָּפַר; expiation (only in plural): -atonement.
from כְּפַר and עַמּוֹנִי, with the article interposed; village of the Ammonite; Kefar-ha-Ammoni, a place in Palestine: Chefar-haamonai.
from כָּפַר; a lid (used only of the cover of the sacred Ark): mercy seat.
a primitive root; to tread down; figuratively, to humiliate: cover.
(Aramaic) a root of uncertain correspondence; to fetter: bind.

or (Am. 9:1) kaphtowr; probably from an unused root meaning to encircle; a chaplet; but used only in an architectonic sense, i.e. the capital of a column, or a wreath-like button or disk on the candelabrum: knop, (upper) lintel.
or (Am. 9:7) Kaphtowr; apparently the same as כַּפְתֹּר; Caphtor (i.e. a wreath-shaped island), the original seat of the Philistines: Caphtor.
patrial from כַּפְתּוֹר; a Caphtorite (collectively) or native of Caphtor: Caphthorim, Caphtorim(-s).

from כָּרַר in the sense of plumpness; a ram (as full-grown and fat), including a battering-ram (as butting); hence, a meadow (as for sheep); also a pad or camel's saddle (as puffed out): captain, furniture, lamb, (large) pasture, ram. See also בֵּית כָּר, כָּרִים.
from the same as כּוּר; properly, a deep round vessel, i.e. (specifically) a cor or measure for things dry: cor, measure. Aramaic the same.
(Aramaic) probably corresponding to כָּרָה in the sense of piercing (figuratively); to grieve: be grieved.
from the same as כֶּ֫בֶל; to gird or clothe: -clothed.
(Aramaic) from a verb corresponding to that of מְכֻרְבָּל; a mantle: hat.
a primitive root; properly, to dig; figuratively, to plot; generally, to bore or open: dig, X make (a banquet), open.
usually assigned as a primitive root, but probably only a special application of כָּרָה (through the common idea of planning implied in a bargain); to purchase: buy, prepare.
from כָּרָה; a purchase: provision.
feminine of כָּר; a meadow: cottage.
of uncertain derivation; a cherub or imaginary figure: cherub, (plural) cherubims.
the same as כְּרוּב; Kerub, a place in Bab.: -Cherub.
(Aramaic) from כְּרַז; a herald: herald.
(Aramaic) probably of Greek origin; to proclaim: make a proclamation.
perhaps an abridged plural of כָּר in the sense of leader (of the flock); a life-guardsman: captains, Cherethites (from the margin).
from כָּרַת; a cut; Kerith, a brook of Palestine: -Cherith.
from כָּרַת; a cutting (of the matrimonial bond), i.e. divorce: divorce(-ment).
expanded from the same as כַּבּוֹן; a rim or top margin: compass.
probably of foreign origin; the crocus: saffron.
of foreign derivation; Karkemish, a place in Syria: Carchemish.
of Persian origin; Karkas, a eunuch of Xerxes: -Carcas.
from כָּרַר; a dromedary (from its rapid motion as if dancing): swift beast.
from an unused root of uncertain meaning; a garden or vineyard: vines, (increase of the) vineyard(-s), vintage. See also בֵּית הַכָּ֫רֶם.
active participle of an imaginary denominative from כָּ֫רֶם; a vinedresser: vine dresser (as one or two words).
from כָּ֫רֶם; gardener; Karmi, the name of three Israelites: Carmi.
patronymically from כַּרְמִי; a Karmite or descendant of Karmi: Carmites.
probably of foreign origin; carmine, a deep red: -crimson.
from כָּ֫רֶם; a planted field (garden, orchard, vineyard or park); by implication, garden produce: full (green) ears (of corn), fruitful field (place), plentiful (field).
the same as כַּרְמֶל; Karmel, the name of a hill and of a town in Palestine: Carmel, fruitful (plentiful) field, (place).
patron from כַּרְמֶל; a Karmelite or inhabitant of Karmel (the town): Carmelite.
feminine of כַּרְמְלִי; a Karmelitess or female inhabitant of Karmel: Carmelitess.
of uncertain derivation; Keran, an aboriginal Idumaean: Cheran.
(Aramaic) corresponding to כִּסֵּא; a throne: throne.
from כָּסַם; to lay waste: waste.
a primitive root; to bend the knee; by implication, to sink, to prostrate: bow (down, self), bring down (low), cast down, couch, fall, feeble, kneeling, sink, smite (stoop) down, subdue, X very.
from כָּרַע; the leg (from the knee to the ankle) of men or locusts (only in the dual): leg.
of foreign origin; byssus or fine vegetable wool: -green.
a primitive root; to dance (i.e. whirl): -dance(-ing).
by variation from קָרַס; the paunch or belly (as swelling out): belly.
of foreign origin; Karshena, a courtier of Xerxes: Carshena.

a primitive root; to cut (off, down or asunder); by implication, to destroy or consume; specifically, to covenant (i.e. make an alliance or bargain, originally by cutting flesh and passing between the pieces): be chewed, be con-(feder-)ate, covenant, cut (down, off), destroy, fail, feller, be freed, hew (down), make a league ((covenant)), X lose, perish, X utterly, X want.
passive participle feminine of כָּרַת; something cut, i.e. a hewn timber: beam.
probably from כָּרַת in the sense of executioner; a Kerethite or life-guardsman (compare טַבָּח) (only collectively in the singular as plural): Cherethims, Cherethites.
apparently by transposition for כֶּ֫בֶשׂ; a young sheep: lamb.
feminine of כֶּ֫שֶׂב; a young ewe: lamb.
from an unused root of uncertain meaning; Kesed, a relative of Abraham: Onesed.

or (occasionally with enclitic) Kasdiymah; towards the Kasdites: into Chaldea), patronymically from Kesed (only in the plural); a Kasdite, or descendant of Kesed; by implication, a Chaldaean (as if so descended); also an astrologer (as if proverbial of that people:--Chaldeans, Chaldees, inhabitants of Chaldea.
(Aramaic) corresponding to כַּשְׂדִּי; a Chaldaean or inhabitant of Chaldaea; by implication, a Magian or professional astrologer: Chaldean.
a primitive root; to grow fat (i.e. be covered with flesh): be covered. Compare כָּסָה.
from כָּשַׁל; properly, a feller, i.e. an axe: -ax.

a primitive root; to totter or waver (through weakness of the legs, especially the ankle); by implication, to falter, stumble, faint or fall: bereave (from the margin), cast down, be decayed, (cause to) fail, (cause, make to) fall (down, -ing), feeble, be (the) ruin(-ed, of), (be) overthrown, (cause to) stumble, X utterly, be weak.
from כָּשַׁל; properly, a tottering, i.e. ruin: fall.
a primitive root; properly, to whisper a spell, i.e. to inchant or practise magic: sorcerer, (use) witch(-craft).
from כָּשַׁף; magic: sorcery, witchcraft.
from כָּשַׁף; a magician: sorcerer.
a primitive root properly, to be straight or right; by implication, to be acceptable; also to succeed or prosperdirect, be right, prosper.
from כָּשֵׁר; success, advantage: equity, good, right.
a primitive root; to grave, by implication, to write (describe, inscribe, prescribe, subscribe): describe, record, prescribe, subscribe, write(-ing, -ten).
(Aramaic) corresponding to כָּתַב: write(-ten).
from כָּתַב; something written, i.e. a writing, record or book: register, scripture, writing.
(Aramaic) corresponding to כְּתָב: prescribing, writing(-ten).
from כָּתַב; a letter or other mark branded on the skin: X any (mark).

or Kittiyiy; patrial from an unused name denoting Cyprus (only in the plural); a Kittite or Cypriote; hence, an islander in general, i.e. the Greeks or Romans on the shores opposite Palestine: Chittim, Kittim.
from כָּתַת; beaten, i.e. pure (oil): -beaten.
from an unused root meaning to compact; a wall (as gathering inmates): wall.
(Aramaic) corresponding to כֹּ֫תֶל: wall.
from כֹּ֫תֶל and אּישׁ; wall of a man; Kithlish, a place in Palestine: Kithlish.
a primitive root; properly, to carve or engrave, i.e. (by implication) to inscribe indelibly: mark.
from כָּתַם; properly, something carved out, i.e. ore; hence, gold (pure as originally mined): ((most) fine, pure) gold(-en wedge).
or kuttoneth; from an unused root meaning to cover (compare כָּתֵף); a shirt: coat, garment, robe.

from an unused root meaning to clothe; the shoulder (proper, i.e. upper end of the arm; as being the spot where the garments hang); figuratively, side-piece or lateral projection of anything: arm, corner, shoulder(-piece), side, undersetter.
a primitive root; to enclose; hence (in a friendly sense) to crown, (in a hostile one) to besiege; also to wait (as restraining oneself): beset round, compass about, be crowned inclose round, suffer.
from כָּתַר; properly, a circlet, i.e. a diadem: -crown.
feminine active participle of כָּתַר; the capital of a column: chapiter.
a primitive root; to butt or pound: bray.
a primitive root; to bruise or violently strike: beat (down, to pieces), break in pieces, crushed, destroy, discomfit, smite, stamp.

or lowi; or loh (Deut. 3:11); a primitive particle; not (the simple or abs. negation); by implication, no; often used with other particles (as follows): X before, + or else, ere, + except, ig(-norant), much, less, nay, neither, never, no((-ne), -r, (-thing)), (X as though...,(can-), for) not (out of), of nought, otherwise, out of, + surely, + as truly as, + of a truth, + verily, for want, + whether, without.
(Aramaic) or lah (Aramaic) (Dan. 4:32); corresponding to לֹא: or even, neither, no(-ne, -r), ((can-))not, as nothing, without.
or Low Dbar (2 Samuel 9:4,5); or Lidbir (Joshua 13:26); (probably rather Lodbar); from לֹא and דֹּ֫בֶר; pastureless; Lo-Debar, a place in Palestine: Debir, Lo-debar.
a primitive root; to tire; (figuratively) to be (or make) disgusted: faint, grieve, lothe, (be, make) weary (selves).
from לָאָה; weary; Leah, a wife of Jacob: Leah.
a primitive root; to muffle: cover.
from לָאַט (or perhaps for active participle of לוּט); properly, muffled, i.e. silently: softly.
from the prepositional prefix and אֵל; (belonging) to God; Lael an Israelite: Lael.
or l owm; from an unused root meaning to gather; a community: nation, people.
plural of לְאֹם; communities; Leum mim, an Arabian: Leummim.
from לֹא and עָם with pronominal suffix; not my people; Lo-Ammi, the symbolic name of a son of Hosea: Lo-ammi.
from לֹא and רָחַם; not pitied; Lo- Ruchamah, the symbol. name of a son of Hosea: Lo-ruhamah.

a form of לֵבָב; the heart; also used (figuratively) very widely for the feelings, the will and even the intellect; likewise for the centre of anything: + care for, comfortably, consent, X considered, courag(-eous), friend(-ly), ((broken-), (hard-), (merry-), (stiff-), (stout-), double) heart((-ed)), X heed, X I, kindly, midst, mind(-ed), X regard((-ed)), X themselves, X unawares, understanding, X well, willingly, wisdom.
(Aramaic) corresponding to לֵב: heart.
plural of לָבִיא; lionesses; Lebaoth, a place in Palestine: Lebaoth. See also בֵּית לְבָאוֹת.

a primitive root; properly, to be enclosed (as if with fat); by implication (as denominative from לֵבָב) to unheart, i.e. (in a good sense) transport (with love), or (in a bad sense) stultify; also (as denominative from לְבִבוֹת) to make cakes: make cakes, ravish, be wise.
from לָבַב; the heart (as the most interior organ); used also like לֵב: + bethink themselves, breast, comfortably, courage, ((faint), (tender-)heart((-ed)), midst, mind, X unawares, understanding.
(Aramaic) corresponding to לֵבָב: heart.
feminine of לֵב; the heart: heart.
for לֶהָבָה; flame: flame.
or lbonah; from לָבָן; frankincense (from its whiteness or perhaps that of its smoke): -(frank-)incense.
the same as לְבוֹנָה; Lebonah, a place in Palestine: Lebonah.
or lbush; from לָבַשׁ; a garment (literally or figuratively); by implication (euphem.) a wife: apparel, clothed with, clothing, garment, raiment, vestment, vesture.
(Aramaic) corresponding to לְבוּשׁ: garment.
a primitive root; to overthrow; intransposed, to fall: fall.

or (Ezek. 19:2) lbiyao; irreg. masculine plural lbaviym; irreg. feminine plural lbaeowth; from an unused root meaning to roar; a lion (properly, a lioness as the fiercer (although not a roarer; compare אֲרִי)): (great, old, stout) lion, lioness, young (lion).
or rather lbibah; from לָבַב in its original sense of fatness (or perhaps of folding); a cake (either as fried or turned): cake.
a primitive root; to be (or become) white; also (as denominative from לְבֵנִים) to make bricks: make brick, be (made, make) white(-r).
or (Gen. 49:12) laben; from לָבַן; white: white.
the same as לָבָן; Laban, a Mesopotamian; also a place in the Desert: Laban.
or Lbanah; the same as לְבָנָה; Lebana or Lebanah, one of the Nethinim: Lebana, Lebanah.
from לָבַן; some sort of whitish tree, perhaps the storax: poplar.
from לָבַן; properly, whiteness, i.e. (by implication) transparency: paved.
the same as לִבְנֶה; Libnah, a place in the Desert and one in Palestine: Libnah.
from לָבַן; properly, (the) white, i.e. the moon: moon. See also לְבָנָה.
from לָבַן; a brick (from the whiteness of the clay): (altar of) brick, tile.
from לְבַב; (the) white mountain (from its snow); Lebanon, a mountain range in Palestine: Lebanon.
from לָבַן; white; Libni, an Israelite: Libni.
patronymically from לִבְנִי; a Libnite or descendants of Libni (collectively): Libnites.

or labesh; a primitive root; properly, wrap around, i.e. (by implication) to put on a garment or clothe (oneself, or another), literally or figuratively: (in) apparel, arm, array (self), clothe (self), come upon, put (on, upon), wear.
(Aramaic) corresponding to לָבַשׁ: clothe.
from an unused root apparently meaning to deepen or hollow (like כַּד); a log or measure for liquids: log (of oil).
from an unused root of uncertain signification; Lod, a place in Palestine: Lod.
from an usused root meaning to gleam; a flash; figuratively, a sharply polished blade or point of a weapon: blade, bright, flame, glittering.
or lahebeth; feminine of לַ֫הַב, and meaning the same: flame(-ming), head (of a spear).
plural of לַ֫הַב; flames; Lehabim, a son of Mizrain, and his descendants: Lehabim.
from an unused root meaning to be eager; intense mental application: study.
from an unused root meaning to glow (compare לַ֫הַב) or else to be earnest (compare לַ֫הַג); Lahad, an Israelite: Lahad.
a primitive root meaning properly, to burn, i.e. (by implication) to be rabid (figuratively, insane); also (from the exhaustion of frenzy) to languish: faint, mad.
a primitive root; properly, to lick, i.e. (by implication) to blaze: burn (up), set on fire, flaming, kindle.
from לָהַט; a blaze; also (from the idea of enwrapping) magic (as covert): flaming, enchantment.
a primitive root; properly, to burn in, i.e. (figuratively) to rankle: wound.
from the prepositional prefix meaning to or for and הֵן; popularly for if; hence, therefore: for them (by mistake for prepositional suffix).
(Aramaic) corresponding to לָהֵן; therefore; also except: but, except, save, therefore, wherefore.
probably from an unused root meaning to gather; an assembly: company.
or lu; or luw; a conditional particle; if; by implication (interj. as a wish) would that!: if (haply), peradventure, I pray thee, though, I would, would God (that).

or Lubbiy (Dan. 11:43); partrial from a name probably derived from an unused root meaning to thirst, i.e. a dry region; apparently a Libyan or inhabitant of interior Africa (only in plural): -Lubim(-s), Libyans.
probably of foreign derivation; Lud, the name of two nations: Lud, Lydia.
or Luwdiyiy; patrial from לוּד; a Ludite or inhabitants of Lud (only in plural): Ludim. Lydians.
a primitive root; properly, to twine, i.e. (by implication) to unite, to remain; also to borrow (as a form of obligation) or (caus.) to lend: abide with, borrow(-er), cleave, join (self), lend(-er).
a primitive root; to turn aside (compare לָוָה, לוּט and לוּן), i.e. (literally) to depart, (figuratively) be perverse: depart, froward, perverse(-ness).
probably of foreign origin; some kind of nut-tree, perhaps the almond: hazel.
probably from לוּז (as growing there); Luz, the name of two places in Palestine: Luz.
or luach; from a primitive root; probably meaning to glisten; a tablet (as polished), of stone, wood or metal: board, plate, table.
or Luchowth (Jer. 48:5); from the same as ל֫וּחַ; floored; Luchith, a place East of the Jordan: Luhith.
active participle of לָחַשׁ; (the) enchanter; Lochesh, an Israelite: Hallohesh, Haloshesh (includ. the article).
a primitive root; to wrap up: cast, wrap.
from לוּט; a veil: covering.
the same as לוֹט; Lot, Abraham's nephew: Lot.
from לוֹט; covering; Lotan, an Idumaean: -Lotan.
from לָוָה; attached; Levi, a son of Jacob: Levi. See also לֵוָיֵא, לֵוִי.
(Aramaic) corresponding to לִוְיַת: Levite.
from לָוָה; something attached, i.e. a wreath: -ornament.
or Leviy; patronymically from לֵוִי; a Levite or descendant of Levi: Leviite.

from לָוָה; a wreathed animal, i.e. a serpent (especially the crocodile or some other large sea- monster); figuratively, the constellation of the dragon; also as a symbol of Bab.: leviathan, mourning.
from an unused root meaning to fold back; a spiral step: winding stair. Compare לֻלָאֹת.
or luwley; from לוּא and לֹא; if not: except, had not, if (...not), unless, were it not that.

or liyn; a primitive root; to stop (usually over night); by implication, to stay permanently; hence (in a bad sense) to be obstinate (especially in words, to complain): abide (all night), continue, dwell, endure, grudge, be left, lie all night, (cause to) lodge (all night, in, -ing, this night), (make to) murmur, remain, tarry (all night, that night).
a primitive root; to gulp; figuratively, to be rash: swallow down (up).

a primitive root; properly, to make mouths at, i.e. to scoff; hence (from the effort to pronounce a foreign language) to interpret, or (generally) intercede: ambassador, have in derision, interpreter, make a mock, mocker, scorn(-er, -ful), teacher.
a primitive root; to knead: knead.
from לוּשׁ; kneading; Lush, a place in Palestine: Laish (from the margin). Compare לַ֫יִשׁ.
(Aramaic) from a root corresponding to לָוָה; properly, adhesion, i.e. (as preposition) with: X thee.
from לוּז; perverseness: perverse.
from an unused root meaning to be new; fresh, i.e. unused or undried: green, moist.
from the same as לָח; freshness, i.e. vigor: -natural force.
or lachum; passive participle of לָחַם; properly, eaten, i.e. food; also flesh, i.e. body: while...is eating, flesh.
from an unused root meaning to be soft; the cheek (from its fleshiness); hence, the jaw-bone: cheek (bone), jaw (bone).
a form of לֶ֫חִי; Lechi, a place in Palestine: Lehi. Compare also רָ֫מַת לֶ֫חִי.
a primitive root; to lick: lick (up).
a primitive root; to feed on; figuratively, to consume; by implication, to battle (as destruction): devour, eat, X ever, fight(-ing), overcome, prevail, (make) war(-ring).
from לָחַם; food (for man or beast), especially bread, or grain (for making it): ((shew-))bread, X eat, food, fruit, loaf, meat, victuals. See also בֵּית לְעַפְרָה.
(Aramaic) corresponding to לָ֫חֶם: feast.
from לָחַם, battle: war.
from לָ֫חֶם; foodful; Lachmi, an Israelite; or rather probably a brief form (or perhaps erroneous transcription) for בֵּית הַלַּחְמִיLahmi. See also יָשֻׁ֫בִילָ֫חֶם.
probably by erroneous transcription for Lachmam; from לָ֫חֶם; food-like; Lachmam or Lachmas, a place in Palestine: Lahmam.
(Aramaic) from an unused root of uncertain meaning; a concubine: concubine.
a primitive root; properly, to press, i.e. (figuratively) to distress: afflict, crush, force, hold fast, oppress(-or), thrust self.
from לָחַץ; distress: affliction, oppression.
a primitive root; to whisper; by implication, to mumble a spell (as a magician): charmer, whisper (together).
from לָחַשׁ; properly, a whisper, i.e. by implication, (in a good sense) a private prayer, (in a bad one) an incantation; concretely, an amulet: charmed, earring, enchantment, orator, prayer.
a form of לָאט or else participle from לוּט; properly, covered, i.e. secret; by implication, incantation; also secrecy or (adverb) covertly: -enchantment, privily, secretly, softly.
probably from לוּט; a gum (from its sticky nature), probably ladanum: myrrh.
from an unused root meaning to hide; a kind of lizard (from its covert habits): lizard.
masculine plural of passive participle of לָטַשׁ; hammered (i.e. oppressed) ones; Letushim, an Arabian tribe: Letushim.
a primitive root; properly, to hammer out (an edge), i.e. to sharpen: instructer, sharp(-en), whet.
a form of לִוְיַת; a wreath: addition.
or (Isa. 21:11) leyl; also laylah; from the same as לוּלִים; properly, a twist (away of the light), i.e. night; figuratively, adversity: ((mid-))night (season).
(Aramaic) corresponding to לָאֵל: night.
from לַיְלָה; a night spectre: screech owl.
from לוּשׁ in the sense of crushing; a lion (from his destructive blows): (old)lion.
the same as לַ֫יִשׁ; Laish, the name of two places in Palestine: Laish. Compare לוּשׁ.

a primitive root; to catch (in a net, trap or pit); generally, to capture or occupy; also to choose (by lot); figuratively, to cohere: X at all, catch (self), be frozen, be holden, stick together, take.
from לָכַד; something to capture with, i.e. a noose: being taken.
from יָלַך; a journey; Lekah, a place in Palestine: -Lecah.
from an unused root of uncertain meaning; Lakish, a place in Palestine: Lachish.
from the same as לוּלִים; a loop: loop.
a primitive root; properly, to goad, i.e. (by implication) to teach (the rod being an Oriental incentive):(un-) accustomed, X diligently, expert, instruct, learn, skilful, teach(-er, - ing).
a prol. and separable form of the prepositional prefix; to or for: at, for, to, upon.
or Lmow el; from לְמוֹ and אֵל; (belonging) to God; Lemuel or Lemoel, a symbolic name of Solomon: -Lemuel.
or limmud; from לָמַד; instructed: -accustomed, disciple, learned, taught, used.
from an unused root of uncertain meaning; Lemek, the name of two antediluvian patriarchs: Lamech.
from לָעַע; the gullet: throat.
a primitive root; to deride: mock.
a primitive root; to deride; by implication (as if imitating a foreigner) to speak unintelligibly: have in derision, laugh (to scorn), mock (on), stammering.
from לָעַג; derision, scoffing: derision, scorn (-ing).
from לָעַג; a buffoon; also a foreigner: mocker, stammering.
from an unused root of uncertain meaning; Ladah, an Israelite: Laadah.
from the same as לַעְדָּה; Ladan, the name of two Israelites: Laadan.
a primitive root; to speak in a foreign tongue: -strange language.
a primitive root; to swallow greedily; causatively, to feed: feed.
from an unused root supposed to mean to curse; wormwood (regarded as poisonous, and therefore accursed): hemlock, wormwood.
or lappid; from an unused root probably meaning to shine; a flambeau, lamp or flame: (fire-)brand, (burning) lamp, lightning, torch.
feminine plural of לַפִּיד; Lappidoth, the husband of Deborah: Lappidoth.
from the prepositional prefix (to or for) and פָּנִים; anterior: before.
a primitive root; properly, to bend, i.e. (by implication) to clasp; also (reflexively) to turn around or aside: take hold, turn aside (self).
from לִיץ; derision: scornful(-ning).
a primitive root; to deride: scorn.
from an unused root thought to mean to stop up by a barricade; perhaps fortification; Lakkum, a place in Palestine: Lakum.

a primitive root; to take (in the widest variety of applications): accept, bring, buy, carry away, drawn, fetch, get, infold, X many, mingle, place, receive(-ing), reserve, seize, send for, take (away, -ing, up), use, win.

from לָקַח; properly, something received, i.e. (mentally) instruction (whether on the part of the teacher or hearer); also (in an active and sinister sense) inveiglement: doctrine, learning, fair speech.
from לָקַח; learned; Likchi, an Israelite: Likhi.
a primitive root; properly, to pick up, i.e. (generally) to gather; specifically, to glean: gather (up), glean.
from לָקַט; the gleaning: gleaning.
a primitive root; to lick or lap: lap, lick.
a primitive root; to gather the after crop: gather.
from לָקַשׁ; the after crop: latter growth.
from an unused root of uncertain meaning; apparently juice, i.e. (figuratively) vigor; also a sweet or fat cake: fresh, moisture.

or lashon; also (in plural) feminine lshonah; from לָשַׁן; the tongue (of man or animals), used literally (as the instrument of licking, eating, or speech), and figuratively (speech, an ingot, a fork of flame, a cove of water): + babbler,bay, + evil speaker, language, talker, tongue, wedge.
from an unused root of uncertain meaning; a room in a building (whether for storage, eating, or lodging): chamber, parlour. Compare נִשְׁכָּה.
from an unused root of uncertain meaning; a gem, perhaps the jacinth: ligure.
the same as לֶ֫שֶׁם; Leshem, a place in Palestine: -Leshem.
a primitive root; properly, to lick; but used only as a denominative from לָשׁוֹן; to wag the tongue, i.e. to calumniate: accuse, slander.
(Aramaic) corresponding to לָשׁוֹן; speech, i.e. a nation: language.
from an unused root thought to mean to break through; a boiling spring; Lesha, a place probably East of the Jordan: Lasha.
from an unused root of uncertain meaning; a measure for things dry: half homer.
(Aramaic) corresponding to מָה; (as indef.) that: + what.
from אָבַס; a granary: storehouse.

from the same as אוּד; properly, vehemence, i.e. (with or without preposition) vehemently; by implication, wholly, speedily, etc. (often with other words as an intensive or superlative; especially when repeated): diligently, especially, exceeding(-ly), far, fast, good, great(-ly), X louder and louder, might(-ily, -y), (so) much, quickly, (so) sore, utterly, very (+ much, sore), well.
or metyah; properly, a primitive numeral; a hundred; also as a multiplicative and a fraction: hundred((-fold), -th), + sixscore.
the same as מֵאָה; Meah, a tower in Jerusalem: Meah.
(Aramaic) corresponding to מֵאָה: hundred.
from אָוָה; a desire: desire.
usually muwm; as if passive participle from an unused root probably meaning to stain; a blemish (physically or morally): blemish, blot, spot.
apparently a form of מְאוּם; properly, a speck or point, i.e. (by implication) something; with negative, nothing: fault, + no(-ught), ought, somewhat, any ((no-))thing.
from מָאַס; refuse: refuse.

or maor; also (in plural) feminine mpowrah; or morah; from אוֹר; properly, a luminous body or luminary, i.e. (abstractly) light (as an element): figuratively, brightness, i.e.cheerfulness; specifically, a chandelier: bright, light.
feminine passive participle of אוֹר; something lighted, i.e. an aperture; by implication, a crevice or hole (of a serpent): den.
from אָזַן; (only in the dual) a pair of scales: -balances.
(Aramaic) corresponding to מֹאזְנָ֫יִם: balances.
from אָכַל; an eatable (includ. provender, flesh and fruit): food, fruit, ((bake-)) meat(-s), victual.
from אָכַל; something to eat with,- i.e. a knife: knife.
from אָכַל; something eaten (by fire), i.e. fuel: fuel.
from אָמַץ; strength, i.e. (plural) resources: force.
from אָמַר; something (authoritatively) said, i.e. an edict: commandment, decree.
(Aramaic) corresponding to מַאֲמַר: appointment, word.
(Aramaic) probably from a root corresponding to אָנָה in the sense of an inclosure by sides; a utensil: vessel.
a primitive root; to refuse: refuse, X utterly.
from מָאֵן; unwilling: refuse.
from מָאֵן; refractory: refuse.
a primitive root; to spurn; also (intransitively) to disappear: abhor, cast away (off), contemn, despise, disdain, (become) loathe(some), melt away, refuse, reject, reprobate, X utterly, vile person.
from אָפָה; something baked, i.e. a batch: -baken.
from the same as אָפֵל; something opaque: -darkness.
prol. feminine of מַאֲפֵל; opaqueness: -darkness.
a primitive root; to be bitter or (causatively) to embitter, i.e. be painful: fretting, picking.
from אָרַב; an ambuscade: lie in ambush, ambushment, lurking place, lying in wait.
from אָרַר; an execration: curse.
from בָּדַל; a separation, i.e. (concretely) a separate place: separate.

from בּוֹא; an entrance (the place or the act); specifically (with or without שָׁ֫מֶשׁ) sunset or the west; also (adverb with preposition) towards: by which came, as cometh, in coming, as men enter into, entering, entrance into, entry, where goeth, going down, + westward. Compare מוֹבָא.
feminine of מָבוֹא; a haven: entry.
from בּוּך; perplexity: perplexity.
from יָבַל in the sense of flowing; a deluge: -flood.
from בִּין; instructing: taught.
from בּוּס; a trampling: treading (trodden) down (under foot).
from נָבַע; a fountain: fountain, spring.
from the same as בּוּקָה; emptiness: void.
from בָּחַר; select, i.e. well fortified: choice.
from בָּחַר; select, i.e. best: choice(-st), chosen.
the same as מִבְחָר; Mibchar, an Israelite: Mibhar.
or mebbat; from נָבַט; something expected, i.e. (abstractly) expectation: expectation.
from בָּטָא; a rash utterance (hasty vow): (that which...) uttered (out of).
from בָּטַח; properly, a refuge, i.e. (objective) security, or (subjective) assurance: confidence, hope, sure, trust.
from בָּלַג; desistance (or rather desolation): comfort self.
from בָּנָה; a building: frame.
from בָּנָה; built up; Mebunnai, an Israelite: Mebunnai.
also (in plural) feminine (Dan. 11:15) mibtsarah; from בָּצַר; a fortification, castle, or fortified city; figuratively, a defender: (de-, most) fenced, fortress, (most) strong (hold).
the same as מִבְצָר; Mibtsar, an Idumaean: Mibzar.
from בָּרַח; a refugee: fugitive.
from בּוּשׁ; (plural) the (male) pudenda: secrets.
from the same as בְּשָׂמִים; fragrant; Mibsam, the name of an Ishmaelite and of an Israelite: Mibsam.
from בָּשַׁל; a cooking hearth: boiling-place.
from the same as גָּבִישׁ; stiffening; Magbish, an Israelite, or a place in Palestine: Magbish.
from גָּבַל; a border: end.
from the same as גִּבְעָה; a cap (as hemispherical): bonnet.
from an unused root probably meaning to be eminent; properly, a distinguished thing; hence something valuable, as a product or fruit: pleasant, precious fruit (thing).
(Zech. 12 or Mgiddow; from גָּדַד; rendezvous; Megiddon or Megiddo, a place in Palestine: Megiddo, Megiddon.
or Migdol; probably of Egyptian origin; Migdol, a place in Egypt: Migdol, tower.
from מֶ֫גֶד and אֵל; preciousness of God; Magdiel, an Idumaean: Magdiel.

also (in plural) feminine migdalah; from גָּדַל; a tower (from its size or height); by analogy, a rostrum; figuratively, a (pyramidal) bed of flowers: castle, flower, tower. Compare the names following.
from מִגְדָּל and אֵל; tower of God; Migdal-El, a place in Palestine: Migdal-el.
from מִגְדָּל and גַּד; tower of Fortune; Migdal-Gad, a place in Palestine: Migdal-gad.
from מִגְדָּל and עֵ֫דֶר; tower of a flock; Migdal-Eder, a place in Palestine: Migdal-eder, tower of the flock.
from the same as מֶ֫גֶד; preciousness, i.e. a gem: precious thing, present.
from גּוֹג; Magog, a son of Japheth; also a barbarous northern region: Magog.
or (Lam. 2:22) maguwr; from גּוּר in the sense of fearing; a fright (objective or subjective): fear, terror. Compare מָגוֹר מִסָּבִיב.
or magur; from גּוּר in the sense of lodging; a temporary abode; by extension, a permanent residence: dwelling, pilgrimage, where sojourn, be a stranger. Compare מָגוֹר.
feminine of מָגוֹר; affright: fear.
feminine of מָגוֹר or of מָגוּר; a fright; also a granary: barn, fear.
from מָגוֹר and סָבִיב with the preposition inserted; affright from around; Magor-mis-Sabib, a symbolic name of Pashur: Magor-missabib.
from גָּזַר; a cutting implement, i.e. a blade: axe.
from an unused root meaning to reap; a sickle: sickle.
from גָּלַל; a roll: roll, volume.
(Aramaic) corresponding to מְגִלָּה: roll.
from the same as גַּם; properly, accumulation, i.e. impulse or direction: sup up.
a denominative from מָגֵן; properly, to shield; encompass with; figuratively, to rescue, to hand safely over (i.e. surrender): deliver.

also (in plural) feminine mginnah; from גָּנַן; a shield (i.e. the small one or buckler); figuratively, a protector; also the scaly hide of the crocodile: X armed, buckler, defence, ruler, + scale, shield.
from מָגַן; a covering (in a bad sense), i.e. blindness or obduracy: sorrow. See also מָגֵן.
from גָּעַר; reproof (i.e. curse): rebuke.
from נָגַף; a pestilence; by analogy, defeat: (X be) plague(-d), slaughter, stroke.
apparently from גּוּף or נָגַף and עָשׁ; exterminator of (the) moth; Magpiash, an Israelite: Magpiash.
a primitive root; to yield up; intensively, to precipitate: cast down, terror.
(Aramaic) corresponding to מָגַר; to overthrow: destroy.
from גָּרַר; a saw: axe, saw.
from מָגַר; precipice; Migron, a place in Palestine: Migron.
from גָּרַע; a ledge or offset: narrowed rest.
from גָּרַף; something thrown off (by the spade), i.e. a clod: clod.

also (in plural) feminine (Ezek. 27:28) migrashah; from גָּרַשׁ; a suburb (i.e. open country whither flocks are driven from pasture); hence, the area around a building, or the margin of the sea: cast out, suburb.
or med; from מָדַד; properly, extent, i.e. height; also a measure; by implication, a vesture (as measured); also a carpet: armour, clothes, garment, judgment, measure, raiment, stature.
(Aramaic) from דְּבַח; a sacrificial altar: altar.
from דָּבַר in the sense of driving; a pasture (i.e. open field, whither cattle are driven); by implication, a desert; also speech (including its organs): desert, south, speech, wilderness.
a primitive root: properly, to stretch; by implication, to measure (as if by stretching a line); figuratively, to be extended: measure, mete, stretch self.
from נָדַד; flight: be gone.

feminine of מִדּוֹ; properly, extension, i.e. height or breadth; also a measure (including its standard); hence a portion (as measured) or a vestment; specifically, tribute (as measured): garment, measure(-ing, meteyard, piece, size, (great) stature, tribute, wide.
(Aramaic) or mindah (Aramaic); corresponding to מִדָּה; tribute in money: toll, tribute.
perhaps from the equivalent of דְּהַב; goldmaking, i.e. exactness: golden city.
from an unused root meaning to stretch; properly, extent, i.e. measure; by implication, a dress (as measured): garment.
from דָּוָה; sickness: disease.
from נָדַח; seduction: cause of banishment.
from דִּין; a contest or quarrel: brawling, contention(-ous), discord, strife. Compare מִדְוָנִים, מְדָנִים.
from the same as מַדְוֵי; extensiveness, i.e. height: stature.
the same as מָדוֹן; Madon, a place in Palestine: Madon.
or madduaa; from מָה and the passive participle of יָדַע; what (is) known?; i.e. (by implication) (adverbially) why?: how, wherefore, why.
(Aramaic) or mdor (Aramaic); or mdar (Aramaic); from דּוּר; a dwelling: dwelling.
or mdurah; from דּוּר in the sense of accumulation; a pile of fuel: pile (for fire).
from דָּחָה; overthrow: ruin.
from דָּחַף; a push, i.e. ruin: overthrow.
of foreign derivation; Madai, a country of central Asia: Madai, Medes, Media.
patrial from מָדַי; a Madian or native of Madai: Mede.
(Aramaic) corresponding to מָדַי: Mede(-s).
(Aramaic) corresponding to מָדַי: Median.
from מָה and דָּי; what (is) enough, i.e. sufficiently: sufficiently.
a variation for מָדוֹן: brawling, contention(-ous).
the same as מִדְוָנִים; Midjan, a son of Abraham; also his country and (collectively) his descendants: Midian, Midianite.
a variation for מִדְיָן: Middin.
from דִּין; properly, a judgeship, i.e. jurisdiction; by implication, a district (as ruled by a judge); generally, a region: (X every) province.
(Aramaic) corresponding to מְדִינָה: province.
patronymical or patrial from מִדְיָן; a Midjanite or descend. (native) of Midjan: Midianite. Compare מְדָנִים.
from דּוּך; a mortar: mortar.
from the same as דֹּ֫מֶן; dunghill; Madmen, a place in Palestine: Madmen.
feminine from the same as דֹּ֫מֶן; a dunghill: dunghill.
the same as מַדְמֵנָה; Madmenah, a place in Palestine: Madmenah.
a variation for מַדְמֵנָה; Madmannah, a place in Palestine: Madmannah.
a form of מָדוֹן: discord, strife.
the same as מְדָנִים; Medan, a son of Abraham: Medan.
a variation of מִדְיָנִי: Midianite.
or maddai; from יָדַע; intelligence or consciousness: knowledge, science, thought.
from דָּקַר; a wound: piercing.
from an unused root meaning to step; properly, a step; by implication, a steep or inaccessible place: stair, steep place.
from דָּרַך; a treading, i.e. a place for stepping on: (foot-)breadth.
from דָּרַשׁ; properly, an investigation, i.e. (by implication) a treatise or elaborate compilation: story.
from דּוּשׁ; a threshing, i.e. (concretely and figuratively) down-trodden people: threshing.
