feminineal sense of superiority in mental action; properly, a pithy maxim, usually of metaphorical nature; hence, a simile (as a adae, compare, use (as a) proverb, speak (in proverbs), utter.
from שָׁמַר; a guard (the man, the post or the prison); a deposit (fig.); also (as observed) a usage (abstr.), or an example (concr.): diligence, guard, office, prison, ward, watch.
for מַסְמְרִים fem.; a peg: nail.

fem. of מִשְׁמָר; watch, i.e. the act (custody), or (concr.) the sentry, the post; obj. preservation, or (concr.) safe; fig. observance, i.e. (abstr.) duty or (obj.) a usage or party: charge, keep, or to be kept, office, ordinace, safeguard, ward, watch.

from שָׁנָה; properly, a repetition, i.e. a duplicate (copy of a document), or a double (in amount); by implication, a second (in order, rank, age, quality or location): college, copy, double, fatlings, next, second (order), twice as much.
from שָׁסַס; plunder: booty, spoil.
from the same as שֹׁ֫עַל; a hollow, i.e. a narrow passage: path.
probably from שָׁעָה; inspection: to supple.
apparently from שָׁעָה; inspection; Misham, an Israelite: Misham.
or mishtan; from שָׁעַן; a support (concretely), i.e. (figuratively) a protector or sustenance: stay.
or mishteneth; feminine of מַשְׁעֵן; support (abstractly), i.e. (figuratively) sustenance or (concretely) a walking-stick: staff.
from סָפַח; slaughter: oppression.
from שָׁפָה (compare שִׁפְחָה); a family, i.e. circle of relatives; figuratively, a class (of persons), a species (of animals) or sort (of things); by extens. a tribe or people: family, kind(-red).

from שָׁפַט; properly, a verdict (favorable or unfavorable) pronounced judicially, especially a sentence or formal decree (human or (participant's) divine law, individual or collective), including the act, the place, the suit, the crime, and the penalty; abstractly, justice, including a participant's right or privilege (statutory or customary), or even a style: + adversary, ceremony, charge, X crime, custom, desert, determination, discretion, disposing, due, fashion, form, to be judged, judgment, just(-ice, -ly), (manner of) law(-ful), manner, measure, (due) order, ordinance, right, sentence, usest, X worthy, + wrong.
from שָׁפָה; a stall for cattle (only dual): burden, sheepfold.
from an unused root meaning to hold; possession: + steward.
from שָׁקַק; a traversing, i.e. rapid motion: running to and fro.

from שָׁקָה; properly, causing to drink, i.e. a butler; by implication (intransitively), drink (itself); figuratively, a well-watered region: butler(-ship), cupbearer, drink(-ing), fat pasture, watered.
from שָׁקַל; weight: weight.
from שָׁקַף in its original sense of overhanging; a lintel: lintel.
from שָׁקַל; weight (numerically estimated); hence, weighing (the act): (full) weight.
or mishqoleth; feminine of מִשְׁקָל or מַשְׁקוֹף; a weight, i.e. a plummet (with line attached): plummet.
from שָׁקַע; a settling place (of water), i.e. a pond: deep.
from שָׂרָה; empire: government.
from שָׁרָה in the sense of loosening; maceration, i.e. steeped juice: liquor.
(Aramaic) from a root corresponding to שָׁרַק; a (musical) pipe (from its whistling sound): flute.
patrial from an unused noun from an unused root; probably meaning to stretch out; extension; a Mishraite, or inhabitant (collectively) of Mishra: Mishraites.
from שָׂרַף; combustion, i.e. cremation (of a corpse), or calcination (of lime): burning.
from the plural of מִשְׂרְפוֹת and מָ֫יִם; burnings of water; Misrephoth-Majim, a place in Palestine: Misrephoth-mayim.
a form for שֹׂרֵק used denominatively; vineyard; Masrekah, a place in Idumaea: Masrekah.
apparently from an unused root meaning to perforate, i.e. hollow out; a pan: pan.
a primitive root; to feel of; by implication, to grope: feel, grope, search.
from שָׁתָה; drink, by implication, drinking (the act); also (by implication) a banquet or (generally) feast: banquet, drank, drink, feast((-ed), -ing).
(Aramaic) corresponding to מִשְׁתֶּה; a banquet: banquet.
from the same as מָתַי; properly, an adult (as of full length); by implication, a man (only in the plural): + few, X friends, men, persons, X small.
denominative from תֶּ֫בֶן; straw in the heap: straw.
from an unused root meaning to curb; a bit: bit, bridle.
from מֶ֫תֶג and אַמָּה with the art. interposed; bit of the metropolis; Metheg-ha-Ammah, an epithet of Gath: Metheg-ammah.
or mathuwq; from מָתַק; sweetsweet(-er, -ness).
from מְתִים and אֵל, with the relative interposed; man who (is) of God; Methusael, an antediluvian patriarch: Methusael.
from מְתִים and שָׁ֫לַח; man of a dart; Methushelach, an antediluvian patriarch: Methuselah.
a primitive root; to stretch out: spread out.
from an unused root meaning to extend; properly, extent (of time); but used only adverbially (especially with other particle prefixes), when (either relative or interrogative): long, when.
or mathkuneth; from תָּכַן in the transferred sense of measuring; proportion (in size, number or ingredients): composition, measure, state, tale.
from מָה and תְּלָאָה; what a trouble!: what a weariness.
contr. from יָלַע; properly, a biter, i.e. a tooth: cheek (jaw) tooth, jaw.
from תָּמַם; wholesomeness; also (adverb) completely: men (by reading math), soundness.
from an unused root meaning to be slender; properly, the waist or small of the back; only in plural the loins: + greyhound, loins, side.
from נָתַן; a present: gift, to give, reward.
the same as מַתָּן; Mattan, the name of a priest of Baal, and of an Israelite: Mattan.
(Aramaic) corresponding to מַתָּנָה: gift.
feminine of מַתָּן; a present; specifically (in a good sense), a sacrificial offering, (in a bad sense) a bribe: gift.
the same as מַתָּנָה; Mattanah, a place in the Desert: Mattanah.
probably patrial from an unused noun meaning slenderness; a Mithnite, or inhabitant of Methen: Mithnite.
from מַתָּן; liberal; Mattenai, the name of three Israelites: Mattenai.
or Mattanyahuw; from מַתָּן and יָהּ; gift of Jah; Mattanjah, the name of ten Israelites: Mattaniah.
from נָשָׂא; (used as abstractly) supreme exaltation: exalted.
a primitive root; to suck, by implication, to relish, or (intransitively) be sweet: be (made, X take) sweet.
from מָתַק; figuratively, pleasantness (of discourse): sweetness.
from מָתַק; sweetness: sweetness.
from מָתַק; a dainty, i.e. (generally) food: feed sweetly.
feminine of מֹ֫תֶק; sweetness; Mithkah, a place in the Desert: Mithcah.
of Persian origin; Mithredath, the name of two Persians: Mithredath.
feminine of מַתָּן abbreviated form; a present: gift.
for מַתִּתְיָה; gift of Jah; Mattattah, an Israelite: Mattathah.
or Mattithyahuw; from מַתָּ֫נֶת and יָהּ; gift of Jah; Mattithjah, the name of four IsraelitesMattithiah.

a primitive particle of incitement and entreaty, which may usually be rendered: "I pray," "now," or "then"; added mostly to verbs (in the Imperative or Future), or to interjections, occasionally to an adverb or conjunction: I beseech (pray) thee (you), go to, now, oh.
apparently from נוּא in the sense of harshness from refusal; properly, tough, i.e. uncooked (flesh): raw.
of Egyptian origin; No (i.e. Thebes), the capital of Upper Egypt: No. Compare אָמוֹן.
or noywd; also (feminine) no)dah; from an unused root of uncertain signification; a (skin or leather) bag (for fluids): bottle.
a primitive root; properly, to be at home, i.e. (by implication) to be pleasant (or suitable), i.e. beautiful: be beautiful, become, be comely.
from נָאָה; a home; figuratively, a pasture: habitation, house, pasture, pleasant place.
from נָאָה or נָוֶה; suitable, or beautiful: becometh, comely, seemly.
a primitive root; properly, to whisper, i.e. (by implication) to utter as a oracle: say.
from נָאַם; an oracle: (hath) said, saith.
a primitive root; to commit adultery; figuratively, to apostatize: adulterer(-ess), commit(-ing) adultery, woman that breaketh wedlock.
from נָאַף; adultery: adultery.
from נָאַף; adultery: adultery.
a primitive root; to scorn; or (Ecclesiastes 12:5) by interchange for נוּץ, to bloom: abhor, (give occasion to) blaspheme, contemn, despise, flourish, X great, provoke.
or nematsah; from נָאַץ; scorn: blasphemy.
a primitive root; to groan: groan.
from נָאַק; a groan: groaning.
a primitive root; to reject: abhor, make void.
the same as נִיב; fruit; Nob, a place in Palestine: Nob.
a primitive root; to prophesy, i.e. speak (or sing) by inspiration (in prediction or simple discourse): prophesy(-ing), make self a prophet.
(Aramaic) corresponding to נָבָא: prophesy.
a primitive root; to pierce; to be hollow, or (figuratively) foolish: hollow, vain.
probably of foreign derivation; Nebo, the name of a Babylonian deity, also of a mountain in Moab, and of a place in Palestine: Nebo.
from נָבָא; a prediction (spoken or written): prophecy.
(Aramaic) corresponding to נְבוּאָה; inspired teaching: prophesying.
of foreign origin; Nebuzaradan, a Babylonian general: Nebuzaradan.

or Nbukadneotstsar (2 Kings 24:1, 10); or Nbuwkadnetstsar (Esther 2:6; Daniel 1:18); or Nbuwkadreotstsar; or Nbuwkadreltstsowr (Ezra 2:1; Jeremiah 49:28); or foreign derivation; Nebukadnetstsar (or -retstsar, or -retstsor), king of Babylon: Nebuchadnezzar, Nebuchadrezzar.
(Aramaic) corresponding to נְבוּכַדְנֶאצַּר: Nebuchadnezzar.
of foreign derivation; Nebushazban, Nebuchadnezzar's chief eunuch: Nebushazban.
feminine plural from the same as נֹב; fruits; Naboth, an Israelite: Naboth.
(Aramaic) of uncertain derivation; a largess: reward.
a primitive root; to bark (as a dog): bark.
from נָבַח; a bark; Nobach, the name of an Israelite, and of a place East of the Jordan: Nobah.
of foreign origin; Nibchaz, a deity of the Avites: Nibhaz.
a primitive root; to scan, i.e. look intently at; by implication, to regard with pleasure, favor or care: (cause to) behold, consider, look (down), regard, have respect, see.
from נָבַט; regard; Nebat, the father of Jeroboam I: Nebat.
(Aramaic) corresponding to נָבִיא; a prophet: prophet.
from נָבָא; a prophet or (generally) inspired man: prophecy, that prophesy, prophet.
feminine of נָבִיא; a prophetess or (generally) inspired woman; by implication, a poetess; by association a prophet's wife: prophetess.
or Nbayoth; feminine plural from נוּב; fruitfulnesses; Nebajoth, a son of Ismael, and the country settled by him: Nebaioth, Nebajoth.
from an unused root meaning to burst forth; a fountain: spring.

a primitive root; to wilt; generally, to fall away, fail, faint; figuratively, to be foolish or (morally) wicked; causatively, to despise, disgrace: disgrace, dishounour, lightly esteem, fade (away, - ing), fall (down, -ling, off), do foolishly, come to nought, X surely, make vile, wither.

or nebel; from נָבֵל; a skin-bag for liquids (from collapsing when empty); hence, a vase (as similar in shape when full); also a lyre (as having a body of like form): bottle, pitcher, psaltery, vessel, viol.
from נָבֵל; stupid; wicked (especially impious)fool(-ish, -ish man, -ish woman), vile person.
the same as נָבָל; dolt; Nabal, an Israelite: Nabal.

from נָבֵל; a flabby thing, i.e. a carcase or carrion (human or bestial, often collectively); figuratively, an idol(dead) body, (dead) carcase, dead of itself, which died, (beast) that (which) dieth of itself.
feminine of נָבָל; foolishness, i.e. (morally) wickedness; concretely, a crime; by extension, punishment: folly, vile, villany.
from נָבָל; properly, disgrace, i.e. the (female) pudenda: lewdness.
apparently from נָבָל and לָט; foolish secrecy; Neballat, a place in Palestine: Neballat.
a primitive root; to gush forth; figuratively, to utter (good or bad words); specifically, to emit (a foul odor): belch out, flowing, pour out, send forth, utter (abundantly).
(Aramaic) from an unused root meaning to shine; a light; plural (collectively) a chandelier: candlestick.
of uncertain derivation; Nibshan, a place in Palestine: Nibshan.

from an unused root meaning to be parched; the south (from its drought); specifically, the Negeb or southern district of Judah, occasionally, Egypt (as south to Palestine): south (country, side, -ward).

a primitive root; properly, to front, i.e. stand boldly out opposite; by implication (causatively), to manifest; figuratively, to announce (always by word of mouth to one present); specifically, to expose, predict, explain, praise: bewray, X certainly, certify, declare(-ing), denounce, expound, X fully, messenger, plainly, profess, rehearse, report, shew (forth), speak, X surely, tell, utter.
(Aramaic) corresponding to נָגַד; to flow (through the idea of clearing the way): issue.

from נָגַד; a front, i.e. part opposite; specifically a counterpart, or mate; usually (adverbial, especially with preposition) over against or before: about, (over) against, X aloof, X far (off), X from, over, presence, X other side, sight, X to view.
(Aramaic) corresponding to נֶ֫גֶד; opposite: toward.
a primitive root; to glitter; causatively, to illuminate: (en-)lighten, (cause to) shine.
from נָגַהּ; brilliancy (literally or figuratively): bright(-ness), light, (clear) shining.
the same as נֹ֫גַהּ; Nogah, a son of David: Nogah.
(Aramaic) corresponding to נֹ֫גַהּ; dawn: morning.
feminine of נֹ֫גַהּ; splendor: brightness.
a primitive root; to but with the horns; figuratively, to war against: gore, push (down, -ing).
from נָגַח; butting, i.e. vicious: used (wont) to push.

or nagid; from נָגַד; a commander (as occupying the front), civil, military or religious; generally (abstractly, plural), honorable themes: captain, chief, excellent thing, (chief) governor, leader, noble, prince, (chief) ruler.

or ngiynath (Psa. 61:title); from נָגַן; properly, instrumental music; by implication, a stringed instrument; by extension, a poem set to music; specifically, an epigram: stringed instrument, musick, Neginoth (plural), song.

a primitive root; properly, to thrum, i.e. beat a tune with the fingers; expec. to play on a stringed instrument; hence (generally), to make music: player on instruments, sing to the stringed instruments, melody, ministrel, play(-er, -ing).

a primitive root; properly, to touch, i.e. lay the hand upon (for any purpose; euphem., to lie with a woman); by implication, to reach (figuratively, to arrive, acquire); violently, to strike (punish, defeat, destroy, etc.): beat, (X be able to) bring (down), cast, come (nigh), draw near (nigh), get up, happen, join, near, plague, reach (up), smite, strike, touch.
from נָגַע; a blow (figuratively, infliction); also (by implication) a spot (concretely, a leprous person or dress): plague, sore, stricken, stripe, stroke, wound.
a primitive root; to push, gore, defeat, stub (the toe), inflict (a disease): beat, dash, hurt, plague, slay, smite (down), strike, stumble, X surely, put to the worse.
from נָגַף; a trip (of the foot); figuratively, an infliction (of disease): plague, stumbling.
a primitive root; to flow; figuratively, to stretch out; causatively, to pour out or down; figuratively, to deliver over: fall, flow away, pour down (out), run, shed, spilt, trickle down.
a primitive root; to drive (an animal, a workman, a debtor, an army); by implication, to tax, harass, tyrannize: distress, driver, exact(-or), oppress(-or), X raiser of taxes, taskmaster.

a primitive root; to be or come (causatively, bring) near (for any purpose); euphemistically, to lie with a woman; as an enemy, to attack; relig. to worship; causatively, to present; figuratively, to adduce an argument; by reversal, to stand back: (make to) approach (nigh), bring (forth, hither, near), (cause to) come (hither, near, nigh), give place, go hard (up), (be, draw, go) near (nigh), offer, overtake, present, put, stand.
from נוּד in the sense of piling up; a mound, i.e. wave: heap.
a primitive root; to impel; hence, to volunteer (as a soldier), to present spontaneously: offer freely, be (give, make, offer self) willing(-ly).
(Aramaic) corresponding to נָדַב; be (or give) liberal(-ly): (be minded of...own) freewill (offering), offer freely (willingly).
from נָדַב; liberal; Nadab, the name of four Israelites: Nadab.

from נָדַב; properly (abstractly) spontaneity, or (adjectively) spontaneous; also (concretely) a spontaneous or (by inference, in plural) abundant gift: free(-will) offering, freely, plentiful, voluntary(-ily, offering), willing(-ly), offering).
from נָדַב and יָהּ; largess of Jah; Nedabjah, an Israelite: Nedabiah.
(Aramaic) from a root meaning to stick; a layer (of building materials): row.

a primitive root; properly, to wave to and fro (rarely to flap up and down); figuratively, to rove, flee, or (causatively) to drive away: chase (away), X could not, depart, flee (X apace, away), (re-)move, thrust away, wander (abroad, -er, -ing).
(Aramaic) corresponding to נָדַד; to depart: go from.
passive participle of נָדַד; properly, tossed; abstractly, a rolling (on the bed): tossing to and fro.
or nada (2 Kings 17:21); a primitive root; properly, to toss; figuratively, to exclude, i.e. banish, postpone, prohibit: cast out, drive, put far away.
from נָדָה in the sense of freely flinging money; a bounty (for prostitution): gifts.

from נָדַד; properly, rejection; by implication, impurity, especially personal (menstruation) or moral (idolatry, incest): X far, filthiness, X flowers, menstruous (woman), put apart, X removed (woman), separation, set apart, unclean(-ness, thing, with filthiness).

a primitive root; to push off; used in a great variety of applications, literally and figuratively (to expel, mislead, strike, inflict, etc.): banish, bring, cast down (out), chase, compel, draw away, drive (away, out, quite), fetch a stroke, force, go away, outcast, thrust away (out), withdraw.
from נָדַב; properly, voluntary, i.e. generous; hence, magnanimous; as noun, a grandee (sometimes a tyrant): free, liberal (things), noble, prince, willing ((hearted)).
feminine of נָדִיב; properly, nobility, i.e. reputation: soul.
probably from an unused root meaning to give; a present (for prostitution): gift.
of uncertain derivation; a sheath (of a sword): sheath.
(Aramaic) from the same as נָדָן; a sheath; figuratively, the body (as the receptacle of the soul): body.
a primitive root; to shove asunder, i.e. disperse: drive (away, to and fro), thrust down, shaken, tossed to and fro.
a primitive root; to promise (pos., to do or give something to God): (make a) vow.
or neder; from נָדַר; a promise (to God); also (concretely) a thing promised: vow((-ed)).
from an unused root meaning to lament; lamentation: wailing.

a primitive root; to drive forth (a person, an animal or chariot), i.e. lead, carry away; reflexively, to proceed (i.e. impel or guide oneself); also (from the panting induced by effort), to sigh: acquaint, bring (away), carry away, drive (away), lead (away, forth), (be) guide, lead (away, forth).
a primitive root; to groan, i.e. bewail; hence (through the idea of crying aloud), to assemble (as if on proclamation)lament, wail.
from נָהָה; an elegy: lamentation, wailing.
feminine of נֶ֫הִי; lamentation: doleful.
(Aramaic) or nehiyruw (Aramaic); from the same as נְהָרָה; illumination, i.e. (figuratively) wisdom: light.
a primitive root; properly, to run with a sparkle, i.e. flow; hence (transitively), to conduct, and (by inference) to protect, sustain: carry, feed, guide, lead (gently, on).
or Nahalol; the same as נַהֲלֹלִים; Nahalal or Nahalol, a place in Palestine: Nahalal, Nahallal, Nahalol.
from נָהַל; pasture: bush.
a primitive root; to growl: mourn, roar(-ing).
from נָהַם; a snarl: roaring.
feminine of נַ֫הַם; snarling: disquietness, roaring.
a primitive root; to bray (as an ass), scream (from hunger: bray.
a primitive root; to sparkle, i.e. (figuratively) be cheerful; hence (from the sheen of a running stream) to flow, i.e. (figuratively) assemble: flow (together), be lightened.
(Aramaic) from a root corresponding to נָהַר; a river, especially the Euphrates: river, stream.
from נָהַר; a stream (including the sea; expec. the Nile, Euphrates, etc.); figuratively, prosperity: flood, river.
from נָהַר in its original sense; daylight: light.
a primitive root; to refuse, forbid, dissuade, or neutralize: break, disallow, discourage, make of none effect.
a primitive root; to germinate, i.e. (figuratively) to (causatively, make) flourish; also (of words), to utter: bring forth (fruit), make cheerful, increase.
or neyb; from נוּב; produce, literally or figuratively: fruit.
from נִיב; fruitful; Nobai, an Israelite: Nebai (from the margin).

a primitive root; to nod, i.e. waver; figuratively, to wander, flee, disappear; also (from shaking the head in sympathy), to console, deplore, or (from tossing the head in scorn) taunt: bemoan, flee, get, mourn, make to move, take pity, remove, shake, skip for joy, be sorry, vagabond, way, wandering.
(Aramaic) corresponding to נָוֶה; to flee: get away.
(only defect. nod); from נוּד; exile: wandering.
the same as נֹדִי; vagrancy; Nod, the land of Cain: Nod.
from נָדַב; noble; Nodab, an Arab tribe: Nodab.
a primitive root; to rest (as at home); causatively (through the implied idea of beauty (compare נָוֶה)), to celebrate (with praises): keept at home, prepare an habitation.

or (feminine) navah; from נָוָה; (adjectively) at home; hence (by implication of satisfaction) lovely; also (noun) a home, of God (temple), men (residence), flocks (pasture), or wild animals (den): comely, dwelling (place), fold, habitation, pleasant place, sheepcote, stable, tarried.

a primitive root; to rest, i.e. settle down; used in a great variety of applications, literal and figurative, intransitive, transitive and causative (to dwell, stay, let fall, place, let alone, withdraw, give comfort, etc.): cease, be confederate, lay, let down, (be) quiet, remain, (cause to, be at, give, have, make to) rest, set down. Compare יָנִים.
or nowach; from נ֫וּחַ; quiet: rest(-ed, -ing place).
feminine of נ֫וּחַ; quietude; Nochah, an Israelite: Nohah.
to quake: be moved.
from נָוָה; residence; Navith, a place in Palestine: Naioth (from the margin).
(Aramaic) or nvaliy (Aramaic); from an unused root probably meaning to be foul; a sink: dunghill.
a primitive root; to slumber (from drowsiness): sleep, slumber.
from נוּם; sleepiness: drowsiness.
a primitive root; to resprout, i.e. propagate by shoots; figuratively, to be perpetual: be continued.
or Nown (1 Chron. 7:27); from נוּן; perpetuity, Nun or Non, the father of Joshua: Non, Nun.
a primitive root; to flit, i.e. vanish away (subside, escape; causatively, chase, impel, deliver): X abate, away, be displayed, (make to) flee (away, -ing), put to flight, X hide, lift up a standard.

a primitive root; to waver, in a great variety of applications, literally and figuratively (as subjoined): continually, fugitive, X make, to (go) up and down, be gone away, (be) move(-able, -d), be promoted, reel, remove, scatter, set, shake, sift, stagger, to and fro, be vagabond, wag, (make) wander (up and down).
from יָעַד and יָהּ; convened of Jah; Noadjah, the name of an Israelite, and a false prophetess: Noadiah.

a primitive root; to quiver (i.e. vibrate up and down, or rock to and fro); used in a great variety of applications (including sprinkling, beckoning, rubbing, bastinadoing, sawing, waving, etc.): lift up, move, offer, perfume, send, shake, sift, strike, wave.
from נוּף; elevation: situation. Compare נֹף.
a primitive root; properly, to flash; hence, to blossom (from the brilliancy of color); also, to fly away (from the quickness of motion): flee away, bud (forth).
or notsah; feminine active participle of נָצָה in the sense of flying; a pinion (or wing feather); often (collectively) plumage: feather(-s), ostrich.
a primitive root; to suckle: nurse.
(Aramaic) from an unused root (corresponding to that of נֵר) meaning to shine; fire: fiery, fire.
a primitive root; to be sick, i.e. (figuratively) distressed: be full of heaviness.
a primitive root; to spirt, i.e. besprinkle (especially in expiation): sprinkle.
from זִיד; something boiled, i.e. soup: pottage.

or nazir; from נָזַר; separate, i.e. consecrated (as prince, a Nazirite); hence (figuratively from the latter) an unpruned vine (like an unshorn Nazirite): Nazarite (by a false alliteration with Nazareth), separate(-d), vine undressed.
a primitive root; to drip, or shed by trickling: distil, drop, flood, (cause to) flow(-ing), gush out, melt, pour (down), running water, stream.
from an unused root of uncertain meaning; a nose-ring: earring, jewel.
(Aramaic) corresponding to the root of נֵ֫זֶק; to suffer (causatively, inflict) loss: have (en-)damage, hurt(-ful).
from an unused root meaning to injure; loss: damage.

a primitive root; to hold aloof, i.e. (intransitivey) abstain (from food and drink, from impurity, and even from divine worship (i.e. apostatize)); specifically, to set apart (to sacred purposes), i.e. devote: consecrate, separate(-ing, self).

or nezer; from נָזַר; properly, something set apart, i.e. (abstractly) dedication (of a priest or Nazirite); hence (concretely) unshorn locks; also (by implication) a chaplet (especially of royalty): consecration, crown, hair, separation.
the same as נ֫וּחַ; rest; Noach, the patriarch of the flood: Noah.
from חָבָה; occult; Nachbi, an Israelite: Nakbi.
a primitive root; to guide; by implication, to transport (into exile, or as colonists): bestow, bring, govern, guide, lead (forth), put, straiten.
from נָחַם; comforted; Nechum, an Israelite: Nehum.
or nichum; from נָחַם; properly, consoled; abstractly, solace: comfort(-able), repenting.
from נָחַם; comfortable; Nachum, an Israelite prophet: Nahum.
from the same as נַ֫חַר; snorer; Nochor, the name of the grandfather and a brother of Abraham: Nahor.

apparently passive participle of נָחַשׁ (perhaps in the sense of ringing, i.e. bell-metal; or from the red color of the throat of a serpent (נָחָשׁ, as denominative) when hissing); coppery, i.e. (figuratively) hard: of brass.
or nchushah; feminine of נָחוּשׁ; copper: brass, steel. Compare נָחָשׁ.
probably denominative from חָלִיל; a flute: (plural) Nehiloth.
from the same as נַ֫חַר; a nostril: (dual) nostrils.

a primitive root; to inherit (as a (figurative) mode of descent), or (generally) to occupy; causatively, to bequeath, or (generally) distribute, instate: divide, have ((inheritance)), take as a heritage, (cause to, give to, make to) inherit, (distribute for, divide (for, for an, by), give for, have, leave for, take (for)) inheritance, (have in, cause to, be made to) possess(-ion).

or (feminine) nachlah (Psalm 124:4); or nachalah (Ezekiel 47:19; 48:28); from נָחַל in its original sense; a stream, especially a winter torrent; (by implication) a (narrow) valley (in which a brook runs); also a shaft (of a mine): brook, flood, river, stream, valley.

from נָחַל (in its usual sense); properly, something inherited, i.e. (abstractly) occupancy, or (concretely) an heirloom; generally an estate, patrimony or portion: heritage, to inherit, inheritance, possession. Compare נַ֫חַל.
from נַ֫חַל and אֵל; valley of God; Nachaliel, a place in the Desert: Nahaliel.
apparently a patronymic from an unused name (apparently passive participle of חָלַם); dreamed; a Nechelamite, or descendant of Nechlam: Nehelamite.

a primitive root; properly, to sigh, i.e. breathe strongly; by implication, to be sorry, i.e. (in a favorable sense) to pity, console or (reflexively) rue; or (unfavorably) to avenge (oneself): comfort (self), ease (one's self), repent(-er,-ing, self).
from נָחַם; consolation; Nacham, an Israelite: Naham.
from נָחַם; ruefulness, i.e. desistance: repentance.
from נָחַם; consolation: comfort.
from נָחַם and יָהּ; consolation of Jah; Nechemjah, the name of three Israelites: Nehemiah.
from נָחַם; consolatory; Nachamani, an Israelite: Nahamani.
for אֲנַ֫חְנוּ; we: we.
a primitive root; to be urgent: require haste.
and (feminine) nacharah; from an unused root meaning to snort or snore; a snorting: nostrils, snorting.
or Nachray; from the same as נַ֫חַר; snorer; Nacharai or Nachrai, an Israelite: Naharai, Nahari.
a primitive root; properly, to hiss, i.e. whisper a (magic) spell; generally, to prognosticate: X certainly, divine, enchanter, (use) X enchantment, learn by experience, X indeed, diligently observe.
from נָחַשׁ; an incantation or augury: enchantment.
(Aramaic) corresponding to נְחוּשָׁה; copper: brass.
from נָחַשׁ; a snake (from its hiss): serpent.
the same as נָחָשׁ; Nachash, the name of two persons apparently non-Israelite: Nahash.
from נָחַשׁ; enchanter; Nachshon, an Israelite: Naashon, Nahshon.

for נְחוּשָׁה; copper, hence, something made of that metal, i.e. coin, a fetter; figuratively, base (as compared with gold or silver): brasen, brass, chain, copper, fetter (of brass), filthiness, steel.
from נְחֹ֫שֶׁת; copper; Nechushta, an Israelitess: Nehushta.
from נְחֹ֫שֶׁת; something made of copper, i.e. the copper serpent of the Desert: Nehushtan.
a primitive root; to sink, i.e. descend; causatively, to press or lead down: be broken, (cause to) come down, enter, go down, press sore, settle, stick fast.
(Aramaic) corresponding to נָחַת; to descend; causatively, to bring away, deposit, depose: carry, come down, depose, lay up, place.
from נְחַת; a descent, i.e. imposition, unfavorable (punishment) or favorable (food); also (intransitively; perhaps from נ֫וּחַ), restfulness: lighting down, quiet(-ness), to rest, be set on.
the same as נָ֫חַת; quiet; Nachath, the name of an Edomite and of two Israelites: Nahath.
from נָחַת; descending: come down.

a primitive root; to stretch or spread out; by implication, to bend away (including moral deflection); used in a great variety of application (as follows): + afternoon, apply, bow (down, - ing), carry aside, decline, deliver, extend, go down, be gone, incline, intend, lay, let down, offer, outstretched, overthrown, pervert, pitch, prolong, put away, shew, spread (out), stretch (forth, out), take (aside), turn (aside, away), wrest, cause to yield.
from נָטַל; laden: that bear.
from נָטַף; a pendant for the ears (especially of pearls): chain, collar.
from נָטַשׁ; a tendril (as an offshoot): battlement, branch, plant.
a prim root; to lift; by implication, to impose: bear, offer, take up.
(Aramaic) corresponding to נָטַל; to raise: take up.
:  : from נָטַל; a burden: weighty.
a primitive root; properly, to strike in, i.e. fix; specifically, to plant (literally or figuratively): fastened, plant(- er).
from נָטַע; a plant; collectively, a plantation; abstractly, a planting: plant.
from נָטַע; a plant: plant.
plural of נָ֫טַע; Netaim, a place in Palestine: plants.
a primitive root; to ooze, i.e. distil gradually; by implication, to fall in drops; figuratively, to speak by inspiration: drop(-ping), prophesy(-et).
from נָטַף; a drop; specifically, an aromatic gum (probably stacte): drop, stacte.
from נָטַף; distillation; Netophah, a place in Palestine: Netophah.
patronymic from נְטֹפָה; a Netophathite, or inhabitant of Netophah: Netophathite.
a primitive root; to guard; figuratively, to cherish (anger): bear grudge, keep(-er), reserve.
(Aramaic) corresponding to נָטַר; to retain: keep.

a primitive root; properly, to pound, i.e. smite; by implication (as if beating out, and thus expanding) to disperse; also, to thrust off, down, out or upon (inclusively, reject, let alone, permit, remit, etc.): cast off, drawn, let fall, forsake, join (battle), leave (off), lie still, loose, spread (self) abroad, stretch out, suffer.
a doubtful word; apparently from נָהָה; lamentationwailing.
from נוּד; motion (of the lips in speech): moving.
feminine of נִיד; removal, i.e. exile: removed.
or niychoach; from נ֫וּחַ; properly, restful, i.e. pleasant; abstractly, delight: sweet (odour).
(Aramaic) or (shorter) niychoach (Aramaic); corresponding to נִיח֫וֹחַ; pleasure: sweet odour (savour).
from נוּן; progeny: son.
of foreign origin; Nineveh, the capital of Assyria: Nineveh.
from נוּס; fugitive: that fleeth.
probably of foreign origin; Nisan, the first month of the Jewish sacred year: Nisan.
from נָצַץ; a spark: spark.
a root probably identical with that of נֵר, through the idea of the gleam of a fresh furrow; to till the soil: break up.
or nir; from נִיר; properly, plowing, i.e. (concretely) freshly plowed land: fallow ground, plowing, tillage.

or nir; also neyr; or ner; or (feminine) nerah; from a primitive root (see נִיר; נוּר) properly, meaning to glisten; a lamp (i.e. the burner) or light (literally or figuratively): candle, lamp, light.
a primitive root; to smite, i.e. drive away: be viler.
or nakat; from נָכָא; smitten, i.e. (figuratively) afflicted: broken, stricken, wounded.
from נְכָאּים; properly, a smiting, i.e. (concretely) an aromatic gum (perhaps styrax) (as powdered): spicery(-ces).
from an unused root meaning to propagate; offspring: nephew, son's son.

a primitive root; to strike (lightly or severely, literally or figuratively): beat, cast forth, clap, give (wounds), X go forward, X indeed, kill, make (slaughter), murderer, punish, slaughter, slay(-er, -ing), smite(-r, -ing), strike, be stricken, (give) stripes, X surely, wound.
from נָכָה; a smiter, i.e. (figuratively) traducer: abject.
smitten, i.e. (literally) maimed, or (figuratively) dejected: contrite, lame.
probably of Egyptian origin; Neko, an Egyptian king: Necho. Compare פַּרְעֹה נְכֹה.
from כּוּן; prepared; Nakon, probably an Israelite: Nachon.
from an unused root meaning to be straightforward; properly, the fore part; used adverbially, opposite: before, over against.
from the same as נֵ֫כַח; properly, the front part; used adverbially (especially with preposition), opposite, in front of, forward, in behalf of: (over) against, before, direct(-ly), for, right (on).
from the same as נֵ֫כַח; straightforward, i.e. (figuratively), equitable, correct, or (abstractly), integrity: plain, right, uprightness.
feminine of נָכֹ֫חַ; properly, straightforwardness, i.e. (figuratively) integrity, or (concretely) a truth: equity, right (thing), uprightness.
a prim root; to defraud, i.e. act treacherously: beguile, conspire, deceiver, deal subtilly.
from נָכַל; deceit: wile.
(Aramaic) corresponding to נְכָסִים: goods.
from an unused root meaning to accumulate; treasure: riches, wealth.

a primitive root; properly, to scrutinize, i.e. look intently at; hence (with recognition implied), to acknowledge, be acquainted with, care for, respect, revere, or (with suspicion implied), to disregard, ignore, be strange toward, reject, resign, dissimulate (as if ignorant or disowning): acknowledge, X could, deliver, discern, dissemble, estrange, feign self to be another, know, take knowledge (notice), perceive, regard, (have) respect, behave (make) self strange(-ly).
or noker; from נָכַר; something strange, i.e. unexpected calamity: strange.
' from נָכַר; foreign, or (concretely) a foreigner, or (abstractly) heathendom: alien, strange (+ -er).
from נֹ֫כֶר (second form); strange, in a variety of degrees and applications (foreign, non-relative, adulterous, different, wonderful): alien, foreigner, outlandish, strange(-r, woman).
probably for נְכֹאת; spicery, i.e. (generally) valuables: precious things.
apparently a primitive root; to complete: make an end.
from בָּזָה, despised: vile.
apparently for יְמוּאֵל; Nemuel, the name of two Israelites: Nemuel.
from נְמוּאֵל; a Nemuelite, or descendant of Nemuel: Nemuelite.
a primitive root; to become clipped or (specifically) circumcised: (branch to) be cut down (off), circumcise.
feminine from נָמַל; an ant (probably from its almost bisected form): ant.
(Aramaic) corresponding to נָמֵר: leopard.
from an unused root meaning properly, to filtrate, i.e. be limpid (comp נִמְרָה and נִמְרִים); and thus to spot or stain as if by dripping; a leopard (from its stripes): leopard.
from the same as נָמֵר; clear water; Nimrah, a place East of the Jordan: Nimrah. See also בֵּית נִמְרָה, נִמְרִים.
or Nimrod; probably of foreign origin; Nimrod, a son of Cush: Nimrod.
plural of a masculine corresponding to נִמְרָה; clear waters; Nimrim, a place East of the Jordan: Nimrim. Compare בֵּית נִמְרָה.
probably from מָשָׁה; extricated; Nimshi, the (grand-)father of Jehu: Nimshi.
from נָסַס; a flag; also a sail; by implication, a flagstaff; generally a signal; figuratively, a token: banner, pole, sail, (en-)sign, standard.
feminine participle passive of סָבַב; properly, an environment, i.e. circumstance or turn of affairs: cause.
a primitive root; to retreat: departing away, remove, take (hold), turn away.
a primitive root; to test; by implication, to attempt: adventure, assay, prove, tempt, try.
a primitive root; to tear away: destroy, pluck, root.
(Aramaic) corresponding to נָסַח: pull down.
from נָסַך; properly, something poured out, i.e. a libation; also a molten image; by implication, a prince (as anointed): drink offering, duke, prince(-ipal).
a primitive root; to pour out, especially a libation, or to cast (metal); by analogy, to anoint a king: cover, melt, offer, (cause to) pour (out), set (up).
a primitive root (probably identical with נָסַך through the idea of fusion); to interweave, i.e. (figuratively) to overspread: that is spread.
(Aramaic) corresponding to נָסַך; to pour out a libation: offer.
(Aramaic) corresponding to נֶ֫סֶך; a libation: drink offering.
or necek; from נָסַך; a libation; also a cast idol: cover, drink offering, molten image.
a primitive root; to wane, i.e. be sick: faint.

a primitive root; to gleam from afar, i.e. to be conspicuous as a signal; or rather perhaps a denominative from נֵס (and identical with נָסַס, through the idea of a flag as fluttering in the wind); to raise a beacon: lift up as an ensign.

a primitive root; properly, to pull up, especially the tent-pins, i.e. start on a journey: cause to blow, bring, get, (make to) go (away, forth, forward, onward, out), (take) journey, march, remove, set aside (forward), X still, be on his (go their) way.
a primitive root; to go up: ascend.
(Aramaic) corresponding to נָסַק: take up.
of foreign origin; Nisrok, a Babylonian idol: Nisroch.
from נ֫וּעַ; motion; Neah, a place in Palestine: Neah.
from נ֫וּעַ; movement; Noah, an Israelitess: Noah.

or naur; and (feminine) nturah; properly, passive participle from נַ֫עַר as denominative; (only in plural collectively or emphatic form) youth, the state (juvenility) or the persons (young people): childhood, youth.
from נ֫וּעַ and אֵל; moved of God; Neiel, a place in Palestine: Neiel.
from נָעֵם; delightful (objective or subjective, literal or figurative): pleasant(-ure), sweet.
a primitive root; properly, to fasten up, i.e. with a bar or cord; hence (denominative from נָ֫עַל), to sandal, i.e. furnish with slippers: bolt, inclose, lock, shoe, shut up.

or (feminine) na`alah; from נָעַל; properly, a sandal tongue; by extens. a sandal or slipper (sometimes as a symbol of occupancy, a refusal to marry, or of something valueless): dryshod, (pair of) shoe((-latchet), -s).
a primitive root; to be agreeable (literally or figuratively): pass in beauty, be delight, be pleasant, be sweet.
from נָעֵם; pleasure; Naam, an Israelite: Naam.
from נָעֵם; agreeableness, i.e. delight, suitableness, splendor or grace: beauty, pleasant(-ness).
feminine of נָ֫עַם; pleasantness; Naamah, the name of an antediluvian woman, of an Ammonitess, and of a place in Palestine: Naamah.
patronymic from נַעֲמָן; a Naamanite, or descendant of Naaman (collectively): Naamites.
from נֹ֫עַם; pleasant; Noomi, an Israelitess: Naomi.
from נָעֵם; pleasantness (plural as concrete): pleasant.
the same as נַעֲמָנִים; Naaman, the name of an Israelite and of a Damascene: Naaman.
patrial from a place corresponding in name (but not identical) with נַעֲמָה; a Naamathite, or inhabitant of Naamah: Naamathite.
from an unused root meaning to prick; probably a brier; by implication, a thicket of thorny bushes: thorn.
a primitive root; to growl: yell.

a primitive root (probably identical with נָעַר, through the idea of the rustling of mane, which usually accompanies the lion's roar); to tumble about: shake (off, out, self), overthrow, toss up and down.

from נָעַר; (concretely) a boy (as active), from the age of infancy to adolescence; by implication, a servant; also (by interch. of sex), a girl (of similar latitude in age): babe, boy, child, damsel (from the margin), lad, servant, young (man).
from נָעַר in its derivative sense of tossing about; a wanderer: young one.
from נָעַר; (abstractly) boyhood (compare נַ֫עַר): child, youth.
feminine of נַ֫עַר; a girl (from infancy to adolescence): damsel, maid(-en), young (woman).
the same as נַעֲרָה; Naarah, the name of an Israelitess, and of a place in Palestine: Naarah, Naarath.
from נַ֫עַר; youthful; Naarai, an Israelite: Naarai.
from נַ֫עַר and יָהּ; servant of Jah; Nearjah, the name of two Israelites: Neariah.
from נַ֫עַר; juvenile; Naaran, a place in Palestine: Naaran.
from נָעַר; something shaken out, i.e. tow (as the refuse of flax): tow.
a variation of מֹף; Noph, the capital of Upper Egypt: Noph.
from an unused root probably meaning to spring forth; a sprout; Nepheg, the name of two Israelites: Nepheg.
from נוּף in the sense of lifting; a height; also a sieve: border, coast, region, sieve.
for נְפִיסִים; Nephushesim, a Temple- servant: Nephisesim (from the margin).

a primitive root; to puff, in various applications (literally, to inflate, blow hard, scatter, kindle, expire; figuratively, to disesteem): blow, breath, give up, cause to lose (life), seething, snuff.
from נָפַח; a gust; Nophach, a place in Moab: Nophah.
or nphil; from נָפַל; properly, a feller, i.e. a bully or tyrant: giant.
plural from an unused root meaning to scatter; expansions; Nephisim, a Temple-servant: Nephusim (from the margin).
from נָפַשׁ; refreshed; Naphish, a son of Ishmael, and his posterity: Naphish.
from an unused root meaning to glisten; shining; a gem, probably the garnet: emerald.

a primitive root; to fall, in a great variety of applications (intransitive or causative, literal or figurative): be accepted, cast (down, self, (lots), out), cease, die, divide (by lot), (let) fail, (cause to, let, make, ready to) fall (away, down, -en, -ing), fell(-ing), fugitive, have (inheritance), inferior, be judged (by mistake for palal), lay (along), (cause to) lie down, light (down), be (X hast) lost, lying, overthrow, overwhelm, perish, present(-ed, -ing), (make to) rot, slay, smite out, X surely, throw down.
(Aramaic) corresponding to נָפַל: fall (down), have occasion.
or nephel; from נָפַל; something fallen, i.e. an abortion: untimely birth.
a primitive root; to dash to pieces, or scatter: be beaten in sunder, break (in pieces), broken, dash (in pieces), cause to be discharged, dispersed, be overspread, scatter.
from נָפַץ; a storm (as dispersing): scattering.
(Aramaic) a primitive root; to issue; causatively, to bring out: come (go, take) forth (out).
(Aramaic) from נְפַק; an outgo, i.e. expense: expense.
a primitive root; to breathe; passively, to be breathed upon, i.e. (figuratively) refreshed (as if by a current of air): (be) refresh selves (-ed).

from נָפַשׁ; properly, a breathing creature, i.e. animal of (abstractly) vitality; used very widely in a literal, accommodated or figurative sense (bodily or mental): any, appetite, beast, body, breath, creature, X dead(-ly), desire, X (dis-)contented, X fish, ghost, + greedy, he, heart(-y), (hath, X jeopardy of) life (X in jeopardy), lust, man, me, mind, mortally, one, own, person, pleasure, (her-, him-, my-, thy-)self, them (your)-selves, + slay, soul, + tablet, they, thing, (X she) will, X would have it.
for נָ֫פַת; a height: country.
from נוּף in the sense of shaking to pieces; a dripping i.e. of honey (from the comb): honeycomb.
from פָּתַח; opened, i.e. a spring; Nephtoach, a place in Palestine: Neptoah.
from פָּתַל; properly, wrestled; but ued (in the plural) transitively, a struggle: wrestling.
plural of foreign origin, Naphtuchim, an Egyptian tribe: Naptuhim.
from פָּתַל; my wrestling; Naphtali, a son of Jacob, with the tribe descended from him, and its territory: Naphtali.
from נָצַץ; a flower (from its brilliancy); also a hawk (from it flashing speed); --blossom, hawk.
a primitive root; to go away; --flee.

a prim root; to station, in various applications (literally or figuratively): appointed, deputy, erect, establish, X Huzzah (by mistake for a proper name), lay, officer, pillar, present, rear up, set (over, up), settle, sharpen, establish, (make to) stand(-ing, still, up, upright), best state.
passive participle of נָצַב; fixed, i.e. a handle: haft.
(Aramaic) from a root corresponding to נָצַב; fixedness, i.e. firmness: strength.

a primitive root; properly, to go forth, i.e. (by implication) to be expelled, and (consequently) desolate; causatively, to lay waste; also (specifically), to quarrel: be laid waste, runinous, strive (together).
feminine of נֵץ; a blossom; --flower.

a primitive root; properly, to glitter from afar, i.e. to be eminent (as a superintendent, especially of the Temple services and its music); also (as denominative from נֵ֫צַח), to be permanent: excel, chief musician (singer), oversee(-r), set forward.
(Aramaic) corresponding to נָצַח; to become chief: be preferred.

or netsach; from נָצַח; properly, a goal, i.e. the bright object at a distance travelled towards; hence (figuratively), splendor, or (subjectively) truthfulness, or (objectively) confidence; but usually (adverbially), continually (i.e. to the most distant point of view); --alway(-s), constantly, end, (+ n-)ever(more), perpetual, strength, victory.
probably identical with נֵ֫צַח, through the idea of brilliancy of color; juice of the grape (as blood red): blood, strength.
or ntsib; from נָצַב; something stationary, i.e. a prefect, a military post, a statue: garrison, officer, pillar.
the same as נְצִיב; station; Netsib, a place in Palestine: Nezib.
from נָצַח; conspicuous; Netsiach, a Temple- servant: Neziah.
from נָצַר; properly, conservative; but used passively, delivered: preserved.

a primitive root; to snatch away, whether in a good or a bad sense:- X at all, defend, deliver (self), escape, X without fail, part, pluck, preserve, recover, rescue, rid, save, spoil, strip, X surely, take (out).
(Aramaic) corresponding to נָצַל; to extricate: deliver, rescue.
from נֵץ; a blossom: flower.
a primitive root; to glare, i.e. be bright- colored: sparkle.

a primitive root; to guard, in a good sense (to protect, maintain, obey, etc.) or a bad one (to conceal, etc.)besieged, hidden thing, keep(-er, -ing), monument, observe, preserve(-r), subtil, watcher(-man).
from נָצַר in the sense of greenness as a striking color; a shoot; figuratively, a descendant: branch.
(Aramaic) from a root corresponding to נָקָה; clean: pure.

a primitive root; to puncture, literally (to perforate, with more or less violence) or figuratively (to specify, designate, libel): appoint, blaspheme, bore, curse, express, with holes, name, pierce, strike through.
a bezel (for a gem): pipe.
the same as נֶ֫קֶב; dell; Nekeb, a place in Palestine: Nekeb.
from נָקַב; female (from the sexual form): female.
from an unused root meaning to mark (by puncturing or branding); spotted: speckled.
active participle from the same as נָקֹד; a spotter (of sheep or cattle), i.e. the owner or tender (who thus marks them)herdman, sheepmaster.
from the same as נָקֹד; a crumb (as broken to spots); also a biscuit (as pricked): cracknel, mouldy.
feminine of נָקֹד; a boss: stud.

a primitive root; to be (or make) clean (literally or figuratively); by implication (in an adverse sense) to be bare, i.e. extirpated: acquit X at all, X altogether, be blameless, cleanse, (be) clear(-ing), cut off, be desolate, be free, be (hold) guiltless, be (hold) innocent, X by no means, be quit, be (leave) unpunished, X utterly, X wholly.
feminine of נָקֹד (in the figurative sense of marked); distinction; Nekoda, a Temple-servant: Nekoda.
a primitive root; to loathe: weary.
or naqiyi (Joel 4:19; Jonah 1:14); from נָקָה; innocent: blameless, clean, clear, exempted, free, guiltless, innocent, quit.
or niqqayon; from נָקָה; clearness (literally or figuratively): cleanness, innocency.
from an unused root meaning to bore; a cleft: hole.
a primitive root; to grudge, i.e. avenge or punish: avenge(-r, self), punish, revenge (self), X surely, take vengeance.
from נָקַם; revenge: + avenged, quarrel, vengeance.
feminine of נָקָם; avengement, whether the act of the passion: + avenge, revenge(-ing), vengeance.
a primitive root; to feel aversion: be alienated.

a primitive root; to strike with more or less violence (beat, fell, corrode); by implication (of attack) to knock together, i.e. surround or circulate: compass (about, -ing), cut down, destroy, go round (about), inclose, round.
from נָקַף; a threshing (of olives): shaking.
from נָקַף; probably a rope (as encircling): rent.
a primitive root; to bore (penetrate, quarry): dig, pick out, pierce, put (thrust) out.
from נָקַר, a fissure: cleft, clift.
a primitive root; to entrap (with a noose), literally or figuratively: catch (lay a) snare.
(Aramaic) corresponding to נָקַשׁ; but used in the sense of נָקַף; to knock: smote.
the same as נֵר; lamp; Ner, an Israelite: Ner.
of foreign origin; Nergal, a Cuthite deity: Nergal.
from נֵרְגַּל and שַׂר־אֶ֫צֶר; Nergal-Sharetser, the name of two Babylonians: Nergal-sharezer.
from an unused root meaning to roll to pieces; a slanderer: talebearer, whisperer.
of foreign origin; nard, an aromatic: spikenard.
or Neriyahuw; from נֵר and יָהּ; light of Jah; Nerijah, an Israelite: Neriah.

or nacah (Psalm 4 : 6 (7)); a primitive root; to lift, in a great variety of applications, literal and figurative, absol. and rel. (as follows): accept, advance, arise, (able to, (armor), suffer to) bear(-er, up), bring (forth), burn, carry (away), cast, contain, desire, ease, exact, exalt (self), extol, fetch, forgive, furnish, further, give, go on, help, high, hold up, honorable (+ man), lade, lay, lift (self) up, lofty, marry, magnify, X needs, obtain, pardon, raise (up), receive, regard, respect, set (up), spare, stir up, + swear, take (away, up), X utterly, wear, yield.
(Aramaic) corresponding to נָשָׂא: carry away, make insurrection, take.
a primitive root; to lead astray, i.e. (mentally) to delude, or (morally) to seduce: beguile, deceive, X greatly, X utterly.
a primitive root (perhaps identical with נָשָׁא, through the idea of imposition); to lend on interest; by implication, to dun for debt: X debt, exact, giver of usury.
passive participle feminine of נָשָׂא; something taken, i.e. a present: gift.
a primitive root; to blow; by implication, to disperse: (cause to) blow, drive away.
a primitive root; to reach (literally or figuratively): ability, be able, attain (unto), (be able to, can) get, lay at, put, reach, remove, wax rich, X surely, (over-)take (hold of, on, upon).
a primitive root; to forget; figuratively, to neglect; causatively, to remit, remove: forget, deprive, exact.

a primitive root (rather identical with נָשָׁה, in the sense of נָשָׁא); to lend or (by reciprocity) borrow on security or interest: creditor, exact, extortioner, lend, usurer, lend on (taker on) usury.
from נָשָׁה, in the sense of failure; rheumatic or crippled (from the incident to Jacob): which shrank.
or rather nsutah; feminine. passive participle of נָשָׂא; something borne, i.e. a load: carriage.
from נָשָׁה; a debt: debt.
or nasi8; from נָשָׂא; properly, an exalted one, i.e. a king or sheik; also a rising mist: captain, chief, cloud, governor, prince, ruler, vapour.
from נָשָׁה; oblivion; --forgetfulness.
(Aramaic) irregular plural feminine of אֱנָשׁ: women.
from נָשַׁק; a kiss: kiss.
a primitive root; to strike with a sting (as a serpent); figuratively, to oppress with interest on a loan: bite, lend upon usury.
from נָשַׁך; interest on a debt: usury.
for לִשְׁכָּה; a cell: chamber.
a primitive root; to pluck off, i.e. divest, eject or drop: cast (out), drive, loose, put off (out), slip.
a primitive root; properly, to blow away, i.e. destroy: destroy.
(Aramaic) corresponding to נְשָׁמָה; vital breath: breath.
from נָשַׁם; a puff, i.e. wind, angry or vital breath, divine inspiration, intellect. or (concretely) an animal: blast, (that) breath(-eth), inspiration, soul, spirit.
a primitive root; to breeze, i.e. blow up fresh (as the wind): blow.
from נָשַׁף; properly, a breeze, i.e. (by implication) dusk (when the evening breeze prevails): dark, dawning of the day (morning), night, twilight.
a primitive root; to catch fire: burn, kindle.

a primitive root (identical with נָשַׂק, through the idea of fastening up; compare חָזַק, חָשַׁק); to kiss, literally or figuratively (touch); also (as a mode of attachment), to equip with weapons: armed (men), rule, kiss, that touched.
or nesheq; from נָשַׁק; military equipment, i.e. (collectively) arms (offensive or defensive), or (concretely) an arsenal: armed men, armour(-y), battle, harness, weapon.
(Aramaic) corresponding to נָ֫שֶׁר; an eagle: eagle.
from an unused root meaning to lacerate; the eagle (or other large bird of prey): eagle.
a primitive root; properly, to eliminate, i.e. (intransitively) to dry up: fail.
probably of Persian origin; an epistle: letter.
(Aramaic) corresponding to נִשְׁתְּוָן: letter.
a primitive root; to dismember: cut (in pieces), divide, hew in pieces.
from נָתַח; a fragment: part, piece.
or (feminine) nthiybah; or nthibah (Jeremiah 6:16); from an unused root meaning to tramp; a (beaten) track: path((-way)), X travel(-ler), way.
or Nathuwn (Ezra 8:17) (the proper form as passive participle), from נָתַן; one given, i.e. (in the plural only) the Nethinim, or Temple-servants (as given to that duty): Nethinims.
(Aramaic) corresponding to נְתִינִים: Nethinims.
a primitive root; to flow forth (literally or figuratively); by implication, to liquify: drop, gather (together), melt, pour (forth, out).

a primitive root; to give, used with greatest latitude of application (put, make, etc.): add, apply, appoint, ascribe, assign, X avenge, X be ((healed)), bestow, bring (forth, hither), cast, cause, charge, come, commit, consider, count, + cry, deliver (up), direct, distribute, do, X doubtless, X without fail, fasten, frame, X get, give (forth, over, up), grant, hang (up), X have, X indeed, lay (unto charge, up), (give) leave, lend, let (out), + lie, lift up, make, + O that, occupy, offer, ordain, pay, perform, place, pour, print, X pull, put (forth), recompense, render, requite, restore, send (out), set (forth), shew, shoot forth (up), + sing, + slander, strike, (sub-)mit, suffer, X surely, X take, thrust, trade, turn, utter, + weep, + willingly, + withdraw, + would (to) God, yield.
(Aramaic) corresponding to נָתַן; give: bestow, give pay.
from נָתַן; given; Nathan, the name of five Israelites: Nathan.
from נָתַן and אֵל; given of God; Nethanel, the name of ten Israelites: Nethaneel.
or Nthanyahuw; from נָתַן and יָהּ; given of Jah; Nethanjah, the name of four Israelites: Nethaniah.
from נָתַן and מֶ֫לֶך; given of (the) king; Nethan-Melek, an Israelite: Nathan-melech.
a primitive root; to tear up: mar.
for נָתַץ; to tear out: break.
a primitive root; to tear down: beat down, break down (out), cast down, destroy, overthrow, pull down, throw down.
a primitive root; to tear off: break (off), burst, draw (away), lift up, pluck (away, off), pull (out), root out.
from נָתַק; scurf: (dry) scall.
a primitive root; to jump, i.e. be violently agitated; causatively, to terrify, shake off, untie: drive asunder, leap, (let) loose, X make, move, undo.
(Aramaic) corresponding to נָתַר: shake off.
from נָתַר; mineral potash (so called from effervescing with acid): nitre.
a primitive root; to tear away: destroy, forsake, pluck (out, up, by the roots), pull up, root out (up), X utterly.
from an unused root meaning to define; a seah, or certain measure (as determinative) for grain: measure.
from סָאַן; perhaps a military boot (as a protection from mud: battle.
a primitive root; to be miry; used only as denominative from סְאוֹן; to shoe, i.e. (active participle) a soldier shod: warrior.
for סְאָה־; measurement, i.e. moderation: measure.
a primitive root; to quaff to satiety, i.e. become tipsy: drunkard, fill self, Sabean, (wine-)bibber.
of foreign origin; Seba, a son of Cush, and the country settled by him: Seba.
from סָבָא; potation, concretely (wine), or abstractly (carousal): drink, drunken, wine.
patrial from סְבָא; a Sebaite, or inhabitant of Seba: Sabean.

a primitive root; to revolve, surround, or border; used in various applications, literally and figuratively (as follows): bring, cast, fetch, lead, make, walk, X whirl, X round about, be about on every side, apply, avoid, beset (about), besiege, bring again, carry (about), change, cause to come about, X circuit, (fetch a) compass (about, round), drive, environ, X on every side, beset (close, come, compass, go, stand) round about, inclose, remove, return, set, sit down, turn (self) (about, aside, away, back).
from סָבַב; a (providential) turn (of affairs): cause.
or (feminine) cbiybah; from סָבַב; (as noun) a circle, neighbour, or environs; but chiefly (as adverb, with or without preposition) around: (place, round) about, circuit, compass, on every side.
a primitive root; to entwine: fold together, wrap.
from סָבַך; a copse: thicket.
from סָבַך, a copse: thick(-et).
(Aramaic) or sabbka: (Aramaic); from a root corresponding to סָבַך; a lyre: sackbut.
from סָבַך; copse-like; Sibbecai, an Israelite: Sibbecai, Sibbechai.
a primitive root; to carry (literally or figuratively), or (reflexively) be burdensome; specifically, to be gravid: bear, be a burden, carry, strong to labour.
(Aramaic) corresponding to סָבַל; to erect: strongly laid.
from סָבַל; a load (literally or figuratively): burden, charge.
(only in the form cubbal; from סָבַל; a load (figuratively): burden.
from סָבַל; a porter: (to bear, bearer of) burden(-s).
from סֵ֫בֶל; porterage: burden.
for שִׁבֳּלִים; an ear of grain: Sibboleth.
(Aramaic) a primitive root; to bear in mind, i.e. hope: think.
dual from a root corresponding to סְבַר; double hope; Sibrajim, a place in Syria: Sibraim.
or Cabtah; probably of foreign derivation; Sabta or Sabtah, the name of a son of Cush, and the country occupied by his posterity: Sabta, Sabtah.
probably of foreign derivation; Sabteca, the name of a son of Cush, and the region settled by him: Sabtecha, Sabtechah.
a primitive root; to prostrate oneself (in homage): fall down.
(Aramaic) corresponding to סָגַד: worship.
from סָגַר; properly, shut up, i.e. the breast (as inclosing the heart); also gold (as generally shut up safely): caul, gold.
feminine passive participle of an unused root meaning to shut up; wealth (as closely shut up): jewel, peculiar (treasure), proper good, special.
(Aramaic) corresponding to סְגָנִים: governor.
from an unused root meaning to superintend; a prefect of a province: prince, ruler.
a primitive root; to shut up; figuratively, to surrender: close up, deliver (up), give over (up), inclose, X pure, repair, shut (in, self, out, up, up together), stop, X straitly.
(Aramaic) corresponding to סָגַר: shut up.
probably from סָגַר in the sense of sweeping away; a pouring rain: very rainy.
from an unused root meaning to estop; the stocks: stocks.
from an unused root meaning to envelop; a wrapper, i.e. shirt: fine linen, sheet.
from an unused root meaning to scorch; burnt (i.e. volcanic or bituminous) district; Sedom, a place near the Dead SeaSodom.
from an unused root meaning to arrange; order: order.
from an unused root meaning to be round; roundness: round.
from the same as סַ֫הַר; a dungeon (as surrounded by walls): prison.
of foreign derivation; So, an Egyptian king: So.
a primitive root; properly, to flinch, i.e. (by implication) to go back, literally (to retreat) or figuratively (to apostatize): backslider, drive, go back, turn (away, back).
a primitive root (probably rather identical with סוּג through the idea of shrinking from a hedge; compare שׂוּג); to hem in, i.e. bind: set about.
from סָגַר; an inclosure, i.e. cage (for an animal): ward.
from יָסַד; a session, i.e. company of persons (in close deliberation); by implication, intimacy, consultation, a secret: assembly, consel, inward, secret (counsel).
from סוֹד; a confidant; Sodi, an Israelite: Sodi.
from an unused root meaning to wipe away; sweeping; Suach, an Israelite: Suah.
from the same as ס֫וּחַ; something swept away, i.e. filth: torn.
from סוּט; roving; Sotai, one of the Nethinim: Sotai.
a primitive root; properly, to smear over (with oil), i.e. anoint: anoint (self), X at all.
(Aramaic) or cuwmponyah (Aramaic); or ciyphonya: (Dan. 3:10) (Aramaic); of Greek origin; a bagpipe (with a double pipe): dulcimer.
(rather to be written Cvenah; for Cven; i.e to Seven); of Egyptian derivation; Seven, a place in Upper Egypt: Syene.
or cuc; from an unused root meaning to skip (properly, for joy); a horse (as leaping); also a swallow (from its rapid flight): crane, horse((-back, -hoof)). Compare פָּרָשִׁים.
feminine of סוּס; a mare: company of horses.
from סוּס; horse-like; Susi, an Israelite: Susi.
a primitive root; to snatch away, i.e. terminate: consume, have an end, perish, X be utterly.
(Aramaic) corresponding to סוּף; to come to an endconsume, fulfill.
probably of Egyptian origin; a reed, especially the papyrus: flag, Red (sea), weed. Compare סוּף.
for סוּף (by ellipsis of יָם); the Reed (Sea): Red Sea.
from סוּף; a termination:--conclusion, end, hinder participle
(Aramaic) corresponding to סוֹף: end.
from סוּף; a hurricane: Red Sea, storm, tempest, whirlwind, Red sea.

or suwr (Hosea 9:12); a primitive root; to turn off (literal or figurative): be(-head), bring, call back, decline, depart, eschew, get (you), go (aside), X grievous, lay away (by), leave undone, be past, pluck away, put (away, down), rebel, remove (to and fro), revolt, X be sour, take (away, off), turn (aside, away, in), withdraw, be without.
probably passive participle of סוּר; turned off, i.e. deteriorated: degenerate.
the same as סוּר; Sur, a gate of the temple: Sur.
perhaps denominative from שָׁ֫יִת; properly, to prick, i.e. (figuratively) stimulate; by implication, to seduce: entice, move, persuade, provoke, remove, set on, stir up, take away.
probably from the same root as מַסְוֶה; covering, i.e. clothing: clothes.
a primitive root; to trail along: draw (out), tear.
from סָחַב; a rag: cast clout.
a primitive root; to sweep away: scrape.
from סָחָה; refuse (as swept off): offscouring.
a primitive root; to scrape off: sweep (away).
a primitive root; to travel round (specifically as a pedlar); intensively, to palpitate: go about, merchant(-man), occupy with, pant, trade, traffick.
from סָחַר; profit (from trade): merchandise.
from סָחַר; an emporium; abstractly, profit (from trade): mart, merchandise.
from סָחַר: traffic: merchandise.
properly, active participle feminine of סָחַר; something surrounding the person, i.e. a shield: buckler.
similar to סֹחֵרָה; probably a (black) tile (or tessara) for laying borders with: black marble.
or cuwg (Ezek. 22:18); from סוּג in the sense of refuse; scoria: dross.
probably of Persian origin; Sivan, the third Heb. month: Sivan.
or Ciychon; from the same as ס֫וּחַ; tempestuous; Sichon, an Amoritish king: Sihon.
of uncertain derivation; Sin the name of an Egyptian town and (probably) desert adjoining: Sin.
from an otherwise unknown name of a man; a Sinite, or descendant of one of the sons of Canaan: Sinite.
of uncertain derivation; Sinai, mountain of Arabia: Sinai.
plural of an otherwise unknown name; Sinim, a distant Oriental region: Sinim.
of uncertain derivation; Sisera, the name of a Canaanitish king and of one of the Nethinim: Sisera.
or Ciyeahai; from an unused root meaning to converse; congregation; Sia or Siaha, one of the NethinimSia, Siaha.

or (feminine) ciyrah; or cirah (Jeremiah 52:18); from a primitive root meaning to boil up; a pot; also a thorn (as springing up rapidly); by implication, a hook: caldron, fishhook, pan, ((wash-))pot, thorn.
from סָכַך; properly, a thicket of men, i.e. a crowdmultitude.
from סָכַך; a hut (as of entwined boughs); also a laircovert, den, pavilion, tabernacle.
fem of סֹך; a hut or lair: booth, cottage, covert, pavilion, tabernacle, tent.
feminine of סָך; an (idolatrous) booth: tabernacle.
or Cukkoth; plural of סֻכָּה; booths; Succoth, the name of a place in Egypt and of three in PalestineSuccoth.
from סֻכּוֹת and the (irreg.) plural of בַּת; booths of (the) daughters; brothels, i.e. idoalatrous tents for impure purpose: Succoth-benoth.
patrial from an unknown name (perhaps סֹך); a Sukkite, or inhabitant of some place near Egypt (i.e. hut-dwellers)Sukkiims.

or sakak (Exod. 33:22); a primitive root; properly, to entwine as a screen; by implication, to fence in, cover over, (figuratively) protect: cover, defence, defend, hedge in, join together, set, shut up.
from סָכַך; inclosure; Secacah, a place in Palestine: Secacah.
for כָּסַל; to be silly: do (make, play the, turn into) fool(-ish, -ishly, -ishness).
from סָכַל; silliness; concretely and collectively, dolts: folly.
from סָכַל; silly: fool(-ish), sottish.
or sikluwth (Eccl. 1:17); from סָכַל; silliness: folly, foolishness.
a primitive root; to be familiar with; by implication, to minister to, be serviceable to, be customary: acquaint (self), be advantage, X ever, (be, (un-))profit(-able), treasurer, be wont.
probably a denominative from שַׂכִּין; properly, to cut, i.e. damage; also to grow (causatively, make) poor: endanger, impoverish.
a primitive root; to shut up; by implication, to surrender: stop, give over. See also סָגַר, שָׂכַר.
a primitive root to be silent; by implication, to observe quietly: take heed.
from סָלַל; properly, a willow twig (as pendulous), i.e. an osier; but only as woven into a basket: basket.
a primitive root; to suspend in a balance, i.e. weigh: compare.
from סָלַל; an embankment; Silla, a place in Jerusalem: Silla.
a primitive root; probably to leap (with joy), i.e. exult: harden self.
from סָלַד; exultation; Seled, an Israelite: Seled.
a primitive root; to hang up, i.e. weigh, or (figuratively) contemn: tread down (under foot), value.
from סָלָה; suspension (of music), i.e. pause: Selah.
or Calluw; or Caluw; or Callay; from סָלָה; weighed; Sallu or Sallai, the name of two Israelites: Sallai, Sallu, Salu.
or callown; from סָלָה; a prickle (as if pendulous); brier, thorn.
a primitive root; to forgive: forgive, pardon, spare.
from סָלַח; placable: ready to forgive.
from סָלַח; pardon: forgiveness, pardon.
from an unused root. meaning to walk; walking; Salcah, a place East of the Jordan: Salcah, Salchah.
a primitive root; to mound up (especially a turnpike); figurative, to exalt; reflexively, to oppose (as by a dam)cast up, exalt (self), extol, make plain, raise up.
or cowllah; active participle feminine of סָלַל, but used passively; a military mound, i.e. rampart of besiegers: bank, mount.
from סָלַל; a stair-case: ladder.
from סָלָה; a twig (as pendulous): basket.
from an unused root meaning to be lofty; a craggy rock, literally or figuratively (a fortress): (ragged) rock, stone(-ny), strong hold.
the same as סָ֫לַע; Sela, the rock-city of Idumaea: rock, Sela(-h).
from סָ֫לַע and the plural of מַחֲלֹ֫קֶת with the article interposed; rock of the divisions; Sela- ham-Machlekoth, a place in Palestine: Sela-hammalekoth.
apparently from the same as סָ֫לַע in the sense of crushing as with a rock, i.e. consuming; a kind of locust (from its destructiveness): bald locust.
a primitive root; properly, to wrench, i.e. (figuratively) to subvert: overthrow, pervert.
from סָלַף; distortion, i.e. (figuratively) viciousness: perverseness.
(Aramaic) a primitive root; to ascend: come (up).
from an unused root meaning to strip; flour (as chipped off): (fine) flour, meal.
from an unused root meaning to smell sweet; an aromasweet (spice).
of foreign origin; Samgar-Nebo, a Babylonian general: Samgar-nebo.
of uncertain derivation; a vine blossom; used also adverbially, abloom: tender grape.

a primitive root; to prop (literally or figuratively); reflexively, to lean upon or take hold of (in a favorable or unfavorable sense): bear up, establish, (up-)hold, lay, lean, lie hard, put, rest self, set self, stand fast, stay (self), sustain.
from סָמַך and יָהּ; supported of Jah; Semakjah, an Israelite: Semachiah.
or cemel; from an unused root meaning to resemble; a likeness: figure, idol, image.
a primitive root; to designate: appointed.
a primitive root; to be erect, i.e. bristle as hair: stand up, tremble.
from סָמַר; bristling, i.e. shaggy: rough.
from an unused root meaning to prick; thorny; Senaah, a place in Palestine: Senaah, Hassenaah (with the article).
of foreign origin; Sanballat, a Persian satrap of Samaria: Sanballat.
from an unused root meaning to prick; a bramble: bush.
the same s סְנֶה; thorn; Seneh, a crag in Palestine: Seneh.
or Cnu.ah from the same as סְנָאָה; pointed; (used with the article as a proper name) Senuah, the name of two Israelites: Hasenuah (including the art), Senuah.
of uncertain derivation; (in plural) blindness: blindness.
of foreign origin; Sancherib, an Assyrian king: Sennacherib.
from an unused root meaning to be pointed; a twig (as tapering): bough.
feminine of a form of סַנְסִן; a bough; Sansannah, a place in Palestine: Sansannah.
of uncertain derivation; a fin (collectively): fins.
from the same as סוּס; a moth (from the agility of the fly): moth.
of uncertain derivation; Sismai, an Israelite: Sisamai.
a primitive root; to support (mostly figurative): comfort, establish, hold up, refresh self, strengthen, be upholden.
(Aramaic) corresponding to סָעַד; to aid: helping.
a primitive root; to rush: storm.
from סָעַף; a fissure (of rocks); also a bough (as subdivided): (outmost) branch, clift, top.
a primitive root; properly, to divide up; but used only as denominative from סְעִיף, to disbranch (a tree): top.
or samiph; from סָעַף; divided (in mind), i.e. (abstractly) a sentiment: opinion.
from סָעַף; divided (in mind), i.e. (concretely) a skeptic: thought.
feminine of סְעִיף; a twig: bough, branch. Compare סַרְעַפֹּת.

a primitive root; to rush upon; by implication, to toss (transitive or intransitive, literal or figurative): be (toss with) tempest(-uous), be sore, troubled, come out as a (drive with the, scatter with a) whirlwind.
or (feminine) ctarah; from סָעַר; a hurricane: storm(-y), tempest, whirlwind.
from סָפַף, in its original sense of containing; a vestibule (as a limit); also a dish (for holding blood or wine): bason, bowl, cup, door (post), gate, post, threshold.
the same as סַף; Saph, a Philistine: Saph. Compare סִפַּי.
a primitive root; properly, to tear the hair and beat the breasts (as Orientals do in grief); generally to lament; by implication, to wail: lament, mourn(-er), wail.

a primitive root; properly, to scrape (literally, to shave; but usually figuratively) together (i.e. to accumulate or increase) or away (i.e. to scatter, remove, or ruin; intransitively, to perish): add, augment, consume, destroy, heap, join, perish, put.
or saphach (Isaiah 3:17); a primitive root; properly, to scrape out, but in certain peculiar senses (of removal or association): abiding, gather together, cleave, smite with the scab.
from סָפַח; the mange (as making the hair fall off): scab.
from סַף; bason-like; Sippai, a Philistine: Sippai. Compare סַף.
from סָפַח; something (spontaneously) falling off, i.e. a self-sown crop; figuratively, a freshet: (such) things as (which) grow (of themselves), which groweth of its own accord (itself).
from סָפַן; a (sea-going) vessel (as ceiled with a deck): ship.
from סָפַר; a gem (perhaps used for scratching other substances), probably the sapphire: sapphire.
from an unused root meaning to depress; a basin (as deepened out): bowl, dish.
a primitive root; to hide by covering; specifically, to roof (passive participle as noun, a roof) or wainscot; figuratively, to reserve: cieled, cover, seated.
from סָפַן; a wainscot: cieling.
a primitive root; properly, to snatch away, i.e. terminate; but used only as denominative from סַף (in the sense of a vestibule), to wait at the threshold: be a doorkeeper.

or saphaq (1 Kings 20:10; Job 27:23; Isaiah 2:6); a primitive root; to clap the hands (in token of compact, derision, grief, indignation, or punishment); by implication of satisfaction, to be enough; by implication of excess, to vomit: clap, smite, strike, suffice, wallow.
or sepheq (Job 20:22; 36:18); from סָפַק; chastisement; also satiety: stroke, sufficiency.

a primitive root; properly, to score with a mark as a tally or record, i.e. (by implication) to inscribe, and also to enumerate; intensively, to recount, i.e. celebrate: commune, (ac-)count; declare, number, + penknife, reckon, scribe, shew forth, speak, talk, tell (out), writer.
(Aramaic) from a root corresponding to סָפַר; a book: book, roll.
from סָפַר; a census: numbering.
the same as סְפָר; Sephar, a place in Arabia: Sephar.
or (feminine) ciphrah (Psa. 56:8 (9)); from סָפַר; properly, writing (the art or a document); by implication, a book: bill, book, evidence, X learn(-ed) (-ing), letter, register, scroll.
(Aramaic) from the same as סְפַר; a scribe (secular or sacred): scribe.
of foreign derivation; Sepharad, a region of Assyria: Sepharad.
from סָפַר; a numeration: number.
patrial from סְפַרְוַיִם; a Sepharvite or inhabitant of Sepharvain: Sepharvite.
(dual)
feminine active participle of סָפַר; a scribe (properly, female); Sophereth, a temple servant: Sophereth.
a primitive root; properly, to be weighty; but used only in the sense of lapidation or its contrary (as if a delapidation): (cast, gather out, throw) stone(-s), X surely.
contracted from סָרַר; peevish: heavy, sad.
from an unused root meaning to sting; a thistle: brier.
(Aramaic) of uncertain derivation; a cloak: coat.
of foreign derivation; Sargon, an Assyrian king: Sargon.
from a primitive root meaning to tremble; trembling; Sered, an Israelite: Sered.
patron from סֶ֫רֶד; a Seredite (collectively) or descendants of Sered: Sardites.
from סוּר; departure; Sirah, a cistern so-called: Sirah. See also סִיר.
from סוּר; apostasy, crime; figuratively, remission: X continual, rebellion, revolt((-ed)), turn away, wrong.
a primitive root; to extend (even to excess): exceeding, hand, spread, stretch self, banish.
from סָרַח; a redundancy: remnant.
for שִׁרְיוֹן; a coat of mail: brigandine.

or caric; from an unused root meaning to castrate; a eunuch; by implication, valet (especially of the female apartments), and thus, a minister of state: chamberlain, eunuch, officer. Compare רַב־סָרִיס.
(Aramaic) of foreign origin; an emir: president.
from an unused root of uncertain meaning; an axle; figuratively, a peer: lord, plate.
for סְעַפּוֹת; a twig: bough.
a primitive root; to cremate, i.e. to be (near) of kin (such being privileged to kindle the pyre): burn.
from סָרַף; a nettle (as stinging like a burn): brier.
a primitive root; to turn away, i.e. (morally) be refractory: X away, backsliding, rebellious, revolter(-ing), slide back, stubborn, withdrew.
from an unused root meaning to hide; winter (as the dark season): winter.
from סָתַר; hidden; Sethur, an Israelite: Sethur.
or satham (Numbers 24:15); a primitive root; to stop up; by implication, to repair; figuratively, to keep secret: closed up, hidden, secret, shut out (up), stop.
a primitive root; to hide (by covering), literally or figuratively: be absent, keep close, conceal, hide (self), (keep) secret, X surely.
(Aramaic) corresponding to סָתַר; to conceal; figuratively, to demolish: destroy, secret thing.

or (feminine) cithrah (Deut. 32:38),; from סָתַר; a cover (in a good or a bad, a literal or a figurative sense): backbiting, covering, covert, X disguise(-th), hiding place, privily, protection, secret(-ly, place).
from סָ֫תֶר; protective; Sithri, an Israelite,: Zithri.

(masculine and feminine); from עוּב; properly, an envelope, i.e. darkness (or density, 2 Chron. 4:17); specifically, a (scud) cloud; also a copse: clay, (thick) cloud, X thick, thicket. Compare עֲבִי.
or sob; from an unused root meaning to cover; properly, equivalent to עָב; but used only as an architectural term, an architrave (as shading the pillars): thick (beam, plant).

a primitive root; to work (in any sense); by implication, to serve, till, (causatively) enslave, etc.:--X be, keep in bondage, be bondmen, bond-service, compel, do, dress, ear, execute, + husbandman, keep, labour(-ing man, bring to pass, (cause to, make to) serve(-ing, self), (be, become) servant(-s), do (use) service, till(-er), transgress (from margin), (set a) work, be wrought, worshipper,
(Aramaic) corresponding to עָבַד; to do, make, prepare, keep, etc.: X cut, do, execute, go on, make, move, work.
(Aramaic) from עֲבַד; a servant: servant.
from עָבַד; a servant: X bondage, bondman, (bond-)servant, (man-)servant.
the same as עָ֫בֶד; Ebed, the name of two Israelites: Ebed.
from עָבַד; a deed: work.
from עָבַד; work; Abda, the name of two Israelites:--Abda
from the active participle of עָבַד and אֱדוֹם; worker of Edom; Obed-Edom, the name of five Israelites: Obed-edom.
from עָבַד and אֵל; serving God; Abdeel, an Israelite: Abdeel. Compare עַבְדִּיאֵל.
or mabowdah; from עָבַד; work of any kind: act, bondage, + bondservant, effect, labour, ministering(-try), office, service(-ile, -itude), tillage, use, work, X wrought.
passive participle of עָבַד; something wrought, i.e. (concretely) service: household, store of servants.
from עָבַד; servitude; Abdon, the name of a place in Palestine and of four Israelites: Abdon. Compare עֶבְרֹן.
from עָבַד; servitude: bondage.
from עָבַד; serviceable; Abdi, the name of two Israelites: Abdi.
from עָ֫בֶד and אֵל; servant of God; Abdiel, an Israelite: Abdiel. Compare עַבְדְּאֵל.
or Obadyahuw; active participle of עָבַד and יָהּ; serving Jah; Obadjah, the name of thirteen Israelites: Obadiah.
from עָ֫בֶד and מֶ֫לֶך; servant of a king; Ebed-Melek, a eunuch of Zedekeah: Ebed-melech.
the same as עֲבֵד נְגוֹ; Abed-Nego, the Babylonian name of one of Daniel's companions: Abed-nego.
(Aramaic) of foreign origin; Abed-Nego, the name of Azariah: Abed-nego.
a primitive root; to be dense: be (grow) thick(-er).
or rabot; from עָבַט; a pawn: pledge.
or rabur; passive participle of עָבַר; properly, crossed, i.e. (abstractly) transit; used only adverbially, on account of, in order that: because of, for (...'s sake), (intent) that, to.
the same as עֲבוּר; passed, i.e. kept over; used only of stored grain: old corn.
a primitive root; to pawn; causatively, to lend (on security); figuratively, to entangle: borrow, break (ranks), fetch (a pledge), lend, X surely.
from עָבַט; something pledged, i.e. (collectively) pawned goods: thick clay (by a false etym.).
or mobiy; from עָבָה; density, i.e. depth or width: thick(-ness). Compare עָב.
(Aramaic) from עֲבַד; labor or business: affairs, service, work.

a primitive root; to cross over; used very widely of any transition (literal or figurative; transitive, intransitive, intensive, causative); specifically, to cover (in copulation): alienate, alter, X at all, beyond, bring (over, through), carry over, (over-)come (on, over), conduct (over), convey over, current, deliver, do away, enter, escape, fail, gender, get over, (make) go (away, beyond, by, forth, his way, in, on, over, through), have away (more), lay, meddle, overrun, make partition, (cause to, give, make to, over) pass(-age, along, away, beyond, by, -enger, on, out, over, through), (cause to, make) + proclaim(-amation), perish, provoke to anger, put away, rage, + raiser of taxes, remove, send over, set apart, + shave, cause to (make) sound, X speedily, X sweet smelling, take (away), (make to) transgress(-or), translate, turn away, (way-)faring man, be wrath.
(Aramaic) corresponding to עֵ֫בֶר: beyond, this side.
