feminine passive participle of פָּקַד; visitation (in many senses, chiefly official): account, (that have the) charge, custody, that which...laid up, numbers, office(-r), ordering, oversight, + prison, reckoning, visitation.
from פָּקַד; a deposit: that which was delivered (to keep), store.
from פָּקִיד; supervision: ward.
from פָּקַד; punishment; Pekod, a symbolic name for Bab.: Pekod.
or piqqud; from פָּקַד; properly, appointed, i.e. a mandate (of God; plural only, collectively, for the Law): commandment, precept, statute.
a primitive root; to open (the senses, especially the eyes); figuratively, to be observant: open.
from פָּקַח; watch; Pekach, an Israelite king: Pekah.
from פָּקַח; clear-sighted; figuratively, intelligent: seeing, wise.
from פָּקַח and יָהּ; Jah has observed; Pekachjah, an Israelite king: Pekahiah.
from פָּקַח redoubled; opening (of a dungeon), i.e. jail-delivery (figuratively, salvation for sin): opening of the prison.
from פָּקַד; a superintendent (civil, military or religious): which had the charge, governor, office, overseer, (that) was set.
from an unused root meaning to burst; only used as an architectural term of an ornament similar to פַּקֻּעֹת, a semi-globe: knop.
from the same as פְּקָעִים; the wild cucumber (from splitting open to shed its seeds): gourd.
or par; from פָּרַר; a bullock (apparently as breaking forth in wild strength, or perhaps as dividing the hoof): (+ young) bull(-ock), calf, ox.
a primitive root; to bear fruit: be fruitful.
or pereh (Jeremiah 2:24); from פָּרָא in the secondary sense of running wild; the onager: wild (ass).
from פֶּ֫רֶא; wildly; Piram, a Canaanite: Piram.
or Parvar; of foreign origin; Parbar or Parvar, a quarter of Jerusalem: Parbar, suburb.
a primitive root; to break through, i.e. spread or separate (oneself): disperse, divide, be out of joint, part, scatter (abroad), separate (self), sever self, stretch, sunder.
from פָּרַד; a mule (perhaps from his lonely habits): mule.
feminine of פֶּ֫רֶד; a she-mule: mule.
feminine passive participle of פָּרַד; something separated, i.e. a kernel: seed.
of foreign origin; a park: forest, orchard.
a primitive root; to bear fruit (literally or figuratively): bear, bring forth (fruit), (be, cause to be, make) fruitful, grow, increase.
feminine of פָּר; a heifer: cow, heifer, kine.
the same as פָּרָה; Parah, a place in Palestine: Parah.
from פּוּר; a hole (as broken, i.e. dug): + mole. Compare חֲפֹר פֵּרוֹת.
for פֻּארָה; foliage; Purah, an Israelite: Phurah.
or Priyda; from פָּרַד; dispersion; Peruda or Perida, one of "Solomon's servants": Perida, Peruda.
passive participle of פָּרַח; blossomed; Paruach, an Israelite: Paruah.
of foreign origin; Parvajim, an Oriental region: Parvaim.
passive participle of פָּרַר in the sense of spreading out (compare פָּרַח); a skillet (as flat or deep): pan, pot.
from an unused root meaning to separate, i.e. decide; a chieftain: village.
from the same as פְּרָזִים; an open country: (unwalled) town (without walls), unwalled village.
from the same as פְּרָזִים; magistracy, i.e. leadership (also concretely, chieftains): village.
or prowziy; from פְּרָזוֹת; a rustic: village.
for פְּרָזִי; inhabitant of the open country; a Perizzite, one of the Canaanitish tribes: Perizzite.
(Aramaic) corresponding to בַּרְזֶל; iron: iron.

a primitive root; to break forth as a bud, i.e. bloom; generally, to spread; specifically, to fly (as extending the wings); figuratively, to flourish: X abroad, X abundantly, blossom, break forth (out), bud, flourish, make fly, grow, spread, spring (up).
from פָּרַח; a calyx (natural or artificial); generally, bloom: blossom, bud, flower.
from פָּרַח; progeny, i.e. a brood: youth.
a primitive root; to scatter words, i.e. prate (or hum): chant.
from פָּרַט; a stray or single berry: grape.
from פָּרָה; fruit (literally or figuratively): bough, ((first-)) fruit((-ful)), reward.
from פָּרַץ; violent, i.e. a tyrant: destroyer, ravenous, robber.
from an unused root meaning to break apart; fracture, i.e. severity: cruelty, rigour.
feminine active participle of the same as פָּ֫רֶך; a separatrix, i.e. (the sacred) screen: vail.
a primitive root; to tear: rend.
of Persian origin; Parmashta, a son of Haman: Parmasta.
of uncertain derivation; Parnak, an Israelite: Parnach.
a primitive root; to break in pieces, i.e. (usually without violence) to split, distribute: deal, divide, have hoofs, part, tear.
(Aramaic) corresponding to פָּרַס; to split up: divide, (U-)pharsin.
from פָּרַס; a claw; also a kind of eagle: claw, ossifrage.
of foreign origin; Paras (i.e. Persia), an Eastern country, including its inhabitants: Persia, Persians.
(Aramaic) corresponding to פָּרָס: Persia, Persians.
feminine of פֶּ֫רֶס; a claw or split hoof: claw, (cloven-)footed, hoof.
patrial from פָּרָס; a Parsite (i.e. Persian), or inhabitant of Peres: Persian.
(Aramaic) corresponding to פָּרְסִי: Persian.
a primitive root; to loosen; by implication, to expose, dismiss; figuratively, absolve, begin: avenge, avoid, bare, go back, let, (make) naked, set at nought, perish, refuse, uncover.
from פָּרַע; the hair (as dishevelled): locks.
feminine of פֶּ֫רַע (in the sense of beginning); leadership (plural concretely, leaders): + avenging, revenge.
of Egyptian derivation; Paroh, a general title of Egyptian kings: Pharaoh.
of Egyptian derivation; Paroh- Chophra, an Egyptian king: Pharaoh-hophra.
or Parpoh Nkow; of Egyptian derivation; Paroh-Nekoh (or -Neko), an Egyptian king: Pharaoh-necho, Pharaoh-nechoh.
probably from פָּרַע and עָשׁ; a flea (as the isolated insect): flea.
the same as פַּרְעֹשׁ; Parosh, the name of our Israelite: Parosh, Pharosh.
from פְּרָעוֹת; chieftaincy; Pirathon, a place in Palestine: Pirathon.
or Pirathoniy; patrial from פִּרְעָתוֹן; a Pirathonite or inhabitant of Pirathon: Pirathonite.
probably from פָּרַר in the sense of rushing; rapid; Parpar, a river of Syria: Pharpar.

a primitive root; to break out (in many applications, direct and indirect, literal and figurative): X abroad, (make a) breach, break (away, down, -er, forth, in, up), burst out, come (spread) abroad, compel, disperse, grow, increase, open, press, scatter, urge.
from פָּרַץ; a break (literally or figuratively): breach, breaking forth (in), X forth, gap.
the same as פָּ֫רֶץ; Perets, the name of two Israelites: Perez, Pharez.
patronymically from פָּ֫רֶץ; a Partsite (collectively) or descendants of Perets: Pharzites.
plural of פָּ֫רֶץ; breaks; Peratsim, a mountain in Palestine: Perazim.
from פָּ֫רֶץ and עֻזָּה; break of Uzza; Perets-Uzza, a place in Palestine: Perez-uzza.
a primitive root; to break off or crunch; figuratively, to deliver: break (off), deliver, redeem, rend (in pieces), tear in pieces.
(Aramaic) corresponding to פָּרַק; to discontinue: break off.
from פָּרַק; rapine; also a fork (in roads): crossway, robbery.
from פָּרַק; soup (as full of crumbed meat): broth. See also מַרְפֵּא.

a primitive root; to break up (usually figuratively, i.e. to violate, frustrate: X any ways, break (asunder), cast off, cause to cease, X clean, defeat, disannul, disappoint, dissolve, divide, make of none effect, fail, frustrate, bring (come) to nought, X utterly, make void.
a primitive root; to break apart, disperse, etc.: break, chop in pieces, lay open, scatter, spread (abroad, forth, selves, out), stretch (forth, out).
a primitive root; to separate, literally (to disperse) or figuratively (to specify); also (by implication) to woundscatter, declare, distinctly, shew, sting.
(Aramaic) corresponding to פָּרַשׁ; to specify: distinctly.
from פָּרַשׁ; excrement (as eliminated): dung.
the same as פֶּ֫רֶשׁ; Peresh, an Israelite: Peresh.
from פָּרַשׁ; a steed (as stretched out to a vehicle, not single nor for mounting (compare סוּס)); also (by implication) a driver (in a chariot), i.e. (collectively) cavalry: horseman.
or pathshegen; of foreign origin; a transcript: copy.
(Aramaic) corresponding to פַּרְשֶׁ֫גֶן: copy.
perhaps by compounding פָּרַשׁ and פָּרַד (in the sense of straddling) (compare פַּרְשֵׁז); the crotch (or anus): dirt.
from פָּרַשׁ; exposition: declaration, sum.
a root apparently formed by compounding פָּרַשׁ and that of פְּרָזִים (compare פַּרְשְׁדֹ֫נָה); to expand: spread.
of Persian origin; Parshandatha, a son of Haman: Parshandatha.
from an unused root meaning to break forth; rushing; Perath (i.e. Euphrates), a river of the East: Euphrates.
of Persian origin; a grandee: (most) noble, prince.
probably from an unused root meaning to disintegrate; stupidity (as a result of grossness or of degeneracy): extremity.
a primitive root; to spread: spread.
a primitive root; to tear in pieces: pull in pieces.
probably from פָּשַׁח; liberation; Pashchur, the name of four Israelites: Pashur.

a primitive root; to spread out (i.e. deploy in hostile array); by analogy, to strip (i.e. unclothe, plunder, flay, etc.): fall upon, flay, invade, make an invasion, pull off, put off, make a road, run upon, rush, set, spoil, spread selves (abroad), strip (off, self).
a primitive root; to stride (from spreading the legs), i.e. rush upon: go.
a primitive root (identical with פָּשַׂע through the idea of expansion); to break away (from just authority), i.e. trespass, apostatize, quarrel: offend, rebel, revolt, transgress(-ion, -or).
from פָּשַׂע; a stride: step.
from פָּשַׁע; a revolt (national, moral or religious): rebellion, sin, transgression, trespass.
a primitive root; to dispart (the feet or lips), i.e. become licentious: open (wide).
(Aramaic) corresponding to פָּתַר; to interpret: make (interpretations), interpreting.
(Aramaic) from פְּשַׁר; an interpretation: interpretation.
corresponding to פְּשַׁר: interpretation.
from the same as פַּשׁ as in the sense of comminuting; linen (i.e. the thread, as carded): flax, linen.
feminine of פִּשְׁתִּי; flax; by implication, a wick: flax, tow.
from פָּתַת; a bit: meat, morsel, piece.
or pothah (Ezek. 13:19); from an unused root meaning to open; a hole, i.e. hinge or the female pudenda:--hinge, secret participle
or pith.om; from פֶּ֫תַע; instantly: straightway, sudden(-ly).
of Persian origin; a dainty: portion (provision) of meat.
of Persian origin; a (judicial) sentence: decree, sentence.
(Aramaic) corresponding to פִּתְגָם; a word, answer, letter or decree: answer, letter, matter, word.

a primitive root; to open, i.e. be (causatively, make) roomy; usually figuratively (in a mental or moral sense) to be (causatively, make) simple or (in a sinister way) delude: allure, deceive, enlarge, entice, flatter, persuade, silly (one).
from פָּתָה and אֵל; enlarged of God; Pethuel, an Israelite: Pethuel.
or pittuach; passive participle of פָּתַח; sculpture (in low or high relief or even intaglio): carved (work) (are, en-)grave(-ing, -n).
of foreign origin; Pethor, a place in Mesopotamia: Pethor.

a primitive root; to open wide (literally or figuratively); specifically, to loosen, begin, plough, carve: appear, break forth, draw (out), let go free, (en-)grave(-n), loose (self), (be, be set) open(-ing), put off, ungird, unstop, have vent.
(Aramaic) corresponding to פָּתַח; to open: open.
from פָּתַח; an opening (literally), i.e. door (gate) or entrance way: door, entering (in), entrance (-ry), gate, opening, place.
from פָּתַח; opening (figuratively) i.e. disclosure: entrance.
from פָּתַח; something opened, i.e. a drawn sword: drawn sword.
from פָּתַח; opening (the act): open(-ing).
from פָּתַח and יָהּ; Jah has opened; Pethachjah, the name of four Israelites: Pethakiah.
or pethiy; or pthaeiy; from פָּתָה; silly (i.e. seducible): foolish, simple(-icity, one).
(Aramaic) from a root corresponding to פָּתָה; open, i.e. (as noun) width: breadth.
of uncertain derivation; probably a figured mantle for holidays: stomacher.
from פֶּ֫תִי; silliness (i.e. seducibility): simple.
from פָּתַל; twine: bound, bracelet, lace, line, ribband, thread, wire.
a primitive root; to twine, i.e. (literally) to struggle or (figuratively) be (morally) tortuous: (shew self) froward, shew self unsavoury, wrestle.
from פָּתַל; tortuous (i.e. crafty): crooked.
of Egyptian derivation; Pithom, a place in Egypt: Pithom.
from an unused root meaning to twist; an asp (from its contortions): adder.

from an unused root meaning to open (the eyes); a wink, i.e. moment (compare פִּתְאוֹם) (used only (with or without preposition) adverbially, quickly or unexpectedly): at an instant, suddenly, X very.
a primitive root; to open up, i.e. (figuratively) interpret (a dream): interpret(-ation, -er).
or pithron; from פָּתַר; interpretation (of a dream): interpretation.
of Egyptian derivation; Pathros, a part of Egypt: Pathros.
patrial from פַּתְרוֹס; a Pathrusite, or inhabitant of Pathros: Pathrusim.
a primitive root; to open, i.e. break:--participle
from יָצָא; issue, i.e. (human) excrement: that (which) cometh from (out).
from an unused root meaning to be slender; the lotus tree: shady tree.

or tsaown (Psalm 144:13); from an unused root meaning to migrate; a collective name for a flock (of sheep or goats); also figuratively (of men): (small) cattle, flock (+ -s), lamb (+ -s), sheep((-cote, -fold, -shearer, -herds)).
from the same as צֹאן used denominatively; sheep pasture; Zaanan, a place in Palestine: Zaanan.
from יָצָא; issue, i.e. produce, children: that which cometh forth (out), offspring.
from an unused root meaning to establish; a palanquin or canopy (as a fixture); also a species of lizard (probably as clinging fast): covered, litter, tortoise.
a primitive root; to mass (an army or servants): assemble, fight, perform, muster, wait upon, war.
(Aramaic) corresponding to פִּתְרוֹן in the figurative sense of summoning one's wishes; to please: will, would.

or (feminine) tsbadah; from צָבָא; a mass of persons (or figuratively, things), especially reg. organized for war (an army); by implication, a campaign, literally or figuratively (specifically, hardship, worship): appointed time, (+) army, (+) battle, company, host, service, soldiers, waiting upon, war(-fare).
or (more correctly) Tsbiyiym; or Tsbiyim; plural of צֶ֫בִי; gazelles; Tseboim or Tsebijim, a place in Palestine: Zeboiim, Zeboim.
feminine active participle of the same as צָב; the canopier (with the article); Tsobebah, an Israelitess: Zobebah.
a primitive root; to amass, i.e. grow turgid; specifically, to array an army against: fight swell.
from צָבָה; turgid: swell.
(Aramaic) from צְבָא; properly, will; concretely, an affair (as a matter of determination): purpose.
passive participle of the same as צֶ֫בַע; dyed (in stripes), i.e. the hyena: speckled.
a primitive root; to grasp, i.e. hand out: reach.
from צָבָה in the sense of prominence; splendor (as conspicuous); also a gazelle (as beautiful): beautiful(-ty), glorious (-ry), goodly, pleasant, roe(-buck).
for צִבְיָה; Tsibja, an Israelite: Zibia.
for צְבִיָּה; Tsibjah, an Israelitess: Zibiah.
feminine of צֶ֫בִי; a female gazelle: roe.
(Aramaic) a root corresponding to that of צֶ֫בַע; to dip: wet.
from an unused root meaning to dip (into coloring fluid); a dye: divers, colours.
from the same as צֶ֫בַע; variegated; Tsibon, an Idumaean: Zibeon.
plural of צָב֫וּעַ; hyenas; Tseboim, a place in Palestine: Zeboim.
a primitive root; to aggregate: gather (together), heap (up), lay up.
from פַּרְעֹשׁ; a pile: heap.
from an unused root apparently meaning to grip; a lock of stalks: handful.
contr. from an unused root meaning to sidle off; a side; figuratively, an adversary: (be-)side.
(Aramaic) corresponding to צַד; used adverbially (with preposition) at or upon the side of: against, concerning.
(Aramaic) from an unused root corresponding to צָדָה in the sense of intentness; a (sinister) design: true.
from the same as צַד; a siding; Tsedad, a place near Palestine: Zedad.
a primitive root; to chase; by implication, to desolate: destroy, hunt, lie in wait.
from צָדַק; just; Tsadok, the name of eight or nine Israelites: Zadok.
from צָדָה; design (compare הַצְדָּא): lying in wait.
plural of צַד; sides; Tsiddim (with the article), a place in Palestine: Ziddim.
from צָדַק; just: just, lawful, righteous (man).
a primitive root; to be (causatively, make) right (in a moral or forensic sense): cleanse, clear self, (be, do) just(-ice, -ify, -ify self), (be turn to) righteous(-ness).
from צָדַק; the right (natural, moral or legal); also (abstractly) equity or (figuratively) prosperity: X even, (X that which is altogether) just(-ice), ((un-))right(-eous) (cause, -ly, - ness).
(Aramaic) corresponding to צְדָקָה; beneficencerighteousness.
from צָדַק; rightness (abstractly), subjectively (rectitude), objectively (justice), morally (virtue) or figuratively (prosperity): justice, moderately, right(-eous) (act, -ly, -ness).
or Tsidqiyahuw; from צֶ֫דֶק and יָהּ; right of Jah; Tsidkijah, the name of six Israelites: Zedekiah, Zidkijah.
a primitive root; to glitter, i.e. be golden in color: X fine.
from צָהַב; golden in color: yellow.
a prim root; to gleam, i.e. (figuratively) be cheerful; by transf. to sound clear (of various animal or human expressions): bellow, cry aloud (out), lift up, neigh, rejoice, make to shine, shout.
a primitive root; to glisten; used only as denominative from יִצְהָר, to press out oil: make oil.
from צָהַר; a light (i.e. window): dual double light, i.e. noon: midday, noon(-day, -tide), window.
or tsav; from צָוָה; an injunction: commandment, precept.
or tsov; from an unused root meaning to issue; soiled (as if excrementitious): filthy.
or tsovah : feminine of צוֹאּים; excrement; generally, dirt; figuratively, pollution: dung, filth(-iness). Marg. for חַרְאֵי.
(Aramaic) corresponding to צַוָּר: neck.

or tsavvar (Nehemiah 3:5); or tsavvaron (Song of Solomon 4:9); or (feminine) tsavva.rah (Micah 2:3); intensively from צוּר in the sense of binding; the back of the neck (as that on which burdens are bound): neck.
or Tsowbah; or Tsobah; from an unused root meaning to station; a station; Zoba or Zobah, a region of Syria: Zoba, Zobah.
a primitive root; to lie alongside (i.e. in wait); by implication, to catch an animal (figuratively, men); (denominative from צָ֫יִד) to victual (for a journey): chase, hunt, sore, take (provision).
a primitive root; (intensively) to constitute, enjoin: appoint, (for-)bid, (give a) charge, (give a, give in, send with) command(-er, -ment), send a messenger, put, (set) in order.
a primitive root; to screech (exultingly): shout.
from צָוַח; a screech (of anguish): cry(-ing).
from an unused root meaning to sink: an abyss (of the sea): deep.
a primitive root; to cover over (the mouth), i.e. to fast: X at all, fast.
or tsom; from from צוּם; a fast: fast(-ing).
from צָעַר; small; Tsuar, an Israelite: Zuar.
a primitive root; to overflow: (make to over-)flow, swim.
from צוּף; comb of honey (from dripping): honeycomb.
or Tsowphay; or Tsiyph; from צוּף; honey-comb; Tsuph or Tsophai or Tsiph, the name of an Israelite and of a place in Palestine: Zophai, Zuph.
from an unused root meaning to expand, breadth; Tsophach, an Israelite: Zophah.
from צָפַר; departing; Tsophar, a friend of Job: Zophar.
a primitive root; to twinkle, i.e. glance; by analogy, to blossom (figuratively, flourish): bloom, blossom, flourish, shew self.
a primitive root; to compress, i.e. (figuratively) oppress, distress: constrain, distress, lie sore, (op-)press(-or), straiten.
a primitive root (identical with צוּק through the idea of narrowness (of orifice)); to pour out, i.e. (figuratively) smelt, utter: be molten, pour.
or (feminine) tsuwqah; from צוּק; a strait, i.e. (figuratively) distress: anguish, X troublous.

a primitive root; to cramp, i.e. confine (in many applications, literally and figuratively, formative or hostile): adversary, assault, beset, besiege, bind (up), cast, distress, fashion, fortify, inclose, lay siege, put up in bags.

or tsur; from צוּר; properly, a cliff (or sharp rock, as compressed); generally, a rock or boulder; figuratively, a refuge; also an edge (as precipitous): edge, X (mighty) God (one), rock, X sharp, stone, X strength, X strong. See also בֵּית צוּר.
the same as צוּר; rock; Tsur, the name of a Midianite and of an Israelite: Zur.
feminine of צוּר; a rock (Job 28:10); also a form (as if pressed out): form, rock.
from צוּר and אֵל; rock of God; Tsuriel, an Israelite: Zuriel.
from צוּר and שַׁדָּי; rock of (the) Almighty; Tsurishaddai, an Israelite: Zurishaddai.
a primitive root; to blaze: burn.
from צָחַח; dazzling, i.e. sunny, bright, (figuratively) evident: clear, dry, plainly, white.
from an unused root meaning to glow; parched: dried up.
a primitive root; to glare, i.e. be dazzling white: be whiter.
from צָחַח; glaring, i.e. exposed to the bright sun: higher place, top.
feminine of צְחִ֫יחַ; a parched region, i.e. the desert: dry land.
from צְחִ֫יחַ; bare spot, i.e. in the glaring sun: higher place.
from an unused root meaning to putrefy; stench: ill savour.
from צָחַח; a dry place, i.e. desert: drought.
a primitive root; to laugh outright (in merriment or scorn); by implication, to sport: laugh, mock, play, make sport.
from צָחַק; laughter (in pleasure or derision): laugh(-ed to scorn).
from an unused root meaning to dazzle; sheen, i.e. whiteness: white.
from the same as צָ֫חַר; whiteness; Tsochar, the name of a Hittite and of an Israelite: Zohar. Compare יִצְחָר.
from the same as צָ֫חַר; white: white.
from צָוָה; a ship (as a fixture): ship.
from the same as צוֹבָה; station; Tsiba, an Israelite: Ziba.

from a form of צוּד and meaning the same; the chase; also game (thus taken); (generally) lunch (especially for a journey): X catcheth, food, X hunter, (that which he took in) hunting, venison, victuals.
from the same as צָ֫יִד; a huntsman: hunter.
or tsedah; feminine of צָ֫יִד; food: meat, provision, venison, victuals.
or Tsiydon; from צוּד in the sense of catching fish; fishery; Tsidon, the name of a son of Canaan, and of a place in Palestine: Sidon, Zidon.
patrial from צִידוֹן; a Tsidonian or inhabitant of Tsidon: Sidonian, of Sidon, Zidonian.
from an unused root meaning to parch; aridity; concretely, a desert: barren, drought, dry (land, place), solitary place, wilderness.
from the same as צִיָּה; a desert: dry place.
from the same as צִיָּה in the sense of conspicuousness (compare נָצַח); a monumental or guiding pillar: sign, title, waymark.
the same (regularly) as צִיּוּן; Tsijon (as a permanent capital), a mountain of Jerusalem: Zion.
or Tsicha(; as if feminine of צִחֵה; drought; Tsicha, the name of two Nethinim: Ziha.
from the same as צִיָּה; a desert-dweller, i.e. nomad or wild beast: wild beast of the desert, that dwell in (inhabiting) the wilderness.
from an unused root meaning to confine; the pillory: stocks.
from צָעַר; small; Tsior, a place in Palestine: Zior.
or tsits; from צוּץ; properly, glistening, i.e. a burnished plate; also a flower (as bright-colored); a wing (as gleaming in the air): blossom, flower, plate, wing.
the same as צִיץ; bloom; Tsits, a place in Palestine: Ziz.
feminine of צִיץ; a flower: flower.
feminine of צִיץ; a floral or wing-like projection, i.e. a forelock of hair, a tassel: fringe, lock.

from צוּר; a hinge (as pressed in turning); also a throe (as a phys. or mental pressure); also a herald or errand-doer (as constrained by the principal): ambassador, hinge, messenger, pain, pang, sorrow. Compare צִיר.
the same as צִיר; a form (of beauty; as if pressed out, i.e. carved); hence, an (idolatrous) image: beauty, idol.
a denominative from צִיר in the sense of ambassador; to make an errand, i.e. betake oneself: make as if...had been ambassador.
from צָלַל; shade, whether literal or figurative: defence, shade(-ow).
(Aramaic) probably corresponding to צָלַע in the sense of bowing; pray: pray.
a primitive root; to roast: roast.
feminine of צֵל; Tsillah, an antediluvian woman: Zillah.
from צָלַל in the sense of rolling; a (round or flattened) cake: cake.

or tsaleach; a primitive root; to push forward, in various senses (literal or figurative, transitive or intransitive): break out, come (mightily), go over, be good, be meet, be profitable, (cause to, effect, make to, send) prosper(-ity, -ous, - ously).
(Aramaic) corresponding to צָלַח; to advance (transitive or intransitive): promote, prosper.
from צָלַח; something protracted or flattened out, i.e. a platter: pan.
from צָלַח; something prolonged or tall, i.e. a vial or salt-cellar: cruse.
from צָלַח; something advanced or deep, i.e. a bowl; figuratively, the bosom: bosom, dish.
passive participle of צָלָה; roasted: roast.
a primitive root; properly, to tumble down, i.e. settle by a waving motion: sink. Compare צָלַל, צָלַל.
a primitive root (identical with צָלַל through the idea of vibration); to tinkle, i.e. rattle together (as the ears in reddening with shame, or the teeth in chattering with fear): quiver, tingle.
a primitive root (identical with צָלַל through the idea of hovering over (compare צֶ֫לֶם)); to shade, as twilight or an opaque object: begin to be dark, shadowing.
from צָלַל; shade: shadow.
from צֵ֫לֶל and the active participle of פָּנָה; shade-facing; Tselelponi, an Israelitess: Hazelelponi (including the article).
from an unused root meaning to shade; a phantom, i.e. (figuratively) illusion, resemblance; hence, a representative figure, especially an idol: image, vain shew.
(Aramaic) or tslem (Aramaic); corresponding to צֶ֫לֶם; an idolatrous figure: form, image.
from צֶ֫לֶם; shady; Tsalmon, the name of a place in Palestine and of an Israelite: Zalmon.
from צֵל and מָ֫וֶת; shade of death, i.e. the grave (figuratively, calamity): shadow of death.
feminine of צַלְמָ֫וֶת; shadiness; Tsalmonah, a place in the Desert: Zalmonah.
from צֵל and מָנַע; shade has been denied; Tsalmunna, a Midianite: Zalmunna.
a primitive root: probably to curve; used only as denominative from צְלָעֹת, to limp (as if one-sided): halt.
from צָלַע; a limping or full (figuratively): adversity, halt(-ing).
the same as צֶ֫לַע; Tsela, a place in Palestine: Zelah.

or (feminine) tsalTah; from צָלַע; a rib (as curved), literally (of the body) or figuratively (of a door, i.e. leaf); hence, a side, literally (of a person) or figuratively (of an object or the sky, i.e. quarter); architecturally, a (especially floor or ceiling) timber or plank (single or collective, i.e. a flooring): beam, board, chamber, corner, leaf, plank, rib, side (chamber).
from an unused root of unknown meaning; Tsalaph, an Israelite: Zalaph.
from the same as צָלָף and אֶחָד; Tselophchad, an Israelite: Zelophehad.
from צֵל and צַח; clear shade; Tseltsach, a place in Palestine: Zelzah.
from צָלַל reduplicated; a clatter, i.e. (abstractly) whirring (of wings); (concretely) a cricket; also a harpoon (as rattling), a cymbal (as clanging): cymbal, locust, shadowing, spear.
from an unused root meaning to split; fissure; Tselek, an Israelite: Zelek.
from the feminine of צֵל; shady; Tsillethai, the name of two Israelites: Zilthai.
a primitive root; to thirst (literally or figuratively): (be a-, suffer) thirst(-y).
from צָמֵא; thirsty (literally or figuratively): (that) thirst(-eth, -y).
from צָמֵא; thirst (literally or figuratively): thirst(-y).
feminine of צָמָא; thirst (figuratively, of libidinousnes): thirst.
from צָמֵא; a thirsty place, i.e. desert: drought, dry ground, thirsty land.
a primitive root; to link, i.e. gird; figuratively, to serve, (mentally) contrive: fasten, frame, join (self).
a yoke or team (i.e. pair); hence, an acre (i.e. day's task for a yoke of cattle to plough): acre, couple, X together, two (donkeys), yoke (of oxen).
from an unused root meaning to fasten on; a veil: locks.
from צָמַק; a cake of dried grapes: bunch (cluster) of raisins.

a primitive root; to sprout (transitive or intransitive, literal or figurative): bear, bring forth, (cause to, make to) bud (forth), (cause to, make to) grow (again, up), (cause to) spring (forth, up).
from צָמַח; a sprout (usually concrete), literal or figurative: branch, bud, that which (where) grew (upon), spring(-ing).
or tsamid; from צָמַד; a bracelet or arm-clasp; generally, a lid: bracelet, covering.
from the same as צַמַּת; a noose (as fastening); figuratively, destruction: robber.
or tsmithuth; from צָמַת; excision, i.e. destruction; used only (adverbially) with prepositional prefix to extinction, i.e. perpetually: ever.
a primitive root; to dry up: dry.
from an unused root probably meaning to be shaggy; wool: wool(-len).
patrial from an unused name of a place in Palestine; a Tsemarite or branch of the Canaanites: Zemarite.
dual of צָ֫מֶר; double fleece; Tsemarajim, a place in Palestine: Zemaraim.
from the same as צָ֫מֶר; fleeciness, i.e. foliage: highest branch, top.
a primitive root; to extirpate (literally or figuratively): consume, cut off, destroy, vanish.
from an unused root meaning to prick; a crag; Tsin, a part of the Desert: Zin.
from an unused root meaning to be prickly; a thorn; hence, a cactus-hedge: thorn.
or tsoneh; for צֹאן; a flock: sheep.
feminine of צִנִּים; a hook (as pointed); also a (large) shield (as if guarding by prickliness); also cold (as piercing)buckler, cold, hook, shield, target.
from an unused root perhaps meaning to be hollow; a culvert: gutter, water-spout.
a primitive root; to alight; (transitive) to cause to descend, i.e. drive down: fasten, light (from off).
or tsanin; from the same as צִנִּים; a thorn: thorn.
or tsanowph; or (feminine) tsaniyphah; from צָנַף; a head-dress (i.e. piece of cloth wrapped around): diadem, hood, mitre.
a primitive root; to blast or shrink: withered.
probably for צַאֲנָן; Tsenan, a place near Palestine: Zenan.
a primitive root; to humiliate: humbly, lowly.
a primitive root; to wrap, i.e. roll or dress: be attired, X surely, violently turn.
from צָנַף; a ball: X toss.
from the same as צִנִּים; a vase (probably a vial tapering at the top): pot.
probably from the same as צִנּוֹר; a tube: pipe.
a primitive root; to pace, i.e. step regularly; (upward) to mount; (along) to march; (down and causatively) to hurlbring, go, march (through), run over.
from צַנְתְּרוֹת; a pace or regular step: pace, step.
feminine of צָ֫עַד; a march; (concretely) an (ornamental) ankle-chain: going, ornament of the legs.

a primitive root; to tip over (for the purpose of spilling or pouring out), i.e. (figuratively) depopulate; by implication, to imprison or conquer; (reflexive) to lie down (for coitus): captive exile, travelling, (cause to) wander(-er).
from an unused root meaning to wrap over; a veil: vail.
or tsanowr; from צָעַר; little; (in number) few; (in age) young, (in value) ignoble: least, little (one), small (one), + young(-er, -est).
the same as צָעִיר; Tsair, a place in Idumaea: Zair.
feminine of צָעִיר; smallness (of age), i.e. juvenility: youth.
a primitive root; to load up (beasts), i.e. to migrate: be taken down.
of Egyptian derivation; Tsoan, a place in Egypt: Zoan.
or (dual) Tsaeanayim; plural from צָעַן; removals; Tsaanannim or Tsaanajim, a place in Palestine: Zaannannim, Zaanaim.
from an unused root meaning to bestrew with carvings; sculpture: image (work).
a primitive root; to shriek; (by implication) to proclaim (an assembly): X at all, call together, cry (out), gather (selves) (together).
from צָעַק; a shriek: cry(-ing).
a primitive root; to be small, i.e. (figuratively) ignoble: be brought low, little one, be small.
from צָעַר; little; Tsoar, a place East of the Jordan: Zoar.
a primitive root; to adhere: cleave.
a primitive root; properly, to lean forward, i.e. to peer into the distance; by implication, to observe, awaitbehold, espy, look up (well), wait for, (keep the) watch(-man).
a primitive root (probably identical with צָפָה through the idea of expansion in outlook, transferring to action); to sheet over (especially with metal): cover, overlay.
from צָפָה; an inundation (as covering): X swimmest.
or Tsphiy; from צָפָה; observant; Tsepho or Tsephi, an Idumaean: Zephi, Zepho.
from צָפָה; encasement (with metal): covering, overlaying.
probably for צִפְיוֹן; Tsephon, an Israelite: Zephon.
or tsaphon; from צָפַן; properly, hidden, i.e. dark; used only of the north as a quarter (gloomy and unknown): north(-ern, side, -ward, wind).
the same as צָפוֹן; boreal; Tsaphon, a place in Palestine: Zaphon.
from צָפוֹן; northern: northern.
patronymically from צְפוֹן; a Tsephonite, or (collectively) descendants of Tsephon: Zephonites.
from the same as צֶ֫פַע; excrement (as protruded): dung.
or tsippor; from צָפַר; a little bird (as hopping): bird, fowl, sparrow.
the same as צִפּוֹר; Tsippor, a Moabite: Zippor.
from an unused root meaning to expand; a saucer (as flat): cruse.
from צָפָה; watchfulness: watching.
from צָפָה; watch-tower; Tsiphjon, an Israelite: Ziphion. Compare צְפוֹן.
from the same as צַפַּ֫חַת; a flat thin cake: wafer.
plural of active participle of צָפָה; watchers; Tsophim, a place East of the Jordan: Zophim.
from צָפַן; a treasure (as hidden): hid.
(Aramaic) corresponding to צָפִיר; a he-goat: he (goat).
from צָפַר; a male goat (as prancing): (he) goat.
feminine formed like צָפִיר; a crown (as encircling the head); also a turn of affairs (i.e. mishap): diadem, morning.
from צָפָה; a sentry: watchtower.

a primitive root; to hide (by covering over); by implication, to hoard or reserve; figuratively to deny; specifically (favorably) to protect, (unfavorably) to lurk: esteem, hide(-den one, self), lay up, lurk (be set) privily, (keep) secret(-ly, place).
or Tsphanyahuw; from צָפַן and יָהּ; Jah has secreted; Tsephanjah, the name of four Israelites: Zephaniah.
of Egyptian derivation; Tsophnath-Paneach, Joseph's Egyptian name: Zaphnath-paaneah.
: ; or tsiph<oniy from an unused root meaning to extrude; a viper (as thrusting out the tongue, i.e. hissing): adder, cockatrice.
feminine from the same as צֶ֫פַע; an outcast thing: issue.
a primitive root; to coo or chirp (as a bird): chatter, peep, whisper.
from צוּף; a willow (as growing in overflowed places): willow tree.
a primitive root; to skip about, i.e. return: depart early.
(Aramaic) corresponding to צִפּוֹר; a bird. -- bird.
from צָפַר and a word elsewhere unused meaning a swamp; a marsh-leaper, i.e. frog: frog.
feminine of צִפּוֹר; bird; Tsipporah, Moses' wife: Zipporah.
from צָפַר (in the denominative sense (from צִפּוֹר) of scratching); properly, a claw, i.e. (human) nail; also the point of a style (or pen, tipped with adamant): nail, point.
from צָפָה; watch-tower; Tsephath, a place in Palestine: Zephath.
from an unused root meaning to encircle; a capital of a column: chapiter.
the same as צְפַת; Tsephathah, a place in Palestine: Zephathah.
or Tsiyqlag (1 Chronicles 12:1,20); of uncertain derivation: Tsiklag or Tsikelag, a place in Palestine: Ziklag.
from an unused root meaning to wind; a sack (as tied at the mouth): husk.

or tsar; from צָרַר; narrow; (as a noun) a tight place (usually figuratively, i.e. trouble); also a pebble (as in צֹר); (transitive) an opponent (as crowding): adversary, afflicted(-tion), anguish, close, distress, enemy, flint, foe, narrow, small, sorrow, strait, tribulation, trouble.
from צָרַר; rock; Tser, a place in Palestine: Zer.
from צוּר; a stone (as if pressed hard or to a point); (by implication, of use) a knife: flint, sharp stone.
or Tsowr; the same as צֹר; a rock; Tsor, a place in Palestine: Tyre, Tyrus.
a primitive root; to burn: burn.
from צוּעָר; conflagration (of fire or disease): burning, inflammation.
or Tsredathah; apparently from an unused root meaning to pierce; puncture; Tseredah, a place in Palestine: Zereda, Zeredathah.
feminine of צָר; tightness (i.e. figuratively, trouble); transitively, a female rival: adversary, adversity, affliction, anguish, distress, tribulation, trouble.
feminine passive participle from the same as צֹ֫רִי; wounded; Tserujah, an Israelitess: Zeruiah.
feminine passive participle of צָרַע; leprous; Tseruah, an Israelitess: Zeruah.
or (shorter) tsror; from צָרַר; a parcel (as packed up); also a kernel or particle (as if a package): bag, X bendeth, bundle, least grain, small stone.
a primitive root; to be clear (in tone, i.e. shrill), i.e. to whoop: cry, roar.
the same as צֹ֫רִי; Tseri, an Israelite: Zeri. Compare יִצְרִי.
or tsoriy; from an unused root meaning to crack (as by pressure), hence, to leak; distillation, i.e. balsam: balm.
patrial from צֹר; a Tsorite or inhabitant of Tsor (i.e. Syrian): (man) of Tyre.
from צָרַח in the sense of clearness of vision; a citadel: high place, hold.
from an unused root meaning to need; need: need.
a primitive root; to scourge, i.e. (intransitive and figurative) to be stricken with leprosy: leper, leprous.
from צָרַע; a wasp (as stinging): hornet.
apparently another form for צִרְעָה; Tsorah, a place in Palestine: Zareah, Zorah, Zoreah.
or Tsortathiy; patrial from צָרְעָה; a Tsorite or Tsorathite, i.e. inhabitants of Tsorah: Zorites, Zareathites, Zorathites.
from צָרַע; leprosy: leprosy.
a primitive root; to fuse (metal), i.e. refine (literally or figuratively): cast, (re-)fine(-er), founder, goldsmith, melt, pure, purge away, try.
from צָרַף; refiner; Tsorephi (with the article), an Israelite: goldsmith's.
from צָרַף; refinement; Tsarephath, a place in Palestine: Zarephath.

a primitive root; to cramp, literally or figuratively, transitive or intransitive (as follows): adversary, (be in) afflict(-ion), besiege, bind (up), (be in, bring) distress, enemy, narrower, oppress, pangs, shut up, be in a strait (trouble), vex.
apparently by erroneous transcription for צְרֵדָה; Tsererah for Tseredah: Zererath.
perhaps from צָהַר; splendor; Tsereth, an Israelite: Zereth.
from the same as צֶ֫רֶת and שָׁ֫חַר with the article interposed; splendor of the dawn; Tsereth-hash-Shachar, a place in Palestine: Zareth-shahar.
perhaps for צְרֵדָה; Tsarethan, a place in Palestine: Zarthan.
or qiys; from קוֹא; vomit: vomit.
from קוֹא; probably the pelican (from vomiting): cormorant.
from קָבַב; a hollow, i.e. vessel used as a (dry) measure: cab.
a primitive root; to scoop out, i.e. (figuratively) to malign or execrate (i.e. stab with words): X at all, curse.
from קָבַב; the paunch (as a cavity) or first stomach of ruminants: maw.
from קָבַב; the abdomen (as a cavity): belly.
from קָבַב; a pavilion (as a domed cavity): tent.
from קָבַץ; a throng: company.
or qburah; feminine passive participle of קָבַר; sepulture; (concretely) a sepulchre: burial, burying place, grave, sepulchre.
a primitive root; to admit, i.e. take (literally or figuratively): choose, (take) hold, receive, (under-)take.
(Aramaic) corresponding to קָבַל; to acquire: receive, take.

(Aramaic) or qobel (Aramaic); (corresponding to קָבָלְ־; (adverbially) in front of; usually (with other particles) on account of, so as, since, hence: + according to, + as, + because, before, + for this cause, + forasmuch as, + by this means, over against, by reason of, + that, + therefore, + though, + wherefore.
from קָבַל in the sense of confronting (as standing opposite in order to receive); a battering-ram: war.
from קָבַל in the sense of opposite (see קֳבָלּוֹ); the presence, i.e. (adverbially) in front of: before.
a primitive root; to cover, i.e. (figuratively) defraud: rob, spoil.
from קָבַע; a goblet (as deep like a cover): dregs.
a primitive root; to grasp, i.e. collect: assemble (selves), gather (bring) (together, selves together, up), heap, resort, X surely, take up.
from קָבַץ and אֵל; God has gathered; Kabtseel, a place in Palestine: Kabzeel. Compare יִקַּבְצְאֵל.
feminine passive participle of קָבַץ; a hoard: X gather.
dual from קָבַץ; a double heap; Kibtsajim, a place in Palestine: Kibzaim.
a primitive root; to inter: X in any wise, bury(-ier).
or (feminine) qibrah; from קָבַר; a sepulchre: burying place, grave, sepulchre.
from the feminine plural of קָ֫בֶר and תַּאֲוָה with the article interposed; graves of the longing; Kibroth-hat-Taavh, a place in the Desert: Kibroth-hattaavah.
a primitive root; to shrivel up, i.e. contract or bend the body (or neck) in deference: bow (down) (the) head, stoop.
from קָדַד; cassia bark (as in shrivelled rolls): cassia.
passive participle of קָדַם; a pristine hero: ancient.
or qadosh; from קָדַשׁ; sacred (ceremonially or morally); (as noun) God (by eminence), an angel, a saint, a sanctuary: holy (One), saint.
a primitive root to inflame: burn, kindle.
from קָדַח; inflammation, i.e. febrile disease: burning ague, fever.
or qadim; from קָדַם; the fore or front part; hence (by orientation) the East (often adverbially, eastward, for brevity the east wind): east(-ward, wind).
(Aramaic) corresponding to קָדוֹשׁ. --holy (One), saint.
a primitive root; to project (one self), i.e. precede; hence, to anticipate, hasten, meet (usually for help): come (go, (flee)) before, + disappoint, meet, prevent.

or qedmah; from קָדַם; the front, of place (absolutely, the fore part, relatively the East) or time (antiquity); often used adverbially (before, anciently, eastward): aforetime, ancient (time), before, east (end, part, side, -ward), eternal, X ever(-lasting), forward, old, past. Compare קִדְמַת.
(Aramaic) or qdam (Aramaic) (Daniel 7:13); corresponding to קֶ֫דֶם; before: before, X from, X I (thought), X me, + of, X it pleased, presence.
feminine of קֶ֫דֶם; the forward part (or relatively) East (often adverbially, on the east or in front): east(-ward).
from קָדַם; priority (in time); also used adverbially (before): afore, antiquity, former (old) estate.
(Aramaic) corresponding to קַדְמַת; former timeafore(-time), ago.
from קָדַם; precedence; Kedemah, a son of Ishmael: Kedemah.
from קָדַם; eastern: east.
or qadmoniy; from קַדְמוֹנָה; (of time) anterior or (of place) oriental: ancient, they that went before, east, (thing of) old.
from קָדַם; beginnings; Kedemoth, a place in eastern Palestine: Kedemoth.
(Aramaic) from a root corresponding to קָדַם; first: first.
from קֶ֫דֶם and אֵל; presence of God; Kadmiel, the name of three Israelites: Kadmiel.
the same as קַדְמוֹנִי; ancient, i.e. aboriginal; Kadmonite (collectively), the name of a tribe in PalestineKadmonites.
from קָדַד; the crown of the head (as the part most bowed): crown (of the head), pate, scalp, top of the head.
a primitive root; to be ashy, i.e. dark-colored; by implication, to mourn (in sackcloth or sordid garments): be black(-ish), be (make) dark(-en), X heavily, (cause to) mourn.
from קָדַר; dusky (of the skin or the tent); Kedar, a son of Ishmael; also (collectively) Bedouin (as his descendants or representatives): Kedar.
from קָדַר; dusky place; Kidron, a brook near Jerusalem: Kidron.
from קָדַר; duskiness: blackness.
adverb from קָדַר; blackish ones (i.e. in sackcloth); used adverbially, in mourning weeds: mournfully.

a primitive root; to be (causatively, make, pronounce or observe as) clean (ceremonially or morally): appoint, bid, consecrate, dedicate, defile, hallow, (be, keep) holy(-er, place), keep, prepare, proclaim, purify, sanctify(-ied one, self), X wholly.
from קָדַשׁ; a sanctum; Kedesh, the name of four places in Palestine: Kedesh.
from קָדַשׁ; a sacred place or thing; rarely abstract, sanctity: consecrated (thing), dedicated (thing), hallowed (thing), holiness, (X most) holy (X day, portion, thing), saint, sanctuary.
from קָדַשׁ; a (quasi) sacred person, i.e. (technically) a (male) devotee (by prostitution) to licentious idolatrysodomite, unclean.
the same as קָדֵשׁ; sanctuary; Kadesh, a place in the Desert: Kadesh. Compare קָדֵשׁ בַּרְנֵ֫עַ.

from the same as קָדֵשׁ and an otherwise unused word (apparently compounded of a correspondent to בָּרָא and a derivative of נ֫וּעַ) meaning desert of a fugitive; Kadesh of (the) Wilderness of Wandering; Kadesh-Barnea, a place in the Desert: Kadesh-barnea.
feminine of קָדֵשׁ; a female devotee (i.e. prostitute): harlot, whore.
a primitive root; to be dull: be set on edge, be blunt.
a primitive root; to convoke: assemble (selves) (together), gather (selves) (together).
from קָהַל; assemblage (usually concretely): assembly, company, congregation, multitude.
from קָהַל; an assemblage: assembly, congregation.
feminine of active participle from קָהַל; a (female) assembler (i.e. lecturer): abstractly, preaching (used as a "nom de plume", Koheleth): preacher.
from קָהַל; convocation; Kehelathah, a place in the Desert: Kehelathah.
from an unused root meaning to ally oneself; allied; Kehath, an Israelite: Kohath.
patronymically from קְהָת; a Kohathite (collectively) or descendants of Kehath: Kohathites.
or qav; from קָוָה (compare קָוה); a cord (as connecting), especially for measuring; figuratively, a rule; also a rim, a musical string or accord: line. Compare קַו־קָו.
or qayah (Jer. 25:27); a primitive root; to vomit: spue (out), vomit (out, up, up again).
a form collateral to כּוֹבָע; a helmet: helmet.
a primitive root; to bind together (perhaps by twisting), i.e. collect; (figuratively) to expect: gather (together), look, patiently, tarry, wait (for, on, upon).
from קָוָה; a (measuring) cord (as if for binding): line.
a primitive root; properly, to cut off, i.e. (figuratively) detest: begrieved, loathe self.

or qol; from an unused root meaning to call aloud; a voice or sound: + aloud, bleating, crackling, cry (+ out), fame, lightness, lowing, noise, + hold peace, (pro-)claim, proclamation, + sing, sound, + spark, thunder(-ing), voice, + yell.
from קוֹל and יָהּ; voice of Jah; Kolajah, the name of two Israelites: Kolaiah.

a primitive root; to rise (in various applications, literal, figurative, intensive and causative): abide, accomplish, X be clearer, confirm, continue, decree, X be dim, endure, X enemy, enjoin, get up, make good, help, hold, (help to) lift up (again), make, X but newly, ordain, perform, pitch, raise (up), rear (up), remain, (a-)rise (up) (again, against), rouse up, set (up), (e-)stablish, (make to) stand (up), stir up, strengthen, succeed, (as-, make) sure(-ly), (be) up(-hold, - rising).
(Aramaic) corresponding to קוּם: appoint, establish, make, raise up self, (a-)rise (up), (make to) stand, set (up).
from קוּם; height: X along, height, high, stature, tall.
from קוּם; elevation, i.e. (adverbially) erectly (figuratively): upright.
a primitive root; to strike a musical note, i.e. chant or wail (at a funeral): lament, mourning woman.
probably from קוּץ in the original sense of cutting off; curtailment; Koa, a region of Bab.: Koa.
or qoph; probably of foreign origin; a monkey: ape.
a primitive root; to clip off; used only as denominative from קָ֫יִץ; to spend the harvest season: summer.

a primitive root (identical with קוּץ through the idea of severing oneself from (compare קוּט)); to be (causatively, make) disgusted or anxious: abhor, be distressed, be grieved, loathe, vex, be weary.
a primitive root (identical with קוּץ through the idea of abruptness in starting up from sleep (compare יָקַץ)); to awake (literally or figuratively): arise, (be) (a-)wake, watch.
or qots; from קוּץ (in the sense of pricking); a thorn: thorn.
the same as קוֹץ; Kots, the name of two Israelites: Koz, Hakkoz (including the article).
feminine passive participle of קוּץ in its original sense; a forelock (as shorn): lock.
from קָו (in the sense of a fastening); stalwart: X meted out.
a primitive root; to trench; by implication, to throw forth; also (denominative from קִיר) to wall up, whether literal (to build a wall) or figurative (to estop): break down, cast out, destroy, dig.
from קוּר; (only plural) trenches, i.e. a web (as if so formed): web.
or Qore7 (1 Chronicles 26:1); active participle of קָרָא; crier; Kore, the name of two Israelites: Kore.
or qorah; from קוּר; a rafter (forming trenches as it were); by implication, a roof: beam, roof.
a primitive root; to bend; used only as denominative for יָקֹשׁ, to set a trap: lay a snare.
from the passive participle of קוֹשׁ and יָהּ; entrapped of Jah; Kushajah, an Israelite: Kushaiah.
from קוּט in the sense of abbreviation; a little, i.e. (adverbially) merely: very.
from an unused root meaning to cut off; ruin: destroying, destruction.
from the same as קָ֫טֶב; extermination: destruction.
from קָטַר; perfume: incense.
feminine passive participle of קָטַר; perfumed; Keturah, a wife of Abraham: Keturah.
a primitive root; to clip off, i.e. (figuratively) destroy: be cut off.
a primitive root; properly, to cut off, i.e. (figuratively) put to death: kill, slay.
(Aramaic) corresponding to קָטַל; to kill: slay.
from קָטַל; a violent death: slaughter.
a primitive root (rather denominative from קָטָן); to diminish, i.e. be (causatively, make) diminutive or (figuratively) of no account: be a (make) small (thing), be not worthy.
from קָטַן; a pettiness, i.e. the little finger: little finger.

or qaton; from קוּט; abbreviated, i.e. diminutive, literally (in quantity, size or number) or figuratively (in age or importance): least, less(-er), little (one), small(-est, one, quantity, thing), young(-er, -est).
the same as קָטָן; small; Katan, an Israelite: Hakkatan (including the article).
a primitive root; to strip off: crop off, cut down (up), pluck.

a primitive root (identical with קְטֻרוֹת through the idea of fumigation in a close place and perhaps thus driving out the occupants); to smoke, i.e. turn into fragrance by fire (especially as an act of worship): burn (incense, sacrifice) (upon), (altar for) incense, kindle, offer (incense, a sacrifice).
a primitive root; to inclose: join.
(Aramaic) from a root corresponding to קְטֻרוֹת; a knot (as tied up), i.e. (figuratively) a riddle; also a vertebra (as if a knot): doubt, joint.
from קָטַר; perfume: incense.
from קָטַר; fumigative; Kitron, a place in Palestine: Kitron.
from קָטַר; a fumigation: (sweet) incense, perfume.
from קָטָן; littleness; Kattath, a place in Palestine: Kattath.
a primitive root; to vomit: spue.
(Aramaic) corresponding to קָ֫יִץ; harvest: summer.
or qiytor; from קָטַר; a fume, i.e. cloud: smoke, vapour.
from קוּם; an opponent (as rising against one), i.e. (collectively) enemies: substance.
(Aramaic) from קוּם; an edict (as arising in law): decree, statute.
(Aramaic) from קוּם; permanent (as rising firmly): stedfast, sure.
from קוּם; an arising: rising up.
from קוּן in the original sense of fixity; a lance (as striking fast): spear.
the same as קֵין (with a play upon the affinity to קָנָה); Kajin, the name of the first child, also of a place in Palestine, and of an Oriental tribe: Cain, Kenite(-s).
from קוּן; a dirge (as accompanied by beating the breasts or on instruments): lamentation.
the same as קִינִים; Kinah, a place in Palestine: Kinah.
or Qiyniy (1 Chron. 2:55); patronymic from קָ֫יִן; a Kenite or member of the tribe of Kajin: Kenite.
from the same as קֵן; fixed; Kenan, an antediluvian: Cainan, Kenan.
from קוּץ; harvest (as the crop), whether the product (grain or fruit) or the (dry) season: summer (fruit, house).
from קוּץ; terminal: out- (utter-)most.
perhaps from קָיָה; the gourd (as nauseous): gourd.
from קָלוֹן; intense disgrace: shameful spewing.
or qir (Isa. 22:5); or (feminine) qiyrah; from קוּר; a wall (as built in a trench): + mason, side, town, X very, wall.
the same as קִיר; fortress; Kir, a place in Assyrian; also one in Moab: Kir. Compare קִיר חָ֫רֶשׂ.
or (feminine of the latter word) Qiyr Chareseth; from קִיר and חָ֫רֶשׂ; fortress of earthenware; Kir-Cheres or Kir-Chareseth, a place in Moab: Kir-haraseth, Kir-hareseth, Kir-haresh, Kir-heres.
or Qeroc; from the same as קַרְסֹל; ankled; Keros, one of the Nethinim: Keros.
from קוֹשׁ; a bow; Kish, the name of five Israelites: Kish.
from קוֹשׁ; winding; Kishon, a river of Palestine: Kishon, Kison.
from קוֹשׁ; bowed; Kishi, an Israelite: Kishi.
(Aramaic) of Greek origin; a lyre: harp.
contracted from קָלַל; light; (by implication) rapid (also adverbial): light, swift(-ly).
(Aramaic) corresponding to קוֹל: sound, voice.
a primitive root (rather identical with קָלָה through the idea of shrinkage by heat); to toast, i.e. scorch partially or slowly: dried, loathsome, parch, roast.
a primitive root; to be light (as implied in rapid motion), but figuratively, only (be (causatively, hold) in contempt): base, contemn, despise, lightly esteem, set light, seem vile.
for קָהַל; to assemble: gather together.
from קָלָה; disgrace; (by implication) the pudendaconfusion, dishonour, ignominy, reproach, shame.
apparently but a form for צַלָּ֫חַת; a kettle: caldron.
a primitive root; to maim: lacking in his parts.
or qaliyi; from קָלָה; roasted ears of grain: parched corn.
from קָלַל; frivolous; Kallai, an Israelite: Kallai.
from קָלָה; insignificance; Kelajah, an Israelite: Kelaiah.
from קָלַט; maiming; Kelita, the name of three Israelites: Kelita.

a primitive root; to be (causatively, make) light, literally (swift, small, sharp, etc.) or figuratively (easy, trifling, vile, etc.): abate, make bright, bring into contempt, (ac-)curse, despise, (be) ease(-y, -ier), (be a, make, make somewhat, move, seem a, set) light(-en, -er, -ly, -ly afflict, -ly esteem, thing), X slight(-ly), be swift(-er), (be, be more, make, re-)vile, whet.
from קָלַל; brightened (as if sharpened): burnished, polished.
from קָלַל; vilification: (ac-)curse(-d, - ing).
a primitive root; to disparage, i.e. ridicule: mock, scoff, scorn.
from קָלַס; a laughing-stock: derision.
intensive from קָלַס; ridicule: mocking.
a primitive root: to sling: also to carve (as if a circular motion, or into light forms): carve, sling (out).
from קָלַע; a sling; also a (door) screen (as if slung across), or the valve (of the door) itself: hanging, leaf, sling.
intensive from קָלַע; a slinger: slinger.
from קָלַל; insubstantial: light.
from an unused root meaning to prick; a prong, i.e. hay-fork: fork.
feminine of active participle of קוּם; something that rises, i.e. a stalk of grain: (standing) corn, grown up, stalk.
from קוּם and אֵל; raised of God; Kemuel, the name of a relative of Abraham, and of two Israelites: Kemuel.
from קוּם; an elevation; Kamon, a place East of the Jordan: Camon.
or qiymowsh; from an unused root meaning to sting; a prickly plant: nettle. Compare קִמְּשֹׂנִים.
from an unused root probably meaning to grind; flour: flour, meal.
a primitive root; to pluck, i.e. destroy: cut down, fill with wrinkles.
a primitive root; to wither: hew down, wither.
a primitive root; to grasp with the hand: take an handful.
from קָמַץ; a grasp, i.e. handful: handful.
from the same as קִמּוֹשׂ; a prickly plant: thorn.
contracted from קָנַן; a nest (as fixed), sometimes including the nestlings; figuratively, a chamber or dwelling: nest, room.
a primitive root; to be (causatively, make) zealous, i.e. (in a bad sense) jealous or envious: (be) envy(-ious), be (move to, provoke to) jealous(-y), X very, (be) zeal(-ous).
(Aramaic) corresponding to קָנָה; to purchase: buy.
from קָנָא; jealous: jealous. Compare קַנּוֹא.
from קָנָא; jealousy or envy: envy(-ied), jealousy, X sake, zeal.

a primitive root; to erect, i.e. create; by extension, to procure, especially by purchase (causatively, sell); by implication to own: attain, buy(-er), teach to keep cattle, get, provoke to jealousy, possess(-or), purchase, recover, redeem, X surely, X verily.

from קָנָה; a reed (as erect); by resemblance a rod (especially for measuring), shaft, tube, stem, the radius (of the arm), beam (of a steelyard): balance, bone, branch, calamus, cane, reed, X spearman, stalk.
feminine of קָנֶה; reediness; Kanah, the name of a stream and of a place in Palestine: Kanah.
for קַנָּא; jealous or angry: jealous.
probably from an unused root meaning to hunt; hunter; Kenaz, the name of an Edomite and of two Israelites: Kenaz.
patronymic from קְנַז, a Kenizzite or descendant of Kenaz: Kenezite, Kenizzites.
from קָנָה; creation, i.e. (concretely) creatures; also acquisition, purchase, wealth: getting, goods, X with money, riches, substance.
from an unused root (meaning to erect); cinnamon bark (as in upright rolls): cinnamon.
a primitive root; to erect; but used only as denominative from קֵן; to nestle, i.e. build or occupy as a nestmake...nest.
from an unused root probably meaning to wrench; perversion: end.
from קָנָה; possession; Kenath, a place East of the Jordan: Kenath.
a primitive root; properly, to distribute, i.e. determine by lot or magical scroll; by implication, to divine: divine(-r, -ation), prudent, soothsayer, use (divination).
from קָסַם; a lot: also divination (including its fee), oracle: (reward of) divination, divine sentence, witchcraft.
a primitive root; to lop off: cut off.
from the same as כּוֹס (or as קָשָׁה); properly, a cup, i.e. an ink-stand: inkhorn.
perhaps from קָלַע in the sense of inclosing; citadel; Keilah, a place in Palestine: Keilah.
from the same as ק֫וֹעַ; an incision or gash: + mark.
probably from קָרַע; a bowl (as cut out hollow): charger, dish.
a primitive root; to shrink, i.e. thicken (as unracked wine, curdled milk, clouded sky, frozen water): congeal, curdle, dark, settle.
a primitive root; to contract, i.e. roll together: cut off.
from קָפַד; shrinking, i.e., terror: destruction.
or qippod; from קָפַד; a species of bird, perhaps the bittern (from its contracted form): bittern.
from an unused root meaning to contract, i.e. spring forward; an arrow-snake (as darting on its prey): great owl.
a primitive root; to draw together, i.e. close; by implication, to leap (by contracting the limbs); specifically, to die (from gathering up the feet): shut (up), skip, stop, take out of the way.
contracted from קָצַץ; an extremity; adverbially (with prepositional prefix) after: + after, (utmost) border, end, (in-)finite, X process.
a primitive root; to clip, or (generally) chop: cut down, shorn.
from קָצַב; shape (as if cut out); base (as if there cut off): bottom, size.
a primitive root; to cut off; (figuratively) to destroy; (partially) to scrape off: cut off, cut short, scrape (off).

or (negative only) qetseh; from קָצָה; an extremity (used in a great variety of applications and idioms; compare קֵץ): X after, border, brim, brink, edge, end, (in-)finite, frontier, outmost coast, quarter, shore, (out-)side, X some, ut(-ter-)most (part).
feminine of קָצֶה; a termination (used like קָצֶה):--coast, corner, (selv-)edge, lowest, (uttermost) participle
and (feminine) qitsvah; from קָצָה; a limit (used like קָצֶה, but with less variety):--end, edge, uttermost participle
from an unused root apparently meaning to incise; fennelflower (from its pungency): fitches.
from קָצָה in the sense of determining; a magistrate (as deciding) or other leader: captain, guide, prince, ruler. Compare עִתָּה קָצִין.
from קָצַע; cassia (as peeled; plural the bark): cassia.
the same as קְצִיעוֹת; Ketsiah, a daughter of Job: Kezia.
from קָצַץ; abrupt; Keziz, a valley in Palestine: Keziz.
from קָצַר; severed, i.e. harvest (as reaped), the crop, the time, the reaper, or figuratively; also a limb (of a tree, or simply foliage): bough, branch, harvest (man).
a primitive root; to strip off, i.e. (partially) scrape; by implication, to segregate (as an angle): cause to scrape, corner.
a primitive root; to crack off, i.e. (figuratively) burst out in rage: (be) anger(-ry), displease, fret self, (provoke to) wrath (come), be wroth.
(Aramaic) corresponding to קָצַף; to become enraged: be furious.
(Aramaic) from קְצַף; rage: wrath.
from קָצַף; a splinter (as chipped off); figuratively, rage or strife: foam, indignation, X sore, wrath.
from קָצַף; a fragment: bark(-ed).
a primitive root; to chop off (literally or figuratively): cut (asunder, in pieces, in sunder, off), X utmost.
(Aramaic) corresponding to קָצַץ: cut off.

a primitive root; to dock off, i.e. curtail (transitive or intransitive, literal or figurative); especially to harvest (grass or grain): X at all, cut down, much discouraged, grieve, harvestman, lothe, mourn, reap(-er), (be, wax) short(-en, -er), straiten, trouble, vex.
from קָצַר; shortness (of spirit), i.e. impatience: anguish.
from קָצַר; short (whether in size, number, life, strength or temper): few, hasty, small, soon.
from קָצָה; a termination (literally or figuratively); also (by implication) a portion; adverbially (with prepositional prefix) after: end, part, X some.
(Aramaic) corresponding to קְצָת: end, partly.
contracted from an unused root meaning to chill; cool; figuratively, quiet: cold, excellent (from the margin).
from the same as קַר; cold: cold.

a primitive root (rather identical with קָרָא through the idea of accosting a person met); to call out to (i.e. properly, address by name, but used in a wide variety of applications): bewray (self), that are bidden, call (for, forth, self, upon), cry (unto), (be) famous, guest, invite, mention, (give) name, preach, (make) proclaim(- ation), pronounce, publish, read, renowned, say.
a primitive root: to encounter, whether accidentally or in a hostile manner: befall, (by) chance, (cause to) come (upon), fall out, happen, meet.
(Aramaic) corresponding to קָרָא: call, cry, read.
properly, active participle of קָרָא; a caller, i.e. partridge (from its cry): partridge. See also קוֹרֵא.
from קָרָא; an encountering, accidental, friendly or hostile (also adverbially, opposite): X against (he come), help, meet, seek, X to, X in the way.

a primitive root; to approach (causatively, bring near) for whatever purpose: (cause to) approach, (cause to) bring (forth, near), (cause to) come (near, nigh), (cause to) draw near (nigh), go (near), be at hand, join, be near, offer, present, produce, make ready, stand, take.
(Aramaic) corresponding to קָרַב: approach, come (near, nigh), draw near.
from קָרַב; hostile encounter: battle, war.
(Aramaic) corresponding to קְרָב: war.

from קָרַב; properly, the nearest part, i.e. the center, whether literal, figurative or adverbial (especially with preposition): X among, X before, bowels, X unto charge, + eat (up), X heart, X him, X in, inward (X -ly, part, -s, thought), midst, + out of, purtenance, X therein, X through, X within self.
from קָרַב; near: approach, come (near, nigh), draw near.
from קָרַב; approach: approaching, draw near.
or qurban; from קָרַב; something brought near the altar, i.e. a sacrificial present: oblation, that is offered, offering.
perhaps from קָדַם in the sense of striking upon; an axe: ax.
feminine of קַר; coolness: cold.

a primitive root; to light upon (chiefly by accident); causatively, to bring about; specifically, to impose timbers (for roof or floor): appoint, lay (make) beams, befall, bring, come (to pass unto), floor, (hap) was, happen (unto), meet, send good speed.
from קָרָה; an (unfortunate) occurrence, i.e. some accidental (ceremonial) disqualification: uncleanness that chanceth.

or qarob; from קָרַב; near (in place, kindred or time): allied, approach, at hand, + any of kin, kinsfold(-sman), (that is) near (of kin), neighbour, (that is) next, (them that come) nigh (at hand), more ready, short(-ly).
a primitive root; to depilate: make (self) bald.
or qorach; from קָרַח; ice (as if bald, i.e. smooth); hence, hail; by resemblance, rock crystal: crystal, frost, ice.
from קָרַח; ice; Korach, the name of two Edomites and three Israelites: Korah.
from קָרַח; bald (on the back of the head): bald (head).
from קָרַח; bald; Kareach, an Israelite: Careah, Kareah.
or qorcha (Ezek. 27:31); from קָרַח; baldness: bald(-ness), X utterly.
patronymic from קֹ֫רַח; a Korchite (collectively) or descendants of Korach: Korahite, Korathite, sons of Kore, Korhite.
from קָרַח; a bald spot (on the back of the head); figuratively, a threadbare spot (on the back side of the cloth): bald head, bare within.
from קָרָה; hostile encounter: contrary.
from קָרָא; called, i.e. select: famous, renowned.
(Aramaic) or qiryah (Aramaic); corresponding to קִרְיָה: city.
from קָרָא; a proclamation: preaching.
from קָרָה in the sense of flooring, i.e. building; a city: city.
plural of קִרְיָה; buildings; Kerioth, the name of two places in Palestine: Kerioth, Kirioth.

or (with the article interposed) Qiryath ha- Arbaw (Neh. 11:25); from קִרְיָה and אַרְבַּע or אַרְבַּע; city of Arba, or city of the four (giants); Kirjath-Arba or Kirjath-ha-Arba, a place in Palestine: Kirjath-arba.
from קִרְיָה and בַּ֫עַל; city of Baal; Kirjath-Baal, a place in Palestine: Kirjath-baal.
from קִרְיָה and the feminine plural of חוּץ; city of streets; Kirjath-Chutsoth, a place in Moab: Kirjath-huzoth.
dual of קִרְיָה; double city; Kirjathaim, the name of two placed in Palestine: Kiriathaim, Kirjathaim.

or (Jer. 26:20) with the article interposed; or (Josh. 18:28) simply the former part of the word; or Qiryath Ariym; from קִרְיָה and the plural of יָ֫עַר or עִיר; city of forests, or city of towns; Kirjath-Jearim or Kirjath-Arim, a place in Palestine: Kirjath, Kirjath-jearim, Kirjath-arim.

or Qiryath Cepher; from קִרְיָה and a simpler feminine from the same as סַנְסִן, or (for the latter name) סֵ֫פֶר; city of branches, or of a book; Kirjath-Sannah or Kirjath-Sepher, a place in Palestine: Kirjath-sannah, Kirjath-sepher.
a primitive root; to cover: cover.
a primitive root; to push or gore; used only as denominative from קָ֫רֶן, to shoot out horns; figuratively, rays: have horns, shine.

from קָרַן; a horn (as projecting); by implication, a flask, cornet; by resembl. an elephant's tooth (i.e. ivory), a corner (of the altar), a peak (of a mountain), a ray (of light); figuratively, power: X hill, horn.
(Aramaic) corresponding to קָ֫רֶן; a horn (literally or for sound): horn, cornet.
from קָ֫רֶן and פּוּך; horn of cosmetic; Keren-hap-Puk, one of Job's daughters: Keren-happuch.
a primitive root; properly, to protrude; used only as denominative from קְרָסִים (for alliteration with קָרַע), to hunch, i.e. be hump-backed: stoop.
from קָרַס; a knob or belaying-pin (from its swelling form): tache.
from קָרַס; an ankle (as a protuberance or joint): foot.
a primitive root; to rend, literally or figuratively (revile, paint the eyes, as if enlarging them): cut out, rend, X surely, tear.
from קָרַע; a rag: piece, rag.

a primitive root; to pinch, i.e. (partially) to bite the lips, blink the eyes (as a gesture of malice), or (fully) to squeeze off (a piece of clay in order to mould a vessel from it): form, move, wink.
(Aramaic) corresponding to קֶ֫רֶץ in the sense of a bit (to "eat the morsels of" any one, i.e. chew him up (figuratively) by slander): + accuse.
from קָרַץ; extirpation (as if by constriction): destruction.
from קָרַע; floor (as if a pavement of pieces or tesseroe), of a building or the sea: bottom, (X one side of the) floor.
the same as קַרְקַע; ground-floor; Karka (with the article prefix), a place in Palestine: Karkaa.
from קוּר; foundation; Karkor, a place East of the Jordan: Karkor.
from an unused root meaning to split off; a slab or plank; by implication, a deck of a ship: bench, board.
from קָרָה in the sense of building; a city: city.
from קָ֫רֶת; city; Kartah, a place in Palestine: Kartah.
from קָ֫רֶת; city-plot; Kartan, a place in Palestine: Kartan.
from קָשַׁשׁ; straw (as dry): stubble.
from an unused root (meaning to be hard); a cucumber (from the difficulty of digestion): cucumber.
a primitive root; to prick up the ears, i.e. hearken: attend, (cause to) hear(-ken), give heed, incline, mark (well), regard.
from קָשַׁב; a hearkening: X diligently, hearing, much heed, that regarded.
or qashshub; from קָשַׁב; hearkening: attent(-ive).
or qasvah; from an unused root meaning to be round; a jug (from its shape): cover, cup.

a primitive root; properly, to be dense, i.e. tough or severe (in various applications): be cruel, be fiercer, make grievous, be ((ask a), be in, have, seem, would) hard(-en, (labour), -ly, thing), be sore, (be, make) stiff(-en, (-necked)).

from קָשָׁה; severe (in various applications): churlish, cruel, grievous, hard((-hearted), thing), heavy, + impudent, obstinate, prevailed, rough(-ly), sore, sorrowful, stiff((necked)), stubborn, + in trouble.
(Aramaic) or qshot (Aramaic); corresponding to קֹ֫שֶׁט; fidelity: truth.
a primitive root; to be (causatively, make) unfeeling: harden.
or qosht; from an unused root meaning to balance; equity (as evenly weighed), i.e. reality: truth.
from קָשָׁה; obstinacy: stubbornness.
from קְשִׁי; hard ground; Kishjon, a place in Palestine: Kishion, Keshon.
from an unused root (probably meaning to weigh out); an ingot (as definitely estimated and stamped for a coin): piece of money (silver).
by reduplication from an unused root meaning to shale off as bark; a scale (of a fish); hence a coat of mail (as composed of or covered with jointed plates of metal): mail, scale.
a primitive root: to tie, physically (gird, confine, compact) or mentally (in love, league): bind (up), (make a) conspire(-acy, -ator), join together, knit, stronger, work (treason).
from קָשַׁר; an (unlawful) alliance: confederacy, conspiracy, treason.
from קָשַׁר; an (ornamental) girdle (for women): attire, headband.
a primitive root; to become sapless through drought; used only as denominative from קָשׁ; to forage for straw, stubble or wood; figuratively, to assemble: gather (selves) (together).
from קָשָׁה in the original sense (of קוֹשׁ) of bending: a bow, for shooting (hence, figuratively, strength) or the iris: X arch(-er), + arrow, bow((-man, -shot)).
intensive (as denominative) from קָ֫שֶׁת; a bowman: X archer.

a primitive root; to see, literally or figuratively (in numerous applications, direct and implied, transitive, intransitive and causative): advise self, appear, approve, behold, X certainly, consider, discern, (make to) enjoy, have experience, gaze, take heed, X indeed, X joyfully, lo, look (on, one another, one on another, one upon another, out, up, upon), mark, meet, X be near, perceive, present, provide, regard, (have) respect, (fore-, cause to, let) see(-r, -m, one another), shew (self), X sight of others, (e-)spy, stare, X surely, X think, view, visions.
from רָאָה; a bird of prey (probably the vulture, from its sharp sight): glede. Compare דָּאָה.
from רָאָה; seeing, i.e. experiencing: see.
active participle of רָאָה; a seer (as often rendered); but also (abstractly) a vision: vision.
for רֹאֶה; prophet; Roeh, an Israelite: Haroeh (including the article).
from the imperative of רָאָה and בֵּן; see ye a son; Reuben, a son of Jacob: Reuben.
patronymic from רְאוּבֵן; a Reubenite or descendant of Reuben: children of Reuben, Reubenites.
from רָאָה; sight, i.e. satisfaction: behold.
feminine passive participle of רָאַם; raised; Reumah, a Syrian woman: Reumah.
from רָאָה; a mirror (as seen): looking glass.
from רָאָה; sight, whether abstractly (vision) or concretely (a spectacle): gazingstock, look to, (that) see(-th).
from רָאָה and יָהּ; Jah has seen; Reajah, the name of three Israelites: Reaia, Reaiah.
from רָאָה; sight: beholding.
a primitive root; to rise: be lifted up.
or rieym; or reym; or rem; from רָאַם; a wild bull (from its conspicuousness): unicorn.
from רָאַם; something high in value, i.e. perhaps coral: coral.
or Ramoth; plural of רָאמוֹת; heights; Ramoth, the name of two places in Palestine: Ramoth.
(Aramaic) corresponding to רֹאשׁ; the head; figuratively, the sum: chief, head, sum.

from an unused root apparently meaning to shake; the head (as most easily shaken), whether literal or figurative (in many applications, of place, time, rank, itc.): band, beginning, captain, chapiter, chief(-est place, man, things), company, end, X every (man), excellent, first, forefront, ((be-))head, height, (on) high(-est part, (priest)), X lead, X poor, principal, ruler, sum, top.
or rowsh (Deut. 32:32); apparently the same as רֹאשׁ; a poisonous plant, probably the poppy (from its conspicuous head); generally poison (even of serpents): gall, hemlock, poison, venom.
probably the same as רֹאשׁ; Rosh, the name of an Israelite and of a foreign nation: Rosh.
from the same as רֹאשׁ; a beginning: beginning.
feminine of רֹאשׁ; the head: head(-stone).

or riishon; from רִאשֹׁת; first, in place, time or rank (as adjective or noun): ancestor, (that were) before(-time), beginning, eldest, first, fore(-father) (-most), former (thing), of old time, past.
from רִאשׁוֹן; first: first.
from the same as רֹאשׁ; the first, in place, time, order or rank (specifically, a firstfruit): beginning, chief(-est), first(-fruits, part, time), principal thing.
from רֹאשׁ; a pillow (being for the head): bolster.

by contracted from רָבַב; abundant (in quantity, size, age, number, rank, quality): (in) abound(-undance, -ant, -antly), captain, elder, enough, exceedingly, full, great(-ly, man, one), increase, long (enough, (time)), (do, have) many(-ifold, things, a time), ((ship-))master, mighty, more, (too, very) much, multiply(-tude), officer, often(-times), plenteous, populous, prince, process (of time), suffice(-lent).
by contraction from רָבַב; an archer (or perhaps the same as רָב): archer.
(Aramaic) corresponding to רָב: captain, chief, great, lord, master, stout.

from רָבַב; abundance (in any respect): abundance(- antly), all, X common (sort), excellent, great(-ly, -ness, number), huge, be increased, long, many, more in number, most, much, multitude, plenty(-ifully), X very (age).

a primitive root; properly, to cast together (compare רְבִיבִים), i.e. increase, especially in number; also (as denominative from רְבָבָה) to multiply by the myriad: increase, be many(-ifold), be more, multiply, ten thousands.
a primitive root (rather identical with רָבַב through the idea of projection); to shoot an arrow: shoot.
from רָבַב; abundance (in number), i.e. (specifically) a myriad (whether definite or indefinite): many, million, X multiply, ten thousand.
a primitive root; to spread: deck.

a primitive root; to increase (in whatever respect): (bring in) abundance (X -antly), + archer (by mistake for rabab), be in authority, bring up, X continue, enlarge, excel, exceeding(-ly), be full of, (be, make) great(-er, -ly, X -ness), grow up, heap, increase, be long, (be, give, have, make, use) many (a time), (any, be, give, give the, have) more (in number), (ask, be, be so, gather, over, take, yield) much (greater, more), (make to) multiply, nourish, plenty(-eous), X process (of time), sore, store, thoroughly, very.
(Aramaic) corresponding to רָבָה: make a great man, grow.
feminine of רָב; great; Rabbah, the name of two places in Palestine, East and West: Rabbah, Rabbath.
(Aramaic) from a root corresponding to רָבָה; increase (of dignity): greatness, majesty.
from רָבַב; or ribbow from רָבַב; a myriad, i.e. indefinitely, large number: great things, ten ((eight)-een, (for)-ty, + sixscore, + threescore, X twenty, (twen)-ty) thousand.
(Aramaic) corresponding to רִבּוֹ: X ten thousand times ten thousand.
from רָבַב; a rain (as an accumulation of drops): shower.
from רָבַד; a collar (as spread around the neck): chain.
or rbiiy; from רָבַע; fourth; also (fractionally) a fourth: foursquare, fourth (part).
(Aramaic) corresponding to רְבִיעִי -- fourth.
from רָבַב; multitude; Rabbith, a place in Palestine: Rabbith.
a primitive root; to soak (bread in oil): baken, (that which is) fried.
from an unused root meaning to be fruitful; fertile; Riblah, a place in Syria: Riblah.
from רָב and a foreign word for a Magian; chief Magian; Rab-Mag, a Bab. official: Rab-mag.
from רָב and a foreign word for a eunuch; chief chamberlain; Rab-Saris, a Babylonian official: Rab-saris.
a primitive root; to squat or lie out flat, i.e. (specifically) in copulation: let gender, lie down.

a primitive root (rather identical with רָבַע through the idea of sprawling "at all fours" (or possibly the reverse is the order of deriv.); compare אַרְבַּע); properly, to be four (sided); used only as denominative of רֶ֫בַע; to be quadrate: (four-)square(-d).
from רָבַע; prostration (for sleep): lying down.
from רָבַע; a fourth (part or side): fourth part, side, square.
the same as רֶ֫בַע; Reba, a Midianite: Reba.
from רָבַע; a quarter:--fourth participle
from רָבַע; a descendant of the fourth generation, i.e. great great grandchild: fourth.

a primitive root; to crouch (on all four legs folded, like a recumbent animal); be implication, to recline, repose, brood, lurk, imbed: crouch (down), fall down, make a fold, lay, (cause to, make to) lie (down), make to rest, sit.
from רָבַץ; a couch or place of repose: where each lay, lie down in, resting place.
from an unused root probably meaning to clog by tying up the fetlock; fettering (by beauty); Ribkah, the wife of IsaacRebekah.
(Aramaic) from רַב; huge (in size); domineering (in character): (very) great (things).
(Aramaic) from רַבְרְבִין; a magnate: lord, prince.
from רָב and שָׁקָה; chief butler; Rabshakeh, a Bab. official: Rabshakeh.
from an unused root meaning to pile together; a lump of clay: clod.
a primitive root; to quiver (with any violent emotion, especially anger or fear): be afraid, stand in awe, disquiet, fall out, fret, move, provoke, quake, rage, shake, tremble, trouble, be wroth.
(Aramaic) corresponding to רָגַז: provoke unto wrath.
(Aramaic) from רְגַז; violent anger: rage.
from רָגַז; commotion, restlessness (of a horse), crash (of thunder), disquiet, anger: fear, noise, rage, trouble(-ing), wrath.
intensive from רָגַז; timid: trembling.
feminine of רֹ֫גֶז; trepidation: trembling.

a primitive root; to walk along; but only in specifically, applications, to reconnoiter, to be a tale-bearer (i.e. slander); also (as denominative from רָ֫גֶל) to lead about: backbite, search, slander, (e-)spy (out), teach to go, view.
(Aramaic) corresponding to רָ֫גֶל: foot.

from רָגַל; a foot (as used in walking); by implication, a step; by euphem. the pudenda: X be able to endure, X according as, X after, X coming, X follow, ((broken-))foot((-ed, -stool)), X great toe, X haunt, X journey, leg, + piss, + possession, time.
from רָ֫גֶל; a footman (soldier): (on) foot(- man).
plural of active participle of רָגַל; fullers (as tramping the cloth in washing); Rogelim, a place East of the JordanRogelim.
a primitive root (compare רְגָבִים, ר֫וּעַ, רָקַם); to cast together (stones), i.e. to lapidate: X certainly, stone.
from רָגַם; stoneheap; Regem, an Israelite: Regem.
feminine of the same as רֶ֫גֶם; a pile (of stones), i.e. (figuratively) a throng: council.
from רֶ֫גֶם and מֶ֫לֶך; king's heap; Regem-Melek, an Israelite: Regem-melech.
a primitive root; to grumble, i.e. rebel: murmur.

a primitive root; properly, to toss violently and suddenly (the sea with waves, the skin with boils); figuratively (in a favorable manner) to settle, i.e. quiet; specifically, to wink (from the motion of the eye-lids): break, divide, find ease, be a moment, (cause, give, make to) rest, make suddenly.
from רָגַע. a wink (of the eyes), i.e. a very short space of time: instant, moment, space, suddenly.
from רָגַע; restful, i.e. peaceable: that are quiet.
a primitive root; to be tumultuous: rage.
(Aramaic) corresponding to רָגַשׁ; to gather tumultuously: assemble (together).
or (feminine) rigshah; from רָגַשׁ; a tumultuous crowd: company, insurrection.
a primitive root; to tread in pieces, i.e. (figuratively) to conquer, or (specifically) to overlay: spend, spread, subdue.
a primitive root; to tread down, i.e. subjugate; specifically, to crumble off: (come to, make to) have dominion, prevail against, reign, (bear, make to) rule,(-r, over), take.
intensive from רָדָה; domineering; Raddai, an Israelite: Raddai.
from רָדַד in the sense of spreading; a veil (as expanded): vail, veil.
a primitive root; to stun, i.e. stupefy (with sleep or death): (be fast a-, be in a deep, cast into a dead, that) sleep(-er, -eth).
a primitive root; to run after (usually with hostile intent; figuratively (of time) gone by): chase, put to flight, follow (after, on), hunt, (be under) persecute(-ion, -or), pursue(-r).
a primitive root; to urge severely, i.e. (figuratively) importune, embolden, capture, act insolently: overcome, behave self proudly, make sure, strengthen.
from רָהַב, bluster(-er): proud, strength.
the same as רָ֫הַב; Rahab (i.e. boaster), an epithet of Egypt: Rahab.
from רָהַב; insolent: proud.
from רָהַב; pride: strength.
a primitive root; to fear: be afraid.
from an unused root apparently meaning to hollow out; a channel or watering-box; by resemblance a ringlet of hair (as forming parallel lines): gallery, gutter, trough.
